{ This position was reached against my then-teammate and current near-neighbour, IM Gerard Welling. The game was played in a youth championship in our province. As a teenager, I was not exactly a strong chess player and certainly did not have a good opening repertoire, while my opponent was already known as a dangerous tactician, who  (just like Anand)  played almost every move tempo. My then 'trainer'  (a childhood friend of two years older who attended my school and also played chess !)  had recommended the Najdorf, but beyond some painfully-vague ideas I actually didn't know what I was doing. The order of the opening moves that I made was not correct, and here I was hit with the thunderbolt: }
1. Nxe6
{ This is a standard sacrifice that has already claimed many victims. On this 'altar' White often sacrifices a bishop, knight or even a rook for the greater good. The piece usually lands with great force; the foundation of Black's position begins to tremble and give way; and the king will not be leaving the centre any time soon. On this occasion my queen is also hanging; things could hardly be worse. }
1... fxe6 2. Bg6+
{ Now with modern engines we can establish that   16.Qg6+  was even stronger:  Kd8  17.exd6  Bxd6  18.Rxe6  and Black is definitely not emerging in one piece. }
2... Kd7 3. Bxh5 d5 4. Bg4
{ A good idea: the pawn on e6 needs to be placed under fire.   18.Bf7 !  would have left Black with even fewer resources. }
4... Bb4 5. Bxe6+
{ 19.Nxd5  Bxd5  20.Rxd5+  would have put an immediate stop to all resistance. }
5... Kxe6 6. Qg6+ Kd7 7. Qxg7+ Kc6 8. Qf6+ Kc5 9. e6 Bxc3 10. Qxc3+ Kb6 11.
Qd4+ Qc5 12. f5 Rhf8 13. e7 Rxf5 14. e8=Q Rxe8 15. Rxe8 Qxd4 16. Rxd4 Kc5 17.
Rh4 h5 18. Kd2 d4 19. g4 hxg4 20. Rxg4 Rf2+ 21. Re2 Rf1 22. h4 Bf3 23. Rg5+ Kc4
24. a3 Bd5 25. b3+ Kc5 26. Ree5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Depasquale, Chris vs. Johansen, Darryl Keith"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kbnr/2qb1ppp/p2pp3/n7/Bp1NPP2/2N1B3/PPP3PP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f5
{ With this precise move White forces the opponent to compromise his pawn structure. }
1... e5
{ Black can't accept the piece sacrifice.   12...bxc3  13.fxe6  Bxa4  Of course   13...fxe6  would lose to  14.Nxe6  with a double attack on f8 and c7.  14.exf7+  Ke7   14...Qxf7  15.Rxf7  Kxf7  16.Qh5+  is no better.  Now White has a cute intermezzo:  15.fxg8=N+ !  (an underpromotion in the opening !)  and now Black loses by force. For instance,  Rxg8  16.Qh5  Kd7  17.Qf7+  Be7  18.Qe6+  and Black loses too much material. }
2. Nd5 { The knight appears on its ideal square. } 2... Qb7 3. Bxd7+ Qxd7 4.
Ne6
{ With this move, White manages to overcome the resistance of the  (then)  second-ranked Australian player. }
4... Rb8
{ The justification of the knight sacrifice is as follows:   15...fxe6  16.fxe6  Qb7   16...Qxe6  doesn't just lose the queen, but after  17.Nc7+  Kd7  18.Nxe6  Kxe6  White also has  19.Qd5+  winning further material.  17.Qh5+ !  The most active and accurate continuation.   17.Rf7  was also strong.  17...g6  18.Rxf8+ !!  Kxf8  19.Rf1+  Kg7  20.Qf3  Now the threat 21. Qf7+ Qxf7 22. Rxf7# can't be prevented. The only logical attempt  Nh6  runs into  21.Qf6+  Kg8  22.Bxh6  . }
5. Ndc7+ Ke7 6. Bg5+ f6
{ After   17...Nf6  18.Bxf6+  gxf6  Black would lose a queen because of  19.Nd5+ !  Ke8  20.Nxf6+ }
7. Nd5+
{ I should fill in some details to explain the conclusion of the game.   18.Nd5+  Kf7   18...Ke8  19.Qh5+  g6  20.fxg6  Qxe6  21.g7+  Kd7  22.gxh8=Q  is over  19.Qh5+  g6  20.fxg6+ !  Kxe6   20...hxg6  21.Qxh8  Qxe6  22.Bxf6  21.Qh3+  and Black gets mated. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Chiburdanidze, Maia vs. Tukmakov, Vladimir B"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/1b3ppp/p3pq2/8/1p1N4/2N4Q/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ncb5 Bc5
{ Black had to accept the piece. But perhaps he felt that White would have obtained a significant advantage with ease, and decided not to do this.   14...axb5  15.Bxb5+  Nc6  16.Rhf1 !  Not   16.Nxc6 ??  Qg5+  17.Kb1  Qxb5  -+  Also not   16.Bxc6+ ?  Bxc6  17.Nxc6  because  Qf4+ !  18.Kb1  Qc4  would be winning for Black !  16...Qg5+  17.Kb1  White has a lot of threats here. }
2. Nxe6
{ This sacrifice has been in the air for a while and now is the best moment for it: when Black is about to castle and the lines need to be blasted open with some urgency. }
2... axb5
{ After   15...fxe6  16.Qh5+  g6  17.Qxc5  White would have won back her piece and retained a very strong attack. It is important to note that  axb5  doesn't work because after  18.Bxb5+  Kf7  19.Qc7+  Black can resign. }
3. Bxb5+ Nc6 4. Bxc6+
{ Even stronger was   17.Nc7+ !  Kf8  18.Rhf1  Qh6+   18...Qg6  19.Nxa8  Bxa8  20.Qc8+  +-  19.Qxh6  gxh6  20.Ne6+  Kg8  21.Nxc5  , winning. }
4... Bxc6 5. Nc7+ Kf8 6. Nxa8 Qf4+ { Clearly,   19...Bxa8  loses to  20.Qc8+ }
7. Kb1 Qb8
{ If Black had time to take the knight on a8 without giving anything in return, he would be in great shape. But that isn't the case here. }
8. Rhf1 Be7
{ 21...Qxa8  22.Qf5  wins a bishop due to the double threat: f7 and c5.  After   21...f6  22.Qe6  Qxa8  White can unleash a terrible attack on the enemy king.  23.Rxf6+ !  gxf6  24.Qxf6+  Kg8  25.Qg5+  Kf7  26.Qf5+  Kg7  27.Qe5+  Kg6  In case of ...Kg8, White would have won the required tempo, and so can take on c5 and then begin attacking anew.  28.Rd3 !  Black is nevertheless not able to avoid losing. For instance:  Qd8  29.Qe6+  Kg7  30.Qg4+  Kf7  31.Rxd8  Rxd8  32.Qf5+  Ke8  33.Qh5+  and White wins the bishop on c5 in such a way that ...Rd1 is not permitted. }
9. Qe6
{ After   22.Qe6 !  Be8  23.Nb6  the knight escapes, and Black stands passively; furthermore, there are worrying threats such as Nd7+. }
*

