[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Van Wely, Loek"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/2qnbppp/p2p4/1p1Qp1P1/8/3BBP2/PPP4P/2KR2R1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. g6
{ In many Sicilian positions, this breakthrough is the right way to open lines against the Black king. White needs these open lines in order to set Black a difficult defensive task. }
1... Nf6
{ Often, in such a situation, the defender blunders immediately. Such is the case here: Black makes a very natural reply  (trying to involve the d7-knight in the defensive effort)  but overlooks some of the latent tactical possibilities in the position.  Since the a8-rook is hanging in so many variations,   19...Rac8  is a possibility. It fails, however, to  20.Bf5 !  Nf6  21.gxf7+  Rxf7  22.Qb3  and with the double threat of Be6 and Bxc8 White wins an exchange.   19...hxg6  20.Bxg6  gives White what he wants most: an open g-file. }
2. gxf7+ Kh8
{ Presumably Van Wely thought White would now have to move his queen, and that one way or another he would pick up the f7-pawn. But there was a surprise awaiting him.   20...Rxf7 ?  didn't work of course:  21.Qxa8+ }
3. Rxg7 { Nicely seen. } 3... Kxg7
{ The queen is protected by the tactic   21...Nxd5  22.Rxh7# } 4. Rg1+ Kh8 5.
Bh6
{ Once more offering the queen ! This strong move effectively ends the game. There isn't a reply that makes Anand do much more work at all. }
5... Ng4
{ 23...Nxd5  24.Bg7#   23...Rxf7  24.Qxf7   23...Nh5  24.Bxf8  Rxf8  25.Rg8+  Rxg8  26.fxg8=R#   23...Rg8  24.fxg8=Q+  Rxg8  25.Qxg8+ !  Nxg8  26.Bg7#  is particularly pretty, although decidedly not the only way to win. }
6. Rxg4 Rxf7 { The last roll of the dice. } 7. Qxa8+
{ What a waste it would have been to play   25.Qxf7 ??  Bg5+  26.Rxg5  Qxf7  and Black wins instead ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Tal, Mihail vs. Mukhin, Mikhail A"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/1b3ppp/p2ppn2/1pn3B1/3NP3/1BN5/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bd5
{ The d5-square now works as a launching pad for White's pieces. With this strong move, White obtains an initiative. }
1... b4
{ Practically losing by force.  The piece sacrifice can't really be taken. Let's see:   11...exd5  12.exd5+  Kd7   12...Be7  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Nf5  sees White take back his piece with a punitive rate of interest.  13.b4 !  The right way to continue with the attack. At this precise moment, the knight can't retreat to d7, and White makes use of this fact.  Na4  14.Nxa4  bxa4  15.c4  This is an automatic and fitting continuation of the sacrificial attack, protecting the d5-pawn and threatening Qxa4+.  Kc7  16.Qxa4  Black is in a grim situation indeed: none of his pieces is especially active, and White has two healthy pawns for the piece he sacrificed. The engine's  16. Rc1 !?  might be even stronger.  16...Qd7  17.Qa5+  Kc8  Or   17...Kb8  18.Bxf6  gxf6  19.Qb6  and here White has two threats: the immediate Nc6+, and the slower but practically unstoppable doubling on the e-file.  18.Rac1  White prepares the thrust c4 and c5, after which his attack will crash through.  Perhaps the least of all evils is   11...Be7  but after  12.Bxb7  Nxb7  13.Nc6  White also has quite a handy advantage. }
2. Bxb7 Nxb7 3. Nd5
{ The second sacrifice on this square ! This one pretty much has to be taken, otherwise the knight becomes very strong indeed. }
3... exd5
{ 13...Be7 ??  would lose to  14.Nc6  Things would only get worse after the natural   13...Rc8  14.Qf3  Be7  15.Nxe7  Qxe7  : just as it looks as if Black has contained the fires, there comes  16.Nf5 !  with crushing effect. Black will lose major material here. }
4. exd5+ Kd7
{ Once more   14...Be7  would give back the piece because of  15.Nf5  , possibly preceded by an exchange on f6. }
5. c3
{ The purpose of this pawn move is clear: threatening Qa4+ and trying to force the c-file open.  Other interesting moves are   15.Nc6 !?  and   15.c4  . }
5... b3
{ Black tries to keep as many files and diagonals closed as possible, but it doesn't help for long.  The game Areshchenko-Akbarinia, 2002, which continued with   15...Qa5  , will be the subject of further discussion later in this book. }
6. Qxb3
{ Perhaps this isn't the most accurate continuation, but the win is not in any real danger.   16.Nc6  also deserved consideration. After  Qb6  17.Bxf6  gxf6  18.Re4  White's attack goes like clockwork.  Also possible is   16.axb3 }
6... Nc5 7. Qc4 { Even now Black is clearly in for a tough time. } 7... Qc8 8.
Nc6 h6
{ This move does not inspire confidence.  Of course he had to consider   18...Nxd5  . White would continue now with  19.Nb4 !  Nxb4  20.Qxf7+  Kc6  21.cxb4  winning back the piece with some interest.  After   18...Kc7  White would play  19.b4  . }
9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Re3
{ A great move by Tal. He prepares to double on the e-file and give mate on e7, simple as that !  Chasing the knight around with   20.b4  Na4  doesn't immediately lead to anything concrete. }
10... Kc7 11. b4 { Of course this comes now. } 11... Rg8
{ 21...Na4  22.Ne7+  wins the queen. } 12. bxc5
{ White has equalised the material situation without lessening the force of his attack. So Black resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Ye, Jiangchuan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1pqb1p2/p1nppb1p/8/3NP3/2N5/PPPQBP2/2KR2R1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is an important moment in the game. Black has obtained the bishop-pair and therefore looks to be better. However, for one more move, his king is stuck in the centre. This is often the cue for a sacrificial attempt and it turns out Anand has seen one such idea here, based on a hidden tactic. }
1. Nf5 { Beautiful and compelling. } 1... Be7
{ So what is this hidden idea ? What if Black simply takes the offered knight ? Well,   17...exf5  first of all removes Black's protection of the d5-square, so the other knight can jump in with tempo. So White plays the logical  18.Nd5  Qd8  and now Anand had undoubtedly prepared the shocking  19.Qxh6 !  which is both elegant and functional. White makes use of the weakness of Black's back rank- this is the reason why the queen can't be taken- and threatens Nxf6+ as well as  (mainly)  Qxh8+ ! Against these two ideas there is no defence.  Black can't bring his king to safety with   17...O-O-O ?  since he would then lose not merely two pawns but also an exchange, following  18.Nxd6+  Kb8  19.Nxf7  .  Black's best try was   17...Kf8 !  but White still has a substantial advantage after  18.Nxh6  Nd4  19.Kb1  Chessable note: It is not entirely clear whether Grooten's evaluation is 100% clear here in case of  Nxe2   17...Bxc3 ?  is not an adequate defence because White keeps his strong knight on d6:  18.Nxd6+  Ke7  19.Qxc3  and White is winning. }
2. Nxe7 { Keeping the Black king in the middle. } 2... Kxe7
{ After   18...Nxe7 !?  White's best continuation is  19.Bh5 !  keeping up the crippling pressure on the opponent's position.  Instead, simply taking back the pawn with   19.Qxd6 ?!  Qxd6  20.Rxd6  h5  would just lead to equality. }
3. Rg3 b5 { After   19...Rag8  20.Rd3  would be intolerable for Black. } 4. Qf4
{ Looking to stir up trouble from the h4-square.   20.Rd3  Rad8  21.Rxd6  Bc8  seems playable for Black, although he is not out of the woods yet. }
4... Rad8
{ 20...Rag8  would be met by  21.Qh4+  Ke8  22.Rgd3  with, again, ever-mounting problems for Black. }
5. Qh4+
{ With the 'clearance move'   21.e5 !  Anand would have made the e4-square available for his knight, and thereby decided the game. Had Anand seen this possibility, he would certainly have played it, not least because it could lead to a pretty queen sacrifice.  dxe5  Now White has the earth-shattering  Or   21...Nxe5  22.Ne4  Bc6  23.Qf6+  Kd7  24.Qxe5  22.Qxf7+ !!  which, however, requires him to notice a couple of quiet moves down the line.  Kxf7  23.Bh5+  Kf8   23...Ke7  24.Rg7+  Kf8   24...Kf6  25.Rf7+  Kg5  26.Rh1  followed by unstoppable mate on e4.  25.Rf7+  Ke8  26.Ne4 !  Ra8  27.Rfxd7+  Kf8  28.Rxc7   23...Kf6  24.Ne4+  Kf5  25.Bg6+  Kf4  26.Rh1  and Black can't prevent mate with Rh4.  24.Rf3+  Ke7   24...Kg7  25.Rg1+  Kh7  26.Rf7#  25.Rf7+  Ke8  26.Ne4  Now the game finishes as in the 23... Ke7 line.  The prosaic   26.Rfxd7+  is also fully sufficient for the win. }
5... Ke8 6. Bxb5
{ Probably White saw this option while thinking about his previous move, and so looked no further. The bishop sacrifice lets White bring his pieces close to the enemy king. }
6... Ne5
{ Taking the sacrifice isn't possible:   22...axb5  23.Nxb5  Qb8  24.Nxd6+  Kf8  25.Qf6  and Black's position begins to take on water. }
7. Be2
{ White stays on track. Material is balanced, but when we consider piece quality it is clear that White is winning. The knight on e5 is unsustainable and a new, decisive wave of attack against the Black king is not far off.  There was no particular problem with taking another pawn.   23.Bxa6 }
7... Qc5 8. Bh5
{ We have already seen this possibility in an earlier line. The light-squared bishop begins to do its attacking work from another angle; now the target is the f7-pawn. }
8... Rf8 9. f4 Nc6
{ After the active   25...Nc4  White would also have a knockout blow, namely  26.Nd5 !  which works the same way as in the game. With this move White breaks the defensive line which Black's queen was keeping, i.e. the 5th rank. }
10. e5
{ Anand has observed correctly that he has a nice combination at his disposal. White aims to close the fifth rank, so that he can soon make use of the h5-square. At the same time he clears e4 for the knight.  Here too, White had the idea of   26.Nd5 !  causing an immediate interference along the fifth rank. The threat of Nc7# forces Black to do something. }
10... d5
{ Now that the fifth rank is closed and White controls the h5-square, we see why Nd5  (in the previous two comments)  would have been another means to the same end. }
11. Bxf7+ { There he goes ! } 11... Rxf7
{ 27...Kxf7  28.Qh5+  Ke7  29.Rg7+  Rf7  30.Qxf7#  would be an even swifter end }
12. Rg8+ Qf8
{ Things would proceed as in the last note after   28...Rf8  29.Qh5+ !  This little check was the reason White had to have control over the h5-square.  Ke7  30.Rg7+  Rf7  31.Qxf7# }
13. Rxf8+ Rxf8 14. Qh5+ Ke7 15. Qg6
{ Being material down and still under attack, Black resigned here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Recubini, Dante vs. Strenzwilk, Denis"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3q1rk1/1p2bppp/p1rppn2/6B1/4P3/P1N5/1PP1QPPP/R3R1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In quite a few positions, when White has placed a bishop on g5, the following 'desperado combination' comes into consideration. Black takes on e4 and breaks the pin along the h4-diagonal with explosive effect. This is something both sides have to be aware of. In this position, it all goes off without a hitch and Black nets a pawn. }
1... Nxe4 2. Bxe7
{ After White takes on e7 in this way, we discover why the tactic acquired the name 'desperado'. Black would lose his knight on e4 if he simply took back on e7 now, but at this precise moment that same knight  (whose death warrant is already signed)  moves again to take another piece. It is crucial that in so doing Black attacks the enemy queen, because his own queen is presently under attack too.  We also need to consider  (briefly)   15.Nxe4  Bxg5  16.Nxg5  Qxg5  but Black is up a very healthy pawn and we need not say more. }
2... Nxc3 3. Bxd8
{ White takes a queen, but Black retaliates in kind immediately.  White is doing even worse than in the game after   16.bxc3 ?  Qxe7  because of his weak doubled c-pawns. }
3... Nxe2+ { It is nice that this move comes with check. } 4. Rxe2 Rxd8
{ This marks the end of the 'transaction'. Black has a healthy, central, and  (most importantly)  extra pawn in this double-rook ending, which he managed to convert into a win. }
5. c3 g6 6. h4 Kg7 7. g4 Rc4 8. f3 h5 9. Rg2 hxg4 10. fxg4 d5 11. Kf2 d4 12.
Rd1 Rd5 13. Rg3 dxc3 14. Rxd5 c2 15. Rg1 exd5 16. Rc1 Rxg4 17. Rxc2 Rxh4 18.
Kg3 Rc4 19. Rd2 Rc7 20. Kf4 Rd7 21. Ke5 d4 22. Ke4 d3 23. Ke5 Re7+ 24. Kf4 Re2
25. Rxd3 Rxb2 26. Ke5 b5 27. Rd7 Re2+ 28. Kf4 Re6 29. Rd5 Rb6 30. Ke4 b4 31. a4
b3 32. Rd1 Rb4+ 33. Kd3 Rxa4 34. Kc3 a5 35. Kxb3 Re4 36. Kc3 a4 37. Kb2 Re3 38.
Rd7 a3+ 39. Ka2 g5 40. Rd4 Kg6 41. Rc4 f5 42. Kb1 f4 43. Kc2 Kf5 44. Kd2 Kg4
45. Rc1 a2 46. Rf1 Rb3 47. Ra1 Rh3 48. Ke2 Kf5 49. Kf2 g4 50. Kg1 Ra3 51. Kg2
Ke4 52. Kf2 Kd3 53. Ke1 Kc2 *

