[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "K, Chris vs. Nakamura, Hikaru"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1k2r/2qnbpp1/3p1n2/4pPB1/pp2P2p/3P3P/PP1Q2P1/1KNR2NR b k - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The situation in this diagram is a lot more complicated. Can Black also take on e4 here ? Nakamura gives the correct answer. }
1... Nxe4
{ Just so ! The move is very strong, despite appearing at first glance to be impossible. }
2. dxe4 Bxg5 { Drawing the queen away from her defensive role. } 3. Qxg5
{ Going anywhere else would lose a second piece:   22.Qe1  Qc2+  23.Ka1  Bxc1  and the resistance is at an end. }
3... Qc2+ 4. Ka1 { Nakamura must have seen this position. } 4... a3
{ Nothing wrong with the simple   23...Qxd1  either, but Black probably reckoned he could play for mate. }
5. bxa3 bxa3
{ 24...bxa3  25.Nd3   25.Qd2  Qxd2 !  26.Rxd2  Rxc1#  25...Qxd1+  26.Nc1  Rxc1+  27.Qxc1  Qxc1# }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Movsesian, Sergei vs. Grooten, Herman"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5rk1/2qnbpp1/p2p1n2/1p2pP1p/2r1P1P1/1NNQB2P/PPP5/1K1R3R b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In countless games in the Sicilian, Black sacrifices a rook for a knight on c3. The offer is often justified, but it is useful to understand the precise reasons why, and this will also tell us when the sacrifice is not such a great idea. First of all, if Black can also take the e4-pawn, the sacrifice is rarely a bad idea. But even if he doesn't get a pawn for the exchange, the following benefits may accrue to him.   
Static benefits: use of the c-file; weakened White pawn structure with the front c-pawn, a-pawn and sometimes e-pawn being weak; influence in the centre.   Dynamic benefits  (in case of White having long-castled)  : other weak squares near the White king; attacking possibilities.     In this position White is threatening to simply mow his opponent over with g4-g5 and then either f5-f6 or g5-g6. Black has to do something, but what ? }
1... Rxc3
{ A thematic exchange sacrifice that is quite common in the Sicilian. In return for the exchange, Black obtains pressure against the White queenside structure and the e4-pawn. }
2. bxc3 Qc6
{ This was the intention- to stop g4-g5, which could have been a source of some embarrassment to Black otherwise. }
3. Bg5
{ This is the only move to avoid giving up the e4-pawn without a fight. } 3...
Rc8 { Black mobilises all his fighting units. } 4. Rhe1
{ Meanwhile, White focuses on stabilising his position in the centre.  One other possibility is   20.gxh5  , remaining focused on the kingside attack and trying to open more lines to that end. However, after  Nb6  (followed by ...Na4)  Black's counterplay develops at pace. }
4... Nb6 5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. Nc1
{ Objectively not the best, but in view of the rating disparity White wanted to keep the game going.  White could have taken on d6, but then a draw would have been likely:   22.Qxd6  Qxc3  23.Qxb6  Very favourable for Black would be   23.Qd3 ?  Na4  , when to stop mate White would have to give back the exchange.  23...Qxc2+  24.Ka1  Qc3+  25.Kb1  Qc2+ }
6... Rd8
{ This move is insufficiently resolute and the timing is poor. While I clearly wanted to continue with ...d6-d5, I failed to realise that 1  the move could have been played immediately and 2  my rook is much better placed on the c-file.  My opponent showed afterwards that Black would have obtained a good position with   22...Nc4 !?  with the idea to play ... h5-h4 as quickly as possible. The idea is to keep the position closed so that the white rooks can't do their thing. After that Black has lots of time to mobilise his pieces for another assault against the White king, and there is little White can do in the meantime.  With hindsight it is easy to be wise, but Black would have gained an almost decisive advantage by playing the thematic central thrust immediately:   22...d5 !!  23.Ne2  Now Black can continue in the manner suggested by my opponent.   23.exd5  Qd6  causes immense problems for White. Black is ready for ...Na4  (or ...Nc4)  and ...Qa3, perhaps also followed by ... e5-e4 and ...Rc4. One sample line:  24.Re4  Rc4 !  25.Ne2  Qa3  26.Ka1  Ra4  27.Rxa4  Nxa4  28.Rb1  e4  and Black breaks through.  23...h4 !  Black should take one tempo out to keep all the lines closed on the kingside, and then he can proceed with the above-mentioned plans. }
7. Rg1
{ White seizes his chance to set up counterplay on the other side of the board. }
7... Na4
{ Not consistent.  Black had the chance to set his own plan in motion with   23...d5  and he didn't go for it. The consequences are by no means unfavourable for him:  24.g5  Be7   24...dxe4 ??  loses to  25.Qxd8+  Bxd8  26.Rxd8+  Kh7  27.g6+  fxg6  28.fxg6+  Kh6  29.Rh8#  25.Ne2   25.f6  Bc5  26.Rg3  g6  would lead to the total closure of the kingside.  25...Bc5  Black is very much 'in the game' now.  26.Rh1  The logical   26.Rg3 ?  would be strongly met by  Rd7 !  (with the threat ... dxe4)  and White suffers great difficulties with his back rank.  26...Rd7  With unclear complications. }
8. Ne2 Qc5
{ Black plays his trump cards, but he has made a mistake in calculation. } 9.
Ka1 d5 { Too late ! } 10. g5 { 26.exd5 ??  would lose immediately to  e4 ! }
10... Qa3 11. Rb1 dxe4 12. Qg3
{ Less good is   28.Qe3  because of  Be7  29.f6 ??   29.g6 !?  h4 !  is unclear.  29...Bc5  and Black is on top again. }
12... h4 13. Qe1
{ This is what I missed earlier: the backwards, diagonal queen move which is so difficult to foresee in calculations ! White has covered c3 adequately and it's no longer possible to continue the queenside attack. }
13... Be7 14. f6
{ Now it's White's turn to attack, and he does not hesitate to make full use of that which he has been gifted. }
14... Bf8 15. g6
{ The future world elite player knows just what to do. White's attack runs on all cylinders. }
15... fxg6 16. Rxg6 e3 17. fxg7 Be7 18. Rh6
{ This finishes things off efficiently. } 18... Rd2 19. Qg1
{ Here I resigned: it is too late to do anything, and White's attack is decisive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Standard Tactics"]
[Black "Beshukov, Sergei vs. Neverov, Valeriy"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/1bqnbpp1/pp1p1n1p/4pP2/P3P1P1/1NN1BB2/1PP4P/R3QR1K b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White starts a flank attack on the kingside, and at first sight it seems to be a dangerous one. But as the adage goes, a flank attack is best met by a pawn push in the centre. That turns out to apply here as well. }
1... d5
{ In general, this move often heralds a forcing game where nobody quite knows what will happen. Neither Black nor White has any way of turning back. Specifically in this position, Black chose this moment for the push because a question was about to be posed to his f6-knight, and he would rather keep it in the centre than retreat it to h7 or e8. }
2. exd5 Bb4
{ This is the immediate point of Black's breakthrough. Because the knight on c3 is pinned, ideas of ...e5-e4, or of capturing on d5, come into play. }
3. Bd2 Bxc3 4. Bxc3 Nxd5
{ Now the knight has found an active post in the centre, but White's kingside remains committed: pawns cannot go backwards. }
5. Bxd5
{ A terrible move: White gives up his light-squared bishop without a fight and that has disastrous consequences. The light squares are now Black's sole dominion.  One idea was   20.Rd1  but then White was probably worried by  Nxc3  . Now say  21.Qxc3  Bxf3+   21...Qxc3  22.bxc3  Bxf3+  23.Rxf3  Nf6  also makes sense.  22.Qxf3  Nf6  and Black stands very well.  The retreat of the bishop with   20.Bd2  would be met by  Rfe8 !  and there is nothing to be done about the advance ...e5-e4; perhaps the e-pawn will not stop there, either. }
5... Bxd5+ 6. Kg1 Nf6 { Black plays very dynamically. } 7. Qg3
{ Grabbing the pawn on e5 would turn out to be a costly mistake:   22.Bxe5 ?  Qxc2  23.Nd2  Rfe8  and Black is winning.  Neither would   22.Qxe5  Qxe5  23.Bxe5  Rxc2  end well for White. }
7... Ne4 8. Qxe5 Qxe5 9. Bxe5 Rxc2 10. Nd4
{ White still seems to be in the game, but there is a twist coming which puts an end to this illusion. }
10... Ng5 11. Rf4
{ White would lose material after, for instance,   26.Rfd1  Nh3+  27.Kf1  Rf2+  28.Ke1  Re8   26.Nxc2  Nh3#  is, of course, the mating motif Black has in mind: observe the dominance of Black's light-squared bishop ! }
11... Nh3+ 12. Kf1 Bg2+
{ 27...Bg2+  28.Ke1  and now Black can win material in several ways  28...Rc5   28...Re8  or even   28...Nxf4  followed by the fork on d3 if White captures on c2. }
*

