[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Chapter Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now that we have studied the typical tactics of the Sicilian, it's time to focus on the typical manoeuvres and conceptual ideas that often occur in Sicilian games. By taking note of these, the club player will be well on his way to familiarising himself with  (grand)  masters' plans, regarding, say, piece trades and changes to pawn structure.  In this way, should you no longer remember the theory, you can still find your way in and through the middlegame. Top players may think of such themes as their 'bread and butter' and recite them in their sleep, but it's something lower-rated players should not take for granted.  By making this inventory of the development patterns and plans of strong players with both White and Black, we will improve our own understanding and our mastery of this position type. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 1 (White): Standard attack against a fianchetto kingside setup by Black"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1pqn1pbp/p2p1np1/4p3/P3PP2/2NB1N2/1PP3PP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Within the f4-system, a pattern emerges that if Black develops his bishop to g7, most of the time White castles short. He prepares  (with Bf1-d3 and O-O)  to attack with Qd1-e1-h4 and eventually Bc1-h6, which we can consider the standard formation and which is also known from the Pirc. Many pieces can be thrown against the Black king's fortifications.   The king's knight can go to g5, its 'colleague' can try and swap itself for black's f6-knight and the white rooks can be doubled with Rf1-f3 and Ra1-f1. Rook-lifts from f3 to h3 are also possible so as to attack the target on h7, one of many that Black has.     The diagram above gives a pictorial view of some of these attacking themes.   Games from the position after the moves of the f-pawn:   
 Nunn-Cserna
 Nunn-Grunfeld }
1. -- *

