[SetUp "1"]

{ Everywhere, but especially in the Bc4 lines  (of both systems)  , the e6-pawn is a potential weakness that White can place under heavy fire. If Black is forced to play e6-e5, White will obtain control of the d5-square, as in the next concept. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 4 (White): Exploiting the outpost on d5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq2k1/4bppp/p1rp4/1p1NpP2/4P3/2PQ4/PP4PP/3R1R1K w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The diagram to the left says it all: White has a monstrous knight against Black's awful bishop on e7. Should White somehow obtain this kind of position, his game is practically positionally won.  But sometimes White has no such knight - see the second diagram below  .     In the diagram above, White has actually sacrificed a pawn, but due to the light-square blockade, he is the one making use of the most important central squares. Black's position here is worse because he additionally suffers from a bad bishop.     In many Sicilian positions such as this one, the b3-knight is a 'weak link' for White. Left far from the action  (and especially from the d5-square)  , it must sometimes seek creative means of reentering the battle for the center. Two routes especially worth trying are Nb3-c1-a2-b4-d5 and Nb3-d2-f1-e3-d5.   It is important to understand the various circumstances under which such long re-routings can be considered-or-even be the optimal solution.   Model games featuring the theme of exploiting d5:   
Fischer - Gadia
Carlsen - So
Karpov - Nunn }
1. -- *

