[Black "Concept 5 (Black): The value of dark-squared bishops"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "q1r3k1/1b1nbpp1/r2p3p/p3pP2/NpP1P1n1/1B1Q2N1/PPR2BPP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the diagram position, White has 'forgotten' to play h2-h3 and Black has managed to get in ...Ng4, with ... Nxf2 following shortly after. Later, the unopposed Be7 became a strong attacking piece that brought Balck the victory.  Model game with this theme:   
Anand - Ivanchuk }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 6 (Black): Exchange sacrifice on c3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1qr1k2r/1b1nbpp1/p2p1n1p/1p2p3/4PPP1/PNN1B2P/1PP1Q1B1/2KR3R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The frequency with which Black offers the exchange sacrifice ... Rxc3 ! in the Sicilian can hardly be overestimated. In the diagram position, it is clear that White's pawn formation will be weakened by the capture on c3.   The strategic compensation offered by the resulting outposts for Black's knight as well as the open c-file is clearly at very least sufficient. Since the White rooks can't really play a role in this position, we can see that positions resulting from such exchange sacrifices can lead to inversions of the usual statement that rooks have a higher value than minor pieces.   Model games with this theme:   
Shirov - Anand
Movsesian - Kasparov
Kanarek - Movsesian }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 7 (Black): The e5-square"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1bqnbp2/p2ppn1p/1p4p1/3NPPP1/P1N2Q2/1PP2BBP/2KR3R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ With his last move ...g7-g5 ! Black initiates the battle for the e5-square. Since White previously played g2-g4, he can no longer reinforce f4 with another pawn.   The f4-pawn will advance or be exchanged, and immediately Black will spring into e5 with his knight. The knight stands amazingly there, blocking the e4-pawn  (and, by extension, the g2-bishop)  , attacking the g4-pawn, and  (last but not least)  giving extra protection to the f7-pawn, which so frequently becomes a target.   The knight may later explore prospects against White's castled setup on the queenside, using c4 as a base.   Model game with this theme:   
Karjakin - Vachier Lagrave }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 8 (White): The thrust g5-g6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1br2k1/2q1bppp/p1npp1P1/1p5P/4PP2/2N1B3/PPPQ4/2KR1B1R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In many positions, White causes trouble with the pawn thrust g5-g6. You should be able to see that this directly undermines at least two other light squares which White frequently targets: f7 and e6. In practice, Black is unable to let the pawn stay there for long, and then White gets to open lines in the vicinity of Black's king.  When Black plays ...hxg6, that opens the h-file. If White has another pawn on h5, he may choose to either take back on g6 or push past with h5-h6, in either case creating great danger for the opposing king.   In practice, Black often takes the marauding pawn with ...fxg6 and then decides how to further defend his king position. It is clear that the stakes are very high for him.     The diagram above shows another kind of position where g5-g6 can be played.   Model games with this theme:   
Smeets - Werle   Rogers - Arencibia Rodriguez }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 9 (White): The blocking sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/2q1bppp/p2pp3/2n3PQ/1p1BP3/1BN5/PPP2P1P/2KR2R1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this position both sides have attacks. But White's is the more dangerous one because with the crisp move Bf6 ! he achieves both positional and tactical ends. Blocking the f-pawn gives White the possibility of Qh6  (!!)  and, immobilizing Black's other pieces sets up the rather slower idea of f2-f4, Rg1-g3-h3.   Model game with this theme:   
Hennings - Möhring }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 10 (Black): Trade of light-squared bishop for knight"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r2kb1r/2q2pp1/p1bp4/3Np1Bn/1n2P2P/1N5B/1PPQ1P1R/1K1R4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In many positions, White places a knight on d5  (see concept 4)  even while it is still controlled by Black pieces. Usually, Black gives his  ('good')  light-squared bishop for the knight, provided that White is compelled to take with the e-pawn.   Then he will try to trade dark-squared bishops and leave White with a light-squared bishop that is hampered by the d5-pawn while Black's own minor pieces suffer no such limitations.  The knight-pair is well suited to half-closed positions with a stable pawn structure. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 11 (Black): Freeing his game with central trades"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1r1k1/1pq1bppp/p1nppn2/8/P2NPP2/2N1B3/1PP1B1PP/R3QR1K w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ With the trade of knights   ....Nc6xd4  and the subsequent Be3xd4 e6-e5 Black can try and free his game. White usually answers with Bd4-e3 and then Black reduces the possible supply of attackers even further by taking on f4. Then his knight from f6 can be routed via d7 to e5, as in this diagram:    Model games with this theme:   
Zhu Chen - Ehlvest
Kamsky - Van Wely }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concept 12 (White): The decision whether to attack with pieces behind or in front of pawns"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1pq1bppp/p1nppn2/8/3NPP2/2N1B3/PPP1B1PP/R3QRK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the classical Scheveningen White very soon faces the point of deciding between two very different methods of attack.   Option 1     White has placed his queen in front of his pawns with the manoeuvre Qd1-e1-g3. He can then direct more pieces to the kingside  (Be2-d3 and/or Be3-d4)  and maybe create some central tension using the e- and f-pawns.   Option 2     Here, White has decided to instead go for the pawn-storm beginning with g2-g3-g4. He needs to be careful about how he prepares; when the g-pawn is pushed, his own king may be weakened. A good rule of thumb: White should only do this if Black cannot open the center with ...e6-e5  (with or without the knight trade on d4)  or possibly ...d6-d5.     A successful example of getting g4-g5 in is shown in the above diagram. White now has a clear plan of giving mate with two major pieces on the h-file.   The question, of course, is how he will accomplish this. In any case the Bf3 will be retreated to g2. But going to h3 with the f-rook is a bit of a waste: the rook already stood well on f1. It can support the push of the f- or g-pawns from f1 just fine, and White should consider both ideas.   Instead, it is more often the a-rook which gets brought to h3 via d1 and d3. When it is on d1, if White times things right, the e3-bishop will be able to slot back neatly to c1 in case it gets attacked by a knight on c4, both getting out of the way and protecting the b2-pawn.   The second game below has more details of how this might happen.   Model games with this theme:   
Ljubojevic - Andersson
Karpov - Kasparov }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Maneuvers and Strategic Concepts"]
[Black "Concluding remarks"]
[Result "*"]

{ That brings us to the end of this consideration of strategic themes. Each theme has found its way into  (grand)  master practice and is common. There are countless examples of each to be found, but in the absence of space, I have contented myself with one or two game references, which correspond to games analyzed later in this book.   When you come to those games, you will find deeper coverage of the ideas than you have seen in this section. An advisory needs to sit at the end of every such section: all rules have exceptions.   For instance, I have indicated in concept 5 that White's dark-squared bishop is typically more important than either Black knight, but you may find examples where a strong grandmaster does still allow that trade with White. The reasons for such decisions are usually specific to the position itself and can be quite involved. }
