1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This move, with a specific associated plan, was popularized and often played by Bobby Fischer. We will soon discuss the most important idea behind this bishop move. Fischer thought so highly of it at one point that he believed he would win with it for sure against any living player. This prompted a question from a journalist, 'Mr. Fischer, are you playing so well that you could beat God too ?' To which he answered: 'No, I wouldn't win against God, though... I think I could draw with him, if he played the Najdorf and allowed me to play Bc4.' }
6... e6 7. Bb3
{ White spends time relocating his bishop. There are three reasons for this otherwise seemingly uncalled-for move, which are related but distinct: firstly, White does not want ... b7-b5 to come with tempo; secondly, White does not want to be confronted with an unexpected ... d6-d5; and thirdly White would like to remove the idea of simplifying combinations based on ... Nf6xe4 from consideration.  For a while people have also been experimenting with   7.a3  Although it is a bit of a waste of time, this small pawn move has two advantages: the bishop can withdraw to a2, avoiding the unwelcome attentions of the opposing knights with which Black often tries to trade it off in other lines; and the pawn push ...b7-b5-b4 is slowed down, reducing the amount of pressure Black can generate against the e4-pawn.    7...Be7  8.Ba2  A nice attacking game in which White's attacking chances are well showcased is Berg-Bezemer, Maastricht 2011. And a counterpart wherein it is Black's counterattack that succeeds: Seeman-Morovic, 1998.  It is, however, more common to first include castling for both sides with   8.O-O  O-O }
7... b5
{ To the question of how Black intends to develop, the answers are mostly clear: ...Be7, ...Nbd7 and ...O-O in combination with a queenside fianchetto. The queen will likely come to c7. Of course, Black should take care when choosing the move order, among other things to avoid motifs of Bxe6 or to discourage f4-f5  (as we shall see.)  The most logical development is   7...Be7  but we won't consider this line.  It has been known for some time that black stays quite safe if he first plays to defend the e6-pawn.   7...Nbd7  The horse heads for  c5  where it not only gives pawn  e6  extra protection, but it can also trade itself off for the strong bishop on  b3.  Kasparov has often played this set-up and he was followed by  (among others)  (Anand and Topalov; and even later, French top player Vachier-Lagrave.   Kasparov won great matches with it)  (for example Bauer-Kasparov, 2001)  , but in 1996 he was comprehensively beaten by Topalov in a beautiful attacking game at the Euwe Memorial.. The move  17.Nd8 !  is especially picturesque. Recently in the rapid game Amonatov-Artemiev, 2018,  Black won a handsome victory. }
8. O-O
{ 8.Bg5  also has its supporters. In the context of this move we should mention a rapid game Ivanchuk-Karjakin, 2008,  wherein White played a stunning queen sacrifice. }
8... Be7 { The safest way to 'survive' the opening. } 9. f4
{ White increases his influence on the center and the queenside. He is now ready for an advance of one of the two pawns. Both e4-e5 and f4-f5  (aiming to disturb the e6-pawn enough to make Black cede the d5-square, by analogy to Fischer-Gadia)  are popular ways to follow up. }
9... O-O 10. e5
{ Not in the style of the Fischer-Gadia game, but this is the most common choice in practice.  There are of course also supporters of the other push.   10.f5  However, as we shall see in the game Anand-Ivanchuk, 1991,  Black turns out not to have any problems here either. }
10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Nfd7 12. Qh5
{ This is the basis of White's idea. The black knight on f6 is no longer in a good defensive position and by rapidly transferring the pieces to the king's wing, White threatens to obtain a powerful kingside attack. Ideas like Rxf7 come into the position- or a rook lift on the third rank- and there is also Nc3-e4 bringing the knight into the action. To begin with, Black uses a little tactical resource. }
*

