[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Najdorf #3: 6 Bg5"]
[Black "Najdorf with 6 Bg5: Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ After   5...e6  we arrive at the usual starting position of the Scheveningen complex. }
6. Bg5
{ This move has for a long time been considered one of the main ones, as it is the single most direct way to put Black under pressure. }
6... e6 7. f4 Nbd7
{ The most natural move.   7...Be7  Black can also develop his minor pieces in the other order, beginning with this. The move takes on independent significance when Black tries to use it to immediately generate tactics, based in general on the h4-d8 diagonal and specifically on the thrust ...g5. Nevertheless, such ideas can be considered premature. An example of what could happen if Black chooses to open this can of worms follows.  8.Qf3  h6  9.Bh4  g5  10.fxg5  Nfd7  This option was popular for a long time. It was analysed a lot by Soviet players, who hoped that they could defeat their ideological rival and famed Najdorf expert in it. The move is enormously provocative, and the most logical attempt at outright refutation also turns out to be quite a convincing response.   10...Nh7  is usually not played because the knight ends up far from its ideal post on e5.  11.Nxe6  fxe6  12.Qh5+  Kf8  13.Bb5 !?  Ever since the 'Argentinian Tragedy' story  (made famous by Kasparov)  circulated, it has been clear that Black's position is practically very challenging after this. However, in modern times the engines have revealed that the most likely outcome following  Rh7  is a perpetual check.   7...b5  The Poluagaevsky variation. The idea is to save time compared to the variations where Black, well, does anything about e4-e5. It is therefore unsurprising that White's most principled  (and best)  response is  8.e5  dxe5  9.fxe5  Now Black shows the tactical point behind his play:  Qc7 !  10.exf6  Generally considered as most principled, exchanging off Black's only developed piece  (except the queen !)  To my knowledge,   10.Qe2  is a less serious test of Black's strategy.  Nfd7  11.O-O-O  Bb7  Here, White has a few continuations, of which the immediate forcing attempts Qh5 and Nxe6 have generally been unsuccessful.  12.Qg4  This position is just the beginning of a whole new world of theoretical content, which occupies countless pages in the literature. I shall attempt to summarise in one paragraph.  Qxe5   12...Qb6 !?  could be considered as safer.  13.Bxb5 !?  Once the antidotes to this sacrifice began to be worked out, White players also investigated 13. Bd3, where it is still not so clear how Black should defend.  axb5  14.Rhe1  h5 !  It is thanks to this in-between move that this variation is at all playable for Black; otherwise, the e6-pawn would become the site of a devastating sacrifice.  15.Qh4  Qc5  with ongoing complications.  10...Qe5+  11.Be2  Qxg5  So, to take stock, Black is behind in development by about 4 tempi and only has his queen out; the next piece to be activated will quite likely be the a8-rook; and his position is... probably about equal. In spite of Black having made a mockery of the standard rules of the opening, to this day no clear refutation has been found to this provocative system. Najdorf players sometimes venture it even to this day, because it is the logical extension of the maximalist spirit of the whole opening: White has no pawn control of the centre whatsoever and must rely on piece play. If he wants to demolish the black position, he will have to sacrifice pieces. And because the black pawn structure is so healthy  (and the position fundamentally sound)  , if Black succeeds in walking the inevitable tightrope his winning chances usually end up much higher than in other lines, because the opponent has gone 'all in'. Polugaevsky won an important Candidates match against former world champion Tal because he managed to stand up against the wizard of Riga, who was unable to find his way through the mess of variations.   7...Qb6  This is the Poisoned Pawn variation.  8.Qd2  White basically has to give up the pawn, because all his methods of covering b2 involve making major concessions which would unacceptably reduce his attacking options.  Qxb2  9.Rb1  Qa3  10.f5  10. e5 also exists.  Nc6  11.fxe6  fxe6  12.Nxc6  bxc6  13.e5  dxe5  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Ne4  Be7  This is one of those positions where a draw is well-nigh inevitable between players with strong preparation, unless Black plays the enterprising   15...f5 !?  Kasparov entered the following line a few times:   15...Qxa2  16.Rd1  Be7  17.Be2  O-O  18.O-O  Ra7  19.Rf3   19.Qh6  Topalov-Gelfand, 1998.  19...Kh8  20.Rg3  A move repetition followed soon in Vallejo Pons-Kasparov, 2004.  16.Be2  h5  17.Rf1   Radjabov-Ye Jiangchuan, 2004.  The most popular option in contemporary times is the 'Delayed Poisoned Pawn' variation, which proceeds as above but with the insertion of ...h6, Bh4. This helps set up tactics based on White's bishop being undefended.   7...h6  8.Bh4  Qb6  One of the biggest specialists in this line is the French player Maxime Vachier-Lagrave. }
8. Qf3 Qc7 9. O-O-O b5
{ 9...Be7  10.g4   10.Bd3  is a bit less common.  h6  11.Bh4  g5  12.fxg5  Ne5  13.Qe2  Nfg4  14.Nf3  hxg5  15.Bg3   15.Bxg5  Bxg5+  16.Nxg5  Qc5  Mamedov-Areshchenko, 2007.  15...Bd7  Shirov-Ivanchuk, 2008.  10...b5  11.Bxf6  Nxf6  Nowadays   11...gxf6  is also being seen, e.g. Motylev-Polgar, 2007.  12.g5  Nd7  13.f5  A well-known pawn sacrifice with which White tries to win time.   13.a3  Rb8  14.h4  b4  15.axb4  Rxb4  16.Bh3  Nc5  17.f5  Qb7  gave Black reasonably good play in Grabarczyk-Dydyshko, 2006.  13...Bxg5+  14.Kb1  Ne5   14...O-O !?  A new move which was tried in Radjabov-Cheparinov, 2007.  15.Qh5  Qe7 !  This is the only natural move.   15...Qd8  leaves e6 undefended, but White's best course of action is not to take it immediately.  16.h4  b4  17.hxg5  bxc3  18.fxe6  and White is better.  16.fxe6   16.h4  b4  is fine for Black now.  16...g6  17.exf7+  Kxf7  18.Qe2  This position, arising after an almost-forced sequence, featured already in the  (somewhat outdated)  book by Daniel King, 'Winning with the Najdorf'.  Bg4  The complications continued in Shabalov-Hellers, 1993. Black is basically fine. }
10. Bd3 Bb7 11. Rhe1 Qb6
{ The modern move. We refer now to the annotated game Shirov-Anand 2008 later in these pages.  Previously   11...Be7  was automatic. The position in fact featured in the world championship match in Reykjavik  (1972)  (between Spassky and Fischer, where the Soviet player chose to play conservatively.)  However, it would be remiss of me to ignore the standard sacrifice  12.Nd5  -which began to be played, with some spectacular results, in the seventies. An example is the Velimirovic-Ljubojevic 1972 game,  which I have also chosen for this book.  Meanwhile, after   12.Qg3  O-O-O  a hard-fought game in the aforementioned Reykjavik match ended in a draw. }
*

