[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Najdorf #3: 6 Bg5"]
[Black "Najdorf with 6 Bg5 #5: Poisoned Pawn Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ 5...e6  we arrive at the usual starting position of the Scheveningen complex. }
6. Bg5
{ This move has for a long time been considered one of the main ones, as it is the single most direct way to put Black under pressure. }
6... e6 7. f4 Qb6 { This is the Poisoned Pawn variation. } 8. Qd2
{ White basically has to give up the pawn, because all his methods of covering b2 involve making major concessions which would unacceptably reduce his attacking options. }
8... Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. f5 { 10. e5 also exists. } 10... Nc6 11. fxe6 fxe6 12.
Nxc6 bxc6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Ne4
{ This is one of those positions where a draw is well-nigh inevitable between players with strong preparation, unless Black plays the enterprising 15... f5 !? }
15... Be7
{ Kasparov entered the following line a few times:   15...Qxa2  16.Rd1  Be7  17.Be2  O-O  18.O-O  Ra7  19.Rf3   19.Qh6  Topalov-Gelfand, 1998.  19...Kh8  20.Rg3  A move repetition followed soon in Vallejo Pons-Kasparov, 2004. }
16. Be2 h5 17. Rf1 { Radjabov-Ye Jiangchuan, 2004. } *

