[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Najdorf #4: 6 Be3 e5"]
[Black "Najdorf with 6 Be3: Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ 5...e6  reaches the starting position of the Scheveningen. Now White can play  6.g4  to initiate the Keres Attack, which is alluded to in a later note. }
6. Be3
{ This variation is known as the 'English Attack'. The reason is that English grandmasters like Nunn and Short were the ones developing the main attacking scheme, which proceeds: Be3, Qd2, f3, O-O-O and g4.  The idea of the 'bayonet' type pawn push g2-g4 is known in many different lines and plays an important role right across the Sicilian spectrum.  In recent years, the English Attack has been played by many of the world's elite players and can be considered as one of the absolute main lines against the Najdorf. }
6... e5
{ A typical Najdorf move. Black immediately indicates that he too has intentions in the centre, and asserts that he will be able to answer the questions relating to the d5-square.   6...e6  With this move, Black enters a specific kind of Scheveningen system, which I shall comment on briefly.  7.f3  Even sharper is   7.g4  , known as the Perenyi attack. The logical comparison is with the Keres Attack against the Scheveningen  (see first note)  , but this line is even more 'all in', because in the following moves White will need to offer at least one piece sacrifice.  e5  8.Nf5  g6  9.g5  gxf5  10.exf5  d5  11.gxf6  d4  12.Bc4  The violent tactical mess that begins from this position is probably best excluded from discussion for now.  7...b5  The sharpest reaction and the one most often seen at the top level.   7...Be7  8.Qd2  Nc6  is the slightly more cautious approach.  9.O-O-O  O-O  Black 'castles into it'. The idea is to organise counterplay later with ...Nxd4 and ...b5. For there to be time for this, it is essential that Black leave his kingside 'as is'; that way, White will need to play five pawn moves  (g2-g4-g5, h2-h4, h4-h5 and g5-g6)  before he has a chance to open up the black king. In general, in such a situation, Black's best reaction to White's offensive ideas is in fact to not react at all.  10.g4  Nxd4  11.Bxd4  b5  12.g5  Nd7  13.h4  and now an example of how black should defend himself against the stereotyped kingside pawn storm can be seen in the further continuation of Svatos-Babula, 1994. }
7. Nb3
{ As in other variations, the knight doesn't stand so well here  (considered by itself)  but the most important factor in choosing its retreat square is staying out of the other pieces' way.  While the text move is considered best, we need to also look at the other options.   7.Nf3  White hopes to someday occupy d5 with a knight and develop his bishop to c4. This move prepares to meet ...Be6 with Ng5, so Black isn't able to contest the a2-g8 diagonal at this moment.  Be7   7...Qc7  is played by, among others, the Bulgarian grandmaster Topalov and offers good practical chances in the dynamic battle to come.  8.Bc4  O-O  9.O-O  Be6  10.Bb3  Nc6  In a rapid game Ivanchuk-Kasparov, 1995 Black did not face too many issues. }
7... Be6 { Ensuring that White can't develop his bishop to c4. } 8. f3
{ White decides to continue in consistent English style. } 8... Be7
{ This is the most normal continuation, but in recent other moves have begun being developed.  The other normal developing move is   8...Nbd7  Black holds off slightly on the kingside development for now, rather beginning to prepare his queenside plans immediately.  9.g4  b5  There is no other logical way to follow up.  10.g5  b4  Necessary, otherwise White would obtain the d5-square without a struggle.  11.Ne2  White wins a pawn with the logical   11.gxf6  bxc3  12.fxg7  Bxg7  13.bxc3  but now Black develops strong compensation based on his dark squares and the doubled c-pawns, starting with the tactic  Bh6 !  11...Nh5  The knight now has to be stationed on the edge of the board, but it has fulfilled its main task of preventing White occupying the d5-square. Now it takes on a new prophylactic role: standing in the way of White's pawn march h2-h4-h5. Black will thereby gain time for his queenside counterplay. An interesting struggle is guaranteed.  12.Qd2  Indeed, we got just such a game between two of the very best players of the time, and also of all time: Anand-Kasparov, 2002.  A radical manner in which Black can thwart the White plan is   8...h5  As we have already seen, if Black develops in a more normal way, White will swiftly push his g-pawn up the board and push the f6-knight to one or other edge of the board. However, the f6-knight is a great defender of the d5-square, so preventing White's pawn push is a logical and productive bit of prophylaxis.  9.Nd5  This is the way in which contemporary top players like to proceed, ever since the game Anand-Topalov, 2008. The game could continue:  9...Bxd5  Black gives up his bishop pair. While that seems like a concession, it is more than justified if he can now trade off the dark-squared bishops too. Then White would have only one bishop- rather than a pair- and it wouldn't have particularly great scope. Additionally the knight on b3 is still not well placed. If that exchange  (which, in the first instance, he would try to achieve by ... g7-g6 and ... Bf8-h6)  doesn't work for black, he usually ends up placing the bishop on g7. After a possible ... f7-f5 and ... e5-e4, the bishop also has a bright future on g7.  10.exd5  Nbd7  11.Qd2  Now we arrive at a very interesting position, where many great players have tested their skills in the last decade. Some, like Topalov, have sat on both sides of the board here. The main move  (although Black can also consider placing his bishop on e7)  is now  (g6   - see for instance the annotated game Topalov-Wojtaszek, 2015.) }
9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. g4
{ The White initiative on the kingside proceeds at pace, so Black can't afford hesitation. }
11... b5 12. g5 b4
{ Before Black moves his f6-knight, he first disturbs its trade rival on c3- otherwise that knight would soon have a very comfortable home on d5. }
13. Ne2 Ne8
{ Usually Black wants to be able to retreat this knight to d7 instead, to avoid disconnecting his rooks. However, there was no spare tempo with which to arrange that. Now White has tried lots of different options, including 14. h4, 14. Kb1 and 14. Ng3 as well as the most recent battleground, 14. f4 - which is considered promising for White. There are top games in both these last two. }
14. f4
{ Topalov-Vallejo Pons, 2005.   14.Ng3  a5  Svidler-Kasimdzhanov, 2005. } *

