[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Najdorf #5: 6 Be2 e5"]
[Black "6.Be2 intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5
{ The so-called Opocensky variation. Black gives up the d5-square for now, intending to control it later with pieces- perhaps even to the extent where he could later consider pushing ...d6-d5.  Black can choose to enter the Scheveningen structure with   6...e6  . }
7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3
{ This has emerged as the main route for White after lots of practical tests. It should not be seen as trivial- after all, by doing this White is essentially committing to not playing f2-f4, because if he tries to play that push now he will lose a tempo with the dark-squared bishop.  The waiting move   9.Kh1  is quite interesting, and now:  b6 !?  This has been determined to be the best reaction.  Meanwhile the logical   9...b5  would allow White to illustrate a major point of his play:  10.a4  Bb7  11.Nd5  10.Be3  Bb7  11.f3  b5  Adams-Anand, 2005.   9.a4  Be6  10.f4  exf4  11.Bxf4  Nc6  12.Kh1  and in this position Black can free his game with  (d5 !   as in Ramirez Alvarez-Kasimdzhanov, 2004.) }
9... Be6 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. a4 Rc8
{ We analyse a good example of how to handle this later: the game Mchedlishvili-Mamedyarov, 2006 which began with  11...Qc7  . }
12. a5
{ White firmly moves the zone of future conflict to the queenside. Model games from this position are, for instance, Karpov-Nunn, 1982 and Ivanchuk-Van Wely, 2008. }
*

