[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Najdorf #6: Sidelines"]
[Black "Najdorf Sidelines: Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3
{ This little pawn push, originally played by Fischer- at least 3 times in 1962, against Bolbochan, Najdorf and Reshevsky- has experienced a new wave of popularity recently. The most important idea is of course to push g2-g4 as soon as possible- and perhaps to press on and disturb the f6-knight.   A second idea, also related to the d5-square, is to fianchetto the f1-bishop and prevent Black from pushing ...d6-d5.       6.Bd3  Given that in some variations the bishop  (having been developed to e2)  needs to head on further to d3, it is logical to ask whether we could do this in one move instead. Practice shows that the move doesn't give real chances of an advantage- but at the same time, it is often used as a surprise weapon by strong players.   6.g3  This move prepares to fianchetto the f1-bishop and place it on the long diagonal without delay. In this way White hopes to get a better grip on the d5-square.  e5  As so often in the Najdorf, Black plays his e-pawn forward two squares, precipitating a battle for piece control of the d5-square.   6...e6  again leads into the Scheveningen structure, a position-type which we handle elsewhere.  7.Nde2  Just like in the related system with 6. h3, the knight returns to this square, with the aim of later rerouting to better ones. After White has played Nd5, a follow-up that often becomes possible is Nec3.  Be7  The process of development sometimes involves slow and 'reliable but unglamorous' moves.  It is also possible to immediately commence the struggle for the d5-square with   7...Be6  as was seen for instance in a game Kramnik-Giri, 2016.  8.Bg2  O-O  9.O-O  b5    It is generally a sound guideline that one should play this expanding move on the queenside at the first realistic opportunity. Black doesn't just want to gain space, though- this move also cues up the knight development ...Nb8-d7-b6 so as to control the d5-square and also set up some possibilities related to the c4-square. Though there are also drawbacks to the pawn push, of course.   The b5-pawn can be used as a 'hook' for White to attack with the typical thrust a2-a4, after which- regardless of Black's reaction- there will be certain weaknesses in the Black queenside. At this time, Black might lose control of the c4-square. White is more or less obliged to try something along those lines now, before Black proceeds any further with the development of his queenside.   9...Nbd7  likely leads to the same thing, unless White now opts to try  10.a4  .  10.Nd5  This jump is needed at some point to draw the e2-knight, which in principle stands rather poorly, into the game.  10...Nbd7  11.Nec3  And now the battle for d5 is joined in earnest  11...Bb7  The most logical: Black completes the development of his minor pieces. Black is now ready to trade as many pieces as possible on the  d5  square and after doing so he will very often have achieved complete equality. Many games from this position end in draws- two good examples are Adams-Van Wely, 2016 and Anand-Giri, Zurich blitz 2016.   11...Nb6  is the alternative and was played by the Polish grandmaster Wojtaszek against Vachier-Lagrave in 2018. Although he misplaced a pawn at some point, with active play he was able to secure a fairly comfortable draw.  The move   6.a4  imparts a rather distinctive flavour to the game. Among the 6th moves at White's disposal, those that do not develop pieces are distinctly in the minority; and this move is completely unique among them in that White immediately prevents Black from pushing ... b7-b5. It looks like it could be a little premature, since White's pawn push is undoubtedly less useful than Black's and it also weakens the often-useful b4-square. Indeed, it wouldn't be taken seriously were it not for the patronage of very strong players - albeit mostly at fast time controls. For instance Carlsen, Anand, Grischuk, Karjakin, Ponomariov and others. The move is good for avoiding theoretical battles and immediately obliging the opponent to think. That being said, it seems to be generally agreed that Black's best reaction is the most 'Najdorfesque' one:  6...e5  Now the preferred retreat square for the knight is f3:  7.Nf3  where it stands in the way of the f-pawn, but complicates Black's task somewhat by discouraging ... Be6- and by extension, making ...d6-d5 harder to execute.  Meanwhile another retreat, namely   7.Nb3  was tried in Zubarev-Areschenko, 2007, with unconvincing results.  Be6   6.f3   6.Rg1  The third point of the move 6. h3 comes to light when Black continues with the logical }
6... e5
{ Now the knight will head neither to b3 nor to f3, but rather to e2, from where it will head to the nice g3-square.  If Black seeks out the Scheveningen structure with   6...e6  then he must have an idea of what to do after White proceeds with the logical  7.g4  He can choose to halt the g-pawn in its tracks, counter-attack the e4-pawn, or neither.  7...h6  Now Black is thinking about ... g7-g5, playing for the ... e5-square. The drawback of this move is of course that Black can no longer consider castling kingside, because the kingside formation has already been compromised. An interesting game to illustrate the possible development of play is Svidler-Vachier-Lagrave, 2016.   7...Be7   7...d5   7...Nfd7 }
7. Nde2
{ So now after the push g2-g4, White intends Ng3 with a nice grip on the f5-square. Therefore, most Black players opt at this stage for prophylaxis. }
7... h5
{ Taking the preferred option of g2-g4 away from White, and leaving him with a choice of two principled ways to continue. }
8. g3
{ 8.Bg5  is also regularly played. A nice game which illustrates White's plans now is Anand-Topalov, 2015. }
8... Be6 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. a4
{ Now, to understand this position, it is advisable to study the game Caruana-Vachier-Lagrave, 2015- but here is a brief summary. As with many positions in the Najdorf, the key feature is Black's ability or otherwise to get in... d6-d5. After both players had more or less completed development  (and with White's queen's bishop on e3)  Black moved his d7-knight to b6, intending to jump into c4. White then had to play b2-b3, seriously weakening the black squares. Black then sacrificed a pawn with ...d6-d5- though to take it, White had to trade off his dark-squared bishop for a knight   Be3xb6.   Vachier-Lagrave remarked of the resulting position that he - despite a pawn deficit - was no worse, because of his possession of the black squares and especially the lack of activity of the white bishop on g2. Also, as is almost always the case after White responds to ...d5 with exd5, Black obtained a kingside majority which he began to push with ...f5 and ...e4. }
*

