[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Nunn, John DM vs. Cserna, Laszlo, Lugano, 1984"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 e5
{ Nunn wrote in 'Beating the Sicilian 3' that this was Black's most popular choice. }
7. Nf3 Qc7 8. a4 Nbd7 9. Bd3 g6
{ It is important for Black to get his f8-bishop into the game in some way. The development to e7 seems logical, however this has a drawback- namely, it allows White the idea of Nf3-h4-f5 gaining tempo against the bishop.  To help illustrate the last comment, let us give an example line.   9...Be7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Qe1  and now the further development of Fernandez-Gulamali, 2003, was that White's knight on f3, after a preparatory fxe5, ...dxe5, reached h4 and threatened to go to f5. If and when Black plays . ..g6 here, he will surely wish that he had begun with that move and then nestled the dark-squared bishop safely in the fianchettoed position. }
10. O-O Bg7
{ A good moment for White to take note of his various ideas. It is fairly clear that Black wants to castle kingside, and therefore equally clear that White should direct his attack thence. This he can accomplish in a few ways, but most of them include the manoeuvre Qd1-e1-h4. At that moment White can choose how to unveil his c1-bishop: with fxe5  (so as not to lose time)  or else with f4-f5. With this in mind we can see the reason why White hasn't developed his bishop to e3 or d2: Nunn would like to bring it from c1 all the way to h6 in a single move ! }
11. Qe1 O-O
{ Black 'castles into it'. With hindsight, this was inadvisable.  One move that comes into consideration is   11...b6  . Black develops his queen's flank and retains the option of playing ...h7-h6 in case White tries the Bh6 ideas mentioned in the last note. }
12. fxe5 dxe5
{ Here   12...Nxe5 ?!  isn't the right solution for Black because of  13.Nxe5  dxe5  14.Bg5  Qd6  15.Qh4  ±  when it is already a bit hard to avoid material loss. }
13. Qh4
{ The queen has arrived at the square where she will find most 'fulfilment' in the upcoming struggle. Note above all that White loses no time in his attack: in particular White is developing his queen's bishop to h6 in one move. The question then arises of how White can develop his kingside initiative further after that.   To which the answer is: having played the bishop to h6, his knight can then move to g5, opening the f-file as a new arena of operations. Following that, he can double on that file with his rooks, whereupon various combinations immediately enter the realm of possibility. }
13... b6
{ The Black queen's knight is already effectively tied down to its defensive duties on d7. If it moves away with   13...Nc5 ?!  then, for example, the following could occur.  14.Bg5  Nxd3  15.cxd3  Qb6+   15...Nh5 ?  16.Nd5  and White is almost winning.  16.Kh1  Black has no way to complete development and the question of the d5-square is still a massive one. }
14. Bh6 Bb7
{ As normal as this developing move seems, it doesn't fit the needs of the position.  The only move was   14...Qc5+  15.Kh1  Bxh6  16.Qxh6  Rd8  making ...Qf8 possible, but here too Black lacks the tempo needed to consolidate his position:  17.Nd5 !?  with continuing problems for him. }
15. Ng5
{ Now we can see the shape that White's standard attack is likely to take- and often does in this line. White wants to provoke an immediate crisis in Black's camp within the next three moves, by doubling on the f-file. }
15... Rfc8
{ This looks strange: black takes his rook away from the kingside even as the storm clouds gather around his king's position. Black wants to involve the queen in the defense with ... Qc5 + and ... Qf8.  It is clear that   15...Nh5 ?  fails completely- White even has a trick:  16.Bxg7  Kxg7  17.Rxf7+ !  Rxf7  18.Ne6+  picking up the queen.  After   15...Rae8  White has, among other things, the computerish yet noteworthy  16.Be2 !  with Bg4 in the pipeline.  In the game Rantanen-Morris, Gausdal 1978   15...Rfe8  was played, and now  16.Bxg7  Kxg7  17.Nxf7 !?  made Black's king position the key feature of the position.  Kxf7 ?  White stands well even after the better   17...Qc5+  18.Kh1  Kxf7  19.Qxh7+  Ke6  20.Rxf6+  Nxf6  21.Qxb7  18.Qxh7+  Ke6  19.Rxf6+ !  Kxf6  20.Rf1+  Ke6  21.Bc4+ !  Kd6   21...Qxc4  22.Qf7+  Kd6  23.Qxc4  22.Rd1+  Kc6  23.Bd5+  Kc5  24.Bxb7  Here Black resigned.   15...Qd6  is given by Nunn in his book as the only move, but here the ex-elite English grandmaster is in error.  16.Rad1 !  would be the answer and here it becomes obvious that Black's last has not solved anything in particular.   15...Qc5+  16.Kh1  Rfc8  could lead to similar play to the game }
16. Kh1
{ White sensibly avoids the check on c5, but there was a better way to do so.   16.Bxg7  Kxg7  doesn't give anything special, because now  17.Nxf7 ?  Kxf7  18.Qxh7+  Ke6  19.Qxg6  Rg8  in fact leads to Black making more use of the now-opened lines on the kingside.  The most accurate is   16.Rf2 !  Qc5  17.Raf1  preventing Black from realising his plan of ...Qf8. In case of  Bxh6  18.Qxh6  Qf8 ?  he loses two pieces for a rook:  19.Qxf8+  Rxf8  20.Rxf6  Nxf6  21.Rxf6  and White is much better. }
16... Qd6 { The queen is headed for f8 'as promised'. } 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nxf7
{ There was but one chance for this strike, so the English grandmaster doesn't wait to be asked again. As we shall see, the sacrifice is extremely strong. }
18... Kxf7 19. Qxh7+ Ke6 20. Qxg6
{ This completely natural move loses White's advantage.   20.Rxf6+ !  was the way to prosecute White's attack.  Nxf6  21.Qxb7  Having ensured a favourable material balance, White can continue with his attack. }
20... Qe7
{ It is clear that Black's king position on e6 is untenable in the long run. The nearest refuge seems to be on c7, and Black naturally hastens to try and get his king there via d6. Nunn doesn't comment on this move, but it is an error, and Black should have chosen another route for his king.  Strangely enough, the only move was   20...Ke7 !  with the idea of reaching c7 via another route. Now it seems Black is holding.  21.Rad1  Worse is   21.Qg7+ ?!  Kd8  22.a5  bxa5  23.Rxa5  Kc7  ∞  when Black has weathered the storm.  21...Rg8   21...Qe6  also seems possible for Black. For instance  22.Nd5+  Bxd5  23.exd5  Qd6  24.Qg7+  Kd8  and the king reaches its safe haven, notwithstanding that White has a decent amount of play left.  22.Qf5  This position is unclear.  The other natural defensive move   20...Rg8 ?  , we should mention, walks into a skewer:  21.Bc4+  and White nets material. }
21. Rad1
{ Here we see the importance of choosing the right route for the Black king's flight to the queenside. }
21... Qh7
{ Black can't ignore White's setup on the d-file:   21...Kd6 ?  22.Bb5+  Kc7  23.Bxd7  Nxd7  24.Rf7  and White wins the house. }
22. Qg3
{ Nunn must have had at the back of his mind that from its new home the White queen has the option of Qg3-b3- or Qg3-a3 in case Black retreats his king to e7. More immediately, he would like to play Nd5, unveiling the power of his d3-bishop after the almost inevitable exchange on d5. These are nice attacking ideas to remember.  Saying that,   22.Qg5 !  is the absolute strongest move.  Qg8  Again,   22...Rg8  fails to  23.Bc4+  Meanwhile, after   22...Qh5  the queen executes an even more powerful switch than the one Nunn intended:  23.Qd2 !  and death awaits Black somewhere on the d-file.  One threat is Be2 followed by Qd6+.  23.Qd2  Ke7  24.Be2  Black is not able to continue running, and modern computers tell us that despite having just retreated two pieces, White has an attack which is nearly unstoppable. }
22... Ke7 23. Nd5+
{ Completely consistent with what had gone before, but again not quite the most accurate.  The surprising   23.Rxf6 !  was a stronger way to break through.  Kxf6  After   23...Nxf6  there follows a string of forcing moves:  24.Qxe5+  Kf7  25.Rf1  Qg7  26.Nd5  Bxd5  27.Qxd5+  Ke7  28.Qe5+  Kf7  and now the lethal yet quiet  29.Qd4 !!  with a winning position. White has four pawns for a rook, but a much more major feature of the positoin is his threat of e4-e5- winning yet more material. The Black king has no more shelter and the threat of Bc4+ is also deadly. However, we cannot blame Nunn- then one of the best calculators in the world- for not noticing this latent possibility.  24.Nd5+ !  Bxd5   24...Kf7  25.Qg5 !  Ke8  26.Rf1  and there is nothing that can be done about Be2-h5+.  25.exd5  Qh5  26.Rf1+  Ke7  27.Qg7+  Kd6  28.Bf5  White keeps up the pressure on Black's best defender- which is the knight on d7.  Rd8  29.Bg4 !  A retreat to allow the f1-rook to join in the fun.  Qe8  30.Rf7  The biggest threat is now Qg6+ followed by Qc6+.  Ra7  The maximalist move, but now Black will find his king gets hunted down !  Meanwhile, the obvious   30...Kc7  loses to  31.Re7  , though maybe Black could survive a few more moves with the best defence 30... Rac8.  31.Qg6+  Kxd5  Black can only go forward.   31...Kc7  loses the queen to  32.Rxd7+  Rxd7  33.Qxe8  32.c4+  Kc5  33.b4+  Kxb4  34.Qd6+  and the king hunt will end in success. }
23... Bxd5 24. exd5 Qh6
{ This blunder lets White play some spectacular tactics.  The only move was   24...e4 !  but nevertheless Nunn's attack would likely have reached its logical end after  25.Rde1  Rg8   25...Rh8 !?  is a decent attempt to bail out:  26.Bxe4  Nxe4  27.Rxe4+  Qxe4  28.Re1  Qxe1+  29.Qxe1+  but this endgame also holds chances only for White.  26.Qc7 !  when White breaks through. }
25. d6+ { Beautifully played by the British attacking maestro. } 25... Kd8
{ 25...Kxd6  is naturally impossible.  26.Bf5+  Kc7  27.Bxd7  Nxd7  28.Rf7  Rd8  29.Qxe5+  and the defence is overwhelmed. }
26. Bf5 { Strong and simple. Black's knights are in a tangle. } 26... Ra7 27.
Bxd7 Rxd7 { 27...Nxd7  28.Qg8+ } 28. Rxf6
{ To clarify, the mate is   28.Rxf6  Qxf6  29.Qg8+  Qf8  30.Qxf8#  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Nunn, John DM vs. Cserna, Laszlo"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1pqn1pbp/p2p1np1/4p3/P3PP2/2NB1N2/1PP3PP/R1B1QRK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. fxe5 dxe5 { 12...Nxe5 ?!  13.Nxe5  dxe5  14.Bg5  Qd6  15.Qh4  ± } 2. Qh4
{ The queen has arrived at the square where she will find most 'fulfilment' in the upcoming struggle. Note above all that White loses no time in his attack: in particular White is developing his queen's bishop to h6 in one move. The question then arises of how White can develop his kingside initiative further after that. To which the answer is: having played the bishop to h6, his knight can then move to g5, opening the f-file as a new arena of operations. Following that, he can double on that file with his rooks, whereupon various combinations immediately enter the realm of possibility. }
2... b6
{ 13...Nc5 ?!  14.Bg5  Nxd3  15.cxd3  Qb6+   15...Nh5 ?  16.Nd5  16.Kh1 } 3.
Bh6 Bb7
{ As normal as this developing move seems, it doesn't fit the needs of the position.   14...Qc5+  15.Kh1  Bxh6  16.Qxh6  Rd8  17.Nd5 !? }
4. Ng5
{ Now we can see the shape that White's standard attack is likely to take- and often does in this line. White wants to provoke an immediate crisis in Black's camp within the next three moves, by doubling on the f-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Nunn, John DM vs. Cserna, Laszlo"]
