1. d6+ { Beautifully played by the British attacking maestro. } 1... Kd8
{ 25...Kxd6  is naturally impossible.  26.Bf5+  Kc7  27.Bxd7  Nxd7  28.Rf7  Rd8  29.Qxe5+  and the defence is overwhelmed. }
2. Bf5 { Strong and simple. Black's knights are in a tangle. } 2... Ra7 3. Bxd7
Rxd7 { 27...Nxd7  28.Qg8+ } 4. Rxf6
{ To clarify, the mate is   28.Rxf6  Qxf6  29.Qg8+  Qf8  30.Qxf8#  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Nunn, John DM vs. Gruenfeld, Yehuda, Telex, 1981"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 Qc7 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8.
Bd3 g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Qe1 O-O
{ Here   10...b5  is seen as the best reply. By waiting a bit with castling, Black is able to slow down his opponent's kingside attack. At the same time, though, the king doesn't stand so well in the centre and White could try and attack it there, for instance proceeding with:  11.e5  dxe5  12.fxe5  Ng4  13.e6  fxe6  14.Qh4  with some compensation for the pawn. }
11. Qh4 b5 12. f5
{ Nunn, playing White, continues in the approved method. His bishop will arrive on h6 in one tempo, and here  (as before)  he doesn't spend time playing Kh1 or Be3. After that, there can follow Ng5 and a doubling on the f-file, with near-inevitable sacrifices thereafter. }
12... Bb7 13. fxg6 fxg6
{ We should mention that in principle that it is dangerous for Black to play   13...hxg6  though it seems to be objectively fine here. White would be wise to prevent his opponent from executing his intended ...Qc5-h5 defensive manoeuvre with  14.Ng5  when he retains pressure on the kingside. }
14. Ng5 { Now White proceeds directly, without bothering with Bh6. } 14... Nc5
{ Black has not realised just what an important defensive function his knight on d7 was fulfilling.  It was obligatory to take the knight fork on e6 out of the equation completely:   14...Qb6+  and now  15.Kh1  Nh5  when nothing is clear yet. }
15. Rxf6
{ The first sacrifice to bring the Black king out of its defensive shell. }
15... Rxf6 16. Qxh7+ Kf8 17. Be3
{ White continues with his development. This move also ensures that the motif of ... Nxd3 followed by ...Qc5+ and ...Rf1# ceases being an issue in this game. }
17... Nxd3
{ Reinforcing the e6-point with   17...Qc8  doesn't work either, because the other light squares are equally weak.  18.Nd5 !  Bxd5  19.exd5  Qg4  20.Bxg6  and the attack will reach its logical conclusion soon. }
18. cxd3 Qd7 19. Nd5
{ Very well played by Nunn, who handled this attack extremely strongly.  Also natural was   19.Rf1  to swap off Black's best defensive piece. }
19... Bxd5 20. exd5
{ White has reinforced his control over the e6-square again, and his knight is poised to land there with powerful effect. }
20... Qf5 21. Ne6+ Rxe6 { Black has to give material back. } 22. dxe6
{ Definitely not   22.Rf1 ??  because after  Qxf1+  23.Kxf1  Rxe3  Black is lots of material ahead. }
22... Qxe6 23. Bh6
{ It is important to see that   23.Bh6  Bxh6  runs into  24.Qh8+ !  Kf7  25.Rf1+  Qf6  26.Rxf6+  exf6  27.Qxa8  winning. }
