[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Lutz, Christopher vs. Svidler, Peter, Frankfurt, 1999"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 g6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Kh1 Nbd7 10. a4 Qc7 11. a5
{ With this move, White tries to clamp down on the opponent's queenside, but it will not be so simple. }
11... b5 { Black nevertheless frees his queenside. } 12. axb6 Nxb6
{ As befits a 'proper' Najdorf player, Svidler has the d5-square well controlled. }
13. Nb3 Bb7 14. Bd3 Nfd7 15. Qe2 Rfc8
{ Perhaps   15...Rac8  was even more accurate.  16.Na5  White gains nothing by   16.Bxa6  because with  Bxa6  17.Rxa6  Bxc3  18.bxc3  Qxc3  Black regains his pawn with a favourable position.  16...Nc5  17.Nxb7  Qxb7  Black has achieved a measure of control over the position. }
16. Ra2
{ This sensible move looks like the right way to reinforce White's position. But now Black obtains very active play.  It was better to attack the b7-bishop and take the bishop-pair.   16.Na5 !  Nc5  17.Nxb7  Qxb7  18.f5  White's idea is then not to prevent the likes of  Bxc3  19.bxc3  Nbd7  but rather to ensure that in the resulting position there is an interesting imbalance to play with. White has two bishops against two knights, which is normally an advantage, although here the knights can count on occupying fairly strong central outposts.  Ftacnik gave the line   19...Nxd3 ?!  which gains a pawn but leads to a decisive advantage for White.  20.cxd3  Rxc3 ?  21.Qf2  f6  22.Rb1  Rc6  23.Be3  Rb8  24.d4 !  +-  White is at least winning back his material and has by far the better minor piece. }
16... Nc4 17. Nd5
{ The exchange on c4 is bad for white because black now gets a typical Sicilian advantage:   17.Bxc4 ?  Qxc4  18.Qxc4  Rxc4  19.Na5  Rc7 !  20.Nxb7  Bxc3  21.Nxd6  A 'desperado' move.   21.bxc3  Rxb7  22.Be3  Rc7  ∓  leads to excellent endgame prospects for Black.  21...Bg7  22.Nb5  Rxc2  23.Na3  Re2  ∓  Here, too, Black holds all the trump cards. }
17... Bxd5 18. exd5 Nf6
{ A logical idea, seeing that the d5-pawn is at this moment without defenders. }
19. Qf3
{ Following   19.Nd2  Nxd2  20.Bxd2  Nxd5  21.f5  we reach some kind of dynamic balance. }
19... Nb6 { Exchanging the a6 and d5 pawns seems like a good deal for Black. }
20. Rxa6 Rxa6 21. Bxa6 Rb8 22. Bd3
{ The pawn can't be kept.   22.c4  Ra8 !  23.Bb5  Nxc4  24.Qc3  Rc8  sees Black get it back, and d5 is still under attack as well. }
22... Nbxd5 23. Bd2 Nb4 24. Bxb4 Rxb4 25. f5
{ White wanted to keep some offensive possibilities, but this is not a good decision.  Better is   25.Ra1  but Black is nevertheless for choice after  e6 !  26.Ra8+  Rb8  27.Nd2  d5 }
25... d5
{ The general rule is that when Black gets ...d6-d5 in, he begins controlling the flow of the game. The rule applies here: not only does Black have good control over important central squares, but there also exist possibilities to play against White's king position with Rc4-h4 and/or ...Nf6-g4, or against the weak pawns on White's queenside. }
26. fxg6
{ This eases Black's task.  Now   26.Ra1  is well met by  Rh4 !  27.Ra8+  Bf8  28.g3  Ng4  and this is already almost winning for black.  The ugly   26.g3  seems to be the best option. }
26... hxg6 27. Qf2 e6
{ Black strengthens his central pawn formation, but the most important feature of this move is that his queen will now afford extra protection to the f7-pawn. This frees up the knight for ventures elsewhere. }
28. g3 { White's dark squares are too weak after   28.h3  Nh5  29.Rb1  Bf8  ∓ }
28... Ng4 29. Qe1 Rb6 30. Qe2
{ 30.Qc1 ?  gives Black a chance for decisive material gain:  Rxb3 !  31.cxb3  Nf2+  32.Kg2  Qxc1  33.Rxc1  Nxd3  with a winning endgame. }
30... Ne5
{ The Black forces occupy commanding positions and dominate the board. White cannot avoid material loss. }
31. Rb1 Nc4 32. Bxc4 dxc4 33. Nd2
{ Jumping to a5 instead offers White no solace:   33.Na5  Rb4  34.c3  Ra4  35.b4  cxb3  36.Nxb3  Qxc3  and Black stands much better. }
33... c3 34. Ne4 Qc6 35. Kg1 Rb4 36. Ra1
{ White, seeing the hopelessness of his position, chose to resign without waiting for Black's reply. }
