[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Al Modiahki, Mohamad vs. Anand, Viswanathan, Hyderabad, 2002."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4
{ In contemporary grandmaster praxis, this possibility is no longer so popular because it is considered relatively 'innocuous'. But because Al Modiahki had won against Hamdouchi with this move earlier in the event, Anand had to take it seriously in his preparation. }
6... Qc7
{ This early queen move by Black serves to eliminate White's idea of Bc4 and set up an idea of his own, i.e. ...e7-e5. }
7. Nf3
{ White doesn't have to fall in line with his opponent's plans.   7.Bd3  is more often played. Black can meet this with  e5   7...g6  has also been played  and then White generally goes back anyway with  8.Nf3  . }
7... Nbd7
{ Najdorf players have always been fond of the knight development to d7.  Due to the particular move-order, if Black plays   7...e6  , White is no longer able to assume the piece formation defined by Qf3, Be3 and the push g2-g4  (which as we have already seen can be somewhat dangerous.) }
8. a4 g6
{ Now the Black setup is some kind of cross between a Najdorf and a Dragon. }
9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Kh1
{ Nunn wrote that this prophylaxis may not be strictly necessary.  White could continue with the immediate   11.Qe1  in an attempt to reach an attacking formation known to us from the game Nunn-Cserna elsewhere in these pages.  Anand wrote in his notes to this game that there was also a possibility for White to proceed with   11.Qe2  , setting up a quick e4-e5 break. }
11... b6 12. Qe2
{ Al Modiahki had a different plan in mind, one that isn't so often seen.  As above, White again had the chance to go for the setup with a queen on h4, beginning with   12.Qe1  . }
12... Bb7
{ This normal, natural developing move also has the side benefit that White cannot play e4-e5 for now. }
13. Bd2
{ White completes his development.  After   13.e5  dxe5  14.fxe5  Ng4  the e5-pawn will be lost, since  15.e6 ?!  leads to even worse consequences:  Nc5  16.exf7+  Rxf7  17.Bc4  e6  and Black's pieces are tremendously active. }
13... Nc5 14. b4
{ This move fits in with White's plans.  Once more   14.e5  dxe5  15.fxe5  Ng4  would not achieve the desired effect for White. }
14... Ncd7
{ Black has lost some time, as well as the use of the c5-square, but these factors are of less importance than the weaknesses White has made in his position.   14...Nxd3  15.cxd3  sees White trade in the bishop-pair for reasonable compensation: he has little ideas in various regions of the board while Black lacks active options and must instead sit and wait  (his normal play along the c-file now being entirely without any targets.) }
15. a5
{ This must be done now, to stop Black having the option of playing ...a5 himself and opening up the c5-square for use by his queen's knight again. }
15... b5
{ Of course Black should think about trying to use the dynamics of the long diagonal in his favour. The logical way to do this would be   15...Nh5  16.Nd5   16.Ra3  Nxf4 !  and the bishop on d2 is overloaded  16...Bxd5  17.exd5  Bxa1  18.Rxa1  . However, Anand would have been aware that this position entails significant risks for him as well. Both his bishops are gone from the board and the two knights which remain are not exceptionally well placed. The compromising of his king safety may prove a relevant factor in what is to come, and it is clear that White has at least fair compensation for the exchange. }
16. Rac1
{ White doesn't feel like allowing any further tactical ideas along the long diagonal, and hastens to remove his rook from it. On c1 the rook also lends support to a future c2-c4. }
16... Rae8
{ Anand develops his last piece and prepares a central pawn break.  It is no secret that the text move was intended to support the push   16...e5  , but it turns out Black can also execute it immediately.  17.fxe5  Maybe   17.f5  could be interesting for White.  17...Nxe5  18.Nxe5  dxe5  19.Nd1  Nh5  and it seems like Black has no problems. It is noteworthy that after  20.c4  he has  Nf4 !? }
17. Nd1 { Both sides are strictly following their declared plans. } 17... e5
18. c4 bxc4 19. Rxc4
{ It looks more normal to take back with the bishop, but White didn't want to leave the e4-pawn unprotected. After   19.Bxc4  Qb8  20.Bxa6  Bxa6  21.Qxa6  Nxe4  22.Rb1  we would have reached an unclear position where both sides are ploughing ahead with their respective plans at pace. Does Black get enough play through the centre in exchange for White's connected passers on the queenside ? I think so, but one can never be certain ! }
19... Qb8 20. fxe5 d5
{ This finesse has become possible because of the way White has played. As Anand was to say: 'A nice trick, even if it isn't as good as I thought'. }
21. exd5
{ The point is that after   21.exf6  Black takes back on f6:  Nxf6 !  and this gives him a clear advantage. }
21... Nxe5 22. Nxe5 Rxe5 23. Qf2 Rxd5
{ Of the three attractive options, Anand opts for this move. The White pieces are slightly out of sync with each other, while the Black ones are nicely arranged. Both bishops cut through the centre along the long diagonals, and also his major pieces and knight participate fully in the battle.  A logical possibility is   23...Bxd5  , also leading to an advantage for Black after an exchange of blows:  24.Bf4  Ng4  25.Qc2  Bxc4  26.Qxc4  Bh6  27.Bxe5  Nxe5  28.Qxa6  Qxb4  While White's passed pawn is certainly strong, his pieces are so poorly arranged that the evaluation cannot favour him.  Black could also play   23...Nxd5  . After both  24.Be4  and   24.Be2  (Black would obtain the upper hand.) }
24. Bc2
{ Although this position is somewhat in his favour, Anand got the impression that the white formation is still quite robust. }
24... Qd8
{ Perhaps not the most promising continuation. Anand analyzes various other options, but perhaps yet another move evaded his notice.   24...Rh5  : After this White can play  25.Bf4 !  when Black still has some edge, but it is unclear whether it is really enough to press for a win.   24...Rfd8  : oddly enough, this move also doesn't give good results after  25.Bf4  Qa8  26.Nc3  R5d7  27.Na4   24...Re8 !  was the move Anand didn't give. By playing this, Anand would have quickly overcome his own pessimistic impressions of the position. A new piece comes into the game and in the following lines White's position begins to look extremely dodgy.  25.Bf4 ?!  or similarly   25.Ne3  Rg5  25...Qd8  In the face of the numerous and imminent threats  (among them ...Ng4 and ...Rh5)  White does not have many sensible defences. }
25. Bc1
{ Al Modiahki makes another mistake.  Tougher was   25.Bc3  Rg5  26.Ne3  when, crucially, Black is not able to win immediately with  Nd5  thanks to the resource  27.Be4 ! }
25... Re8
{ Black brings his last piece into the centre. White's defences against the as-yet-undefined threats are becoming harder to arrange.  Another way to a large advantage was   25...Re5  going for a domination approach. For instance  26.Ne3  Qe7  and Black manages to get the job done, bit by bit. }
26. Nc3 Rh5 27. Kg1
{ Since the White king wasn't feeling so comfortable along the long diagonal. }
27... Kh8
{ Anand awards himself an exclamation mark for this, but I am not so sure, and almost gave it the 'dubious' symbol. The move serves two purposes: a waiting move in a position where White cannot easily find something to do himself, and also preparation for moving the f6-knight  (i.e. if he does so now, then Qxf7 will no longer come with check.)  However, it is a fairly unnatural move and in addition, black has something better.  The move   27...Qe7  would have made more constructive use of Black's advantages. White is at a loss for a good move. For instance:  28.Rd1   28.h3  Nd5 !  29.Nxd5  Bxd5  30.Rc5  Qb7  is also problematic for White  28...Qe6 !  poses White great problems because of the double threat of ...Qxc4 and ...Ng4. }
28. Qb6
{ After long deliberation, White chose this queen move. But besides getting him into time trouble, the move also failed in its main intention of defusing some of Black's threats.  White could have tried to free himself more convincingly by   28.Rd1  , when the idea analogous to the one from my previous comment doesn't work so well:  Qe7  29.h3  Qe6  30.Rc7  . Because Black has lost time on ...Kh8, he is no longer able to play ...Ng4 here and so White gets counterplay. }
28... Qb8 { 28...Qe7  was again worth considering. } 29. Rc7
{ Cutting out a significant part of Black's play.   29.Qc7 ?  doesn't work because of  Qxc7  30.Rxc7  Ng4 !  ∓  31.Rxb7 ?  Bd4+   29.h3  looks rather implausible but the attempt to punish it backfires spectacularly:  Rxh3 ?  30.Bf4  and White wins ! Thus, White wins the necessary time with which to protect himself. }
29... Ng4 30. Bf4 Qd8 { Anand must have seen this from afar. } 31. Rc4
{ The only move to prevent Black's threat of ...Bd4+. } 31... Qh4
{ Anand: 'However, since he was down to 7 seconds, I couldn't resist just bashing out this move'. It turns out to have been a bad mistake that could have cost him the whole game.  Instead   31...Qa8  32.Be4  is just equal. The weakness of Black's back rank prevents him from taking the offered piece.  Bxe4  33.Nxe4  Rxe4 ?  34.Rxe4  Qxe4  35.Qd8+  Bf8  36.Qxf8#   31...Qxb6+  32.axb6  is nothing special for Black either because  Bxc3  can be met by  33.Bd1 !   33.Rxc3  Re2  Much stronger was   31...Qd7 !  when Black still has the upper hand. }
32. Bg3
{ The White player thinks he has found a clever move repetition to bring him closer to the time control.  But Black was bluffing: White could simply take the bishop on b7 with   32.Qxb7  and now after  Nxh2  White is in time to defend himself against the threat of ...Ng4 and mate.  33.Qc6 !  This move is not so easy to notice in extreme time-trouble. White needs to shove the e8-rook away from the e-file, and then none of Black's tricks work any more.  A terrible trick which Anand surely intended to play on his opponent comes about in the line   33.Qxf7 ??  Nf3+ !!  Now White loses.  34.gxf3   34.Rxf3  Qh1+  35.Kf2  Qe1#  34...Qh1+  35.Kf2  Rh2+  36.Bxh2  Qxh2#  33...Rf8  34.g3  The attack will be beaten back. }
32... Qg5 33. Bf4
{ The answer to this, though, will have come as a rude awakening to White.  No longer is it possible to take on b7:   33.Qxb7  Qe3+  34.Bf2   34.Kh1  Qxg3  34...Nxf2  35.Rxf2  and now the pretty  Qxc3 !  would be the right way to finish off the exchange of tactics.  36.Rxc3  Re1+  37.Rf1  Bd4+  and mate in two. }
33... Rxh2 { A great move ! } 34. Qxb7
{ After this move, Black's attack is irresistible, and an attacking maestro like Anand could be relied upon to finish the job.   34.Bxh2  was the damage-limiting move.  Nxh2  Once again,   34...Bxg2 ??  would even lose to  35.Bf4 !  35.Ne4   35.Qxb7  Nxf1  36.Kxf1  Bxc3  37.Rxc3  Qc1+  is losing for White  Now Black has  35...Qd5 !  , with a likely  (but not certain)  win.  If the queen is taken Black has mate in three:   34.Bxg5  Rxg2+  35.Kh1  Rh2+  36.Kg1  Rh1# }
34... Qh5 35. g3 Rxc2
{ After   35...Rxc2  36.Qh1  Qxh1+  37.Kxh1  Rxc3  Black will simply be a piece up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Al Modiahki, Mohamad vs. Anand, Viswanathan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1q2rrk1/1b1n1pbp/p2p1np1/P3P3/1PR1P3/3B1N2/3BQ1PP/3N1R1K b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... d5
{ This finesse has become possible because of the way White has played. As Anand was to say: 'A nice trick, even if it isn't as good as I thought'. }
2. exd5
{ The point is that after   21.exf6  Black takes back on f6:  Nxf6 !  and this gives him a clear advantage. }
2... Nxe5 3. Nxe5 Rxe5 4. Qf2 Rxd5
{ Of the three attractive options, Anand opts for this move. The White pieces are slightly out of sync with each other, while the Black ones are nicely arranged. Both bishops cut through the centre along the long diagonals, and also his major pieces and knight participate fully in the battle.  A logical possibility is   23...Bxd5  , also leading to an advantage for Black after an exchange of blows:  24.Bf4  Ng4  25.Qc2  Bxc4  26.Qxc4  Bh6  27.Bxe5  Nxe5  28.Qxa6  Qxb4  While White's passed pawn is certainly strong, his pieces are so poorly arranged that the evaluation cannot favour him.  Black could also play   23...Nxd5  . After both  24.Be4  and 24. Be2 Black would obtain the upper hand. }
