[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Fischer, Robert James vs. Gadia, Olicio, Mar del Plata, 1960"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 8. O-O
Bb7 9. f4 Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. f5
{ This is the practical idea behind White's play so far. He wants to place the e6-pawn under pressure, so that it has to move and weaken the d5-square. Then the d5-square would be in a vice-like grip, being under the immediate control of White's b3-bishop and c3-knight. White now has very good prospects of placing a piece on the d5-square permanently. }
11... e5
{ Yes, I know what I said, but does the e6-pawn really have to move ? Let's investigate reinforcing it with the queen instead.   11...Qd7  The answer is that this move is slightly better than the text, but Black will nevertheless encounter significant problems. The clearing of the a2-g8 diagonal and the f-file can only ever be of benefit to White, who already has pieces in place to use those lines.  12.fxe6  fxe6  Now let's look forward another few moves, beginning with the cautious  13.a3  to remove ...b4 from the picture and only then focus attention on the weak e6-pawn.  Be7  14.Qf3  O-O  15.Qh3  Black is experiencing difficulties here. }
12. Qd3 Be7
{ Given what happens later on in this game, of course Black can consider beginning with   12...h6  , but it may well happen that the h6-pawn itself becomes a target for White  (in particular, for the c1-bishop.)  For instance  13.Re1  Be7  14.Qg3  and Black is already unable to castle short because of Bxh6. }
13. Bg5 { Perfectly thematic. } 13... Qb6+
{ The interesting attempt to break free with   13...Ng4  would be best met by  14.Qe2 !  which, in passing, prevents the idea of a knight check on f2 after the moves ...Qb6+, Kh1.  Bxg5  15.Qxg4  and here, as in the game, White threatens to obtain his ideal formation with Bd5 next. Here, Black has time to prevent the exchange of light-squared bishops with  Rc8  so as to answer  16.Bd5  with  Bd7  Computers actually want to play   16...Bxd5  here, giving White the opportunity to plant his knight on d5 without a fight. This is because Black can take a pawn after  17.Nxd5  Rxc2  -but in fact this pawn does not compensate Black for his trouble.  18.h4  Bh6  (otherwise White wins the c-file with the move Rc1)  19.b3  and White stands better. }
14. Kh1 O-O
{ It is clear-from the lack of evasive action- that the Black player doesn't understand the strategic danger facing him. Lucky for us, because now we obtain an ideal textbook example. }
15. Bxf6 { Trading off a good bishop for a knight. } 15... Bxf6 16. Bd5
{ This was the point of the previous move- now White gets to trade the light-squared bishops and cement his control of the d5-square further. }
16... Rac8 17. Bxc6 Rxc6 18. Rad1
{ It is important to reinforce the queen before jumping to d5.    18.Nd5  would be premature due to  18...Qd4  and now White is unable to play  19.c3  because his Queen is hanging }
18... Rfc8 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. c3 Be7
{ Fischer wrote about this position that he usually only got such setups in his dreams. Visually, indeed, White has a very strong grip on the situation. The main specific feature working in his favour is the strong knight, to which Black's weak bishop on e7 cannot compare. That's because it sits on the d5-square, irrevocably weakened by Black in the late opening phase. White has more space on the kingside, which is reserved for his exclusive use by the advanced 'bulwark' pawn on f5. In general, White's pieces are better centralized and harmonized than their Black counterparts. The only compensating factor Black has is some space on the queenside, which is thanks to having gotten in the push b7-b5. Black would preferably like to push this pawn onward to b4, or else co-ordinate some play against the e4-pawn, in either case using the position of his rooks on the c-file. }
21. Ra1
{ A formidable move, born of a very deep strategic insight.  Many players, having reached this position, would have continued   21.f6  which is more in line with the expectation people have of how to 'slay a Sicilian'... Indeed, the Black king's position would be quite desolate following  Bxf6  22.Nxf6+  gxf6  and it transpires that White is much better, if not winning, in this position. Therefore it is a matter of taste whether this is more convincing than what Fischer played. We will see why later.  23.Qh3 !  The most accurate continuation. White prepares for an as-yet-unspecified rook lift along the the third rank.  d5  This is the best move- doing something to avoid getting squashed- but of course Black will be a lot worse if he doesn't even have a pawn to hold onto.  Things go wrong faster after   23...Kh8 ?!  though:  24.Rf5  Rc4  Or   24...b4  25.Rd3  bxc3  26.Rg3  and the threat of Qxh7+ followed by Rh5# is too strong.  25.Re1 !  White follows up with Re3 and it turns out that the idea of finishing with Rh5# is decisive here as well. Still, coming up with this set of moves, especially in the right order, is certainly not easy during a game. }
21... f6
{ Trying to definitively prevent the idea of f5-f6.   This would have been better accomplished by   21...Bf8  , notwithstanding which, White could implement his queenside plan in full anyway.  22.a4  Rc4  After   22...Rb8  there comes  23.Nb4 !  Rcb6  24.a5  winning major material.   22...bxa4  23.Rxa4  a5  The a-pawn will also get surrounded and won after   23...Ra8  24.b4  followed by Rfa1.  24.f6  g6  25.b3  Rb8  26.c4  Followed by Rfa1, whereupon the a5-pawn will be lost.  23.b3  R4c5  24.axb5  axb5  25.b4  Rc4  26.f6  g6  27.Ra5  White has played every single move that featured in his plan, right up to the actual winning of material- which is now unstoppable. }
22. a4
{ The idea behind White's last move. He breaks up the opponent's structure on the queenside, leaving weaknesses everywhere in it. We can consider that the queenside is the logical theatre of operations for White, because all his pieces are poised to make a difference there- while Black lacks one critical unit, the bishop on e7. That piece can't play on the queenside in a meaningful way. White plans to liquidate the queenside  (possibly winning a pawn en route)  , obtain a passed b-pawn and then use the knight to shepherd it home. }
22... Rb8
{ Black blunders, ending the fun abruptly. That is something of a shame, because I'd have liked to be able to show the technique with which Fischer would definitely have finished off the game in the absence of this blunder.  Better was   22...bxa4  , but then White would have won exactly as mentioned in the note to his 22nd move.  23.Rxa4  a5  24.Rfa1  Rc5  25.h3  Avoiding the eventuality of getting mated when the c-file opens.  Bf8  26.b4  axb4  27.cxb4  Rc1+  28.Kh2  R1c2  29.Qb3  Kh8  30.b5  and it's over. Notice how strong the knight is at d5 and what role it plays in this position. Fischer probably knew right from the moment his knight reached d5 that it would win him the game almost without his paying any particular attention. White can prosecute his advantage at a leisurely rate, without having to calculate too much. }
23. Nxe7+ Qxe7
{ After   23...Qxe7  24.Qd5+  the rook on c6 is lost immediately. } *

