3. Nxe7+ Qxe7
{ Black played this, and resigned without waiting for the inevitable response.  After   23...Qxe7  24.Qd5+  the rook on c6 is lost immediately. }
4. Qd5+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Areshchenko, Alexander vs. Akbari Syed Arash, Kuala Lumpur, 2002, "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O b5 8. Bb3
Bb7 9. Re1 Nbd7 10. Bg5 Nc5
{ A known mistake here is   10...Be7 ?  which invites a successful piece sacrifice.  11.Bxe6  fxe6  12.Nxe6  Qb6  13.Nxg7+  and here with three pawns for the piece and an ongoing attack against the exposed Black king, White stands better. }
11. Bd5 { White begins with a bishop sacrifice at the approved location. }
11... b4
{ Asking for it a bit.  Taking the offer doesn't promise Black great success.   11...exd5  12.exd5+  Kd7   12...Be7  simply doesn't work at all because White regains the material with interest after  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Nf5  .  13.b4 !  There's no logical retreat for the c5-knight.  Na4  14.Nxa4  bxa4  15.c4  A nice move with a dual point: White protects his d5-pawn and simultaneously threatens Qxa4+.  Kc7  16.Qxa4  White has a virtually won game in spite of still not having regained the piece; this all happened in Beliavsky-Marjanovic, 1971. }
12. Bxb7 Nxb7 13. Nd5
{ The second sacrifice on the same square ! This one can hardly be declined, because Black would end up in a real mess if he did. }
13... exd5
{ Protecting the b4-pawn lets White show his second threat:   13...a5  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Nc6  and White wins due to a cute mate:  Qc8  16.Nxf6#   13...Rc8  stops the idea of Nc6, but Black's development is too poor to defend against all the threats.  14.Qf3 !  This strong move threatens 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. Bxf6, thus  Be7  is forced.  15.Nxe7  Qxe7  Apparently Black has things basically covered, but now there comes:  16.Nf5 !  and now everything falls apart for Black.  Qf8  Now, with the help of an engine one can find the most mathematically precise path:  17.e5 !  Nothing wrong with   17.Nxg7+  either.  17...Nd5  18.Rad1  and the attack is decisive. }
14. exd5+ Kd7 15. c3
{ Now   15.Nc6  would also be quite a respectable way to continue. } 15... Qa5
{ Black takes Qd1-a4 out of the picture, but finds himself faced with an attack from a new angle. }
16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. cxb4
{ Even better is   17.Nc6  Qb5  18.cxb4  when the Black king has no way to leave the centre. }
17... Qxd5
{ The floodgates are also opened wide after   17...Qxb4  :  18.Rc1   18.Qg4+  Kc7  19.Ne6+  18...Nc5  19.Qg4+  f5   19...Kc7  20.Ne6+  followed by Qxb4 wins the queen  20.Qxf5+  Kc7  21.Nc6  Qxb2  22.Qxf7+  with a won game. }
18. Qa4+ Kc7 19. Rac1+ Nc5
{ Beginning to haemorrhage material in an already lost position. One might as well resign here.   19...Kb8  offers no respite because of  20.Nc6+  Kc7  21.Ne7+  picking up the queen  Meanwhile   19...Kb6  20.Rc6+  Ka7  21.Qxa6+  Kb8  22.Re8+  is simply mate. }
20. bxc5 dxc5
{ White has his piece back, while the black king is still in terrible trouble. None of Black's pieces, apart from the queen, play any role whatsoever. It is simply a case of force majeure, and the remainder of the drama unfolded in the expected manner, with no surprises. }
21. Red1 Rg8 22. g3 Kb6 23. Nb3 Qh5 24. Rd7 Rc8 25. Qa5+ Kc6 26. Rcd1 Qe2 27.
Nd4+ cxd4 28. Qd5+ Kb6 29. Rb7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
