[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Areshchenko, Alexander vs. Akbarinia, Syed Arash"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/1b3ppp/p2ppn2/1pn3B1/3NP3/1BN5/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bd5 { White begins with a bishop sacrifice at the approved location. } 1...
b4
{ Asking for it a bit.  Taking the offer doesn't promise Black great success.   11...exd5  12.exd5+  Kd7   12...Be7  simply doesn't work at all because White regains the material with interest after  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Nf5  .  13.b4 !  There's no logical retreat for the c5-knight.  Na4  14.Nxa4  bxa4  15.c4  A nice move with a dual point: White protects his d5-pawn and simultaneously threatens Qxa4+.  Kc7  16.Qxa4  White has a virtually won game in spite of still not having regained the piece; this all happened in Beliavsky-Marjanovic, 1971. }
2. Bxb7 Nxb7 3. Nd5
{ The second sacrifice on the same square ! This one can hardly be declined, because Black would end up in a real mess if he did. }
3... exd5
{ Protecting the b4-pawn lets White show his second threat:   13...a5  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Nc6  and White wins due to a cute mate:  Qc8  16.Nxf6#   13...Rc8  stops the idea of Nc6, but Black's development is too poor to defend against all the threats.  14.Qf3 !  This strong move threatens 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. Bxf6, thus  Be7  is forced.  15.Nxe7  Qxe7  Apparently Black has things basically covered, but now there comes:  16.Nf5 !  and now everything falls apart for Black.  Qf8  Now, with the help of an engine one can find the most mathematically precise path:  17.e5 !  Nothing wrong with   17.Nxg7+  either.  17...Nd5  18.Rad1  and the attack is decisive. }
4. exd5+ Kd7 5. c3
{ Now   15.Nc6  would also be quite a respectable way to continue. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Areshchenko, Alexander vs. Akbarinia, Syed Arash"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4b1r/1n1k1ppp/p2p1n2/q2P2B1/1p1N4/2P5/PP3PPP/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxf6 gxf6 2. cxb4
{ Even better is   17.Nc6  Qb5  18.cxb4  when the Black king has no way to leave the centre. }
2... Qxd5
{ The floodgates are also opened wide after   17...Qxb4  :  18.Rc1   18.Qg4+  Kc7  19.Ne6+  18...Nc5  19.Qg4+  f5   19...Kc7  20.Ne6+  followed by Qxb4 wins the queen  20.Qxf5+  Kc7  21.Nc6  Qxb2  22.Qxf7+  with a won game. }
3. Qa4+ Kc7 4. Rac1+ Nc5
{ Beginning to haemorrhage material in an already lost position. One might as well resign here.   19...Kb8  offers no respite because of  20.Nc6+  Kc7  21.Ne7+  picking up the queen  Meanwhile   19...Kb6  20.Rc6+  Ka7  21.Qxa6+  Kb8  22.Re8+  is simply mate. }
5. bxc5 dxc5
{ White has his piece back, while the black king is still in terrible trouble. None of Black's pieces, apart from the queen, play any role whatsoever. It is simply a case of force majeure, and the remainder of the drama unfolded in the expected manner, with no surprises. }
6. Red1 Rg8 7. g3 Kb6 8. Nb3 Qh5 9. Rd7 Rc8 10. Qa5+ Kc6 11. Rcd1 Qe2 12. Nd4+
cxd4 13. Qd5+ Kb6 14. Rb7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Morozevich, Alexander vs. Kasparov, Garry, Astana, 2001"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 8. O-O
Be7 9. Qf3
{ Gaining a tempo with which to route the queen to a square where it points at the Black king, by virtue of the present threat of e4-e5. }
9... Qc7
{ It goes without saying that Black must beware of the standard sacrifices.   9...Bb7  , for instance, fails to  10.Bxe6 !  fxe6  11.Nxe6  Qd7  12.Nxg7+  when White has three pawns for the piece and a strong attack against the Black king. }
10. Qg3 O-O 11. Bh6
{ White keeps developing at pace, gaining tempo wherever possible. } 11... Ne8
12. Rad1 Bd7
{ Black needs to keep playing carefully.  The apparently normal   12...Nc6  leads to some issues.  13.Nd5 !?  exd5   13...Nxd4  14.Nxe7+  Qxe7  15.Rxd4  is better for White.  14.Nxc6  dxe4  15.Nxe7+  Qxe7  16.Bg5  Qd7  17.Qh4  and this is rather unappetizing for Black. }
13. f4
{ The most logical development of the initiative.  An alternative is   13.Nf3  , known since the 1993 games Kasparov-Gelfand and Short-Kasparov  (WC, 18th game.)  Meanwhile in the 20th game- Short's next White game in that match- he chose   13.a3  . }
13... Nc6 14. f5
{ Almost always the idea in this variation. White would like to encourage the e6-pawn to advance. }
14... Nxd4 15. Rxd4
{ Black has avoided the tactics on e6 but still has to be careful. There are now some tricks involving the g7-square in the position, sometimes using a rook lift: e4-e5 and Rd4-g4. }
15... Bf6
{ Kasparov secures his position against that entire class of tactical motifs. }
16. Rd3 Be5
{ A new move at the time of this game. Kasparov stops the possibility of e4-e5 pawn sacrifices.  After   16...b4  Kasparov feared  17.fxe6  fxe6  18.e5  Here   18.Nd5 ?  doesn't work because after  exd5  19.Bxd5+  Kh8  20.Bxa8  the bishop on h6 hangs-  gxh6  and Black is much better, with two pieces for the rook and superior control of the dark squares.  18...Bxe5  19.Rxf8+  Kxf8  20.Qf3+  Bf6  21.Ne4  with roughly equal chances.  Like 18. Nd5,   21.Qxa8 ?  leads to a material advantage for Black after  bxc3  22.bxc3  gxh6  . }
17. Qg4 b4 { Not a moment too soon. } 18. f6
{ Looks strong, but Kasparov has an answer ready.  The intermezzo   18.fxe6  is not so good for White.  Bxe6 !  19.Bxe6  and now Black can reply to White's intended 'clever' move  bxc3  20.Bd5  with his own:  Qc8 ! }
18... g6
{ This exchange sacrifice puts an end to White's kingside initiative and signals the beginning of Black's counter on the queenside. }
19. Ne2
{ All in all, it still seems that white will remain in charge somehow. Because can't he still prepare an attack against the black king with Qh4 and Rh3 ?  It seems like   19.Nd1 !?  is more of the same after  a5 }
19... a5 { Black's strategic idea is that the b3-bishop is in jeopardy. } 20.
Bxf8
{ Taking the material that Black is offering without delay.  After   20.Qh4  a4  White's attack might not be so successful as he originally thought.  21.Bxf8  The previously indicated idea of   21.Rh3  axb3  22.Bxf8  can be met with  h5  23.Qg5  bxa2  and it turns out that White doesn't have the slightest possibility of threatening mate.  21...axb3  22.Qh6  Bxf6 !  But despite the favourable evaluation, Black still needs to show vigilance.  If he were to take the a-pawn now, there would arise a mating net of rare elegance:   22...bxa2  23.Rh3 !  Bxf6  and now the genuinely amazing  24.Be7 !!  when mate can no longer be prevented !  23.Rxf6  White's attack looks impressive, but Black has the ice-cold  Qa7+ !  24.Re3  bxa2  25.Rf1  a1=Q  26.Rxa1  Qxa1+  27.Kf2  Qxb2  when he has managed to fend off the attack and remains with a  (likely decisive)  material advantage. }
20... Kxf8 21. Qh4 a4
{ Kasparov simply ignores the threats near his king and continues along the path to which he has already committed. }
22. Qxh7 Qa7+
{ Looks perfectly logical, but this wasn't the most precise move. The queen voluntarily stops attacking the c4-square, giving White's bishop an 'out'. And there was as yet no particular need to protect the rook on a8.  The direct   22...Nxf6 !  23.Qh8+  Ng8  is a much better idea: Black wins a second piece for his rook and stands clearly better. }
23. Kh1 Nxf6
{ Kasparov can see that the king is very safe on e7 and that his fantastic bishop on e5 offers great compensation for the missing exchange. }
24. Qh6+ Ke7 25. Bc4 Qc5 26. b3 axb3 27. Bxb3
{ The bishop is now very secure on b3, but the white pawn structure is terribly weakened. In addition, he loses control of the diagonal f1-a6 and black now makes good use of it.  The normal move is   27.axb3 !  . Surely the problem  (or so White thought)  is that Black has the possibliity of trapping White's bishop:  d5  -but then White has another amazing tactic to level the material and even come out on top.  28.Qg5 !  dxc4  29.Rd5 !!  A master stroke !  exd5  30.Qxe5+  -with Qxf6 to follow. }
27... Bb5 { Black's bishop pair starts to come into its own. } 28. Nf4
{ Morozevich goes to war with the courage of despair. He is prepared to sacrifice the exchange to generate counterplay based on sacrifices on e6 or g6.  It is not mandatory to give back the exchange. After the passive   28.Rd2  , however, Black has quite a nice idea:  Rg8 !  Very precise. Black wants to cut off White's queen from the rest of his forces by playing ...g6-g5. Thereafter, ideas like ...Qe3 and . ..Ng4, especially taken together, will have lethal effect. }
28... Bxf4
{ Kasparov need not have taken the sacrifice on g6 that seriously. It was rare for him to 'believe' his opponents this much ! Turns out he would have won rather easily in case of   28...Bxd3  29.Nxg6+ ?  fxg6  30.Qg7+  Kd8  31.Qf8+  Kc7  32.Qxa8  Bxf1  when the position is simply won. }
29. Qxf4 Qe5
{ Black is playing a very aesthetic concept, but objectively his chances are no better than equal ! }
30. h3
{ Not particularly accurate.  The better way to give the king breathing room was   30.Qf2  Rh8  31.h3  maintaining equality. }
30... g5
{ The point of the last note was to avoid the queen swap- after   30...Qxf4  31.Rxf4  Bxd3  32.cxd3  Black has ample winning chances in the endgame, say with  g5  33.Rf3  Ra5 }
31. Qf2
{ Trading queens the other way also gives Black good winning chances:   31.Qxe5  dxe5  32.Rc1  Bxd3  33.cxd3  Nh5  and White's bishop on b3 is not functioning well. }
31... g4 32. Qb6
{ Black had to see that after   32.Qxf6+  Qxf6  33.Rxf6  Kxf6  34.Rxd6  g3  White's king is entombed and so he is toast. }
32... Nd7 33. Qf2 Nf6 34. Qb6 Rh8
{ Here the ex-world champion makes a genuine mistake.  The moment for the trade was now:   34...Bxd3  and after  35.cxd3  Rh8  Black is doing well. }
35. Rxd6
{ A good idea in the wrong order. In all likelihood it was time trouble that prevented Morozevich from seeing how he could have saved half a point.  He had to first insert   35.Qc7+  Nd7  and only then play  36.Rxd6 !  Black cannot take either rook, so must resort to kitchen-sink tactics:  Rxh3+  The point is that   36...Qxd6 ?  loses the queen and the game to  37.Rxf7+  Kxf7  38.Qxd6  .  37.gxh3  Qxe4+  38.Kg1   38.Kh2 ?  Qe2+  38...Qe3+  39.Rf2  Qe1+   39...g3  40.Rdd2  40.Kg2  Qe4+  Black has nothing better than to repeat moves. }
35... Qxd6 36. Qxd6+
{ One problem is that Black wins after the plausible   36.Qxb5 ?!  gxh3  37.e5 ?  (other moves are no help either)  hxg2+  38.Kxg2  Qd2+  with mate. }
36... Kxd6 37. Rxf6 Rh7
{ In the endgame you have to be careful with your material !  After   37...gxh3  38.Rxf7  Bc6  39.Rf6  hxg2+  40.Kxg2  Bxe4+  41.Kg3  Bf5  a draw is the most likely result. }
38. Kh2 Ke5
{ This is the problem for white. The black king is supreme in the center and when the e4-pawn inevitably falls, his central pawn formation will be strong as well. }
39. Rf2 gxh3 40. gxh3 Bc6
{ Black chooses to take on e4 with the bishop so that it immediately acts as a sort of shelter for the far-advanced king. It is striking here how important the pawn structure is. White has two isolated pawns on a2 and c2, which are controlled by a single Black pawn on b4. In addition, White's runner has become a kind of 'monument' that is barely participating in the battle. }
41. Bc4
{ A nice variation is   41.Re2  Bxe4  42.c3  trying to introduce a trick into the position. However, Black can simply 'fall for it':  bxc3 !  43.Rxe4+  Kxe4  44.Bc2+  Ke3  45.Bxh7  and after  f5  there is no way to stop the c3-pawn from queening. }
41... Bxe4 42. Re2 { But now Rxe4 is a real threat, of course. } 42... f5 43.
Bd3
{ This still seems worthwhile to do because it threatens to double Black's central passed pawns. }
43... Kf4
{ Given how strong the front e-pawn is going to become, Kasparov elects to allow the doubling of the pawns.   43...Rh4  44.Kg3  Rf4  45.h4  Rg4+  46.Kh3  was another possibility. }
44. Bxe4 fxe4 45. Rf2+ Ke3
{ There is a stark difference in king activity between the two sides. } 46. Rf8
e5 47. Re8 Rc7 48. Rxe5 Kf4 49. Rb5 Rxc2+ 50. Kg1 e3 51. Rxb4+ Kf3
{ In the meantime, black has actually lost a pawn. But that pawn has no meaning whatsoever, while the e3-pawn is now so far advanced that it can't be stopped. }
52. Rb1
{ The thematic winning method of driving the White king as far as possible from the passed pawn is illustrated here:   52.Rb8  Rc1+  53.Kh2  e2  54.Rf8+  Ke3  55.Re8+  Kd3  56.Rd8+  Kc3  57.Rc8+  Kb2  Escaping from the checks at last.  58.Re8   58.Rb8+  Kxa2  59.Ra8+  Kb3  60.Rb8+  and now Black 'zigzags' up the a- and b- files with his king until the checks are exhausted.  58...e1=Q  59.Rxe1  Rxe1  60.Kg3  Now Black would have had to find a strong and instructive move:  Re4 !  The 'fourth-rank cutoff' is key when you want to stop a passed pawn using only a rook. After  (for instance)  61.h4  Kxa2  62.h5  Kb3  White can no longer push the pawn without losing it, and his king remains cut off, so the position is lost. }
52... Rg2+ 53. Kh1 e2 54. a4 Kf2 55. a5 Rg5 56. Kh2
{ 56.a6  Ra5  57.Kh2  Rxa6  also wins. } 56... Rxa5 57. h4 Ra3
{ White's king is once again cut off from supporting his passed pawn. He realised that there is no longer any way to stop ...e1=Q. }
*

