[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Ivanchuk, Vassily, Linares, 1991."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Be7 8. Bb3
O-O 9. f4 b5 10. f5
{ As we already know, this move is the most thematic one for White, but that's not necessarily the same thing as being the best.  Here   10.e5  is seen as the most important option.   10.a3  also has considerable support. }
10... b4
{ Prodding the knight away from its vigil over the d5-square, in preparation for the otherwise rather weakening ...e5 push.   That being said, after   10...e5  11.Nde2  Bb7  12.Ng3  Nbd7  White's control over d5 isn't 'set in stone' and Black should be able to hold things together. }
11. Na4
{ Not for nothing do they say that 'a knight on the rim is dim'.  A line known since the time of Fischer was   11.Nce2  e5  12.Nf3  Bb7  13.Ng3  Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Qe1  Bxf3  16.Rxf3  Nc6  and White had obtained full compensation for the offered pawn in Fischer-Smyslov, 1959. }
11... e5 12. Ne2 Bb7 13. Ng3 Nbd7 14. Qe1
{ This move does not seem to be worth repeating.   14.Qf3  is played more often, for instance in Muller-Hoffmann, 1994, but also in this game things did not end well with the white player. }
14... a5 15. c4 Qc7 16. Qe2 Rfc8 17. Bg5
{ It looks to be the case that white's biggest problem is his terrible knight on a4. But strangely enough, it is not clear at the moment how black can benefit from this, and since the knight arrived there the position has evolved somewhat. That is why Ivanchuk takes a different approach. }
17... Nc5
{ Another move that came into consideration was   17...h6  intending to sideline another of White's minor pieces. After  18.Bh4  Bd8  19.Rad1  Bc6  White faces very significant problems. }
18. Rac1
{ Despite the knight trade being technically on the table, White will not be freed of his burdensome beast quite so easily.   18.Nxc5  Qxc5+  19.Kh1  a4  sees Black win the c4-pawn. }
18... h6
{ Ivanchuk found the gain of a pawn with   18...Bxe4  19.Nxe4  Ncxe4  to be insufficiently attractive. In fact, White has fair compensation after  20.Be3  . }
19. Be3
{ Maybe-despite the massive concession which trading off the dark-squared bishop usually is- White had to opt for   19.Bxf6 !? }
19... Ncd7
{ The knight returns whence it came, now that White no longer has his pin on the h4-d8 diagonal.   19...Bc6  is rather placid, and after  20.Nxc5  dxc5  21.Bc2 =  White has equalised the game again. }
20. Bf2 Ra6
{ Black comes up with an interesting concept. The a8-square is being reserved for his queen. }
21. Rc2 Qb8 22. Re1 Qa8 23. Qd3
{ Anand does not recognize the danger.  White would have been better served by staying in 'waiting' mode, for instance with   23.h3 }
23... Ng4
{ That is suddenly possible and that means that white has to part with his bishop. }
24. Nf1
{ Strategically speaking, this is like rolling over and dying.  White still had some counterplay after   24.Nh5  Nxf2  25.Rxf2  Bf8  . }
24... Ndf6 25. Nd2
{ To the ambitious attempt to keep the bishop alive with   25.Bh4  there is of course a refutation:  Bxe4 !  26.Rxe4  Nxe4  27.Bxe7  Qa7+  and Black wins the house. }
25... Nxf2 26. Kxf2 Bc6
{ Not the best order.  Even stronger was   26...Qa7+ !  27.Kf1  Bc6  introducing a new threat of ... Qd7 into the position and ganging up on the beleaguered a4-knight. }
27. Rcc1
{ Anand sees that ...Qa7-d7 is still an idea, and prepares Qd3-c2 to cover the weak knight. His is not a luxurious existence right now.  On   27.Kg1  follows  Ng4  with the threat of ...Qa7+. }
27... Qa7+ 28. Ke2 Rd8
{ Ivanchuk manoeuvres his pieces to the positions where they have greatest prospects. }
29. Bd1
{ Now that the white king has encamped in the center and the white pieces are in each other's way, Ivanchuk thinks it's time to forcefully break open the center. }
29... d5 { Nicely seen ! } 30. cxd5
{ Likewise after   30.exd5  Black would take twice on d5-  Nxd5  31.cxd5  Rxd5 }
30... Nxd5 31. exd5 Rxd5 32. Qb3
{ The queen faced an odd shortage of safe squares. } 32... Bg5 33. Rc2 Bxd2
{ After   33...Bxd2  34.Rxd2  Bb5+  35.Kf3  Rxd2  not only does Black have a material superiority, but his attack is also unstoppable. }
*

