[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Planinc, Albin vs. Najdorf, Miguel, Wijk aan Zee, 1973"]
[Result "*"]

{ Before commencing with this part, I would like to say a few words about I my senior in school, Huub van Dongen, who gave me chess tutoring in my early years because he wanted to boost the strength of the team. To that end we began looking together at this most serious of openings, the Najdorf Sicilian. We analysed the positions thoroughly, fascinated by the many beautiful and unexpected tactical twists that this opening offered. And although we sometimes suffered heavy defeats in this line, we did not let ourselves get discouraged by them. Just as later in our careers we had to take bitter disappointments in our stride, at that time we allowed the appreciation of chess beauty to trump our ego.   In the case of Huub, it was not difficult because results were less important to him than the creation of a particular aesthetic impression. He died too young, though. I penned an obituary about him  (in Dutch)  at http: //@@LinkStart@@www.schaaksite@@LinkEnd@@. nl / 2011/07/22 / portret-van-duizendpoot-huub-van-dongen. Likewise, he is remembered in an annual memorial event, which recently assumed its rightful venue in his hometown: @@LinkStart@@http://www.schaaksite.nl/2016/07/07/@@LinkEnd@@ kunstzinnige-editie-huub-van-dongen-memorial-prooi-voor-manuel-bosboom . The 2016 edition was won by Manuel Bosboom, another creative spirit of the chess world whose brain overflows with brilliant ideas. Huub and I analysed the game which follows in the early years of our comradeship. It was a revelation to both of us and probably best described as a 'roller coaster ride'. The Black player was, of course, Najdorf himself: born in Poland in 1910, but best known as an Argentinian player since he moved there at the outbreak of the Second World War.   Originally his first name was Mieczyslaw, but when he adopted his new citizenship in 1944 he changed his name to Miguel. While he did belong to the world elite for some time, his main claim to fame ended up being the opening to which our book is devoted. Najdorf died in 1997. The White player in this game is perhaps less well known outside of his home region. Albin Planinc  (1944 - 2008)  was born in Slovenia. His best result was probably the shared first place with Petrosian in Amsterdam 1973. In Nice 1974, his last olympiad with Yugoslavia, he won the silver medal with his team.   He departed suddenly from the chess world, but what is known is that he suffered from depression throughout his life, spending his last years in a psychiatric ward in Ljubljana because of it. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7
{ Normally, to reach the game position after 7 moves, people start with   6...e6  which can lead after  7.f4  to the Poisoned Pawn Variation:  Qb6  8.Qd2  Qxb2  9.Rb1  Qa3  10.f5  etc. with complications and heavy theory. }
7. f4 e6 8. Qf3
{ This is the purpose of White's set-up. He strives for a fast O-O-O, after which he can commence central actions. }
8... Be7 9. O-O-O Qc7 10. Bd3
{ 10.g4  is the alternative, which is played slightly more often. } 10... h6
{ We can transpose to the line we have as the main one in the introduction after:   10...b5  11.Rhe1  Meanwhile the sacrifice   11.e5  Bb7  12.Qh3  dxe5  13.Nxe6 ?!  will not be successful after  fxe6  14.Bxf6  Nxf6  15.Qxe6  and now the strongest continuation  e4 !  11...Bb7  Diagram We saw that in this position many contemporary players were interested in the possibility of a knight sacrifice on d5.  12.Nd5 !?  We will spare you the variations for now. The remarkable thing is that Fischer accepted the risk of entering all this with Black in the World Championship match in Reykjavik against defending champion Spassky. However, Spassky did not go for the sacrifice.  To remind you, the world championship match game was drawn after Spassky's   12.Qg3  . }
11. Qh3
{ This is the second most common move. White pins the h6-pawn, but the disadvantage is that now her majesty finds herself on the same diagonal as Black's c8-bishop.  After   11.Bh4  Black answers with  g5 !?  offering a timely pawn sacrifice to obtain the strong e5-post for his knight.  12.fxg5  Ne5  The knight will be unshakeable here.  13.Qe2  Nfg4  14.Nf3  hxg5  15.Bg3  After   15.Bxg5  Bxg5+  16.Nxg5  Qc5 !  it is known that Black has great compensation.  15...Bd7  An exciting position has arisen in which both players have opportunities. }
11... Nc5 { 11...hxg5 ??  12.Qxh8+ } 12. Rhe1 Rg8
{ Black gives up the right to short castling; that's the price of resolving the pin along the h-file.  In comparison with the previous note, here it is clear that   12...e5  does not work so well because after  13.Nf5  Bxf5  14.exf5  O-O-O  White is in a position to answer by swapping off the only defender of the d5-square:  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Nd5  Black faces problems here because it will take a while to deal with the issue of the d5-knight.  Unsurprisingly,   12...O-O ?  runs into  13.Bxh6  gxh6  14.Qxh6  when White's attack is not far from crashing through.  The best move was probably the calm   12...Bd7 }
13. e5 { This is the beginning of a powerful attack from White. } 13... dxe5
{ Bad is   13...hxg5  14.exf6  gxf6 ?  Meanwhile,   14...Bxf6  15.Bh7  Rh8  leads to similar developments as in the main game. White has excellent prospects here after  16.Nd5 !  15.Qh7 !  Rf8  16.fxg5  fxg5  17.Nf5 !  With this move, White cracks open the central defences and wins. }
14. fxe5 hxg5
{ After   14...Nd5  there follows  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  whereupon Planinc himself gave  16.Bh7  Better may well be   16.Nxd5  exd5  17.Bf5  when White is positionally winning; the Black pieces cannot develop or co-ordinate in any meaningful sense.  16...Rh8  Maybe ...Nxc3 offered better chances.  17.Nf5 !  Qg5+   17...exf5  18.Nxd5  is simply winning.  18.Rd2  Rxh7  19.Nd6+  Kf8  20.Nxd5  exd5  21.Nxc8  when White has a huge positional advantage- and soon also an extra pawn. }
15. exf6 Bxf6
{ Better, but by no means trouble-free was:   15...gxf6  when after  16.Kb1 !  White develops a strong attack. This move defends the pawn at a2 and prevents a possible future ...Qf4 from being check.  Bd7 !?  The best practical try.  Exchanging minor pieces is less good:   16...Nxd3  17.Rxd3  e5  18.Qh7  Kf8  19.Nd5  Qa5  20.Rdd1  White's position is overwhelming, and computers indicate that Black in fact needs to huddle and hope with a queen sacrifice:  Qxd5  21.Nf5  Bxf5   21...Qe6  22.Nh6  wins the house   21...Qxd1+  22.Rxd1  Bxf5  23.Qxf5  is similar, but perhaps having a rook isn't as good as having a bishop for Black here.  22.Qh6+  Rg7  23.Rxd5  The game will continue, but Black should be lost.  17.Bh7  g4 !   17...Rh8  18.Nf5  is curtains- Black's best is to castle and leave the e7-bishop to its fate.  18.Nd5 !  White wins the exchange anyway, although Black has a pawn and some chances. }
16. Nd5 Qd8 17. Bh7
{ This original move unleashes the power of the d1-rook with gain of tempo. Also there comes into the picture the idea of a 'queen lift' along the third rank- to c3 or a3. But if Black had now found the only defense, White would have found that he had lost his advantage.  With hindsight it seems like   17.Bc4 !?  was the best move.  However after  Bxd4  Not   17...Kf8 ?  18.Nxf6  Qxf6  19.Qa3 !  with a simple win.  White has to find  18.Qg3 !  when Black is lucky to not simply be dead, e.g.  Kf8  19.Rxd4  g6 !  White's attack continues, but maybe he got here and didn't find anything too conclusive.   17.Bb5+ ?  on the other hand simply doesn't work because of a counterpunch:  axb5  18.Nxb5  and now  Rxa2 !  19.Ndc7+  Ke7  20.Rxd8  Rxd8  and Black is winning.  Possible, however, is   17.Qh7 !?  Nxd3+  18.Rxd3 !   18.Kb1  is met by the hardly surprising  Qxd5 !   18...Rf8 ?  19.Nxf6+  gxf6  20.Rxd3  with a large advantage for White.  19.Qxg8+  Ke7  Black gets decent counterplay.  18...Kf8  19.Nxf6  Qxf6  20.Rf3 !  White has a safe advantage and continuing attack. }
17... Rh8
{ Fortunately for the spectators, Black fails to find the most accurate defence.   As in some of the above notes, Black had to sacrifice an exchange:   17...Qxd5 !  18.Bxg8  Qxa2 !  The white king now finds itself under threat as well, so it seems the chances are balanced.  Also possible is   18...Bxd4  which leads after  19.Qh5  Bd7 !   19...g6  20.Qh7  doesn't help  20.Qxf7+  to an advantage for White, however the damage is not as bad as it might seem.  Kd8  21.Qf8+  Kc7  22.Qxa8  Na4  Black has good counterplay for his material.  Now a major point for Black is that he can answer  19.Qh5  with  e5 !  defending the f7-pawn with the queen, whose reach extends all the way back from a2 ! }
18. Nf5
{ A great move after which there is no doubt about the storm clouds descending on the Black king. The aesthetic appeal of having knights 'hanging' on d5 or f5 is one of the biggest factors leading to some White players massively enjoying playing against the Sicilian. }
18... g4
{ Played after a long think. There is no real solution to Black's problems now.  After   18...Kf8  19.Nxf6   19.Qa3 ?  b6  is simply a brick wall: with three pieces hanging White needs something to work now, but nothing does.  19...Qxf6  there is the extremely strong overloading move  20.Qc3 !  White threatens the knight on c5, but also the Black queen on f6 has a duty to prevent mate on d8, which would follow in case of a queen trade on either c3 or f6.  Nd7   20...Qxc3  21.Rd8#   20...Rxh7  21.Qxf6  gxf6  22.Rd8#   20...b6  21.Qxf6  gxf6  22.Rd8#  21.Qb4+  Ke8  Diagram  22.Rxe6+ !!  Normally, I wouldn't bother showing the concluding fireworks in such a winning position, but this is especially nice !  fxe6  Diagram   22...Qxe6  23.Nxg7+  23.Bg6+ !  This is the point. Mate is inevitable.  Kd8   23...Qxg6  24.Qe7#  24.Qb6# }
19. Qg3
{ Good, but not quite best.   19.Qe3  We can forgive White for missing this slightly stronger move. }
19... Kf8
{ 19...Rxh7 ?  loses the queen to  20.Nc7+   19...Bd7  20.Nc7+  Kf8  21.Nxa8  Rxh7   21...exf5  22.Bxf5  with continuing threats.  22.Qd6+ !  Black will not get a second piece for the rook, and neither will he manage to get into an ending. For instance:  Be7  23.Nxe7  Qxe7  24.Qb8+  Qe8  25.Qc7  winning. }
20. Nxf6
{ The conclusion of this game could have been this standard overloading motif:   20.Nxf6  Qxf6  21.Qd6+  Ke8  22.Nxg7+ !  Qxg7  23.Qd8# }
*

