[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Velimirovic, Dragoljub vs. Ljubojevic, Ljubomir, Umag, 1972"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4
{ In the set-ups  (collectively referred to as the Three Piece System)  where Black continues with ... Nbd7, ... Qc7, ... b5 and ... Bb7, it is wise to postpone the final developing move ...Be7 for as long as possible. This is because in case of knight sacrifices on f5 or d5, a near-automatic follow up for White will be swinging the other knight in, with gain of tempo against Black's dark-squared bishop- which will often just have to retreat. }
7... Be7
{ 7...Nbd7  8.Qf3  Qc7  9.O-O-O  b5  10.Bd3  Bb7  11.Rhe1  Now Black would get the same position as in our main game if he chose ...Be7. But herein lies the difference: modern theory generally holds that a superior choice now is  Qb6  , for details of which see the next game: Shirov-Anand, 2008. }
8. Qf3 Qc7 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. Bd3 b5 11. Rhe1 Bb7 12. Nd5
{ This bold knight sacrifice was extensively researched in the 1970s. It looks dangerous and Black must be well prepared to withstand the onslaught. The correctness of the sacrifice, however, was doubted even then, as we can tell from the fact that Bobby Fischer invited this sacrifice in the famous World Cup match against Spassky.  Fischer was, it seems, willing to collect the material and then rely on his defense skills.  Computer analysis in the modern era bears out the natural suspicion. But nevertheless, Black faces very definite dangers if he accepts a sacrifice like this one. }
12... Nxd5
{ Let's look at the most principled move   12...exd5  .  For a long time it was thought that White had to play  13.Nf5 ?!  but Black, in this line just like the other, has enough resources to defend.   13.exd5  Kf8 !  14.Nf5  Bd8  15.Qg3  The threat is Bh6 with mate, but  Rg8 !  is enough to repulse the attack.  16.Nxg7  Rxg7  17.Bh6  Nh5 !  and Black is better.  13...Kf8 !  Now White seems to have nothing better than taking on d5, leading to the just-analysed 13. exd5 line.  However,   13...dxe4 ?!  is dangerous.  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Rxe4  Bxe4   15...O-O  16.Nxe7+  Kh8  17.Nd5  is a plus for White, but still the lesser evil, perhaps.  16.Qxe4  O-O  17.Nxe7+  Kh8  18.Rd3 !?  White brings another piece into the attack and threatens to set up Anastasia's mate with Qxh7+ !  Now ...h6 runs into a devastating sacrifice on the same square, while  g6  is strongly met by the geometrically satisfying  19.Rh3  Qc5  20.Qe1 !  with the deadly threat of Rxh7+ ! }
13. exd5 Bxg5
{ It is important to see what happens after   13...Bxd5  : White can use the complexities of the e-file pins in his favour with a bolt from the blue.  14.Nxe6 !!  Also quite satisfying is   14.Qxd5 !  exd5  15.Rxe7+  Kf8  16.Bf5  .This works due to the follow-up  Rd8  17.Be6 !  which, however, White has to see from quite some distance away.  14...fxe6  15.Qh5+  Kf8  16.Bxe7+  Kxe7  17.Qxd5  White has recovered his piece while retaining a decisive attack. }
14. Rxe6+
{ Velimirovic was not known for his circumspection ! Objectively, this is maybe not the best move, but in a practical game such a sacrifice would definitely have a significant psychological impact on the opponent.  From an objective standpoint,   14.fxg5  was better, when after the thematic and relatively obvious  Ne5 !  Black can stay in the game. }
14... fxe6 15. Nxe6 Qa5
{ This, however, is not correct.  Black should have chosen the other square for Her Majesty.   15...Qb6 !  16.Qh5+  g6  17.Qxg5   17.Bxg6+  Ke7 !  18.Qxg5+  Nf6  -+  Now the point is  17...Qe3+ !  which is a very important 'intermezzo'. After this insertion Black has almost permanently prevented a White rook from appearing on the e-file. }
16. Qh5+ g6 17. Qxg5 Rg8 18. Rd2
{ Now that White has activated almost every piece, the question remains of how the last piece  (the rook)  is coming into play. Had Black played his queen to b6 on the last move, there wouldn't be any way to do this, but now White has a choice of methods. As it transpires, White needs the rook on both the e- and f-files.  The better way was with   18.c3 !  so that after the logical  Kf7  White can continue to persecute the Black king in its new home, still using the rook:  19.Rf1  with a winning position. There is no way to prevent f4-f5, e.g.  Qb6  20.f5  and the White attack is too strong. }
18... Nf8
{ A second mistake, but it is a well-known fact that players who are under pressure often go wrong.  The only move was   18...Kf7 !  Now play continues:  19.Re2  Here lies the point of my last note: after   19.Rf2 ??  White would face the rude shock of  Qe1#  ...  19...Nf6  when Black is holding the balance- and White should begin thinking of convincing reasons why he is a rook down. }
19. Nxf8 Qd8 { 19...Rxf8  20.Re2+  Kd7  21.Qe7+  is lights out. } 20. Nxh7
{ It is nothing short of a minor miracle that White has enough material to be fine with a queen trade. In what follows, his kingside pawn phalanx basically steamrollers Black. }
20... Qxg5 21. fxg5
{ This is the point: White retains the d5-pawn and gets to station his knight on the favourable f6-square. }
21... Kf7 22. Nf6 Rh8 23. g3 Bc8 24. h4 Bf5 25. Bxf5 gxf5 26. h5 Ra7 27. Rf2
{ Here Black gave up the ghost, seeing that he was about to be buried alive by White's kingside pawn armada. }
*

