1. Nd5
{ This bold knight sacrifice was extensively researched in the 1970s. It looks dangerous and Black must be well prepared to withstand the onslaught. The correctness of the sacrifice, however, was doubted even then, as we can tell from the fact that Bobby Fischer invited this sacrifice in the famous World Cup match against Spassky.  Fischer was, it seems, willing to collect the material and then rely on his defense skills.  Computer analysis in the modern era bears out the natural suspicion. But nevertheless, Black faces very definite dangers if he accepts a sacrifice like this one. }
1... Nxd5
{ Let's look at the most principled move   12...exd5  . For a long time it was thought that White had to play  13.Nf5 ?!  but Black, in this line just like the other, has enough resources to defend.   13.exd5  Kf8 !  14.Nf5  Bd8  15.Qg3  The threat is Bh6 with mate, but  Rg8 !  is enough to repulse the attack.  16.Nxg7  Rxg7  17.Bh6  Nh5 !  and Black is better.  13...Kf8 !  Now White seems to have nothing better than taking on d5, leading to the just-analysed 13. exd5 line.  However,   13...dxe4 ?!  is dangerous.  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Rxe4  Bxe4   15...O-O  16.Nxe7+  Kh8  17.Nd5  is a plus for White, but still the lesser evil, perhaps.  16.Qxe4  O-O  17.Nxe7+  Kh8  18.Rd3 !?  White brings another piece into the attack and threatens to set up Anastasia's mate with Qxh7+ ! Now ...h6 runs into a devastating sacrifice on the same square, while  g6  is strongly met by the geometrically satisfying  19.Rh3  Qc5  20.Qe1 !  with the deadly threat of Rxh7+ ! }
2. exd5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Velimirovic, Dragoljub vs. Ljubojevic, Ljubomir"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1bqn1ppp/p2pp3/1p1P2b1/3N1P2/3B1Q2/PPP3PP/2KRR3 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rxe6+
{ Velimirovic was not known for his circumspection ! Objectively, this is maybe not the best move, but in a practical game such a sacrifice would definitely have a significant psychological impact on the opponent.  From an objective standpoint,   14.fxg5  was better, when after the thematic and relatively obvious  Ne5 !  Black can stay in the game. }
1... fxe6 2. Nxe6 Qa5
{ This, however, is not correct.  Black should have chosen the other square for Her Majesty.   15...Qb6 !  16.Qh5+  g6  17.Qxg5  Now the point is   17.Bxg6+  Ke7 !  18.Qxg5+  Nf6  -+  17...Qe3+ !  which is a very important 'intermezzo'. After this insertion Black has almost permanently prevented a White rook from appearing on the e-file. }
3. Qh5+ g6 4. Qxg5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Velimirovic, Dragoljub vs. Ljubojevic, Ljubomir"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkNr1/1b5p/p2p2p1/1p1P2Q1/5P2/3B4/PPPR2PP/2K5 w q - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxh7
{ It is nothing short of a minor miracle that White has enough material to be fine with a queen trade. In what follows, his kingside pawn phalanx basically steamrollers Black. }
1... Qxg5 2. fxg5
{ This is the point: White retains the d5-pawn and gets to station his knight on the favourable f6-square. }
2... Kf7 3. Nf6 Rh8 4. g3 Bc8 5. h4 Bf5 6. Bxf5 gxf5 7. h5 Ra7 8. Rf2
{ Here Black gave up the ghost, seeing that he was about to be buried alive by White's kingside pawn armada. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Shirov, Alexei vs. Anand, Viswanathan, Morelia/Linares, 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Nbd7 8. Qf3
Qc7 9. O-O-O b5 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. Rhe1 Qb6
{ Detailed and sustained analysis has shown that Black should wait a while before developing the f8-bishop. He chooses to do something with the time- attacking White's knight on d4. }
12. Nb3
{ It is still instructive to look at the typical knight sacrifice   12.Nd5 !?  which Black is best advised to take.  exd5  Worse is   12...Qxd4 ?  in view of  13.Bxf6 !  gxf6  14.Bxb5  .Now after  Qc5  15.b4  Black's main choice now is how  (rather than if)  he should give up his queen.  Qxb5 !   15...Qc8 ??  16.Bxd7+ !  wins the queen for only two pieces.   15...Qa7  16.Nxf6+  Ke7  17.Bxd7  regains a piece with a continuing initiative, although the position is still quite messy.  16.Nc7+  Ke7  17.Nxb5  axb5  White seems to have an advantage here, although the situation is never clear when we deal with the material imbalance of three pieces for a queen.  13.Nc6 !?  An imaginative pseudo-sacrifice, inverting the move-order to keep Black's king trapped in the centre.   13.exd5+ ?!  Kd8  sees Black get away and soon consolidate his extra material.  13...dxe4   13...Bxc6 ?  14.exd5+  Kd8  15.dxc6  Nc5  16.c7+ !  has gone totally wrong for Black  14.Bxe4  Nc5  15.Bxf6  gxf6  16.Qg4  Ne6  Now White keeps the attack going with the pretty  17.Bg6 !  but Black is still in the game here:  Kd7  18.Bxf7  Kxc6  19.Qxe6  and the complications continue. Seemingly, Black's only move is ...Qd8 and White should force perpetual check in that case. }
12... Rc8
{ Here Anand wrote, in his analysis of the game: "I found this idea only shortly before the game, but it seemed to me similar enough to Movsesian-Kasparov, Sarajevo 2000". Chess-culture fans will know that this was the game where Kasparov called his opponent a 'tourist'!  Previously the theoretical move was   12...b4  13.Nb1  Be7  14.N1d2  Qc7  15.Qh3  e5  16.Nc4  O-O  17.Nba5  Bc8  18.Qg3  Shirov-Karjakin, 2007. }
13. Qh3 Rxc3 { Of course, this was the idea. } 14. bxc3 Qc7 15. Kb1 Be7 16. e5
{ In the aforementioned Kasparov game, White's f-pawn was on f3 rather than f4, hence this counterstrike wasn't possible. }
16... dxe5 17. f5
{ Thematic, but the e5-pawn is too good a defender.   17.fxe5 !  was indicated.  Nd5   17...Nxe5 ?!  fails to immediate tactics:  18.Qg3 !  Bd6  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Qg7  ±  18.Bxe7  Kxe7 !  Now not   18...Nxc3+  19.Ka1  Kxe7  20.Qh4+  when White is better.  Not great either is   18...Nxe7  19.Qg4  when White also has an advantage.  19.Rd2  Qxc3  20.Qh4+  Ke8  21.Bf1  with a sharp position and chances for both sides. }
17... Nd5 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 19. fxe6 fxe6
{ Anand's move is a bit too sophisticated.  Here, unlike in the previous note, Black gets more traction out of another move-order:   19...Nxc3+ !  20.Kc1   20.Ka1 ?  Nxd1 !  is the point: Black need not waste time taking back on e6 when he has the threat of ...Qc3 with mate.  20...Nf6  Black holds his kingside together and is doing well.  Though now,   20...Nxd1 ?  loses:  21.exd7  Nc3  22.Qg3 !  and there is no escape from the threats. }
20. Qg3
{ Black's last move offered White an interesting chance to use another square on the g-file:   20.Qg4  when Black should choose the order he used in the game due to some intricate move-order nuances:  Nxc3+   20...g6 !  21.Kc1  g6   21...Kf7 !  can be met now with  22.Qh5+ !  although Black should still choose this.  22.Qh4+  Nf6  23.Rf1  Rf8  24.Rxf6 !  Here it is Black who has all the problems. }
20... g6
{ Black should probably have played   20...Nxc3+  again, with the following likely continuation:  21.Ka1   21.Kc1  Kf7 !  is good for Black.  21...Kd8  It is important to see that now   21...Nxd1 ?!  is now met by  22.Qxg7+  Kd6  23.Rxd1  and Black must be extremely careful.  22.Qxg7  Re8  with equal chances. }
21. Rd2
{ It is critical for Black that   21.Qh4+ ?!  is now not as good as before:  N7f6  22.Rd2 ?  Now comes the beautiful   22.Kc1 !?  22...e4 !  This pawn is protected tactically by ... Nxc3+ and the upshot is that White's attack is formally relegated to the realm of history. }
21... Rc8
{ With the text move Black's rook comes into the game for real.  Anand kept the tension, thinking that   21...Nxc3+  would lead to unclear complications. }
22. Qg5+
{ Not the best reaction.  The other check is more natural:   22.Qh4+  N7f6  23.Rf2  leading to a position with even chances. }
22... Ke8 23. Qg4
{ But this is a real mistake.  The sacrifice didn't work:   23.Bxg6+ ?  hxg6  24.Qxg6+  Ke7  25.Qg7+  Kd6  when Black's king finds itself oddly safe in the middle of the board, and after all can also make its way to the queenside if need be.  Now   23.Rf2 ?  runs into  e4 !  , an idea also seen in an earlier note.  The only move to keep counterplay is the immediate placement of the queen on the h-file:   23.Qh6 !?  however Black keeps a slight endgame plus after  Nxc3+  24.Ka1  e4  with the point  25.Qxh7  Nf8 !  26.Qxc7  Rxc7 }
23... Nxc3+ 24. Ka1 Bd5
{ The black pieces now dominate the center. Strangely enough, the black doubled pawns are now an advantage. They cover important squares and protect their king extremely well. }
25. Re3 Nf6 26. Qh4 Qe7 27. Bf1
{ 27.Qg3  doesn't improve, for instance  Bxb3  28.cxb3  e4  29.Bf1  Nfd5  30.Re1  e3  with major material gain.  White gets mated after the pawn grab   27.Rxe5 ??  because there is absolutely no answer to  Qa3  directly hammering the a2-pawn.  Now Black eliminates the main defender of White's king: the knight on b3. }
27... Bxb3 28. cxb3 Nce4 { A pretty find from Anand. } 29. Rb2
{ The point after   29.Rxe4  is the strong  Qa3  30.Bd3   30.Rb2  only delays the mate after  Rc1+  31.Rb1  Rc2  -+  30...Qc1+  31.Bb1  Qxd2  with a totally winning position. }
29... Rc1+ 30. Rb1 Qc5
{ After this strong move, Shirov decided that enough was enough. Mate on d4 is hard enough to stop, but the second threat is ...Qc2 and the third is simply taking on e3. It is all just too much. }
