[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Karjakin, Sergey vs. Vachier Lagrave, Maxime, London, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6
{ A development from the last few years is that   6...Nbd7  is coming into use. The French grandmaster, however, has always played the text move. }
7. f4 h6
{ The 'Poisoned Pawn Variation' was present already in the repertoire of Fischer. But a new wrinkle is the inclusion of ...h6 before ...Qb6, to gain tempo off White's bishop. The current state of modern theoretical knowledge is that in this way, Black can favourably take on b2. }
8. Bh4 Qb6
{ MVL has full confidence in its preparation, it seems: he has played this move against elite players like Giri, Nakamura and Caruana, among others. Needless to say, they tend to be well prepared- and yet the Frenchman continues. }
9. a3
{ Karjakin doesn't want to go into the complications of the pawn sacrifice.  The complications after   9.Qd2  Qxb2  10.Rb1  Qa3  11.e5  dxe5  12.fxe5  Nfd7  13.Ne4  are contested to this day. The maxim from olden times, 'Never take on b2, even if it is good !' received the deserved disdain of Dutch grandmaster van Wely, who once replied 'I always take on b2, because not only do you take a pawn, you also take the whole structure with it !' We should also note that with the inclusion of ...h6, we mostly rule out White's option of playing 11. f5 in place of 11. e5. }
9... Be7
{ The point is that now   9...Qxb2 ??  runs into  10.Na4  trapping the queen. }
10. Bf2 Qc7 11. Qf3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4
{ This position has become something of a tabiya for the lines where Black delays ...Qb6 and then White chooses to preserve the b2-pawn. }
13... Bb7
{ We've already seen a few times in these pages that Black can often choose the move   13...g5 !?  with the idea of opening up the e5-square for his knights.  14.h4  This is the most principled choice.  After   14.fxg5  Ne5  15.Qg3  hxg5  Black definitely does not stand worse.  14...gxf4  Now it is important that White still has the flexibility to develop his bishop on the other side:  15.Be2 !  An idea introduced in the game Giri-Vachier-Lagrave, 2016. White won the opening battle, but still lost the game. Clearly, White is still not threatening to take on f4 immediately, but by covering his g4-pawn again he opens up the option of meeting ... Ne5 with Qxf4. White also threatens g5.  Rg8   15...Ne5  16.Qxf4  Nexg4  17.Bxg4  e5  18.Qxf6 !  is a tactical point well worth noting.  The position is complicated, but had White found  16.g5 !  he would have got a definite advantage. }
14. Bg2
{ White has completed his development in a way that prevents ...d6-d5.  Here   14.h4  doesn't work as well: Black's best response is  d5 ! }
14... g5
{ This is the right time for this strategic idea: White can no longer cover g4 with the bishop.  Now   14...d5 ?  doesn't work because of  15.exd5  Nxd5  and now the clever but unexpected  16.Nf5 !  comes, leaving Black with insurmountable problems. }
15. h4
{ With this move Karjakin chooses to continue following a game between Yu Yangyi and Naiditsch. Both players were undoubtedly still in preparation. }
15... gxf4 16. g5
{ Similarly to the above variations  (note to Black's 13th)  White tries to create a kingside initiative. }
16... Ne5
{ There is nothing more natural than this 'zwischenzug'. Where else would the knight want to go than e5 ? }
17. Qxf4 hxg5
{ This was a new move at the time of the game, which is strange considering how logical it is. Actually strange, because it looks pretty logical. I imagine most people did not fancy releasing the tension and leaving the h-file indisputably in White's hands, but the French grandmaster seems to have an adequate follow-up in mind.  Previously   17...Nfg4  and   17...Nh5 ?!  were played. However, they did not bring Black the desired results. }
18. hxg5 Rxh1 19. Rxh1 Nfd7 20. Kb1
{ White could choose to flick in   20.Rh8+  Nf8  but it may well be counterproductive because Black gains back the tempo by bringing a knight to g6 whenever he wants. }
20... O-O-O
{ We have now decidedly left the realm of opening theory. Black has completed his development and brought his king to safety. He has acquired the strong e5 outpost and White's g5-pawn has become a target for some future phase of the game. }
21. Rh3
{ This move is a known idea for White: a rook lift along the third rank which will enable him to target the Black king along the c-file.  But perhaps it was worth trying to undermine Black's centre with   21.Nf3 !?  when Black has to be a little bit careful.  Another idea to test Black is   21.g6 !?  when there is only one good answer.  Rg8 !  Both sides now need to calculate accurately:  22.gxf7  Rxg2  23.Nxe6  Qc4 !  24.Rh8+ !  The immediate promotion   24.f8=Q+ ?  fails to  Nxf8  25.Nxf8  Qf7 !!  winning material- because after the forced  26.Qxf7  Nxf7  two White pieces remain under threat and only one can be saved.  24...Nf8  25.Nxf8  Qf1+  It seems that now Black has been successful, but there are some further twists:  26.Be1 !!  A typical computer move which is very hard for humans to see.  Black remains a simple piece up after   26.Ka2  because in the line  Rxf2  27.Ng6+  Kc7  he will always be able to count on a check on c4 with which he can defend himself.  This last nuance is something which isn't present anymore after White draws the Black queen to e1.  26...Qxe1+  White will be a pawn up in the endings after the queen swap   26...Qxf4  27.Ng6+  Kd7  28.Nxf4  27.Ka2  Rf2  Black again wants to take on f7, so White has to have a specific idea up his sleeve- one which is made possible by the absence of ...Qc4+.  28.Ng6+  Kc7  29.f8=Q !  Bxf8  30.Rh7+  Kb6  31.Qh4  White gains adequate counterplay because he is threatening both Qd8+ and Nxf8. The game ends in perpetual check after Black takes on g6, and there is unlikely to be anything better for him. }
21... Kb8 22. Be3 Rg8 23. Rg3 Rg7
{ Vachier-Lagrave tackles things calmly. He overprotects f7 and introduces a few new possible ways of attacking the g5-pawn: the manoeuvres ...Qd8-g8 and ...Nf8-h7. }
24. Bh3
{ White's light-squared bishop wasn't doing any useful work, so Karjakin brings it to a new diagonal, where it threatens Bxe6 ! However, after a couple of moves we can see that the e4-pawn can be meaningfully attacked after all. }
24... Rh7 25. Qf2 Nc5
{ The loose e4-pawn causes White to withdraw his bishop back whence it came. }
26. Bg2 Qc8
{ Quite a nice move. The queen can be used in conjunction with the rook on the kingside  (on either g8 or h8)  but Black also introduces the possibility of ... Be7-d8-b6 into the position. It would be in Black's interest to exchange dark-squared bishops because then the weakness of the White's remaining bishop would be brought into clearer focus. }
27. Bc1 Bd8 28. Nf3
{ Karjakin finally comes up with the idea of challenging Black's e5-knight, but this would have been better several moves ago. }
28... Ng6
{ Other than  (as just mentioned)  the dark-squared bishop, Black's minor pieces are of much better quality than their counterparts, so he is best off avoiding this trade.  By the same token,   28...Nxe4  would be bad because it trades all the minor pieces other than the dark-squared bishops- even if White did not also have the clever  29.Nxe4  Bxe4  30.Nxe5  Bxg2  31.Nxf7  at his disposal. Black is finished after  Bd5  32.g6 }
29. Nd4 Ne5 30. Nf3 Ng6 31. Nd4
{ White doesn't mind the repetition, since in this position it is hard to imagine the possibility of his having an advantage. But MVL opts to continue. }
31... Bb6 { The bishop completes its rerouting in the logical way. } 32. Be3
Ne5 33. b3
{ A move that White rarely wants to have to make in the Sicilian !  After the two bishop moves,   33.Nf3 ?!  is no longer a good idea. There follows  Nc4  when Black wins the bishop pair by force as otherwise there would come a nasty discovered attack by the c5-knight.  Maybe the least evil was   33.Nb3  to finally trade some knights, but Black is still better after  Qc7 }
33... Rh4
{ The pressure on the white position is increased. Although objectively the immediate threats are quite limited, we can see that Karjakin's job in holding the position together will not be trivial in the medium- to long-term. He starts extremely well. }
34. Nde2
{ A strong defensive move, in keeping with Karjakin's reputation as 'The Russian Minister of Defence.' White contests the e3-b6 diagonal and defends the knight on c3 against tactics. }
34... Qc7 35. Bd4 Ncd7
{ The logical end of the plan which was begun 10 moves ago with ...Qc8 !  Once more it is bad to take the e4-pawn:   35...Nxe4 ?  36.Bxe4  Bxd4  37.Nxd4 !  Better than the queen recapture, on which Black would trivially regain his piece with ...d5.  Bxe4  38.Nxe6 !  fxe6  39.Nxe4  Rxe4  40.g6  The pawn cannot be stopped by normal methods and therefore Black would find himself giving back the piece and facing a tremendous attack on his king following  Nxg6  41.Rxg6  when it seems White is close to winning. }
36. Bxb6
{ After this mistake White will find himself suffering for real.  It was time to press the emergency button:   36.g6 !?  fxg6  37.Bh3  and now for the price of a pawn White has managed to generate some mess in the centre. For instance:  Nc5  38.b4  Nxe4  39.Nxe4  Bxd4  40.Nxd4  Rxe4  41.Bg2  Rh4  42.Nxe6  and while Black is certainly still a pawn up, there is now serious counterplay against his king and the centre is wide open. }
36... Qxb6 37. Qxb6 Nxb6 38. Nd4 Ng6
{ The knight has been transferred between e5 and g6 more times than we can count, but now it looks to be on g6 for a while, as Black transfers the other knight to e5 to cement his control over the centre. It was useful to start with this move to avoid the possibility of White playing g6. This endgame is good for black. This is due to three factors: better pawn structure, better bishop and the outpost on e5. }
39. Kc1 Nd7 40. Kd2 Nf4
{ One of several ideas at Black's disposal: in spite of what we have just said, Black only needs one knight on the board to sit on e5- the other one can be usefully traded for White's bishop in order to weaken the e4-pawn. }
41. Ke3 { 41.Bf3  does not keep the bishop alive:  (Ne5 ∓) } 41... Nxg2+
{ As hinted before, MVL shows with this move that he does not blindly follow dogma. Black can afford this trade because White's centre is now going to be extremely weak. }
42. Rxg2 Rh3+ 43. Kd2
{ Of course, there was also a temporary tactical reason for Black's trade: now Black has even more space in which to operate and has driven White back from the third rank.   43.Nf3  loses to  Ne5  44.Rf2  Ng4+ }
43... Ne5
{ The second knight appears on this square. We can consider the move mainly as prophylaxis: Black wants to remove the idea of g5-g6 from consideration.  For instance,   43...Nc5 ?!  would lose the advantage after  44.g6 !  fxg6  45.Rxg6 }
44. Nde2
{ For the second time, this turns out to be the proper defensive try.  Here it was nevertheless interesting to consider playing   44.g6 !?  but I suspect both sides had seen the problem with it.  fxg6  45.Nxe6  An active try is   45.Rf2 !?  but now it will be extremely hard for White to regain his pawn:  Bc8  46.Rf6  Rh2+  47.Nce2  Kc7  48.Nxe6+  Bxe6  49.Rxe6  Kd7  50.Rf6  Ke7  51.Rf1  g5  and Black's winning chances are significantly improved by the swiftly advancing passed pawn.  45...Nf3+  Now White loses material by force, with the point being  46.Ke2  Nh4 !  and after  47.Rg4  the final touch:  Bc8 }
44... Nf3+ 45. Kc1 Nh4 46. Rg1
{ 46.Rf2  Rf3  47.Rh2  Ng6  48.Kd2  Kc8  49.Rg2  Kd7  is similar- a tough defensive job is in prospect. }
46... Ng6
{ As we are taught: 'Do not hurry'. Black has in fact not made any particular progress in the last few moves, but in some sense that is unimportant, because neither does White have any way of dramatically changing the nature of his defensive job. }
47. Kd2 Kc7
{ This move does make a constructive change to Black's position. The king hurries to the center where he will be tasked with the defense of the f7-pawn, and by extension the e6-pawn, ruling out such tricks as g5-g6. }
48. Nd4
{ It doesn't change anything to start with   48.Rf1  :  Ne5  and now White has nothing better  (due to the threat of ...Nf3)  than  49.Nd4  Kd7 }
48... Kd7 49. Rf1 Ke7 50. Rg1 Ne5 51. Rg2 Ba8 52. Nde2
{ It is time for Black to do something concrete, since he has made all the obvious improving moves. }
52... Nf3+ { A check to force the White king further from the centre. } 53. Kc1
Rh1+
{ This was of course the idea, chasing the White king to the passive b2-square. }
54. Kb2 Nh4
{ The job having been done, the knight once again retreats to cover against White's idea of g5-g6. }
55. Rg4 Ng6 56. Nf4
{ This loses a pawn, but of course White was in an unenviable situation with his passive king and the weak e4- and g5-pawns.  For instance,   56.Ng3  is met by  Rh3 !  with the threat of ...Ne5.  57.Nf1  This is White's lesser evil, and the only way to avoid losing a pawn by force for now.  After   57.Nge2  Black nevertheless picks up a pawn:  Ne5  58.Rg2   58.Rg3  Rxg3  59.Nxg3  Nf3  drops the other pawn instead  58...Rh4  The e4-pawn cannot be defended.  57...Ne5  58.Rg2  Rh4  59.Nd2  Bc6  This is prophylaxis against a3-a4. Black generally intends to exchange rooks  (though not necessarily)  and then bring his king around to g6 to attack the g5-pawn. Meanwhile, the White knights are stuck in their current positions because the e4-pawn needs to be defended twice.  Similar again is   56.Rg3  Rh4  57.Nd4  Ne5 !  Black continues playing extremely prophylactically. There is no longer any way to forestall the loss of a pawn.  Not   57...Bxe4  58.Nxe4  Rxe4  59.Nc6+  with counterchances. }
56... Nxf4 57. Rxf4 Rg1 58. Rh4 Rxg5 59. Kc1
{ You may wonder why White doesn't try and get inside Black's camp with his rook:   59.Rh8  Bc6  60.Rb8  but the point is that White's counterplay is way too slow after  Re5  61.Rb6  Bxe4  62.Rxa6  f5  and now there are no more chances for him. }
59... d5
{ A possible continuation was:   59...d5  60.Rh8  Bc6  61.exd5  Bxd5  62.Rb8  Re5  63.Rb6  f5  64.Rxa6  f4  and there is no way to stop the f-pawn. }
*

