[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. So, Wesley, Saint Louis, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3
{ The move which initiates the English Attack. } 6... e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 Nbd7
{ At the time this game was played, we can safely say that both players, both white and black, already had significant experience with this opening.  Later we will pay some attention to the critical move   8...h5 }
9. Qd2
{ If White had wanted to 'punish' Black for his omission of ...h5, then this was the moment to rule that possibility out for good with   9.g4  . }
9... b5 10. O-O-O Be7
{ Even at this stage it is possible to continue with   10...h5  . In an email game Repp-Avotins, 2010 the continuation was  11.Nd5  Bxd5  12.exd5  Nb6  13.Qc3  with messy complications. }
11. g4
{ Finally this advance. It is worth noticing that the current position could also have arisen from 8... Be7. }
11... b4
{ Wesley So chooses to deviate from the main line, though this doesn't yet leave theory completely.  The main variation continues:   11...O-O  12.g5  b4  13.Ne2  Ne8  14.f4  a5  15.f5  a4  and this has been a major area for top players' investigations for a while now. Most recently, White has been trying to show some advantage after:  16.fxe6  axb3  17.cxb3  fxe6  18.Bh3 !  and Black has to decide how to deal with the threat to the e6-pawn. Principled is  Rxa2   18...Nc7  19.Kb1  likewise seems to lead to a pleasant edge for White.  19.Bxe6+  Kh8  and after  20.Ng3  Nc7  21.Bc4  Qa8  22.Rhf1  Rxf1  23.Rxf1  Ra1+  24.Kc2  Rxf1  25.Bxf1  White had a small but stable edge in the game Saric-Wojtaszek, 2015. The advantage is due to his bishop pair, especially the light-squared bishop. With this in mind Black would minimise the damage by playing that thematic Sicilian break,  d5 !?  One other alternative for Black is the natural   11...Nb6  which yielded an interesting game, following the moves  12.g5  Nh5  13.Nd5  Nxd5  14.exd5  Bd7  15.Na5  in the rapid encounter Dominguez Perez-Nepomniachtchi, 2014. }
12. Nd5 { Accepting the challenge is most common, and correct. } 12... Bxd5
{ Here, as in many other lines of the English Attack, Black gives up his bishop for the strong central knight. }
13. exd5 Nb6 14. Na5 { The alternative   14.Qxb4  is also well regarded. }
14... Nbxd5
{ It doesn't seem so great to take with the other knight:   14...Nfxd5 ?!  because of  15.Nb7 !  Qc7  16.Bxb6  Nxb6  17.Nxd6+  Kf8  Black loses material in the endgame following   17...Bxd6  18.Qxd6  Qxd6  19.Rxd6  18.Nf5 !?  White obtains good chances. The black king stands badly, and the h8-rook has yet to meaningfully enter the game.  Another idea is   18.f4  opening up lines towards the Black king.  The world champion now opts to make it a 'genuine' sacrifice. }
15. Nc4
{ White can also take material back with   15.Nc6  Qc7  16.Nxb4  but in the process he loses some control. }
15... Nxe3
{ Black has to take on e3 now- if he delays, White obtains a trick:   15...O-O  16.g5  Nxe3  and now the intermezzo  17.gxf6 !  is good for White.  Recapturing with the knight gives no particular advantage:   17.Nxe3  Nh5  18.h4  Nf4  17...Nxd1  18.fxe7  Qxe7  19.Qxd1  The point is that with two pieces for a rook  (and a pawn)  White has a slight nominal advantage, added to which is the fact of his better co-ordination and central control. }
16. Nxe3
{ The key position for visualising Carlsen's concept. Despite the pawn deficit, it is he who is trying to be better, because of his control of the central light squares. Black's dark-squared bishop is hindered by the two fixed pawns on d6 and e5. }
16... O-O
{ In a game Perez Garcia-Razmyslov, 2008 Black opted to totally give up control of the light squares now rather than be forced to by a later g5. He played   16...Nd7  with the point being to develop his bad bishop via .. .Be7-g5. In fact the diagonal c1-h6 looks like a significant tactical weakness in White's camp, but there is an answer:  17.Nd5 !  Bh4  Black is alert, but his position is still worse.  Probably he only realised now that after   17...Bg5  18.f4 !  exf4  there comes  19.h4 !  Bxh4 ?   19...Be7  20.Qxf4  Ne5  21.Qxb4  is close to winning for White.  20.Rxh4  Qxh4  21.Nc7+  Everything drops.  18.Qxb4  and White stands better.  It would be reasonable to ask whether Black can simply try and return the pawn with   16...d5  . However after  17.g5 !  Nh5  18.Qxd5  Qxd5  19.Nxd5  Black has not solved anything in particular. A further pawn trade is almost forced:  Bxg5+  20.Kb1  O-O  21.Nxb4  a5  22.Nc6  In this position White has the usual Sicilian queenside majority, which can play a role in what is to come much faster than Black's majority on the other side. Additionally, it is very inconvenient to deal with the White knight on c6, which disrupts the flow of Black's play. }
17. Bc4
{ This logical move was a novelty: the world champion recognised that the most important feature of this position is control of the white squares in the centre. Engines are initially quite opposed to this move, but they soon come to their senses.  Previously the move   17.h4  was played. }
17... Nd7
{ 17...Rc8  18.h4  does not do anything to challenge the White hegemony.  The possible break with   17...d5  might have been met by  18.Qe2 !?  The position is about equal after   18.Nxd5  Nxd5  19.Qxd5  18...d4  19.Nf5  White has his pieces on active squares, but the question remains to be answered of whether there is an actual advantage for him. }
18. h4 a5
{ Black tries to create some kind of counterplay on the queenside. By playing this move he also supports the b4-pawn.  The pawn is immune:   18...Bxh4 ?  19.Qh2  g5  20.Rxd6  and White wins.   18...Nb6  is plausible, and probably best met by  19.Bd5 !?  to try and obtain a pure 'good knight versus bad bishop' position.  Nxd5   19...Rb8  20.Be4  sees White transfer his bishop to an even better diagonal. White is now intending the direct g5-g6.  20.Nxd5  Black's position may not be lost yet, but it is quite prospectless. }
19. g5 Rc8 20. Bd5 Nb6 21. Kb1 Qc7
{ White has a firm grip on the position and Black can hardly control a single light square.  Perhaps he could have chosen   21...Rc5  achieving a slightly better version of the game if  (as is likely)  White continues with the same plan of  22.Rhf1 }
22. Rhf1 Nxd5
{ This move indicates some nervousness about Black's situation, and doesn't improve things because the knight on d5 will dominate the board just as well as the bishop did. But Carlsen would likely have been more than satisfied with the development of circumstances in any case.   22...Kh8  is a logical try to get out of the pin.  23.f4  Here too Black is in big trouble whichever way he goes.  a4  This is best, to try and set up counterplay in the future.   23...exf4  24.Rxf4  would almost be game over.  24.f5  f6  25.Be6  Black has temporarily managed to close the kingside, but White still has most of the chances.  Like everything else,   22...Qc5  fails to prevent  23.f4  .But after  exf4  24.Rxf4  Nxd5  25.Nxd5  Rce8  the position might well be holdable. }
23. Nxd5 Qb7 24. f4 f5
{ We often see this type of defence in the English Attack. Black would like to stop the kingside pawn storm in its tracks.  After   24...exf4  White can take back with the queen without worrying about his c2-pawn, unlike the previous note:  25.Qxf4  and the pawn storm continues as intended. }
25. Qe3
{ After the natural capture on f6 the kingside files do open but White's initiative will nevertheless be defused soon:   25.gxf6 ?!  Bxf6  In fact it could even be the Black position which makes more sense here, and he is still up a pawn. }
25... e4
{ Black can defend the e5-pawn with tactics but then White strikes at a completely different point:   25...Rce8 ?!  26.Qb3  Kh8  27.a3  with a large advantage. }
26. h5 Rc5 27. h6 g6
{ Black keeps the lines around his king tightly closed, but there is still room in-between them: a White piece would do untold damage on g7.  Taking the knight loses immediately:   27...Rxd5 ?  28.Qb3  +-  The logical solution seems to be   27...Rf7  . Here, too, White can play  28.Qb3  which, we should note, does not lose a piece. The overloading move  a4  would be answered by  29.Nxe7+  Qxe7  30.Qxa4  and in the position with only major pieces left, Black has two weak pawns on b4 and d6. }
28. Qb3 Rf7 29. a4
{ Saying all that, the concrete   29.Rd4 !  was arguably a better move, consolidating the position of the d5-knight and preparing to double on the d-file. }
29... Bd8 30. Rd4 Kf8 31. Rfd1
{ White has a fairly stable advantage in any case, but you could make an argument for regrouping immediately so as to attack d6.   31.Ne3  Qe7  32.Rfd1  Bc7  33.Nc4  with continuing pressure. }
31... Rc6
{ The only move was   31...Rd7  so as to meet the logical  32.Ne3  Be7  33.Nc4  with  Qa6  when there is still a long way to go. }
32. Ne3 Bb6 33. Nc4
{ What was not so simple to see were the concrete details which make   33.Rxd6 !  a significantly better choice.  Rxd6  34.Rxd6  Bc7  The trade of minor pieces is not useful:   34...Bxe3  35.Qxe3  Rd7  and now White has a little wrinkle which means that Black will neither get to trade rooks nor activate his rook.  36.Qd4 !  Now  Rxd6  loses the queen after  37.Qh8+  Ke7  38.Qg7+  but there was no better alternative anyway.  35.Rd5 !?  Now White's pieces are coming in, and it's important to note that Black cannot obtain relief by trying to 'eat his way out'.  Bxf4   35...Qc6  36.Rb5  Bd8  37.Nc4  demonstrates the mechanism by which White intends to penetrate  36.Rxa5  Bxg5  37.Rb5  Next will be Qxb4 and the attack is unstoppable. }
33... Bxd4
{ So far small mistakes have been made on both sides, but after this gamble there will be no going back.   Meanwhile   33...Rxc4 !  would have generated real counterchances.  34.Qxc4 !  Black's point is that after   34.Rxc4  Rd7 !  Black is decidedly not worse in view of the unstoppable ...d6-d5 which is coming next.  34...Bxd4  35.Qxd4  While this looks unpleasant for Black, it turns out that after  Qc6  there is nothing better than trading queens with  36.Qxd6+  Qxd6  37.Rxd6  Ra7  and White must win the game anew. }
34. Nxa5 Qb6 35. Nxc6 Bc5
{ By contrast to the last note, after   35...Qxc6  36.Rxd4  Black has huge problems because material has already been equalised but he remains with the two extremely weak pawns on b4 and d6. }
36. Qd5 e3 37. a5
{ Carlsen, meanwhile, pushes his own passed pawn, and it turns out Black cannot very well defend against both that and the kingside attack. }
37... Qb5
{ The tactical motifs of this position are perhaps not entirely surprising given the configuration of pieces on the kingside. For instance:   37...Qb7 ?  38.Qxc5  dxc5  39.Rd8#  Relatively best but also not a solution was   37...Qc7  . White needs to find an accurate set of moves to use the b-file for his rook:  38.c3 !  bxc3  39.b4  c2+  40.Kxc2  Bxb4  41.Kd3 !  with a large advantage. }
38. Nd8 { The steed soweth death and destruction! } 38... Ra7
{ In fact there aren't any safe squares for the rook; White can attack a rook on e7 by playing Ne6-d4-c6 at the right time, while on c7 it gets immediately forked by Ne6.  Let us clarify that last comment with a line.   38...Re7  39.Ne6+  Ke8  40.Nd4  Qb7  41.Nc6  e2  Or   41...Rf7  42.Qe6+  Kf8  43.Nd8  +-  42.Re1  Re4  Now here the a-pawn plays its role.  43.a6 !  Qf7  The fork   43...Qxa6  44.Qg8+  Kd7  45.Nb8+  is White's main point  44.a7 !  A study-like move.  Bxa7   44...Qxd5  45.a8=Q+  Kd7  46.Qd8+  Kxc6   46...Ke6  47.Qe7#  47.Qa8+  is a beautiful skewer  45.Qa5 !  Double attack ! This move is suggested by the computer. Black cannot prevent mate on d8 and also preserve the bishop's life.  Simplifying with   45.Qxf7+  Kxf7  46.Nxa7  is the human approach and would also work, albeit after minor technical issues.   38...Rd7  39.Ne6+  and next the knight will withdraw to d4, cuing up a killer check on either e6 or g8. }
39. Ne6+ Ke8 40. Nd4
{ Carlsen tries to follow the ideas from the above variations. However, flexibility was called for.   The most convincing move was now   40.Nxc5  : Black needs to keep the rook protected with  Qxc5  but there nevertheless follows  41.Qg8+  Kd7  42.Qxh7+  Kc6  43.Qxg6  upon which White has successfully netted two pawns, making his own kingside pawns 'passed' in the process. Of course, there is still the slight inconvenience of the e3-pawn. Let us check some lines and see that White is able to control it.  Re7   43...e2 ?  44.Qe8+  44.Qg8 !  Threatening to swap queens, and also having in mind defences involving a check on c4. Such as:  e2  45.Re1  Qf2  46.Qc4+  and all counterplay will be completely extinguished following Qxb4. }
40... Qxa5 41. Qg8+ Kd7 42. Qxh7+ Kc8 43. Qg8+ Kb7
{ So Black's king has slipped the net and White is himself faced with the threat of mate. Presumably, he saw in advance how he could extricate himself, otherwise, his whole train of thought would have been flawed. }
44. c3
{ Absolutely the only move to continue playing for a win.   44.Nb3 ??  would block the protection of a2 and allow a calamity on that square:  Qa2+  45.Kc1  Qa1+ !  46.Nxa1  Rxa1# }
44... bxc3 45. Qb3+ Qb6
{ The endgame after   45...Qb4  46.bxc3  Qxb3+  47.Nxb3  is, as before and also in the game, winning given a modicum of care. }
46. Qxb6+ { Carlsen trades off into a winning endgame. } 46... Kxb6
{ Following   46...Bxb6  it is wise for White to retain the minor pieces on the board, because of how good his knight is as a blockader.  47.Ne2 !  The rook endgame is, oddly, not that simple now. If we compare the following line with what happens in the game, the difference is that White cannot take on d6 with check...   47.bxc3  Bxd4  48.cxd4  Kc6  49.Rh1 !  This is winning, but White has to really think about it.  Rh7  50.Kc2  Kd5  51.Kd3  e2  52.Re1  The pawn only needs to be stopped on e2. Next, White will take on e2 and g6, regardless of whether Black grabs the d4-pawn; then the two connected pawns will defeat the lone d-pawn. For instance:  Ra7  53.Rxe2  Ra3+  54.Kd2  Rh3  55.Re8  Kxd4  56.Ke2  Kc4  57.Re6  d5  58.Rxg6  d4  59.Rc6+  Kd5  60.Rc7  winning  47...Kc6  48.bxc3  White is winning. }
47. bxc3
{ White's protected passed pawn is vital in the evaluation of this position. It is winning for him, but technique is still needed. }
47... Bxd4 48. Rxd4 { Strongly played! } 48... Kc6
{ 48...e2  49.Rxd6+ !  is the point: the e-pawn's freedom to run was illusory...  Kc5  50.Re6  ...and it is lost on the very next turn.  The most intuitive move   48...Kc5  gets met by  49.Kc2  Re7  50.Kd1  e2+  51.Ke1  Re3  52.Ra4  Rxc3  53.Ra8  Rh3  54.Kxe2  with another winning rook endgame of a type we have already seen: White has time to pick up the g6-pawn and only then concern himself with the counterplay based on the passed d-pawn.  d5  55.Ra6  Kd4  56.Rxg6  Ke4  57.Rg7  Kxf4  58.h7  The white pawns run home.  It doesn't matter that Black can decoy the White king away from the promotion square of e1 with   48...Ra1+  , because the intent was to stop that pawn with the rook anyway. In fact after  49.Kxa1  e2  it is possible to stop that pawn either by Rxd6-e6 as before, or the new option  50.Rb4+  followed by Rb1. }
49. Kc2 Ra2+ 50. Kd1 { Definitely not   50.Kd3 ??  because of  e2 } 50... Rf2
51. Ke1 Kd7 52. Ra4 Ke6 53. Ra8 { Threatening h7. } 53... Rh2 54. c4
{ Carlsen is very good at reducing counterplay.   The perfectly natural   54.Rg8  aiming to take on g6 is also winning, but only after White admits the mistake:  Kd5  and now the only move is in fact  55.Re8 !  to stop ...Ke4. Otherwise the counterplay is too fast. }
54... Kf7
{ After   54...d5  White has a little tactic:  55.h7 !  Rxh7  56.Ra6+  Kf7  57.Ra7+  Kg8  58.Rxh7  Kxh7  59.c5  and the c-pawn queens. }
55. Rb8 { This move by the world champion places his opponent in zugzwang. }
55... Ke6
{ Losing the g-pawn.   55...Rh4  leads to a second zugzwang after  56.Ke2  Rh3  57.Kd3  Similarly,   55...e2  56.Kd2 }
56. Rg8
{ The point is that   56.Rg8  Kf7  doesn't preserve the g-pawn after  57.Rg7+ }
*

