[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. So, Wesley"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k2/5r1p/2Np2pP/PqbQ1pP1/1p3P2/4p3/1PP5/1K1R4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nd8 { The steed soweth death and destruction ! } 1... Ra7
{ In fact there aren't any safe squares for the rook; White can attack a rook on e7 by playing Ne6-d4-c6 at the right time, while on c7 it gets immediately forked by Ne6.  Let us clarify that last comment with a line.   38...Re7  39.Ne6+  Ke8  40.Nd4  Qb7  41.Nc6  e2  Or   41...Rf7  42.Qe6+  Kf8  43.Nd8  +-  42.Re1  Re4  Now here the a-pawn plays its role.  43.a6 !  Qf7  The fork   43...Qxa6  44.Qg8+  Kd7  45.Nb8+  is White's main point  44.a7 !  A study-like move.  Bxa7   44...Qxd5  45.a8=Q+  Kd7  46.Qd8+  Kxc6   46...Ke6  47.Qe7#  47.Qa8+  is a beautiful skewer  45.Qa5 !  Double attack ! This move is suggested by the computer. Black cannot prevent mate on d8 and also preserve the bishop's life.  Simplifying with   45.Qxf7+  Kxf7  46.Nxa7  is the human approach and would also work, albeit after minor technical issues.   38...Rd7  39.Ne6+  and next the knight will withdraw to d4, cuing up a killer check on either e6 or g8. }
2. Ne6+ Ke8 { The most convincing move was now } 3. Nxc5
{ : Black needs to keep the rook protected with   40.Nd4 ?!  Carlsen tries to follow the ideas from the above variations. However, flexibility was called for. }
3... Qxc5 { but there nevertheless follows } 4. Qg8+ Kd7 5. Qxh7+ Kc6 6. Qxg6
{ upon which White has successfully netted two pawns, making his own kingside pawns 'passed' in the process. Of course, there is still the slight inconvenience of the e3-pawn. Let us check some lines and see that White is able to control it. }
6... Re7 { 43...e2 ?  44.Qe8+ } 7. Qg8
{ Threatening to swap queens, and also having in mind defences involving a check on c4. Such as: }
7... e2 8. Re1 Qf2 9. Qc4+
{ and all counterplay will be completely extinguished following Qxb4. } *

