[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Topalov, Veselin vs. Wojtaszek, Radoslaw, Skopje, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3
h5
{ This move, with which Black prevents the push g2-g4 as soon as it was threatened, has gained popularity in the last decade. Black takes a big risk because the kingside castled position is now less likely to be safe. Yet neither is it so easy- it appears from praxis- for white to start an attack on that flank. If he plays h2-h3  (with the intention of g2-g4)  , black can always answer h5-h4.   The advance g2-g4 is then countered by an en-passant capture, opening the g-file but crippling the White pawn-structure. Alternatively, if white wants to end up with a pawn on g4- to be able to chase the knight away from f6 and thereby fight for d5- then he first needs g2-g3, then h2-h3 to play before he can finally play g3-g4. This takes quite a while and Black will not be idle in the meantime. In particular, Black is looking to push his queenside pawns. All this, of course, also holds true in the  (extremely common)  case where White decides to rule out the possibility of ... d6-d5 by stationing his knight on that square, where it promptly gets traded off for Black's light-squared bishop.   However, specifically in that case  (as we shall see)  it is important to pay attention to Black's efforts to exchange the dark-squared bishops. If he manages, then Black's remaining minor pieces will have much greater mobility than White's, because White's light-squared bishop would be constricted by its pawns- especially the one which will by then have arrived on d5 ! Lots to take in... but in any case, this move by Black promises an interesting fight. }
9. Nd5
{ Black cannot ignore this knight- it is facilitating the threat of Bb6. } 9...
Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7 11. Qd2 g6
{ One of the important options Black has. The idea is that someday ... Bh6 will become a possibility. In particular, if White for some reason trades his dark-squared bishop for a knight on b6 or f6. The modest pawn push might also help support a future ...f5 break. }
12. O-O-O
{ In a game Topalov-Dominguez Perez, 2014 there followed   12.Be2  Qc7  13.Rc1  Ng8 !?  14.O-O  Ne7   14...Bh6 ?!  In theory Black should be looking to trade off his dark-squared bishop, but the idea is too slow now because of  15.f4 !  when Black has a major problem with development.  15.Bg5  f6  16.Be3  O-O-O  17.c4  and White later got an advantage. }
12... Nb6
{ It was Topalov himself who introduced this move in a game against Anand in 2008. }
13. Qa5
{ And two months before the present game was played, it was Grischuk  (in Saint Louis)  who essayed   13.Kb1  ...against Topalov himself. What followed failed to bother the Bulgarian grandmaster handling the black pieces:  Nbxd5  14.Bg5  Be7  15.Na5  Rb8  16.Bc4  Nb6  17.Bxf6  Bxf6  18.Qxd6  Qxd6  19.Rxd6  Bd8  20.Rd3  Bc7  and Black had equalised. }
13... Bh6
{ Here is why black wants to play ... g7-g6 in this variation. The exchange of dark-squared bishops in principle benefits him, since the scope of White's remaining bishop leaves much to be desired. }
14. Bxh6 Rxh6
{ So, what was Topalov's intention in 'switching sides' and opting to face his own pet variation from the first player's perspective ? We now see the reason: }
15. g3
{ White is planning a pawn storm on the kingside. If he tried to prepare g4 immediately with h2-h3 he would find his pawn-structure fixed forever with ... h5-h4. With the text, though, white can now consider playing those two moves soon- having first ensured that his h1-rook is defended.  Meanwhile, another natural move was played in Anand-Topalov, 2008, and later led to some advantage for White:   15.Kb1  - but this wasn't quite the optimal solution, because White can make better use of this particular tempo. Nevertheless, white cannot easily continue for long with a king on c1 because black will soon start developing with ... Rc8 lining up against the king. Also White would like to give his central pawn some cover with c2-c4. }
15... Kf8 16. Kb1 { Indispensable in the long run. } 16... Kg7 17. Be2
{ This was the novelty.  In the correspondence game Bell-Isolfsson, ICCF 2014   17.f4  was played. After the further  h4  18.fxe5  dxe5  19.d6  Nbd7  20.Bg2  Qxa5  21.Nxa5  e4  22.Nxb7  Rh5  23.c4  Rb8  24.c5  Nxc5  25.Nxc5  Rxc5  the game was equal. }
17... Rh8
{ Linking up the rooks and intending to play ...Rc8 next.  You could be forgiven for thinking that the immediate   17...Rc8  prevented White's next, but this is not so.  18.c4  Nxc4 ??  loses a piece to  19.Qxd8  Rxd8  20.Bxc4  . }
18. c4 Rc8 19. Rc1 Nfd7 20. Rhd1
{ White protects his d5-pawn, envisaging the future possibility of playing c4-c5. Other moves are possible, but none seems clearly better.  It is obvious to continue here with a move like   20.Qb4  vacating the a5-square for the knight. However the knight doesn't do much there after  Nc5  21.Na5  Nbd7  when White's position has not improved.  An interesting idea is   20.Rhf1 !?  to set up the f4-break. }
20... Rc7
{ Black is finding it hard to make useful moves.  There is no point to   20...h4  which allows White to, at a moment of his choice, push past with  21.g4  .  A strong possibility is the intuitive   20...Nc5  to definitively remove c4-c5 from the equation. A possible follow-up:  21.Nd2  Nbd7  22.Qxd8  Rhxd8  23.b4  Na4  and now  24.Ne4  is nothing special due to  Nf6 }
21. Qa3
{ With this move, Topalov asks a concrete question- because he is threatening the d6-pawn.  An attractive possibility is   21.c5  but perhaps the position becomes simplified too fast:  dxc5  22.Nxc5  Rxc5  23.Rxc5  Nxc5  24.Qxc5  Nd7  25.Qc3  Qc8  and White still has work to do to prove a real advantage in the endgame. }
21... Nc8
{ Causing a bit of a pile-up.   One of Topalov's main points was a pawn-push at the end of a natural line:   21...Qe7 ?!  22.c5 !  Nxc5  23.Nxc5  Rxc5  24.Rxc5  dxc5  and by contrast to the previous note, White can play  25.d6  with tempo, and only then Qxc5- with an advantage.   21...Nf6  was seemingly the best answer, when White should again choose to follow the plan from the game. }
22. Nd2
{ Black's last move served a prophylactic purpose: after   22.c5 ?!  White will not get to push his d-pawn at the critical moment.  Nxc5  23.Nxc5  dxc5  24.Rxc5  Rxc5  25.Qxc5  Nd6  and the knight reaches the beautiful blockading square d6, after which we can only speak about a black advantage. The pawn on d5 is completely blockaded forever and the e2-bishop has no future. }
22... Nf6
{ On   22...f5 ?!  there would follow an instructive switchback:  23.Rg1 !  and after the inevitable g3-g4 Black's king position will be somewhat suspect.   22...Nc5  makes sense because  23.b4  Nd7  would lead to White's own king position coming under some scrutiny. The position would then enter razor-sharp territory after  24.c5 }
23. h3
{ This was White's plan when he chose Qa5 in the opening.  The knight trade   23.Ne4 ?!  is not to White's advantage:  Nxe4  24.fxe4  with no problems for Black. }
23... Re7 24. g4
{ It took a long time, but finally the long-anticipated advance comes through. }
24... hxg4
{ In principle, Black wants to keep lines closed near his king, so let us make a remark on the logical   24...h4  . Now there follows  25.Qe3 !  , a move which underlines that in fact Black has not kept anything closed. Both c4-c5 and various kingisde pawn pushes are on the agenda, and either would enable the White bishop to finally come into its element. }
25. fxg4
{ One point of Qa3 is revealed. The queen defends the h-pawn along the third rank. White has a clear advantage here because the f-file is  (half-)  open and he is the only one that can use it.  By contrast after   25.hxg4 ?!  it would be Black who found himself in possession of an open file. }
25... e4
{ White gets something he's been secretly wanting for a while: the central and kingside dark squares are no longer essentially Black's property. However, this concession comes at the cost of Black having some activity. }
26. g5 Nd7 27. Bg4
{ An important part of White's strategy. Now the dark squares have been revealed to be definitively more important, and White hastens to exchange off one of Black's defenders of them.  Another interesting plan was also available:   27.h4 !?  If Black accepts the sacrifice, then a surprising but thematic strike follows on the other side:  Rxh4  28.c5 !  This move brings the ongoing drama surrounding the e5-square to a climax. The h-file is, of course, the scene of the final act; let me show some lines.  dxc5   28...Nxc5 ?  29.Qc3+  Kg8  30.Rh1  and White wins material.  29.Qc3+  Kg8 ?  It was mandatory to offer some material back...by blocking on e5 with the rook. After that the game would be quite interesting.  30.Rh1 !  The White initiative is again deadly.  Here it was interesting to play   27.Qc3+ !?  immediately as well, likely leading to a big advantage. As well as continuing as in the game, White would also have the option of  Kg8  28.Qd4 !?  intending to include the knight in his attack with Nxe4. }
27... e3 28. Qc3+ Kg8
{ The lesser evil was perhaps   28...Kh7 !?  since right now, there is no particular downside to having the king on the h-file. }
29. Nf3
{ The knight doesn't get to reach its ideal attacking post on e4, but here it covers the e5-square, all but ensuring that the d7-knight will be removed from the board. }
29... Ne5 30. Nxe5 Rxe5 31. Re1
{ This was a reasonable to play the long-anticipated   31.c5 !  trying to undermine the rook on e5.  Ne7  One downside is that the variations after   31...e2  32.Re1  Rxd5  are far from trivial. Now White should continue  33.c6 !  and after  bxc6  he would have a strong and surprising response.   33...Rc5 ??  34.cxb7 !  Rxc3  35.Rxc3  Nb6  36.Rc8  is a dramatic end- White nets a piece:  Nxc8  37.bxc8=Q  Qxc8  38.Bxc8  34.Qf6 !  This is not simple to see at all, especially at distance.  Qxf6  35.gxf6  Na7  36.Rxe2  and despite the pawn deficit White stands better. Mostly this is due to the poor positions of Black's knight and h8-rook.  32.c6  Qc7  33.Qa3 !  White is for choice here. }
31... Nb6 32. Qd4 Nd7
{ The second knight takes the place of its predecessor in fighting for certain important dark squares- especially c5 and e5. }
33. Rc3 e2 34. Rc2 Rxg5
{ Pawn-grabbing is often an attractive proposition, but here the temptation should perhaps have been avoided.  It was no longer possible to speak of equality, but   34...b5  was worth trying for Black.  35.cxb5  axb5  36.Rcxe2  Rxe2  37.Rxe2  Ne5  38.Qf4  Here Black is in the game, though the poor position of the h8-rook does mean that he lacks many prospects. }
35. Bxd7
{ To nobody's great surprise, Topalov saw that it was of paramount importance to snap this knight off the board before it could hope to get to e5. Of course, now the h8-rook comes to life somewhat, but that is a price worth paying. }
35... Qxd7 36. Rcxe2 Kh7 { There was no choice, because Re8 was threatened. }
37. a3
{ This kind of 'small move' is one of the distinguishing features of strong players. Before he plays his trump cards, he first gives his own king complete safety. A check on f5 can now be met by Ka2, where there will be no further checks and certainly no back-rank tricks.The difference in the safety of both kings becomes clearly noticeable here. The black one will soon be attacked anew, while White's has few worries right now.  By contrast to the game, after   37.Re7  Qf5+  38.Ka1  there is no way to include the e1-rook in the attack, because White's back rank is simply too weak. }
37... b5
{ This loses almost immediately, but Black had a tough defensive task anyway.    37...Rf8  was a lot tougher, but let us see how White could nevertheless cause trouble here.  38.Re7  Qxh3  39.Rxb7  and White has various ways to continue from here, e.g. Ka2 followed by Rb3, or the game's idea of Re4. }
38. Re7 { Playing the trump card. } 38... Qf5+ 39. Ka2
{ White now has a few mate motifs at his disposal. You are invited to play around with the position and check that by now Black actually has no way to avoid imminent defeat. }
39... Rg8 40. Re8 Qd7 41. R8e7 Qf5 42. R1e4
{ The second rook takes its position. The most obvious intention is to play Rf4, while in some lines it might also be useful to play Rh4. Black has no defence, and promptly resigned. }
*

