[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Dai, Changren vs. Jakovenko, Dmitrij"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6
{ This is seen as the most accurate order. Black wants to develop the queenside as fast as possible, choosing to delay the move . .. Be7, which might otherwise be seen as a natural one. That is because sometimes Black wants to continue with ... g7-g6 and. ..Bf8-g7  (or in exceptional cases even ... Bf8-h6.) }
8. f3 h5
{ This push fits in with a number of Black's other intentions. Right now he wants to prevent an early advance with g2-g4.   8...Be7  is the most normal and commonly played move- in spite of what we have just said- but this game isn't the place to discuss it. }
9. Nd5
{ Clarifying the situation in the centre. The reason for this move, apart from threatening Bb6  (as mentioned before)  is to prevent the freeing move ...d6-d5.  White can also play something neutral, such as   9.Qd2  . After  Nbd7  we will often nevertheless reach similar structures to the game, because Nc3-d5 is the only way to prevent Black from liberating his game by pushing the d-pawn in the long term. }
9... Bxd5
{ This would normally be considered a double-edged decision, with some players decidedly against doing such things. All else being equal, giving up the bishop pair at such an early stage of the game is a bad idea; however here the structure has been clarified enough for the move to actually be fully correct. }
10. exd5 Nbd7
{ Time to take stock and to review the plans of both players. After the exchange on d5, white no longer has control of that square, but instead a potentially vulnerable pawn there, which Black is often planning to attack by means of ... Nd7-b6. White can of course counter the attack on d5 by exchanging his dark-squared bishop for the knight when it appears there, but then the dark squares are likely to become very vulnerable, particularly due to White having played f2-f3. }
11. Qd2 Qc7 12. O-O-O Be7
{ Let us note in passing that Black's plan here is somewhat different from the one in Topalov-Wojtaszek. }
13. Kb1 Nb6 14. Qa5 Bd8
{ It's not possible to play   14...Nbxd5 ?  because  15.Rxd5  wins significant material for White. }
15. c3 Rc8 16. Bxb6 Qxb6 17. Qa4+ Kf8 18. g3 Rc7 19. Bh3 h4 20. f4 Re7
{ A superficial look at this position might give the impression that the black pieces are somewhat poorly co-ordinated. The bishop on d8 and queen on b6 seem to lack any targets, and the black king on f8 also looks curious. But on closer inspection we see that the Black pieces are in fact the more harmoniously arranged. The queen on a4 is offside, the bishop on h3 has no future and the b3-knight is not active either. The black rooks are also well positioned, occupying files which can be opened only when Black chooses. }
21. Bf5
{ Ineffectual.  It was high time to bring the queen into play with   21.Qc4 }
21... e4
{ Black has a passed pawn now and it gets moving without any further ado. There is a risk that the bishop on f5 will find itself trapped under certain circumstances  (... h3, ... g6)  . }
22. Bh3 { Recognising the futility of his last move. } 22... hxg3 23. hxg3 Qf2
{ A very strong move, attacking the g3-pawn as well as supporting Black's own passed pawn. }
24. Qb4 e3
{ This pawn is very strong and Black already has ideas like ...e2 and ... Rxh3. }
25. Bg4
{ White sees that Black's play is becoming too real, so tries to take evasive action with the bishop. This is the third move by the same piece in rather quick succession. }
25... Rxh1 26. Rxh1 Kg8 27. Qxd6 e2
{ Jakovenko continues to find the very best moves.  Black would also be winning after for instance   27...Re8 }
28. Bxe2 { The piece has to be given up, else Black would promote. } 28... Qxe2
29. Rc1
{ The point is that after   29.Qxd8+  Re8  Black threatens the queen on d8 as well as the lethal fork ...Qe4+, and White can't protect against both ideas. }
29... Qe4+ 30. Ka1 Qxd5
{ Swapping off into a trivially won position for Black. } 31. Qxd5 Nxd5 32. Rd1
Bb6 { Black lifts the pin and thereby ends all chances of counterplay. } *

