[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Shirov, Alexei vs. Giri, Anish, ZÃ¼rich, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

{ In general, it is not a good idea to analyse blitz games. But this one nevertheless provides a pretty illustration of some of Black's ideas in the system with 8... h5. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3
h5 9. Nd5 Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7 11. c4 a5
{ With this move Black immediately starts targeting the dark squares.  We have already commented on the ideas behind the usual and flexible   11...g6  in this type of position. }
12. Be2
{ A little bit meek.  Perhaps White could have gotten a head start in the pawn play to come on the queenside, starting with   12.Nd2 }
12... a4 13. Nd2 g6
{ This is Black's idea: now the trade of dark-squared bishops is practically unstoppable. The dark-squares will start to become a major nuisance for White. }
14. Nb1
{ A good positional concept: the knight will stand well on c3, and the queen on d2. But getting there will take time, and Black will not be sitting idly by.  It's possible to consider evading the bishop trade with   14.O-O  Bh6  15.Bf2  but of course Black's bishop gains a tremendous amount of scope in the course of this sequence.  We should also consider the radical idea of   14.g4 ?  trying to prevent ...Bh6.  hxg4  15.fxg4  Now White runs into considerable trouble on the now-open h-file:  Rh3 !  16.Bf2  Bh6  and now for example there could follow  17.Bf1  Bxd2+  18.Qxd2  Rf3  with the strong threat of ...Ne4. }
14... Bh6 15. Bxh6 Rxh6 16. Nc3 Qb6 17. Qd2 Rh8 18. O-O-O
{ Now that he can no longer castle short, Shirov opts to go long instead. But the king isn't particularly safe here either. }
18... Kf8
{ Giri brings his king to a safe place -g7 - and awaits further developments. The plan is to just improve the position slowly. Of course, he really wanted to castle short here, but the h8-rook has already moved- even in blitz we shouldn't forget this rule ! }
19. g4
{ White is dreaming of a kingside attack but this only plays into Black's hands.  Perhaps the correct way of handling this position was with the patient   19.Kb1 }
19... hxg4 20. fxg4 a3
{ A nice move to flick in; it helps cement control over even more dark squares, including the b2-square, which can become a focal point of the coming attack- as indeed happens. That's because in theory a queen landing there could spell instant mate. Additionally, having fixed White's a2-pawn on such a backward square- of the wrong colour- could be of great importance in an endgame. }
21. b3 Rh3
{ A logical move with which black puts pressure on the white pieces. It also prevents h2-h4.  More accurate but less natural was   21...Nc5 !  because of the threat of ...Nce4 and ... Nf2.  22.Rdf1  Now Black has   22.h4 ?  for instance allows  Nce4  in its originally intended form  22...Nfe4  23.Nxe4  Nxe4  24.Qd3  and finally the queen trade  Qd4 !  at the end of the line. In the endgame after  25.Qxd4  exd4  Black has various plans available to him to try and grow his advantage. }
22. g5 Rxc3+ { Undoubtedly seen in advance. } 23. Qxc3 Ne4 24. Qh3 Nf2
{ Regaining the exchange, and highlighting the fact that through this sophisticated piece trade Black has gained control over some dark squares. }
25. Qf3
{ The moment has come for concrete answers from White, because his situation is critical. This is the only move and now the position demands good calculation from both players.  Both sides had seen the possibility of winning the a8-rook, but it was counterproductive for White to indulge himself thus. Here are some cute variations:   25.Qh8+ ?  Ke7  26.Qxa8  Qe3+  27.Rd2   27.Kb1  Qxe2  28.Qxa3  Nxd1  with decisive material gains  27...Qc3+  28.Kb1  A pretty mate motif arises after   28.Rc2  Qa1+  29.Kd2  Ne4+  30.Ke3  Qd4+  31.Kf3  Qf2+  32.Kg4   32.Kxe4  Nc5#  32...f5+  33.gxf6+  Ndxf6+  34.Kh3  Ng5#  Beautiful teamwork between the knight  (s)  and queen !  28...Qxd2  29.Qxa3  Nxh1  Again Black is up a decisive amount of material. }
25... Nxh1
{ 25...Nxd1  26.Rxd1  Ke7  could be safer and is slightly better for Black. }
26. Rf1
{ This counterpunch, which had to be seen in advance by both sides, is the main reason White's position is still playable. }
26... f5 27. gxf6
{ In New in Chess magazine, GM Judit Polgar wrote a nice article about the idea of a king hiding behind an 'umbrella'. By this she meant that in situations like this, an advanced pawn  (here, the one on f6)  fulfils certain definite attacking functions, but also prevents White from using the file on which it stands for offensive operations. }
27... Qd4 28. Qh3
{ Trying to get in, 'under' the umbrella ! Black now has definite problems to solve, and only with a concrete answer to them can he claim his position is legitimate. }
28... Qa1+ 29. Kd2 Qxa2+
{ Here Giri goes terribly wrong.  He had a draw in hand with   29...Qb2+  30.Ke1  Not   30.Ke3 ?!  Qd4+  31.Kf3  Qc3+  32.Kg4  Qxh3+  33.Kxh3  Kf7  34.Rxh1  Nxf6  ∓  with an advantageous endgame for Black.  30...Qb1+  31.Kd2  Qb2+  and it turns out that neither side can do better than a draw. }
30. Kc3
{ 'Returning the favour', as top players often say in annotations.  White could have punished his opponent with:   30.Ke3 !  Qxb3+  31.Bd3  Black has no useful check and so it is now White that stands better. }
30... Qb2+ 31. Kb4
{ The king must head away from the rest of its army.  After   31.Kd3  Nc5+  32.Ke3  the knight on h1 plays its final role- preventing the king's flight to f2:  Qc3+  33.Bd3  Qxd3# }
31... Qd2+
{ He didn't feel like entering the wholly unproductive desperate struggle after   31...Qd2+  32.Qc3   32.Kb5  Ra5#  32...Qxe2 }
*

