[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi vs. Korobov, Anton, Karpov Poikovsky, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3
h5 9. Nd5 Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7 11. Qd2 g6 12. O-O-O
{ This more or less implies a pawn sacrifice. } 12... Nb6 13. Kb1
{ Protecting d5 with   13.c4  is counter-productive. Black wins a pawn anyway with  Rc8  14.Na5  Nfxd5  . }
13... Nbxd5 14. Bg5 Be7
{ It is clear that white has nice compensation for the sacrificed pawn. His pieces have good scope and Black has somewhat weakened light squares- as a result of having traded the bishop whose job it was to guard them. }
15. Bd3
{ This is all well known. The text was played by Hungarian GM Peter Leko in his game against Areschenko, 2017.   15.g3  is an important alternative  (and played by Leko as well.) }
15... Rc8
{ The Leko-Areschchenko game continued   15...Qc7  16.Rhe1  O-O-O  17.c4  Nb6  18.c5  dxc5  19.Nxc5  Qxc5  20.Rc1  Nc4  21.Rxc4  Qxc4  22.Bxc4  Rxd2  23.Bxd2  Rh7  24.Rxe5  and White had great winning chances in this endgame because of his bishop-pair. }
16. Rhe1
{ For the time being, White plays through the center, commencing his preparations for the push f3-f4. }
16... O-O
{ That is exactly what white was after. The black king could not stay in the center for long, but once he's played ... O-O, Korobov definitively confines his king to one place for the whole middlegame. }
17. h3 { Naturally White now plays for g3-g4 instead without delay. } 17... b5
18. g4 h4
{ Black only returns his extra pawn because he could not find an adequate answer to the gxh5 threat. }
19. Bxh4 Nf4 20. Bg3
{ Handing over the bishop pair, but on his terms.  The automatic   20.Bf1 ?!  tries to keep the bishop pair, but fails in this regard- as well as running counter to the essence of the position.  N6d5 !  and Black stands better. }
20... Nxd3
{ There are pawns which really should not be taken. Here, the one on h3 does not merely carry a health warning on its packaging, but also a skull and crossbones.   20...Nxh3 ??  21.Qh6  Nf4  22.Bxf4  exf4  23.Rh1  is simply mate. }
21. Qxd3 Qc7
{ White has the luxury of choosing between several promising routes. The obvious and instinctive attacking formulation of h3-h4-h5  (which we can also see in the Dragon)  is foremost in the mind. But another idea is f3-f4 to put Black's centre under pressure. Another plausible plan is transferring the b3-knight over to the kingside. }
22. c3 { Vidit actually comes up with a fourth idea. } 22... Qc4 23. Qd2
{ Entering an endgame is often to Black's advantage in the Najdorf, but in this example   23.Qxc4  bxc4  24.Nd2  would leave him with too many weak pawns for it to be enjoyable for him. White intends to proceed with Nd2-e4 and keeps decent winning chances. }
23... Qc6 24. f4
{ This is too early right now.  The plan needed preparation- first   24.Qe3  and only then f3-f4. }
24... Ne4 25. Qd3
{ This all seems very good for White. But he must always take into account the traditional Sicilian breakthrough ! }
25... d5
{ Also interesting was   25...Nxg3 !?  26.Qxg3  b4 !  bringing Black's major pieces to life. For example  27.cxb4  Qc2+  28.Ka1  Bf6  and suddenly it is Black who is developing threats against the enemy king.  29.f5  Definitely not   29.Rd2 ??  exf4 !  30.Rxc2  fxg3  29...e4  30.Rb1  Be5  Here Black is fully in the game. }
26. fxe5 b4 27. cxb4 Bxb4
{ At first glance it seems that black is back in the game. Mainly because the attacking possibilities with ... a6-a5-a4 look dangerous for white. But Vidit finds a way out. }
28. Re2 a5 29. Bf4
{ Now the bishop is no longer 'hanging' and White threatens to take on d5. }
29... Qb6
{ Reinforcing the threat of .. .a5-a4.  The point is that after   29...a4  White could answer with  30.Qxd5 !  rather than moving the knight. Then after  axb3  31.Qxc6  Rxc6  32.Rxe4  bxa2+  33.Kxa2  White has reached a position where his pawn advantage will be of real use. }
30. a4
{ Vidit commented in his analysis that this was possibly the most important move of the entire game for him. Black's ... a5-a4 push has now been removed- in radical fashion- from consideration. The question is what other cards Black has available to play here.  Of course now   30.Qxd5  simply loses major material to  Rfd8 !  . }
30... g5
{ The tactical skirmish after   30...Nc3+ ?  does not really deliver what Black wants:  31.bxc3  Rxc3  32.Qxd5  Be7  and here, despite the twin threats of ... Rd8 and ...Rxb3, White has an extremely strong answer.  33.Rd3 !  and Black remains a piece down after  Rd8  34.Qxd8+  Bxd8  35.Rxc3  The only way to stay in the game was with another tactical finesse:   30...Bc3 !?  Then the following sequence is more or less forced.  31.Qb5 !  Rb8 !  32.e6  The obvious choice.  White can also bail out and enjoy a minimal advantage with   32.Qxb6  Rxb6  33.Rxd5  Rxb3  34.Rb5  32...Qxb5  33.axb5  Rxb5  34.e7  Re8  35.Rxe4 !  Rxb3  Definitely not   35...dxe4 ??  because  36.Rd8  wins on the spot.  36.Rxd5  f6 !  To bring the defensive idea of ... Kf7  (and possibly even ... Be5)  into the position.  The tempting   36...Rxb2+  37.Kc1  f6  38.Rd8  Kf7  39.Bd6  offers White good winning chances.  37.Kc2  Rb4  38.Re3  This endgame is promising for White, but Black also has a fair shot at weathering the storm.  Any other normal move such as   30...Rfd8  can also be met by  31.Qb5 !  when White trades queens and keeps an exceedingly comfortable endgame a pawn up. }
31. Be3 Qg6
{ Naturally this was something Black had in mind when playing his previous move. }
32. Ka2
{ Better safe than sorry. White leaves the b1-h7 diagonal and protects his knight on b3.  Slightly less cautious but no less strong was the natural   32.Nd4 !?  seeking to utilise the very square-f5- which Black irrevocably weakened with his pawn push two moves ago. }
32... Rfd8 33. Nd4 Rc4 34. Rc2
{ Black was threatening to take control over the c-file, so a stop is put to that. }
34... Qa6
{ White had to see that the tactical details work in his favour after   34...Rdc8  35.Rdc1  Rxc2   35...Nc3+ ?  36.Rxc3  36.Rxc2  Nc3+  : there is the answer  37.Rxc3  Bxc3  38.Qxg6+  fxg6  39.bxc3  Rxc3  and although endgames with a rook against two pieces can be extremely tricky, this particular one is technically winning.  40.Bf2 !  It is amusing that White should target the a-pawn rather than playing with the passed pawn he already has.  Rxh3  41.Be1  Rh2+  42.Kb3  Rg2  43.Bxa5  Rxg4  44.Bc3  White can push his a-pawn faster than Black can push his g-pawn, so this is winning. }
35. Nb5
{ Looks logical because d5 hangs and the black queen is cut off.  If White had instead chosen   35.Nf5 !  , Black would have been left without even the slightest chance.  Re8  36.Rxc4  Qxc4+  37.Qxc4  dxc4  38.Rd4  Nc5  39.Nd6  Rxe5  40.Nxc4  and Black's position falls apart. }
35... Be7
{ Avoiding immediate defeat and creating some new practical chances. } 36. Rxc4
{ 36.Na3 !? } 36... dxc4 37. Qc2 Rxd1 38. Qxd1 Qe6
{ Black's queen pops up where it isn't wanted again ! } 39. Qd4
{ Vidit starts to prove himself equal to the task of 'winning the game again'. }
39... Nc5
{ The discovered check with   39...c3+  doesn't bring Black anything, and in fact loses the pawn after  40.b3  . }
40. Nc3 Nd3 41. Kb1
{ The king is no longer safe on a2.  A not-too-subtle trap had been set for White:   41.Nd5 ??  Qxd5 !  42.Qxd5  Nb4+  -but Vidit didn't fall for it. }
41... Nxe5
{ So Black has clawed his pawn back by sheer force of willpower- but two of his pawns are still targets for White's pieces. In particular, the one on a5 looks juicy. }
42. Qe4
{ Intending Nd5 or Bd4.  It seems more natural to try and directly take the queens off the board with   42.Qd5 !  after which Black's weak queenside pawns will cost him dearly.  Qg6+  43.Ne4 !  Nf3  44.Ka2  and White is very firmly in control. }
42... Bb4 43. Bd4 Bxc3
{ Neither does   43...f6  offer relief anymore:  44.Nd5 !  Threatening Nxf6+.  Kg7  45.Bxe5  Qxe5  46.Qxc4  and the technical conversion phase must surely be successful for White. }
44. Bxc3 f6 45. Qa8+ Kf7 46. Qxa5
{ Taking Black's most important pawn. It remains only to defuse Black's remaining counterplay. }
46... Nd3 47. Qb5
{ Strongly played. The queen makes way for the a-pawn, and at the same time keeps Black worrying about his c-pawn. }
47... Qe4 48. Ka2
{ The usual saying is that queen and knight collaborate better than queen and bishop in such endings, but here White has good enough king safety that he can repel the threats while pushing his a-pawn. }
48... Nc1+ 49. Ka3 Qe7+ 50. Qb4 Qc7 51. a5 Nd3 52. Qb6 Qe7+ 53. Ka2
{ It is quite difficult indeed to arrange for a substantial sequence of checks when White's king is on a2- from there it can run either forward to a3, or back to b1. }
53... Nc1+ 54. Kb1 Qe4+
{ Giving up the knight for a few checks. White needs to calculate with a little final touch of precision, to see how he can escape from the perpetual.  White has a nice answer if Black tries to arrange mate:   54...Nb3  55.a6  Qe4+  56.Ka2  Qh1  Threatening mate in one. But now there comes  57.Qb7+ !  winning. }
55. Kxc1 Qh1+ 56. Kd2 Qh2+ 57. Ke1
{ White's queen ends up blocking the checks after   57.Ke1  Qh1+  58.Ke2  : for instance,  Qe4+  59.Qe3  Qg2+  60.Qf2  - and now Black's checks are almost at an end.  Qe4+  61.Kd2  Qd3+  62.Kc1 }
*

