1. a4
{ Vidit commented in his analysis that this was possibly the most important move of the entire game for him. Black's ... a5-a4 push has now been removed- in radical fashion- from consideration. The question is what other cards Black has available to play here.  Of course now   30.Qxd5  simply loses major material to  Rfd8 !  . }
1... g5
{ Korobov is clearly scrambling, because this advance cannot really be to his advantage. He voluntarily weakens squares on the kingside. There were a few alternatives:  The tactical skirmish after   30...Nc3+ ?  does not really deliver what Black wants:  31.bxc3  Rxc3  32.Qxd5  Be7  and here, despite the twin threats of ... Rd8 and ...Rxb3, White has an extremely strong answer.  33.Rd3 !  and Black remains a piece down after  Rd8  34.Qxd8+  Bxd8  35.Rxc3  The only way to stay in the game was with another tactical finesse:   30...Bc3 !?  Then the following sequence is more or less forced.  31.Qb5 !  Rb8 !  32.e6  The obvious choice.  White can also bail out and enjoy a minimal advantage with   32.Qxb6  Rxb6  33.Rxd5  Rxb3  34.Rb5  32...Qxb5  33.axb5  Rxb5  34.e7  Re8  35.Rxe4 !  Rxb3  Definitely not   35...dxe4 ??  because  36.Rd8  wins on the spot.  36.Rxd5  f6 !  To bring the defensive idea of ... Kf7  (and possibly even ... Be5)  into the position.  The tempting   36...Rxb2+  37.Kc1  f6  38.Rd8  Kf7  39.Bd6  offers White good winning chances.  37.Kc2  Rb4  38.Re3  This endgame is promising for White, but Black also has a fair shot at weathering the storm.  Any other normal move such as   30...Rfd8  can also be met by  31.Qb5 !  when White trades queens and keeps an exceedingly comfortable endgame a pawn up. }
2. Be3 Qg6
{ Naturally this was something Black had in mind when playing his previous move. }
3. Ka2
{ Better safe than sorry. White leaves the b1-h7 diagonal and protects his knight on b3.  Slightly less cautious but no less strong was the natural   32.Nd4 !?  seeking to utilise the very square-f5- which Black irrevocably weakened with his pawn push two moves ago. }
