[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Caruana, Fabiano vs. Topalov, Veselin, Zug FIDE GP, 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ It is perhaps worthwhile to mention that Topalov, going into this game, was the sole tournament leader by half a point. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3
Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O
{ Now that the players have castled on opposite wings, a sharp game is guaranteed ! }
10... a5
{ A known plan: the a-pawn is used as a battering ram, and  (if not stopped)  it will go all the way to a3 to break up the opponent's pawn-structure. }
11. a4
{ Note the phrase 'if not stopped': White always has the option at his disposal of simply making the further advance of Black's a-pawn illegal ! }
11... Na6
{ The knight heads for c7 where it can join the battle against White's control of the b5-square. Why bother, when White controls it 3 times ? Well, that square is a chokepoint for Black's queenside counterplay. As soon as Black solves this one problem there will be good prospects against the White king. A second idea of placing the knight on c7 is to- you guessed it- support that perennial Sicilian advance, ...d6-d5. }
12. Bb5 Nc7
{ Black wants to undermine White's blockading formation on the queenside by exchanging off the light-squared bishop for the c7-knight. However Caruana is not minded to allow this, deciding instead to exchange off his other bishop for that knight.  Black could also try and support ...d6-d5 by another method:   12...Nb4  -however, this doesn't gain a tempo and so White has time to continue with  13.g4  d5  14.g5  , leaving White in the driver's seat. Neither can Black really complicate matters with  Nxe4  15.fxe4  d4  because of the strong reply  16.Qg2 ! }
13. Bb6
{ Going back with   13.Be2 ?!  is inconsistent and hands Black the advantage after he plays  d5 ! }
13... Qc8 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. g4
{ Despite the absence of a dark-squared bishop, White confidently sets out to attack as normal on the kingside. The plan is to push g5 and drive Black's knight from f6, handing White control over the d5-square. }
15... Rfd8
{ But Black threatens ...d6-d5 immediately, forcing White to act before he is ready. }
16. g5 Nh5 17. Nd5
{ In the game, White had to take back on d5 with the queen because the g5-pawn was hanging.  Hence why I said he wasn't ready to 'act'.  Trying to fix that problem now with   17.h4  doesn't really get anywhere either because Black can cover d5 with his knight in a different way:  Nf4  and White's plans have been completely frustrated. }
17... Bxd5 18. exd5 g6 19. Kb1
{ Time to take stock of the position, in which two main imbalances have emerged. The first one is the opposing pawn majorities: Black's is on the kingside and White's is on the queenside. The detail of this imbalance works in Black's favour, because his pawns are relatively effective in holding back White's queenside majority- meaning that it will not be simple to create a strong passed pawn there, even in an endgame. Meanwhile, White's odd kingside structure will probably be a source of trouble in time to come: the thrusts ... h6 or ...f6 can be prepared relatively soon, likely leading to White having two isolated pawns there, of which the one on f3 is also 'backward'. This fact would be compensated for if White had attacking chances on the kingside either before or after Black makes a pawn push there-but there are none, mostly because he has no possibility of a pawn break himself. The second imbalance is the opposite-coloured bishops, which  (as quite often)  imply that both sides' plans will develop largely in isolation for some time. We know what Black wants to do, but what can White do ? Perhaps the only profitable plan for him in this position is to improve the position of his b3-knight. }
19... Rf8 20. Qe3 Qd8
{ The direct   20...Nf4  21.h4  f6  also leads to good outcomes. } 21. h4 Nf4
22. Qg1 h6
{ Despite seemingly having spent a while preparing ... f7-f6  (by moving his rook back to f8)  Black now changes tack and plays the other kingside break. The intention is to undermine the g5-pawn and then push his own f-pawn two squares rather than one, perhaps with the long-term goal of ...e5-e4 to give his dark-squared bishop prospects on the long diagonal.  Topalov realised that by now   22...f6 ?!  was maybe not such a great idea because of  23.gxf6  Bxf6  24.h5 !  g5  25.h6  when his nice pawn-structure has been divided into several pieces and White has the beautiful e4-square primed for almost immediate occupation by his hitherto useless b3-knight. }
23. Nd2
{ The knight rushes into battle.   23.gxh6  Bxh4  24.h7+ !?  Kh8  25.Nd2  gave an interesting game. }
23... Kg7 24. gxh6+ Kxh6
{ No fear of ghosts ! The king seems exposed here, but given the control that black has over the important surrounding squares, he indeed has nothing to fear. }
25. Nc4
{ At first glance a strange move. But it carries a threat which is strong in spite of being rather unaesthetic: Nb6 winning an exchange. The knight can also be rerouted to the kingside.  In spite of which, the move   25.Ne4  was a lot more combative.  Rh8  26.h5 !?  A pawn offer to open lines.  After   26.Ng3  Bxh4  27.Rd2  Kg7  28.Rdh2  Kf8  the game is dynamically equal.  26...gxh5  If Black keeps the files closed with   26...g5 ?  then White can use the diagonals instead, to his considerable advantage:  27.Qg4  followed by Ng3-f5 will be a major nuisance.  27.Qf2  Here black must be extremely careful. The chances are, however, balanced after for example  Qc7 }
25... Qc7 26. Qe3 Kh7 27. h5
{ Sometimes a pawn has negative value. Because it stands in the way of a rook, for example. In which case you might as well sacrifice it, as Caruana does here. }
27... g5
{ Of course Topalov isn't taking the pawn. As long as White's h5-pawn remains on the board, there is no crack in the Black king's shelter. With ...f7-f5 to come next, the last weak diagonal will be sealed up.  Very unhealthy indeed is   27...Nxh5 ??  because now the kingside is blasted open:  28.f4 !  Rh8  29.Rxh5+ !  gxh5  30.fxe5  and the breakthrough is immediate and decisive. An example line:  Rag8  31.Qf4  Bg5  32.Qf5+  Rg6  33.Nxd6  Kg7  34.Rf1  and Black is in no shape to defend himself.   27...gxh5  avoids White playing f3-f4, but now the danger comes from another angle:  28.Nb6  Rad8  and now White has a surprising move to gain an edge:  29.Rd3 !  with the strong threat of Rc3. The rook cannot be taken because of disaster on the h-file:  Nxd3 ??  30.Rxh5+  Kg8  31.Qg1+  Bg5  32.Qxg5# }
28. h6 f5
{ As promised. Black seems to have made at least some optical gains, with his strong knight on f4 and mobile majority. }
29. Qd2
{ Caruana defends very well. He clears the e3-square for the knight so that he can immediately put pressure on Black's f5-pawn. }
29... Rf6 30. Rdg1 Rg6 31. Ne3 Rf8 32. Nc4
{ An odd move. The knight stood well on e3.  However, a reasonable idea was to try and trade it off for the even better-placed black knight:   32.Ng2 !?  Nxg2  33.Rxg2  and now there will be a race for both sides to activate their respective bishops.  A solid and decent idea is   32.Bd3  Nxd3  33.Qxd3  Qd7  34.b3  keeping chances essentially equal. }
32... Bd8 33. Rd1 Rff6 34. Qf2 Rxh6
{ So Topalov goes a pawn up and Caruana, who was in some time trouble by now, immediately has to seek the most accurate method of proving compensation. }
35. Qa7
{ This queen excursion turns out to be counterproductive. But it was not easy to come up with a better constructive idea.  Going back again with   35.Ne3  now fails to trouble Black, who keeps everything under control with  Qf7  It seems maybe the best idea was   35.c3  which at least tries to go somewhere with b2-b4. But anyway Black stands clearly better. }
35... Rxh1 36. Rxh1+ Rh6 37. Qg1
{ Slightly better was   37.Rxh6+  Kxh6  38.Qg1  so that Black cannot apply the same finesse to the trade of rooks that he ends up using in the game. }
37... Rh4
{ The finesse. Now if White trades rooks Black instantly obtains a very dangerous passed pawn. }
38. Ne3 Qf7 39. Ng2 { Black was winning, but this move makes it easier. } 39...
Rxh1 40. Qxh1+ Qh5 41. Qxh5+ Nxh5
{ Black now has a healthy extra pawn and he turns it into a win, although he still had something of a fight on his hands. }
42. Ne3 Ng3 43. Kc1 Kg6 44. Kd1 g4
{ A lot more logical was   44...e4 !  45.fxe4  Nxe4  46.Bd7  Ng3  when there is no longer any way to stop the two connected passed pawns. }
45. fxg4 f4
{ Even this is good for Black, but he now needs to play rather accurately. }
46. Nc4
{ White fails to make use of his windfall.  The only chance lay in the endgame with opposite-coloured bishops after   46.Nf5 !  Nxf5  47.Bd3  f3  48.Kd2  Kg5  49.Bxf5  Kf4  50.Kd3  . At this precise moment White is managing to restrain both of Black's connected passed pawns. However a bit of scrutiny reveals that he will soon run out of moves, because the f5-bishop needs to defend the g4-pawn as well as the e4-square. So Black loses a few moves:  Bb6  51.c3  Bc5  52.b3  Ba7 !  and thereby reaches a 'zugzwang' position.  53.Bg6  The pawn is now lost; we show the winning method.   53.b4 ?  also loses after Black creates a third passed pawn with  b5 !  54.axb5  a4  53...Kxg4  54.Be4  Kg3  55.Kd2  Kf4  56.Kd3  f2  57.Bg2  Kg3  58.Bf1  Kf3  Followed by ...e5-e4, which is now unstoppable. }
46... Bc7 47. Bd7 Kg5 48. Ke1 f3
{ The Black king reaches f4, where it supports both pawns in ideal fashion. }
49. Ne3 Bb6 { And Caruana resigned here. } *

