[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Karpov, Anatoly vs. Nunn, John DM, Amsterdam, 1985"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. a4 { The most common move in this position. }
11... Rc8 12. a5
{ White tries to fix the structure on the queenside. In any case, the push ...b7-b5 is now out of the question for Black. }
12... Qc7 13. Rfd1 Rfd8
{ 13...Rfe8  has also been seen in games involving elite players. For instance, the games Fernandez Garcia-Anand, 2003, Adams-Svidler, 2008 and Nakamura-A. Korobov, 2013.  14.Qe1  One could rightly ask if this would be a good moment for Black to try and chase down the opponent's bishop pair with  Ng4  15.Bxg4  Bxg4  . Turns out he can, but after  16.Nd5  Qb8   16...Qxc2 ?!  17.Nxe7+  Rxe7  18.Rdc1  17.Nxe7+  Rxe7  Black has also lost his bishop pair. That development means that the d6-pawn will be somewhat weak in what follows after  18.Rd2  : the pressure on that point will soon be significant. }
14. Qe1
{ A typical little prophylactic move for this kind of position. The queen avoids standing on the same file as Black's rook on d8. }
14... Qc6
{ Black now simply loses material outright after   14...Ng4 ??  15.Bxg4  Bxg4  16.Nd5  so that move is unplayable. As we saw, the analogous line would have been playable- if not especially pleasant- had Black chosen the other square for his f8-rook on the 13th move. }
15. Bf3 { White must in any case keep the d5-square in an iron grip. } 15...
Bc4
{ An important moment in the struggle. White has managed to hold back ...d6-d5, but most of his pieces are tied up with that job- which one can he possibly improve ? The knight on b3 suggests itself, because that's the worst-placed piece White has in this position. Karpov sets it in motion along a long route to d5. }
16. Nc1 h6 17. N1a2 Nc5 18. Nb4 Qe8 19. g3
{ There is no rush- plenty of time for this strengthening move. } 19... Rc7 20.
Bg2 Rdc8
{ Now the idea of   20...Ng4 ?!  becomes absurd. While the bishop on e3 is certainly important, by doing this Black would lose the last bit of control over his light squares- and not even get the bishop he was chasing after !  21.Ncd5  Bxd5  22.Nxd5  White gains tempo off the rook- exactly the tempo needed to retreat the e3-bishop with  Rc6  23.Bd2  and stand incontrovertibly better. }
21. b3 Be6 22. Ncd5 { Finally White installs a knight on d5. } 22... Nxd5 23.
Nxd5 Bxd5
{ The knight was so strong that it had to be taken. But the exchange is a significant concession: Black loses the bishop pair, and White's humble g2-bishop  (being unopposed)  may later ascend to great heights of glory. }
24. Rxd5
{ White's strategy has been successful. While it wasn't possible to keep a knight on the d5-square, he has managed to keep total control of the square and maintain a piece on it.  Note that the pawn recapture would be much worse. }
24... Rc6 25. Rad1 Ne6 26. c4
{ White now has the ideal pawn structure for this opening, with the d5-square his for eternity and the d6-pawn a sitting duck. With this in mind, Black comes up with an interesting way to sacrifice that useless pawn to gain control of some dark squares. }
26... Bg5 27. Ba7
{ But Karpov has no interest in trading off half of his bishop pair for a measly pawn.  Let us see how the game would proceed if White took the pawn:   27.Rxd6  Rxd6  28.Rxd6  Qe7  There is not much to choose between the two different orders.   28...Bxe3  29.Qxe3   29.fxe3  succeeds in controlling the weak square on d4- but the doubled pawn will persist for a very long time and White's g2-bishop is without a useful job right now, therefore he stands only a little better.  29...Qe7  30.Rd5  Nd4  -see next diagram.  29.Rd5  Bxe3  30.Qxe3  Nd4  Black obtains a measure of counterplay based on the strong central knight and certain other ideas like ... Qb4. }
27... Ra8 28. Bb6 Bd8 { Continuing to pursue the White bishop. } 29. Be3
{ 29.Rxd6 ?!  Bxb6  30.axb6  Nd4  gives White nothing whatsoever because one of his b-pawns is going to fall soon. }
29... Bc7
{ Deciding to stop offering the pawn sacrifice.  Following   29...Bg5  White obtains-thanks to his triangulation- a somewhat better version than before after  30.Rxd6  Rxd6  31.Rxd6  -because Black's rook finds itself on a8 rather than c8.   29...Qe7  30.Qd2  would nevertheless have forced Black to play ...Bc7. }
30. Qe2 b6
{ Trying to resolve his positional problems by tactical means, but White is able to reinforce the a5-pawn in a logical way. }
31. b4
{ Ensuring that White can at least take back on a5- but he has something even better in mind.  Nunn's point was   31.axb6  Bxb6  32.Rxd6  Nd4  when White's advantage would once more be history. }
31... bxa5 32. b5
{ The point of the last move is revealed: White's b-pawn is very strong. }
32... axb5 33. cxb5 Rc5
{ An exchange sacrifice that is more or less forced, and also Black's best chance.  Both sides knew that   33...Rc3 ?  34.b6  Bd8   34...Bb8 ?  35.b7  traps the rook on a8 !  35.Rxd6  is no fun at all for Black. For instance now   35.Qb2  Rxe3  36.fxe3  Rb8  37.Rxd6  is also strong  35...Rb3  36.Qc4  a4  37.Bh3 !  and the White bishop pair dominates the game. }
34. Bxc5
{ White must give up his best unit to win the material being offered. } 34...
Nxc5 35. Bf1
{ Karpov again decides to give his least well-deployed piece a new job. The bishop is heading for the diagonal a2-g8.  Perhaps   35.b6 !?  Bxb6  36.Rxd6  was also a strong option. }
35... a4 36. Qc2 { Making way for the bishop. } 36... a3 37. Bc4
{ Karpov has made his strong concept into a reality. With the queen and bishop working in harmony on the light squares, he not only restrains the passed a-pawn but also hints at tactical motifs on, say, d5 or f7. }
37... Ne6 { Trying to jam the battery of queen and light-squared bishop. } 38.
R5d3 Nd4 39. Qa2 Bb6 40. Rxa3
{ Here Black lost on time but there was no more hope at all for him anyway because his great trump, the a-pawn, had been removed from the board. }
*

