1. b4
{ Ensuring that White can at least take back on a5- but he has something even better in mind.  Nunn's point was   31.axb6  Bxb6  32.Rxd6  Nd4  when White's advantage would once more be history. }
1... bxa5 2. b5
{ The point of the last move is revealed: White's b-pawn is very strong. } 2...
axb5 3. cxb5 Rc5
{ An exchange sacrifice that is more or less forced, and also Black's best chance.  Both sides knew that   33...Rc3 ?  34.b6  Bd8   34...Bb8 ?  35.b7  traps the rook on a8 !  35.Rxd6  is no fun at all for Black. For instance now   35.Qb2  Rxe3  36.fxe3  Rb8  37.Rxd6  is also strong  35...Rb3  36.Qc4  a4  37.Bh3 !  and the White bishop pair dominates the game. }
4. Bxc5 { White must give up his best unit to win the material being offered. }
