[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Nakamura, Hikaru, Wijk aan Zee, 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3
{ This is a clever move order from Carlsen.  Given the course of the game, we could ask whether   8.g4  is also on the cards for White. However, Black can answer quite cleverly:  h6 !  This answer is possible because Black has not castled yet. Among others, this sequence occurred in Shirov- Van Wely, 1997.  The normal   8.O-O  is common and seen in, for instance, Ponomariov-Anand, 2011. }
8... O-O
{ 8...b5 ?!  is also too early because it compromises Black's queenside. There follows  9.a4 !  b4  10.Nd5  when Black is in trouble; the b4-pawn is hanging and another idea is Bb6.  Here   8...Be6  is the most neutral move. Black postpones castling and awaits developments. In case of  9.g4 ?!  White obtains the sharp game he is after, but not in a favourable way:  d5  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Bxd5  and White's strategy has not worked. }
9. g4
{ Now that ...h6 is out of the question  (with a castled king position like this one, pawn weaknesses on that side of the board take on even higher importance than usual)  the 16th world champion grabs the opportunity to advance on the kingside. }
9... Be6
{ An incredible piece sacrifice was tried in Yemelin-Nevostrujev, 2005:   9...Nc6  10.g5  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  d5  12.Ng3  d4  13.Bd2  - but there wasn't enough play to be had, particularly after  a5 ?   13...Bxg5  had to be tried but there's also not enough compensation after  14.Rg1 !  14.h4  Here White was almost winning.  The immediate   9...a5  can be met by  10.g5  Nfd7  11.h4  a4  12.Nd2  and White has won the opening battle. }
10. g5 Nfd7
{ The most normal retreat square for this knight, but it somewhat interferes with the development of the other knight.   10...Ne8  is a worse move because the overall piece co-ordination is no better than the game, and the knight stands worse on e8 than d7.  11.Qd2  Nd7  12.f4  g6  13.O-O-O  and White is clearly better. }
11. h4
{ Carlsen has always had a knack for finding the best order in which to execute a given plan.  Most games had continued with   11.Qd2  but then  a5 !?  seems to be an interesting way for Black to try and 'throw a spanner in the works'.  12.f4  a4  13.f5  axb3  14.fxe6  fxe6  15.cxb3  and Black had nothing to complain about here, for instance see the game Dolmatov-Gelfand, 1988. }
11... Nb6
{ 11...Nc6 !?  seems like a practical chance. In any case after  12.f4  Black obtains a decent level of activity with  exf4  13.Bxf4  Nc5  when both of his knights contribute to the battle for the centre.  Compared to the variation beginning with 11. Qd2, we have to consider   11...a5  12.f4  a4  13.f5  as a better version for White, because he already has the useful move h4.  After   11...b5  we see an advantage of White retaining his queen on d1 for one move more.  12.Bg4  The light-squared bishops now get traded, which is to White's advantage. }
12. Qd2
{ Now that Black has no knight which can immediately leap to e5,   12.f4 !?  enters the picture as an interesting option.  exf4  13.Bxf4  Black still has to direct one of his knights to e5, because what else can he do ?  Nc6  Black is poorly prepared for the opening of the centre that would occur after   13...d5 ?!  ; a strong answer is  14.Qd3 !  with a large advantage.  dxe4  15.Qxd8  Bxd8  16.O-O-O  ±  14.Qd2  The possession of the e5-square does not hide the fact that Black must be careful about his king position now that the white pawns have advanced so far.  At this exact moment the positionally desirable   12.Bg4  would have run into a strong answer from Black:  Nc4 }
12... N8d7 13. f4
{ It is possible that Carlsen was a bit reluctant to allow Black the easy and obvious plan ... a6-a5-a4, which would be the answer in case he had chosen to castle long. White's last was an interesting novelty when the game was played. Black can't allow f4-f5 under any circumstances, because after ... Bc4, white can exchange bishops  (even if Black then also swaps off the one on e3)  because he will then permanently have the d5-square in his control, soon to be occupied by the c3-knight.  Previously   13.O-O-O  was played. Now the a-pawn advances down the board like a battering ram, and given that White hasn't previously traded off Black's e5-pawn, there is no option to move the attacked knight on b3 forward to d4. Instead it must retreat:  a5 !?  14.Kb1  a4  15.Nc1  and while the knight still has some prospects  (for instance, a2-a3 and then Nc1-a2-b4-d5)  this plan is rather slow. }
13... exf4
{ Let us illustrate the comment about White's 13th.   13...Rc8  14.f5  Bc4  and now a strong continuation would be  15.O-O-O  Bxe2  16.Qxe2  As a consequence of allowing f4-f5, White now has a very strong grip over the d5-square. Black now has to attempt the somewhat desperate  Rxc3  in order to break this, but there isn't enough compensation. His pieces simply don't work that well together. }
14. Bxf4 Ne5 15. O-O-O
{ This position can also occur from variations of the 6. Be3 e5 system where White is able to get in the f4-break. For instance, Ponomariov-Karjakin, Wijk aan Zee 2007. }
15... Rc8 16. Kb1 Qc7
{ Black continues hesitating.  Perhaps   16...Nec4  was a better idea but after  17.Bxc4  Nxc4  18.Qd3  White still stands somewhat better. He has control of the d5-square, and the b3-knight, the laggard of this line, can at some moment swing into the picturesque f5-square via d4. }
17. h5
{ Carlsen sees the chance to increase the pressure on Black's kingside. } 17...
Rfe8 18. Ka1
{ Strong players often have a very good eye for minute details. The king's current position on b1 admits the occasional 'coincidence' or 'accident', so Carlsen decides to play a prophylactic move.  An example of the tactical issues which White decided to dodge:   18.Nd4  Nbc4  19.Qe1  Qb6  and now in response to White's natural defence there is an easily missable tactic.  20.Bc1 ?  If White got this far, he should admit that he made a mistake somewhere and retreat-   20.Nb3  20...Na3+  21.Ka1  Qxd4 !  gives Black an advantage. }
18... Bf8 { Black also makes a prophylactic move. } 19. Nd4
{ It took a while, but finally this horse can ride into the battle on the kingside. This is the main reason for trading White's f-pawn for Black's e-pawn, and a convincing remedy to the usual poor position of this knight. }
19... Qc5
{ This move allows White to break through.  In the post-mortem Nakamura suggested   19...g6 !?  with the idea . ..Bg7.  20.hxg6  hxg6  Now there follows an instructive series of moves culminating in some drama on the h-file.   20...fxg6  will lose material after  21.Bxe5  dxe5  22.Nxe6  Rxe6  23.Nd5  or indeed   23.Bg4  .  21.Nxe6  Rxe6  22.Be3  Bg7   22...Nbc4  23.Bxc4  Nxc4  24.Bd4  Bg7  25.Qh2  and the Black position is hopeless.  23.Bd4  White can double or even triple major pieces on the h-file, while Black is basically just looking on. }
20. g6 Nec4
{ But of course White needs some supporting details for his attack.   Accepting such pawns is almost always a terrible idea.  20...fxg6  21.hxg6  Nxg6   If instead Black tries to block the h-file, then there is a trick here too:  21...h6  22.Nxe6  Rxe6  23.Bxe5 !  The knight protected both the g4-square, needed for a skewer, and the f7-square, needed for the most plausible mate-motif. Depending how Black takes back, one of these ideas now comes to the fore.  23...dxe5   23...Rxe5  allows a beautiful attacking combination:  24.Qf4  Re7  25.Bg4  Rd8  26.Be6+ !  Kh8  27.Rdf1  with mate.  24.Bg4  White wins material  22.Nxe6  Rxe6  23.Bg4  Nxf4  24.Qxf4  Rf6  25.Qh2  Black is close to losing here too. }
21. Bxc4 Nxc4 22. Qd3
{ The Black counter-attack doesn't amount to much, while White's pressure on the kingside is reaching a crescendo. }
22... fxg6
{ 22...h6 !?  is basically the same idea as in the game- here White starts with  23.Bc1 !  Ne5  24.Qg3  and the attack proceeds very similarly to the game.  Queenside play is way too slow:   22...b5  23.gxh7+  Kh8  24.h6  g6  25.Nxe6  Rxe6   25...fxe6  26.e5 !  +-  26.Nd5  ±  and the second wave of attack will be decisive. }
23. hxg6
{ White opens the h-file.  White could also have started with   23.Nxe6  Rxe6  24.Qh3  Rce8  25.hxg6  h6  26.Nd5  keeping the tricky attacking resource Qh3-f5-f7 on the cards.  Rxg6  27.Qf5  Ree6  and now White has the deadly  28.Rdf1  with the threat of Bxh6 and Qxf8. }
23... h6 24. Qg3
{ Here the white queen fulfills an important role. The d6-pawn, as so often, is in the cross-hairs; but more importantly, the idea of Bxh6 is starting to enter certain variations because of the followup g6-g7. }
24... Qb6
{ Black doesn't have any play after   24...Nxb2  -White can simply absorb the few checks and then enjoy his extra piece.  25.Kxb2  Qb4+  26.Nb3  d5  27.exd5  Qa3+  28.Kb1  with a winning position. }
25. Bc1 Qa5
{ Nakamura is not one to reconcile himself to passive defence.  The other try to get active with   25...d5  can be met simply by  26.e5  Bb4  and now the very calm  27.Nce2 }
26. Rdf1
{ Bringing all the attacking pieces into formation.  Now, too, it was possible to consider   26.Nxe6  . }
26... Ne5
{ Keeping White vigilant. The spectacular threat of ...Rxc3 and mate on a2 is introduced ! }
27. Nd5 Bxd5 28. exd5
{ Black's threat has been parried and now another piece sacrifice  (Nd4-f5-h6)  becomes a distinct possibility. }
28... Qxd5
{ Black tries to call White's bluff, but it wasn't a bluff.  Against the last-mentioned White idea, Black could try   28...Rc4  but now a different knight move succeeds.  29.Ne6 !   29.Nf5  is now countered by  Rg4  29...Rg4   29...Qxd5  30.Rxh6  gxh6  31.g7 !  is also decisive  30.Qf2  Rxg6  31.Rhg1 !  Rxg1  32.Qxg1  White is winning because the threat Rxf8+ is so strong as to force Black to give up an exchange. }
29. Bxh6
{ Of course there was no longer any time to lose, but it is nice to see how Carlsen plays the final offensive. It all seems to go like clockwork, but right here he is offering two pieces to be captured... }
29... gxh6
{ It is not difficult to see that   29...Qxd4  30.Be3  is a decisive blow. Because what can Black possibly do against the threat of Rh8+ followed by a queen mate on h7 ?   29...Qe4  seems like a try, but it fails. White has  30.Bg5 !  Specifically here, so as to cover the e7-square !  Qxg6  31.Qh3  Nf7  32.Rxf7 !  Kxf7  33.Qb3+  A nice finish. }
30. g7
{ This push was always going to happen sometime. Either the g-file will become completely open for various attacking ideas, or the far-advanced pawn will itself become a lethal attacking weapon  (or even a queen.) }
30... Be7
{ It turns out White has a concrete answer to   30...Bxg7  as well:  31.Nf5  Rc7  32.Nxh6+  Kh7  33.Ng4+  Kg8  and now the frisky knight gets to give a decisive check-  34.Nf6+  winning the queen ! }
31. Rxh6 { Threatening mate in one. } 31... Nf7 32. Qg6
{ The most circumspect way to win.  Obviously, Carlsen saw that after   32.Rh8+  there is no direct mate because Black controls the h1-square:  Nxh8  33.gxh8=Q+  Kxh8  . But upon reaching this position, he would surely have noticed that the position is winning anyway-  34.Nf5 !  Bf6  35.Qg6  and Black is finished. }
32... Nxh6 33. Qxh6 Bf6 34. Qh8+
{ 34.Qxf6  Qh5  35.Ne6  Kh7  36.Nf4  Qh6  37.Qf5+  Kg8  38.Nh5  +-  wins as well, but the text move is more forceful. }
34... Kf7 35. g8=Q+ Rxg8 36. Qxf6+ Ke8 37. Re1+
{ 37.Re1+  Qe5   37...Kd7  is mate in one-  38.Qe7#  38.Rxe5+  dxe5  39.Qe6+  sees White additionally win one of the two rooks with check. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Nakamura, Hikaru"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1rbk1/1p3ppp/pn1pb3/2q1n1PP/3NPB2/2N5/PPPQB3/K2R3R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. g6 Nec4
{ But of course White needs some supporting details for his attack.  Accepting such pawns is almost always a terrible idea.   20...fxg6  21.hxg6  Nxg6  If instead Black tries to block the h-file, then there is a trick here too:   21...h6  22.Nxe6  Rxe6  23.Bxe5 !  The knight protected both the g4-square  (needed for a skewer)  and the f7-square  (needed for the most plausible mate-motif.)  Depending how Black takes back, one of these ideas now comes to the fore.  dxe5   23...Rxe5  allows a beautiful attacking combination:  24.Qf4  Re7  25.Bg4  Rd8  26.Be6+ !  Kh8  27.Rdf1  with mate.  24.Bg4  White wins material.  22.Nxe6  Rxe6  23.Bg4  Nxf4  24.Qxf4  Rf6  25.Qh2  Black is close to losing here too. }
2. Bxc4 Nxc4 3. Qd3
{ The Black counter-attack doesn't amount to much, while White's pressure on the kingside is reaching a crescendo. }
*

