[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Unzicker, Wolfgang vs. Fischer, Robert James, Varna, 1962"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be6
{ Fischer sometimes played this order.  A few years previously Fischer had chosen   7...Be7  in the game Pilnik-Fischer 1959. }
8. O-O
{ A small note on move-orders. If White intends to encourage black to play ...Qc7, he may as well do it right away:   8.f4  and now after the 'autopilot' move  Qc7  it's been known for a while that White gets an advantage with the sharp  9.g4 !?  exf4  10.g5  Nfd7  11.Bxf4  Nc6  12.Qd2  followed by O-O-O. }
8... Nbd7 9. f4 Qc7
{ It turns out that   9...Rc8  is more precise. The point is that after  10.f5  Bc4  11.Bxc4  Rxc4  the rook stands better on c4 than would a queen, and there is the additional possibility of an exchange sacrifice with ...Rxc3. }
10. f5 Bc4 11. a4 { To stop ...b5. } 11... Be7
{ Now   11...Rc8 ?  would be a positional error:  12.Bxc4  Qxc4   12...Qb6+  13.Kh1  Rxc4  14.Nd2  Rc6  15.Rf3  and White develops a strong grip on the d5-square with Rd3 and Nf1-e3.  13.a5 !  Black's co-ordination is now disrupted. It's important to notice that a tactical detail prevents him from taking on e4-  Nxe4 ?  14.Ra4 }
12. Be3 O-O 13. a5
{ People also tried the sharp   13.g4  here. But by the time of Amed-Gunina, 2005 it was already clear how Black should react to the pawn-storm:  h6  and Black's position is fine. }
13... b5
{ This is the way to free Black's game.   13...h6  doesn't quite fit the needs of the position anymore. The game Asrian-Minasian, 1999 continued  14.Kh1  Rfc8  15.Bxc4  Qxc4  16.Qf3  with a nice position for White. }
14. axb6 Nxb6 15. Bxb6
{ This ugly move has rightly been called a strategic mistake. However, we should be fair to the White player: in the game Fischer-Gadia  (discussed previously)  the very same type of strategic decision was ultimately crowned with success. White swapped light-squared bishops, and gave up his dark-squared bishop for a knight, creating a minor piece imbalance and leaving his opponent with a bad bishop. So why should this case be any different ? And why the question mark ? Let us see...  Since another game in the same year, it has been known that the prophylactic   15.Kh1 !  should be chosen instead. Now play could proceed  Rfc8  16.Bxb6  (Only now !)  Qxb6  17.Bxc4  Rxc4  18.Qe2  Rb4  19.Ra2 !  as in Geller-Fischer, 1962. }
15... Qxb6+ 16. Kh1 Bb5
{ This is the nuance. Black is trying to improve his pawn structure, and if White opts not to accept the piece trade then Black will simply retain the bishop pair with ...Bc6, thank you very much.  If Black had played   16...Rfc8  we would transpose to the previous note. But he has something much stronger. }
17. Bxb5
{ Capturing with the knight leads after   17.Nxb5  axb5  18.Qd3  to a similar set of problems as in the game. }
17... axb5 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. Qxd5
{ This position looks like the culmination of everything White had been aiming for. He has a good knight against a bad bishop and almost no weaknesses. So what is Fischer doing on the Black side ? Let me begin by qualifying both of my last two statements: the knight on b3 is rather far away from its ideal home on d5, and there are some small weaknesses in White's position- such as the c2- and e4-pawns. Admittedly, to use those weaknesses- and even try and combine them with pressure on the White king- requires the mind of a genius. But the world champion from New York is one such. }
19... Ra4
{ Fischer probably saw this strong move in advance. It is almost the only one to keep Black in contention for the a-file, and at the same time he attacks the e4-pawn from the side. }
20. c3
{ Note that trading rooks drops a pawn for White:   20.Rxa4 ?  bxa4  21.Nd2  Qxb2  and Black is much better. }
20... Qa6
{ One of Black's ideas. He 'suggests' the possibility that he might win control of the a-file by tripling major pieces. }
21. h3
{ Creating an escape square for the king in case of potential back rank motifs.  Later another world champion accepted the challenge of playing this position against the same opponent: Tal-Fischer, 1962. That game continued   21.Rad1  and White later managed to get his b3-knight over to d5, even though doing so cost him a pawn. Fischer was able to maintain the balance by giving up an exchange to get the knight off the board. }
21... Rc8 22. Rfe1 h6
{ Black also creates space for his king and waits for White's next plan. } 23.
Kh2 Bg5 24. g3
{ This is a big mistake from White. But he faced major problems in any case.  A normal move like   24.Rad1  is suggested in many sources as an improvement. However now there could come  Ra2 !  and White again experiences difficulties keeping everything together.  25.Qxd6 ?  is met with  Qxd6  26.Rxd6  Rxb2  27.Na5  Rxc3  when Black has not only a clean extra pawn but also dominance on the seventh rank- meaning that his task is virtually done.   24.Qd3  can be met by, for instance, the 'computerish' but accurate  Qa7 !? }
24... Qa7
{ Fischer makes optimal use of all his pieces. The queen threatens to invade on f2 now that the second rank has opened. }
25. Kg2 Ra2
{ Another tricky move for White to face: the threatened ...Rxb2+ would be terminal. }
26. Kf1
{ It is clear that the storm clouds are gathering around the White position, but where is the clincher ? }
26... Rxc3
{ The key variations:   26...Rxc3  27.Rxa2   27.bxc3 ?  Qf2#  27...Rf3+  28.Ke2  Rf2+  29.Kd3  Qxa2  .Now the net around the White king is so tight that it has to try and flee alone...  Weirdly,   29...Qc7  threatening mate on c2 also works !  30.Kc3   30.Ra1  Qxb2  -+   30.h4  Rxb2  is also decisive  30...Qxb2+  31.Kb4  Bd2+  ...but in fleeing, White drops a rook  (though doubtless other moves won too.)  32.Kxb5  Bxe1  Here we can end the analysis.  After   26.Rxa2  Qxa2  27.Re2  Black wins with the obvious  Rxc3 ! }
