[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Mchedlishvili, Mikheil vs. Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar, Mainz, 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. O-O
Be7 9. a4 Nbd7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qd2
{ 11.a5  is an important alternative. In a game Kuzubov-Nigalidze, 2014, Black later triumphed with  Rc8 }
11... Qc7
{ Here too   11...Rc8  is a key alternative.   11...Nb6  is an interesting way of playing that seems to have been adopted by various top players, e.g. Carlsen, Giri, Anand and Nepomniachtchi. }
12. Rfd1
{ The White player in this game opts to try and make do without the push f2-f4. }
12... Rac8 13. a5 Rfd8 14. Bf3
{ A serious, no-nonsense approach to the position: Black will be prevented from playing ...d5.  By far the most common move in this position is   14.Qe1 }
14... h6 15. Nc1
{ Mchedlishvili follows Karpov's plan against Nunn  (as discussed earlier)  . But Mamedyarov knows his classics and reacts with the move that I already gave as an improvement in that game. }
15... b6 16. axb6 Nxb6 17. N1e2
{ The pawn on a6 is far more trouble than it's worth:   17.Rxa6  Nc4  18.Qe1  Nxb2  and Black regains the pawn, leaving all the White pieces hanging. }
17... Nc4 18. Qc1
{ Now Black has a significant advantage, and various ways to try and grow it. }
18... g5
{ True to his style, Mamedyarov seeks a combination-based solution. Initially, the artifact of the position that he is using is the trapped position of White's bishop on f3. But serious questions remain regarding whether this move is either necessary or advisable.   18...Qb7  or   18...Nxe3  19.Qxe3  a5  seem to be competent ways of consolidating Black's significant edge. }
19. g3
{ White falls under the spell somewhat.   19.Rxa6  was now compulory, whereupon  Rd7  is a plausible answer.  It is important to see that   19...g4 ?  does not win a piece because Black loses the e7-bishop after  20.Ra7  .  20.Ra7  Qb8  21.Rxd7  Bxd7  and now White has exhausted the 'normal' methods but can scramble good enough play for a piece with:  22.Bxg5 !?  hxg5  23.Qxg5+  Kh8  24.Qh6+  Nh7  25.Nd5  Bg5  26.Qh5 }
19... Ng4 { Well played by Black. } 20. Rxa6
{ Trading the light-squared bishop with   20.Bxg4  looks wholly unnatural and after  Bxg4  the gaping weaknesses on f3 and h3 will play their part in a very, very small number of tempi's time.  Best is   20.Bd2  but obviously Black isn't complaining here either.  Qb6  But now taking the other bishop is inadvisable:   20...Nxd2  21.Qxd2  Qb7  22.Bxg4  Bxg4  23.Nd5  with an advantage for White.  21.Bxg4  Bxg4  22.Nd5  Qb7  with good play for Black. }
20... Ngxe3
{ White should never have allowed this trade. Suddenly he gets stuck with an ugly pair of doubled pawns, and the end is not far off. }
21. fxe3 Qb7 22. Ra1 g4 23. Bg2 Bg5
{ Now the White position collapses like a house of cards. } 24. Rd3 Nxb2 25.
Qb1 Rb8
{ After   25...Rb8  the rook on d3 has nowhere to hide. It should go to d5, but in any case Black is bringing home the bacon in short order. From the many possibilities after  26.Rd5  ,  Qc7 !?  looks like the most accurate one. }
*

