[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Giri, Anish vs. Gruenfeld, Yehuda, Baku, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 7. Nde2 h5
{ This prophylactic move is seen as the best reaction to White's 6th. The point is that if Black continues without it, then White will certainly continue with g2-g4, creating a space advantage on the kingside. And not only that: if the pawn gets to march on to g5  (attacking the knight on f6)  that will strengthen White's grip on the d5-square. }
8. g3
{ One idea of 6. h3 was to fianchetto the king's bishop, so Giri goes for that now. }
8... Nbd7
{ As always, the queen's knight belongs on d7 in the Najdorf. Black intends to develop his queen's bishop to b7 and then to bring the d5-square under control with ... Nb6.  Slightly more common is   8...Be6 }
9. a4
{ Giri does not feel like allowing ...b7-b5 any longer. The timing of this move is spot-on, because we've seen in past cases that a drawback of it can be that it allows the Black queen's knight to head to b4 via c6; however right now, since that knight is already on d7 the drawback doesn't apply. There's now no way for Black to use his queen's knight to control the d5-square. }
9... Be7 10. Bg2 b6
{ This is a fairly important moment, because White has various ways to continue, all espoused by strong players. A selection of the different options: }
11. Nd5
{ Choosing to use the d5-square immediately.   11.Bg5  was seen in, e.g. Kryvoruchko- Khismatullin, 2015.   11.Be3  Karpov-Ivanchuk, 1994.   11.O-O  Inarkiev-Oparin, 2014. }
11... Nxd5
{ The knight had to be traded because in this case it would have been significantly to White's advantage to trade on e7. Then the backward pawn on d6 would have become vulnerable. }
12. Qxd5 Rb8 13. Nc3
{ White again delays castling, the better to direct his second knight to d5 as soon as possible. }
13... Bb7 14. Qd2
{ A novelty at the time of the game. On the one hand, the queen blocks the c1-bishop's immediate line of development, but on the other hand White can now double major pieces on the d-file faster than otherwise.  The existing   14.Qd1  had conferred a rather minimal advantage on White in a number of games. }
14... Rc8 15. h4
{ One of the basic features of White's game is being able to push this pawn to consolidate the kingside structure- and the dark squares everywhere. It creates a new future for his king's bishop on h3 and removes an advantage Black previously enjoyed: that of holding the idea of ...h5-h4 over White's head like a sword of Damocles. }
15... Nf6 16. Qd3
{ This slight tempo loss is permitted, now that Black's knight is no longer in position to hit the queen with ...Nc5. }
16... O-O 17. O-O Qd7 18. Bg5
{ All played very consistently. White's point is to reinforce his control of the d5-square and to this end he threatens to remove one of its defenders  (the knight on f6.) }
18... Rfd8 19. Rfd1 g6 20. Rd2 Kf8
{ This is a sign: Black is at a loss for an active plan. } 21. Rad1
{ In the meantime White has tripled on the d-file. It is clear that the d6-pawn is weak, and motifs related to winning it are beginning to crop up. }
21... Rc6 22. Bxf6
{ Now that black has to use more and more resources to avoid losing his d6-pawn, he's no longer paying so much attention to the d5-square. Giri cashes in on this fact. }
22... Bxf6 23. Nd5 Be7 24. Qe3
{ An elegant queen move. Her majesty is 'staring daggers' in two directions: the b6-pawn, and a juicy potential site of a check on h6... }
24... b5
{ There is nothing else that can be suggested: this pawn was attacked twice and could not be defended a second time. }
25. axb5 axb5 26. Bf1
{ Now Giri's light-squared bishop also plays its role on the queenside. } 26...
Rc5
{ This is a perfectly plausible move from Black, but it allows a nice combination that Giri is very much capable of finding. }
27. Nxe7 Kxe7 { 27...Qxe7  28.Qxc5  wins two rooks and a piece for the queen. }
28. Rxd6 { The first point. } 28... Qxd6 29. Rxd6 Kxd6
{ At first sight Black seems to be largely unscathed in the short term, but there is a second twist to the combination. }
30. b4 Rc7 31. Qb6+
{ Made possible by that earlier sly sideways slide of the queen to e3. } 31...
Bc6 32. Bh3
{ After   32.Bh3 !  the Black king is in a terminal tangle. The threat is Qc5# and Black must surrender major material to avert it, so rather than play on with the miserable  Rcd7  or something, he chose to resign. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Giri, Anish vs. Gruenfeld, Yehuda"]
