[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Najdorf"]
[Black "Naiditsch, Arkadij vs. Carlsen, Magnus, Karlsruhe/Baden-Baden, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3
{ Naiditsch is known for his sharp style. However, in this game he chooses a rather less aggressive formation. }
6... e5 7. Nb3
{ Visually speaking, the knight doesn't stand very well here- but an important plan is to route it to d5 via via d2-f1  (or c4)  -e3.   7.Nde2  is a more direct route to d5,  via c3, as in the Giri-Gruenfeld game but without the inclusion of h2-h3 and ...h7-h5. This is the most theoretically significant approach. }
7... Be7 8. Bg2
{ We have previously seen that in similar cases White can try   8.a4  to cut out the possibility of ...b7-b5. Here that doesn't work as well as in some other cases, because Black can develop counterplay by routing his knight to b4, beginning with  Nc6 !  followed by...Nc6-b4 controlling the d5-square. Boleslavsky would be proud ! }
8... O-O 9. O-O Be6
{ Carlsen opts to develop his bishop first.  The alternative is an immediate   9...b5 !?  , which gives Black the extra choice of developing his queen's bishop to b7 instead of e6. Naiditsch had faced this before, and that game continued  10.Nd5 !?  Nxd5  11.Qxd5  Ra7  12.Be3  Be6  13.Qd2  Ra8  14.a4  Nc6  15.axb5  axb5  16.Rxa8  Qxa8  17.Ra1  Qb7 =  with an equal game in Naiditsch-Vidit, 2017. }
10. Re1
{ With this, White prepares the previously mentioned knight manoeuvre: the f1 square is now cleared. At the same time, the rook does a good job here of ensuring that if Black ever plays ...d6-d5, he must also worry about whether his e5-pawn will be hanging.  In an earlier game Naiditsch had also tried   10.a4  .  Nbd7  Now that White has played a2-a4, it is thematic to once again consider trying to develop the knight via c6 to b4:   10...Nc6 ?!  However in this case the idea doesn't work well because Black's knight never gets to b4.  11.Nd5 !  Bxd5  12.exd5  Here if Black nevertheless persists with  Nb4 ??  then  13.c3  wins the knight.  11.Re1  Initiating the standard plan with Nd2-f1-e3. In this case, since White has spent a tempo on a2-a4, Black obtains one extra option, which is important to show...  Qc7  12.Nd2  and now:  Bd8 !  Now that there is hardly any play against d6 for White, Black plays his poorly placed bishop to the a5-square, which has been weakened by a2-a4. From a5 the bishop can exert unpleasant pressure on the opponent's queenside. There will no longer be any time for White to get a knight to d5.  13.Nf1  Qc5  From this position there have been two significant games, in both of which Black obtained a comfortable position.  14.Ne3  In a game Naiditsch-Sunilduth Lyna, 2016 there followed   14.h3  Ba5  15.Be3  Qc7  16.Bd2  Rac8  17.Ne3  and now with  Bxc3 !  18.Bxc3  Nc5  Black would have solved his opening problems.  14...Ba5  15.Bd2  Rac8  and Black had also obtained a satisfactory game in Wei-Giri, 2016. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nd2
{ Showing a slight lack of foresight.  With   11.a4  White would have entered the variations already discussed under 10. a4. In those lines the position is around equal, but after the game's move Black begins to take over the game a little. }
11... b5
{ Although the b-pawn can sometimes become a weakness after its advance, Black decides it is more important to gain space on the queenside and pose a small question to the knight on c3. }
12. Nf1 Bg4
{ A probing move by Carlsen, the aim of which is to disrupt the coordination between White's pawns and pieces.  The text move is not the only possibility. Black could also have followed Balogh-Wojtaszek, 2014, where the Polish grandmaster chose a very standard Najdorf plan.   12...Nb6  And now it is interesting to see how Black handled the next phase of the game.  13.Ne3  b4  14.Ncd5  Nfxd5  15.exd5  Bd7  16.Bd2  a5  17.a3  bxa3  18.Rxa3  a4  19.Bb4  Qb8  20.c3  Bg5  21.Ra1  f5  Black held the initiative and eventually won. }
13. f3
{ Most players would probably make the same decision- the moral compulsion to win tempi is high- but this is what Carlsen wanted. Now the dark squares in White's centre and queenside are weakened.  A somewhat artificial-looking move might have served White better:   13.Qd2  This leaves the pawn structure intact and more importantly: the f1-knight can now also be brought into the game via e3  (with a gain of tempo)  and brought to the desired d5-square as quickly as possible. The fact that the bishop on c1 is blocked for a moment by his own queen is perhaps less important. But such advice is easier dispensed than followed, especially when one's opponent is the reigning world champion. }
13... Be6 14. Ne3 Rc8 15. a3
{ A somewhat slow move.  So White has expended lots of energy getting his b3-knight to e3- it has moved 6 times in total. Why not complete the plan and plant a knight on d5 ? Let us see.   15.Ncd5  Bxd5  16.exd5  Nb6  White is worse here because the d5-pawn is weak: in particular it is vulnerable to the ideas of ...Rc8-c5 and ...Qd8-a8. }
15... Nb6
{ It is clear that the black player has achieved something of a dream Najdorf position. White cannot post a piece on d5 because in the end he will be forced to capture back there with the e-pawn, leaving that pawn weak and handing Black a strong kingside majority. In the meantime, Black is getting ready to free his game with ... d6-d5. }
16. f4
{ Something like this was called for, interrupting for some time Black's plan of executing ...d6-d5. }
16... Re8
{ It was also possible to swap off on f4 first with   16...exf4  17.gxf4  Re8  after which White's centre is a little bit weak. }
17. Kh1 Bf8 18. f5
{ Black has made all the necessary preparations for ...d6-d5, so White plays this to force a postponement. }
18... Bd7 19. Qd3
{ White has still not had the opportunity to develop his queen's bishop. He must keep an eye on the d5-square, since Black's breakthrough has only been stalled, not halted. }
19... h6 20. b3
{ Obviously White realised that with this move he weakens the c-file. But he needs to develop somehow, and this move prepares Bc1-b2 and Ra1-d1.  After the alternative developing move   20.Bd2  Naiditsch presumably did not like the prospect of facing the logical  Nc4 }
20... Bc6
{ Carlsen's bishop shifts to a new working diagonal: a8-h1. It could also have gone there early in the opening- see note to move 9- but then, of course, a whole set of other features would also have developed differently. }
21. Bd2
{ So why not now   21.Bb2  ? Given the circumstances, this seems a much more logical decision. But perhaps Naiditsch thought his bishop would find little work there or that he should prevent Black's f8-bishop from being routed to the h6-c1 diagonal too easily. }
21... Qc7 22. Rac1 Qb7
{ It is clear that black has a pleasant game. His pieces are now operating at close to full potential and he is once again ready to play ...d6-d5, even at the expense of a pawn sometimes. }
23. Ned5
{ Naiditsch is done waiting and decides to finally place a piece on d5. That gives us clarity about what the structure will look like in the rest of the middlegame. }
23... Bxd5 24. exd5
{ If White were to trade another pair of pieces with   24.Nxd5  Nbxd5  25.exd5  Black would obtain the better chances using a by-now-familiar bishop manoeuvre: ...Bf8-e7-d8-b6. }
24... Nbd7
{ The knight had done its work on b6 and now seeks a better life for itself, heading via d7 to the promising c5-square. There it would not only chase the White queen away from her present fairly active post but also support the further advance of the e5-pawn, which  (apparently almost by accident)  has in fact become a protected passed pawn and a major trump for Black in what is to come. }
25. Nd1
{ White is also capable of improving the position of his pieces. The knight was doing relatively little on c3 and now it heads to e3 to blockade the oncoming e-pawn.  An alternative to improving the knight is to try and trade it with   25.Ne4 !?  . }
25... e4
{ The Black player knows perfectly well that his opponent is trying to unravel and now seeks to force matters. However, this move is a little bit too impatient. Of course, there was another, more strategic option available.   25...Be7 !?  would be the logical way to start the bishop maneuver to b6 which has already been mentioned. }
26. Qd4 { Naturally   26.Bxe4 ??  loses material to  Nc5  . } 26... Ne5
{ The right follow-up, leaving the e4-pawn to fend for itself.  Trading the central pawns is very much to Black's disadvantage:   26...Qxd5 ?!  27.Qxd5  Nxd5  28.Bxe4  and White has no problems. }
27. Nf2
{ With this move, White denies himself the respite he had been working so hard towards.  The correct way to continue was   27.Nc3 !  so as to defend the d5-pawn, after which White has equalised the game. }
27... Nf3
{ This knight jump guarantees Black a significant advantage. White needs to trade his light-squared bishop and the centre opens- which is indisputably to Black's benefit. White will now face problems with his king security due to both of these factors. }
28. Bxf3 exf3
{ There is now no way to defend the d5-pawn other than by opening more lines. }
29. c4 bxc4 30. bxc4 Re5
{ There were several strong options at Black's disposal.   30...Rxe1+  came into consideration too.  31.Bxe1  and now for instance  Nd7  with fantastic chances for Black.  Likewise the immediate   30...Nd7 !?  was also reasonable, seeking to play the knight to either c5 or e5 without delay. }
31. Re3
{ Black's point is that   31.Rxe5 ?  dxe5  32.Qxe5  Bxa3  leaves White completely lost. His back rank must be defended and for that reason the c1-rook is unable to keep protecting the vital c4-pawn from immediate capture. }
31... Rxe3
{ The pawn trade   31...Rxf5  32.Qd3  was perhaps not as promising. } 32. Qxe3
Qb2
{ Black's queen obtains its entry point and the repercussions are immediate. }
33. Nd3 Qxa3 34. Qxf3 Qa2
{ It may be called a miracle that material is still level. But it is clear that the white pieces do not work together, his king protection is limited and the centre is beyond repair. But now material joins the list of problems White has to surmount. }
35. Bc3
{ Neither does White keep the material after   35.Qd1  Rxc4  36.Ra1  Qc2 ! }
35... Rxc4
{ Beginning to clean up.  It was also possible to consider   35...Nd7 !?  , deferring material gains for the time being and maintaining the Black kingside pawn structure. }
36. Ra1 Qb3 37. Bxf6 gxf6 38. Kg2
{ Perhaps under some clock pressure as well, White goes wrong.  Some drawing chances were retained by   38.Qd1 !  Qb5  39.Nf4  a5  although I suspect Carlsen would still have won. }
38... Rc3 39. Rd1
{ 39.Qg4+  Bg7  40.Nf4  also loses to  Qb2+  41.Kh3  Qxa1  42.Nh5  Qf1+  43.Kh4  Rc4 }
39... h5 { A precise move to limit the opponent's counterchances. } 40. Kh3 Bh6
41. Re1 Rxd3 42. Qxh5 Re3
{ The point was that after   42...Re3  43.Rc1  Black has the simple answer  Rxg3+ !  44.hxg3  Bxc1  prepared. }
*

