[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scheveningen: Introduction"]
[Black "Background of the Scheveningen"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6
{ The Scheveningen variation is named after a Dutch seaside town situated near The Hague.   During a tournament held there in 1923, future world champion Max Euwe tried the opening against Geza Maroczy  (1870-1951)  .   Black would like to prepare short castling with ...Be7 and then swiftly depart the center with his king. The knights most often go to their intuitive posts on c6 and f6, and the queen's bishop to d7. Then Black can decide whether he would like to continue with  ...a7-a6 and ...Qd8-c7, after which he will have connected his rooks.  A recurring theme for Black in these positions is that he can  (by means of ... Nc6xd4 and Bd7-c6)  reduce White's influence in the center. A subsidiary but no less important theme is the idea of ...e6-e5, liquidating some central pawns  (if f4 advance has been played)  and increasing the scope of Black's pieces.    Finally, we note that many black players omit the development of the queen's bishop. In addition to the usual idea of going to d7 as above, Black also has the option  (if he can manage this ...e6-e5)  of completing development with ...Be6 instead.  It is also worth bearing in mind that this bishop can also often reach the long diagonal after ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scheveningen: Introduction"]
[Black "Fundamentals of the Scheveningen"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lots of players have asked me how to get started in the Sicilian, or which line to learn first. The question might be asked by a player with a classical style who is looking for something a bit more interesting than 1. e4 e5, or by anyone who wants an opening to play against lower-rated players with Black.   In either case, almost any Sicilian line would be acceptable, because there is a lot of play in the resulting positions. But where to start ? Almost all World Champions have mastered at least one variation of the opening from the Black side. Garry Kasparov, for example, popularised the Scheveningen variant, which he then published a book about, together with his trainer/second Alexander Nikitin.   The most important reason to start with the Scheveningen system is that this opening can actually be played without too much theoretical knowledge, provided you have a fair degree of common sense. Of course, there are traps, but my experience is that generally, well-educated players manage to survive in unfamiliar positions, unless they are just too complicated.   The following outline describes the essence of the Scheveningen system. Black develops his knights to the logical squares f6 and c6, the bishops go to e7 and d7, the king castles quickly so that the rooks are connected, and the queen sits happily on c7. She is unlikely to be disturbed there because at one moment or other black has typically included ... a7-a6 to protect against a knight intrusion on b5.   Moving into the early middlegame, Black can also try and gain space on the queenside with ... b7-b5. There are various choices for the Black rooks, but a common formation is to have them on c8 and e8. We often see that they go to c8 and e8. A typical trade he may choose to execute is ... Nc6xd4, freeing up the c6-square for his bishop and ensuring that a future ... e6-e5 wins a tempo. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ We take this to be the 'official' way of reaching the Scheveningen. Of course, one has to bear in mind that there are two orders by which this position can be reached, as well as various ways to transpose  (from other Sicilian systems)  into the material that follows.   The Scheveningen's debut in high-level play was made at a strong tournament held in 1923 a Dutch spa town of the same name  (it is situated near Den Haag, on the North Sea.)  Several players tried the opening during the event  (including the local hero and future world champion Euwe, who played it against Maróczy)  , hence the choice to name it after the town instead!   The basic set-up is, as mentioned:   
 knights to f6 and c6;   bishops  (usually)  to e7 and d7;   short castling;   queen on c7;   rooks on c8 and e8;   ...a7-a6, and then either ...b7-b5-b4  (if possible)  or    a knight manoeuvre to c4 or an exchange for the knight on d4  
  A short introduction, but it's almost enough to get started with already. You might as well try and use this knowledge to play practice games with the Scheveningen, so you have some experience and fun while you set up your repertoire- then enter your game in a database, look for other similar games, rinse and repeat! You're on your way to becoming a Sicilian player...  Chessable note: In this course, the material from the book devoted to the Scheveningen is divided into several subsequent chapters, as follows:  
 Overview Of Scheveningen #1: 6 f4  (Tal Variation)     Overview Of Scheveningen #2: 6 Bc4  (Fischer-Sozin Variation)     Overview Of Scheveningen #3: 6 g4  (Keres Attack)     Overview Of Scheveningen #4: 6 Be3 e6  (English Attack)     Overview Of Scheveningen #5: 6 Be2  (Classical Variation)     Scheveningen: Model Games }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #1: 6 f4"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.f4 (Tal Variation): Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. f4
{ For people whose repertoire includes the Open Sicilian with White, but don't want to learn reams of theory, this move is a sensible choice. John Nunn advocated it in his 'Beating the Sicilian'. On Wikipedia this move is quoted as the 'Tal Variation', after the eighth world champion. }
6... a6
{ Black hopes to lead the position back into 'Najdorf courts'.  I learned through painful experience that the immediate   6...Nc6  allows White a very interesting setup with which he can try and storm Black's position immediately.  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qf3  Not messing around. White intends to start operations on the d-file as soon as possible  (with long castling)  and also keeps the g2-g4-g5 thrust on the cards. A little more hidden, but no less dangerous, is the idea to put pressure on point e6 with Nd4xc6, followed by Bf1-c4 and f4-f5. This move has been dubbed the 'Boey variation' after multiple Belgian champion- and correspondence grandmaster- Josef Boey.  O-O  The attempt to hit back in the centre right away with   8...e5  can be met by  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.f5  Now Black has several tries:  Qa5   10...d5  tries to free Black's game, but there's a nasty cross-pin after  11.exd5  cxd5  12.O-O-O  Bb7  13.Bc4  - as seen in a game Lutz-Vogt.   10...Rb8  would be a clever way to set up ...d6-d5 next and avoid the above line, if White did not also have a precise order at his disposal.  11.Bc4 !  As seen in Boey-Hartoch, 1974,  although White later lost the game.  11.Bc4  Now Radjabov-Morozevich, 2006 and Sigurjonsson-Sax, 1976 are good illustrative games to follow. Both sides will connect their rooks on the same move following the natural  Bb7  12.O-O-O  O-O  .  9.O-O-O  Qc7  10.g4  One should be aware that this move implies a pawn sacrifice.  Nxd4  11.Bxd4  e5  12.fxe5  dxe5  One of White's tactical points comes in the line   12...Bxg4  13.Qg3  dxe5   13...Bxd1 ?  14.exf6  Bxf6  15.Bxf6  wins for White.  14.Bxe5  Qc5  15.Bxf6  Bxf6   15...Bxd1 ??  16.Qxg7#  16.Rd5 !  Also winning is   16.Qxg4 ?!  Bxc3  17.bxc3  Qxc3  but Black's practical counterchances here are significant.  16...Qc8  17.Rg1  Be6  18.e5  Bxd5  19.Nxd5  White gains decisive material.  13.Qg3  Nxg4  14.Nd5  and White had good chances in the game Sax-Kasparov, 1983. }
7. Qf3
{ Because it turns out that white is too late to start with 7. Be3  (Black gets exactly enough time to put his bishop on b7 to oppose the queen on the long diagonal)  White chooses this order.  It took a while for people to understand that   7.Be3  is not a good way for White to seek an advantage. Black replies with the immediate  b5  so as to meet  8.Qf3  with  Bb7  and now Black has his fair share of the tactics along the long diagonal. Specifically:  9.Bd3  Nbd7  10.g4  (b4 !   This is a significant improvement of Black's game. In Timman-Hodgson,1983, Black failed to continue like this.)  Instead Black immediately played   10...Nc5  and White gained the upper hand because the move doesn't gain tempo.  11.g5  b4   11...Nfd7  12.a3  +=  12.gxf6  bxc3  13.fxg7  Bxg7  14.b4 !?  Nxd3+  15.cxd3  and White eventually won.  11.Nce2  Nc5  12.Ng3  Here Timman came up with a deep strategic idea for Black.  Rc8 !  Giving extra protection to the c5-knight.  13.g5  Nfd7  14.h4  e5 !  This is the idea: black now obtains the e5-square for one of his knights. White now more or less has to trade his dark-squared bishop off.  15.Nb3  exf4  16.Bxf4  Ne6 !  Of course, on strategic grounds this knight is worth more than the one on  b3.  White now continued in Chandler-Timman, 1984,  with:  17.Nf5  Black is also doing excellently if White chooses to give up the other bishop instead:   17.Be3  Ne5  18.Qe2  Nxd3+  19.cxd3  d5  .  17...Nxf4  18.Qxf4  Ne5  With this extremely powerful knight on e5 Black now holds the trumps in the position- but later he fell into difficulties. }
7... Qb6
{ The queen will not stay here, but Black is rather just trying to drive the d4-knight back to a worse square. Then he'll retreat the queen co c7 and continue with ... b7-b5 so as to meet the usual tactic of e4-e5 with the simple ...Bb7. Now White normally responds: }
8. Nb3
{ and Black retreats 'as promised' to c7.  White can opt out of this mutual loss of tempo:   8.a3 !?  which is an interesting idea- White keeps the knight's central post through tactics. Apparently it was GM Quinteros who first applied this idea in his game against Salazar in 1982.  Nc6  The point is of course that   8...Qxd4 ?  9.Be3  traps the queen. Now the creative Dutch IM Manuel Bosboom played  Qxc3+  10.bxc3  Bd7  and claimed that Black's position was playable...Back in the real world, though, it would be irresponsible for me to give this line as a recommendation to anyone.  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.b3  Now that black has the b-file instead of the c-file, it doesn't matter so much if the c3-knight is briefly vulnerable. The bishop will be well situated on b2 and White intends to castle long.  Bb7  11.Bb2  d5  12.O-O-O  This move isn't good, but White must almost play it anyway, otherwise his concept makes no sense.  Qa5  13.e5  Nd7  14.Na4  Qc7  In the Almasi-Kasparov, 1994,  game Black quickly gained the upper hand because the white king is rather unsafe. }
8... Qc7 9. g4 { Consistent with what we have said about White's plan. } 9...
b5 10. g5 Nfd7
{ 10...b4  did not work out so well for Black in J.Polgar-Van Wely, 1995. } 11.
Be3
{ Over the years, various players have tried almost all the possible riffs on the motif of a kingside attack. For instance   11.Bd3  Bb7  and now a switch of diagonal:  12.Qh3  with the threat g5-g6. In most cases, sharp positions arise in which Black is not worse.  GM Smirin swears by   11.a3  with which he managed to win some games. }
11... Nb6 12. O-O-O N8d7 13. Qh3 b4 14. Ne2 Nc4
{ Thus far as in Polgar-Kasparov, 1996. After Black executes the basically forced trade of this knight for the opponent's e3-bishop, he doesn't really have any problems. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #1: 6 f4"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.f4 (Tal Variation) #1: Black plays early Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. f4
{ For people whose repertoire includes the Open Sicilian with White, but don't want to learn reams of theory, this move is a sensible choice. John Nunn advocated it in his 'Beating the Sicilian'. On Wikipedia this move is quoted as the 'Tal Variation', after the eighth world champion. }
6... a6 { Black hopes to lead the position back into 'Najdorf courts'. } 7. Qf3
{ Because it turns out that white is too late to start with 7. Be3  (black gets exactly enough time to put his bishop on b7 to oppose the queen on the long diagonal, white chooses this order.)  It took a while for people to understand that   7.Be3  is not a good way for White to seek an advantage. Black replies with the immediate  b5  so as to meet  8.Qf3  with  Bb7  and now Black has his fair share of the tactics along the long diagonal. Specifically:  9.Bd3  Nbd7  10.g4  (b4 !   This is a significant improvement of Black's game. In Timman-Hodgson,1983, Black failed to continue like this.)  Instead Black immediately played   10...Nc5  and White gained the upper hand because the move doesn't gain tempo.  11.g5  b4   11...Nfd7  12.a3  +=  12.gxf6  bxc3  13.fxg7  Bxg7  14.b4 !?  Nxd3+  15.cxd3  and White eventually won.  11.Nce2  Nc5  12.Ng3  Here Timman came up with a deep strategic idea for Black.  Rc8 !  Giving extra protection to the c5-knight.  13.g5  Nfd7  14.h4  e5 !  This is the idea: black now obtains the e5-square for one of his knights. White now more or less has to trade his dark-squared bishop off.  15.Nb3  exf4  16.Bxf4  Ne6 !  Of course, on strategic grounds this knight is worth more than the one on  b3.  White now continued in Chandler-Timman, 1984,  with:  17.Nf5  Black is also doing excellently if White chooses to give up the other bishop instead:   17.Be3  Ne5  18.Qe2  Nxd3+  19.cxd3  d5  .  17...Nxf4  18.Qxf4  Ne5  With this extremely powerful knight on e5 Black now holds the trumps in the position- but later he fell into difficulties. }
7... Qb6
{ The queen will not stay here, but Black is rather just trying to drive the d4-knight back to a worse square. Then he'll retreat the queen co c7 and continue with ... b7-b5 so as to meet the usual tactic of e4-e5 with the simple ...Bb7. Now White normally responds: }
8. Nb3
{ and Black retreats 'as promised' to c7.  White can opt out of this mutual loss of tempo:   8.a3 !?  which is an interesting idea- White keeps the knight's central post through tactics. Apparently it was GM Quinteros who first applied this idea in his game against Salazar in 1982.  Nc6  The point is of course that   8...Qxd4 ?  9.Be3  traps the queen. Now the creative Dutch IM Manuel Bosboom played  Qxc3+  10.bxc3  Bd7  and claimed that Black's position was playable...Back in the real world, though, it would be irresponsible for me to give this line as a recommendation to anyone.  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.b3  Now that black has the b-file instead of the c-file, it doesn't matter so much if the c3-knight is briefly vulnerable. The bishop will be well situated on b2 and White intends to castle long.  Bb7  11.Bb2  d5  12.O-O-O  This move isn't good, but White must almost play it anyway, otherwise his concept makes no sense.  Qa5  13.e5  Nd7  14.Na4  Qc7  In the Almasi-Kasparov, 1994,  game Black quickly gained the upper hand because the white king is rather unsafe. }
8... Qc7 9. g4 { Consistent with what we have said about White's plan. } 9...
b5 10. g5 Nfd7
{ 10...b4  did not work out so well for Black in J.Polgar-Van Wely, 1995. } 11.
Be3
{ 11.Bd3  Bb7  and now a switch of diagonal:  12.Qh3  with the threat g5-g6. In most cases, sharp positions arise in which Black is not worse.  GM Smirin swears by   11.a3  with which he managed to win some games. }
11... Nb6 12. O-O-O N8d7 13. Qh3 b4 14. Ne2 Nc4
{ Thus far as in Polgar-Kasparov, 1996. After Black executes the basically forced trade of this knight for the opponent's e3-bishop, he doesn't really have any problems. }
