[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. f4
{ For people whose repertoire includes the Open Sicilian with White, but don't want to learn reams of theory, this move is a sensible choice. John Nunn advocated it in his 'Beating the Sicilian'. On Wikipedia this move is quoted as the 'Tal Variation', after the eighth world champion. }
6... Nc6
{ allows White a very interesting setup with which he can try and storm Black's position immediately. }
7. Be3 Be7 8. Qf3
{ Not messing around. White intends to start operations on the d-file as soon as possible  (with long castling)  and also keeps the g2-g4-g5 thrust on the cards. A little more hidden, but no less dangerous, is the idea to put pressure on point e6 with Nd4xc6, followed by Bf1-c4 and f4-f5. This move has been dubbed the 'Boey variation' after multiple Belgian champion- and correspondence grandmaster- Josef Boey. }
8... e5 { can be met by } 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. f5
{ . Now Black has several tries: } 10... Qa5
{ 10...d5  tries to free Black's game, but there's a nasty cross-pin after  11.exd5  cxd5  12.O-O-O  Bb7  13.Bc4  - as seen in a game Lutz-Vogt.   10...Rb8  would be a clever way to set up ...d6-d5 next and avoid the above line, if White did not also have a precise order at his disposal.  11.Bc4 !  As seen in Boey-Hartoch, 1974,  although White later lost the game. }
11. Bc4
{ Now Radjabov-Morozevich, 2006 and Sigurjonsson-Sax, 1976 are good illustrative games to follow. Both sides will connect their rooks on the same move following the natural  11...Bb7  12.O-O-O  O-O }
11... Bb7 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Bb3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #2: 6 Bc4"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Bc4 (Sozin system): Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4
{ A Fischeresque system- he used to play this way against the Najdorf. } 6...
Be7
{ 6...a6  brings us back to the Najdorf proper.  Meanwhile   6...Nc6  offers another transposition, to the Sozin variation of the Classical Sicilian.  Analogously to the 6. Bc4 Najdorf, White retreats this bishop to b3 immediately, thereby preventing tricks based on ...Nxe4 and then the pawn fork ...d5. }
7. Bb3
{ While this is the most important move, there are alternatives to the immediate bishop retreat that are worth mentioning.  The extremely sharp   7.g4  h6  8.Be3  a6  9.Bb3  b5  featured in a blitz game Khusnutdinov-Aronian, 2016.   7.Be3  O-O  8.Qe2  a6  leads to an interesting fight.  9.a4   9.O-O-O  b5  10.Bb3  b4  quickly got out of control for White in Mirabile-Kamsky, 2005.  Now in Papp-Firat, 2012,  Black stirred the hornet's nest with  9...Nxe4  10.Nxe4  d5  but after  11.O-O-O  it worked out to his opponent's advantage. }
7... O-O
{ Black should take note that   7...Nbd7 ?  is not to be played. His kingside pawns are now put to the sword -starting with the typical sacrifice  8.Bxe6 !  as happened in  Kobese-Lopez, 2010.  fxe6  9.Nxe6  Qa5  10.Nxg7+  Kf7  11.Nf5  with a large advantage for White. }
8. Be3 Na6
{ Here we see an important difference between the Scheveningen and Najdorf systems. The knight comes to c5- but it doesn't need to do so via d7. The a6-square is now not occupied by a pawn so Black can use it as a rest-stop for the knight and avoid the sacrificial motifs on e6. }
9. f4 Nc5 10. Qf3
{ This is an interesting position. White has developed all his minor pieces, but not yet committed his king. He can still therefore castle on either side, or  (in theory)  not at all. Black also has a choice now- his is to do with how he develops his queenside. }
10... a5
{ This possibility has independent  (i.e. non-Najdorf)  significance. I have some experience with it myself. The plan is to simply throw the a-pawn forward as hard as it will go, and hope to break up White's queenside structure.  The equally logical   10...a6  leads the game more or less back onto a Najdorf-type trajectory. I won't elaborate on this possibility beyond mentioning that it exists. }
11. O-O-O
{ It's critical that White can't stop the a-pawn before it even gets started:   11.a4 ?!  e5  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.Nf5  Bxf5  14.exf5  e4  15.Qe2  Nxb3  16.cxb3  Here Black basically has an extra pawn because there is no prospect of White managing to solve the issue of his doubled pawns in the short- or medium-term.  My opponent in Moe-Grooten, 1984 chose the 'hell-for-leather' approach:  11.f5 ?!  with the continuation  a4  12.Bc4  a3  13.fxe6 ?  fxe6  14.Nf5  axb2  15.Rb1  . Rather than continue this line here, though, I shall leave it as an example- it can be found in that part of the book. Finding a strong continuation here took me rather a lot of time. }
11... a4 12. Bc4 a3 13. b3
{ Now in various games, including a couple by Romanian Mihai Suba, there followed now a pseudo-sacrifice on e4: }
13... Nfxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 d5 16. Bxd5 exd5
{ Black has at least equalised. To compensate for his isolated pawn, he has the bishop pair. Perhaps even more important though is the fact that White's queenside castled position is not secure; the holes created by the battering-ram on the a-file  (as well as the continuing presence of the pawn itself)  lead to a significant number of mate motifs. }
*

