[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #3: 6 g4"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.g4 (Keres Attack): Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4
{ Causing the game to enter the Keres Attack, a sharp line which we can consider as an important 'independent' possibility arising from the canonical Scheveningen order  (i.e. this one.)  Notice that the analogous White 6th move is not possible in the Najdorf. }
6... h6
{ The most principled answer.  Black can also let the White attack continue and hope it burns out:   6...Nc6  7.g5  Nd7  8.Be3  Be7  9.h4  O-O  Black 'castles into it'- a dangerous decision at the best of times. Now there are some beautiful attacking games for White; but amidst all the chaos Black's position continues to impress, time and time again, with its resilience.  10.Qd2  a6  11.O-O-O  This position has long been the subject of discussion. White will soon be ready for decisive action with f2-f4 or Rh1-g1, then h4-h5 and eventually g5-g6. But while he does this, Black will not be idle. With ... Nxd4 and ... b5 followed by ...Bb7 he can complete his development. Once that has been done, his play comes apace as well. For instance ...b5-b4 and the remaining knight to c5 or e5. His rooks may come to b8 and c8, or Black can opt for a pawn storm just as White has done on the opposite side. An exciting fight is guaranteed ! }
7. h4 Nc6
{ The most normal and logical move.  Previously   7...Be7  was also an often-played line. The main idea was that  8.Rg1  can be met by:  d5  -following the principle that a push on the flank should be countered by one in the centre.  9.exd5  The point of preparing with 7... Be7 is that following the disruptive check   9.Bb5+  Black can step aside with the king rather than having to weaken his centre.  Kf8  Yet despite the solid reasoning, this is not necessarily a healthy way for Black to proceed. White now plays  10.e5  and an example of how fast things can go wrong for Black is seen in the game Panchanathan - Yermolinsky, 2010.  9...Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  Black has obtained good results from this position. }
8. Rg1 h5
{ This looks strange at first sight. With ... h6, black seemed to be trying to slow down White's pawn storm a bit, but now he reverses his decision and provokes g4-g5. }
9. gxh5
{ And this is also paradoxical, but White benefits more from having the g-file open.  Practice has shown that after   9.g5  Ng4  10.Be2  Qb6  Black doesn't have any problems at all, as seen- inter alia- in the game Rodriguez-Adorjan, 1982. }
9... Nxh5
{ Adorjan quite often played   9...Rxh5  10.Bg5  Rh8  obtaining the same position as in the game, but with one crucial difference: Black has lost the right to castle short. This could come back to haunt him later. }
10. Bg5 Nf6 11. Qd2 Qb6 12. Nb3
{ White does not want the queens to be traded, because Black would obtain an advantage in the endgame due to his better pawn structure. }
12... a6
{ Black has managed to build a defensive setup with his pawns on the third rank that is rather difficult to break down in practice. The Swedish GM Ulf Andersson is a master at playing this system. }
13. O-O-O Bd7
{ The game Cardoso-Andersson, 1974 now gives a good account of Black's prospects, while the White plans can be seen in the game Badolati - Hoyos Millan  (e-mail)  . }
*

