{ Black has managed to build a defensive setup with his pawns on the third rank that is rather difficult to break down in practice. The Swedish GM Ulf Andersson is a master at playing this system. }
13. O-O-O Bd7
{ The game Cardoso-Andersson, 1974 now gives a good account of Black's prospects, while the White plans can be seen in the game Badolati - Hoyos Millan  (e-mail)  . }
14. Kb1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #3: 6 g4"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.g4 (Keres Attack) #2: Black reacts with h6-d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4
{ Causing the game to enter the Keres Attack, a sharp line which we can consider as an important 'independent' possibility arising from the canonical Scheveningen order  (i.e. this one.)  Notice that the analogous White 6th move is not possible in the Najdorf. }
6... h6 { The most principled answer. } 7. h4 Be7
{ was also an often-played line. The main idea was that } 8. Rg1
{ can be met by: } 8... d5
{ Following the principle that a push on the flank should be countered by one in the centre. }
9. exd5
{ 9.Bb5+  Black can step aside with the king rather than having to weaken his centre.  9...Kf8  Yet despite the solid reasoning, this is not necessarily a healthy way for Black to proceed. White now plays  10.e5  and an example of how fast things can go wrong for Black is seen in the game Panchanathan - Yermolinsky, 2010. }
9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Be3
{ Black has obtained good results from this position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #3: 6 g4"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.g4 (Keres Attack) #3: Black allows g5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4
{ Causing the game to enter the Keres Attack, a sharp line which we can consider as an important 'independent' possibility arising from the canonical Scheveningen order  (i.e. this one.)  Notice that the analogous White 6th move is not possible in the Najdorf. }
6... Nc6 7. g5 Nd7 8. Be3 Be7 9. h4 O-O
{ Black 'castles into it'- a dangerous decision at the best of times. Now there are some beautiful attacking games for White; but amidst all the chaos Black's position continues to impress, time and time again, with its resilience. }
10. Qd2 a6 11. O-O-O
{ This position has long been the subject of discussion. White will soon be ready for decisive action with f2-f4 or Rh1-g1, then h4-h5 and eventually g5-g6. But while he does this, Black will not be idle. With ... Nxd4 and ... b5 followed by ...Bb7 he can complete his development. Once that has been done, his play comes apace as well. For instance ...b5-b4 and the remaining knight to c5 or e5. His rooks may come to b8 and c8, or Black can opt for a pawn storm just as White has done on the opposite side. An exciting fight is guaranteed ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #4: 6 Be3"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Be3 (English Attack): Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 a6
{ 6...Be7  A sensible and common pattern of play for Black in the Scheveningen: the idea is to castle quickly and only later make decisions regarding the queenside.  7.f3  O-O  8.Qd2  The outlines of the English attack can now be seen clearly. If Black plays ...a6 at any moment from moves 7-9, we will reach a position discussed within 6... a6, so let's continue looking at what happens if he avoids the move permanently.  Nc6  9.O-O-O  By now the only indepdendent move left is:  d5  . The truism is that this break is something Black would always like to accomplish in the Sicilian. While it most often occurs in response to a kingside pawn thrust from White, one can also execute it here- as quite a few strong players have done. It is important that white cannot immediately respond with e4-e5, which is why black first put his horse on c6.  10.Be2 !?  The most promising continuation for White, completing development and connecting the rooks.   10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  As in other subvariations shown here White seems to have an advantage, it has been proven that in practice Black does not have great problems reaching a draw.  10...dxe4  ()  (A rapid game)  Giri-Van Wely, 2017 continued  10... a6 11. Kb1 Qc7 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Nb3  (Improving upon)   14.f4   after which Black won in a game  Balogh-Van Wely, 2016.  14...Rd8  And here White can be said to be better, but that proved insufficient to win in the end.   11.Nxc6  This is White's idea. He hopes to reach an advantage in the endgame by virtue of his better piece co-ordination. To which end he begins exchanging pieces; this move scores rather well for him.  bxc6  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.Rxd8+  Bxd8  14.Rd1  Be7  15.Nxe4  Nxe4  16.fxe4  In this endgame White has a pawn majority on the queenside. Because his bishops are developed  (in contrast to Black's)  as well as having better targets in general, White has good winning chances here. }
7. f3
{ Since Black has played a fast ...a6, we've transposed into a Najdorf- specifically that line in which Black chooses ...e6 over the previously discussed ...e5. }
7... b5
{ The stereotypical thrust on the queenside. Black would like to take more space  (and possibly continue with ... b5-b4 to pose the question to White's knight)  and the move also guarantees the c8-bishop an active post in the near future. What is not so obvious is that Black implicitly agrees to keep his king in the centre. The advance g2-g4 will be answered with ... h7-h6, but that will mean that ... O-O is no longer really possible, because his majesty's position would be weakened too much.  Black can also castle quickly with   7...Be7  . While going for this short castling plan, Black adheres to the principle of not making pawn weaknesses on that side of the board. He can bide his time coolly in the face of the coming 'bayonet blast' White might play  (with g2-g4, g5, h2-h4 and then possibly h4-h5 and g5-g6)  . Only in response to the very last of these moves does Black finally need to take action- and even then he might not move a kingside pawn. The game might continue:  8.Qd2  O-O  9.O-O-O  Nc6  10.g4  Nxd4   10...Nd7  is also played, to try and get a knight on e5.  11.h4  Nde5  Threatening to take on d4 and then on f3.  12.Qg2  The queen assumes the menial task of defending f3. She can take some solace in the fact that she is also doing another two jobs: preparing the advance f3-f4 by defending the g-pawn; and lining up behind the g-pawn so that after it has advanced and cleared that file, mate will be easier to arrange !  Nxd4  13.Bxd4  Nc6  14.Be3  b5  15.g5  and now the game begins for real.  11.Bxd4  b5  12.g5  Nd7  13.h4  Note that Black is keeping the queen on d8. Thereby the advance h4-h5 is slowed down a bit more, because White has to worry about his g-pawn. Saying that, the queen can also be useful on c7 sometimes  (to help arrange the manoeuvre ... Nd7-e5-c4.)   This is a good time to think properly about Black's square choices for all his pieces in fact, not just the queen. There are a few different options to bear in mind for creating counterplay.   For starters, developing the queen's bishop to b7 seems to follow automatically from having played ...b7-b5, but that does not make it the best option. On b7, Black prepares a future ...d6-d5, and then after exd5 Bxd5, the bishop will occupy a very active post. White's central control then leaves something to be desired, which will slow down his attack.  On the other hand, Black could also play ... Bc8-e6 instead  (after ... e6-e5 and ...Nd7-c5/ b6.)  Then the bishop will support Black's own pawn storm on the queenside, as well as performing some defensive tasks on the kingside  (in particular, the f7-square comes to mind.)    13...b4  Black cannot do without this move. The c3-knight must be chased away. But there is a difference of learned opinion as regards timing. Both   13...Bb7  and   13...Qc7  were played here before black decided on ... b5-b4.  14.Na4  Here the knight serves as a barricade against the pawn-storm.   14.Ne2  a5  15.f4  Bb7  16.Ng3  Qc7  17.Kb1  gives Black very clearly defined counterchances - ...Nd7-c5, ...Rf8-b8, ...a5-a4.  14...Qa5  15.b3  Nc5  The knight on a4 must be traded off if Black is to obtain real counterplay on the queenside.  16.Bxc5  Since White also recognises this fact, he is prepared to give up his good bishop instead of the knight on a4 !  (dxc5  This interesting position has been tested many times in practice. Although black has the bishop pair, White's strong central position and his blockade on the a4 and especially c4 squares is)  (more than)  (sufficient for a small advantage. An example can be seen in the game Ye,J - Xu,J, 2003.)  The prophylactic   7...h5  historically did not have such a good reputation in the Scheveningen setup, but there are now many strong players defending this approach. In particular, elite American grandmaster Hikaru Nakamura believes in this way of playing. He lost with it to Caruana in 2016,  but beat Topalov twice in 2017. Black players who play this should realize that they can no longer play ...  O-O  after this because ... h7-h5 weakens the king's position too much, and that a White bishop can appear in short order on  g5  since Black has somewhat abandoned that square. In a Khalifman-Van Wely game, 2002,  the white player was able to demonstrate the defects of black's setup. }
8. Qd2
{ The pre-emptive   8.g4  would now rule out the defensive construction with ...h5, but it is far from clear that Black wants to do that anyway in the present structure. }
8... Nbd7
{ This appears to be the most precise order. The reason is that black wants to take control of the e5 square as soon as possible so that he does not see his plan of ... b5-b4 followed by ... d6-d5 met by e4-e5, which in most cases is advantageous for white. A knight on d4 is the perfect piece for White to have if Black has fixed pawns on d5 and e6.  It is probably too early for   8...Bb7  which can be met by:  9.a4  b4  10.Na2  Now Black basically needs to play  d5  for consistency, but now White gets to answer with e4-e5.  11.e5  Nfd7  12.f4    Here we see that the white knight has become very strong, mainly due to the very firm control White has of d4. Neither would it be a complete solution if Black at some stage traded knights on d4 with ...Nb8-c6xd4 because White would retain blockading capabilities. White has good chances here and proceeded to win in the Holzmueller-Guevara, 2009 e-mail game. }
9. g4 h6
{ Black holds back g4-g5 for the time being, but at the cost of weakening the kingside position so much as to make short castling impossible. Also, should White nevertheless manage to get g4-g5 in  (and perhaps even g5-g6)  there would automatically follow a very significant attack for him.  Another move that has been tried here is   9...Nb6  . Then White invariably continued:  10.a4 !  White is not going to castle long in the near future. He senses weakness in the Black queenside and proceeds to attack it without delay.  In one email game, though, White played something else:   10.O-O-O  Bb7  11.Qf2  Nfd7  12.Bd3  Rc8  13.Nce2  Qc7  14.Kb1  d5  15.e5  Qxe5  16.Nf4  Mueller-Jedrejowski, 2010  (email)  .  10...Nc4  11.Bxc4  bxc4  12.a5  So as to make Na4-b6 possible.  Bb7  13.Na4  d5  14.g5  Normally White would answer   14.e5  but the consistent followup  Nd7  15.f4  would simply lose a pawn to  Qh4+  .  14...Nd7  Finally the time has come for White to castle long. Here, it is an attacking move: the d-file is weak.  15.O-O-O !  A remarkable decision- incidentally, also a pawn sacrifice- but very well-founded. With almost all the pieces in the game, an underdeveloped black position and the king in the middle, white has every chance on his side.  dxe4  Even after a move like   15...Qc7  hinting at a possible flight by the king with ...O-O-O, White's attack goes through the defences like a hot knife through butter. For instance:  16.exd5  Bxd5  17.Rhe1  O-O-O  18.Bf4  Bd6  19.Bxd6  Qxd6  20.Nf5 !  with a huge advantage.  16.Rhf1  c3  Giving back the goodies.  17.Nxc3  The point of Black's idea is revealed if White takes with the Queen:   17.Qxc3  Rc8  The main idea! Black has counterplay.  17...Bb4  18.fxe4  Nc5  All seems to be in order, though it really isn't.  Incorrect is   18...Qxa5 ?  because of  19.Nb3  Qc7  and now the momentous  20.Rxf7 !!  This combination wins decisive material.  Kxf7  21.Qxd7+  Qxd7  22.Rxd7+  19.Qf2  The best move. White threatens both Qxf7# and various discoveries- chiefly Nc6 or Nxe6.  Another possibility is   19.Rxf7 !?  but Black declines the offer:  Qxa5 !  Chessable note Grooten stopped here, but it would appear that after Qe2 or Nb3, White has a large advantage   19...Kxf7 ?!  20.Qf2+  Kg8  21.Nc6  Qc7  22.Nxb4  gives White an advantage. Chessable note: It seems Grooten made a mistake in his evaluations. It is not entirely clear what happens after Black takes on e4.  19...Qe7  20.Nde2  Nxe4  Safer is   20...O-O  as played in Van Oosterom-Murray, 2007  (corr.)   but then too White will be left with a significant advantage after the game move,  21.Qh4 !  21.Nxe4  Bxe4  22.Qf4  Bg6  23.Qe5  O-O  24.Nf4  with a big advantage for white. The threat of Bd4 is just the tip of the iceberg. }
10. O-O-O Bb7 11. h4 b4
{ There is nothing to be gained by further preparation. } 12. Na4 Qa5 13. b3
{ This position has been the subject of investigations for a long time. Leading the way were the interesting encounters Kasparov-Topalov, 2001 and Caruana-Van Wely, 2016, in which many ideas of this position were illustrated. }
13... Nc5
{ The itchy hand wants to play   13...d5 ?  and indeed, it looks almost as if it could work. But there follows a nasty surprise.  14.e5 !  Nxe5  15.Nxe6  fxe6   15...d4  is the only move to save the queen but Black is completely busted after  16.Nxd4  anyway.  16.Bb6  White wins the queen. }
14. a3
{ All these moves were logical and more or less forced. White is now trying to use the fact that Black's b4-pawn is pinned. He threatens to simply take it. }
14... Nxa4
{ Here the move   14...Rc8  is also sometimes tried  (with the point axb4 Nxb3+)  but Black quickly falls into difficulties. A good illustration of White's attack after  15.Qxb4  Qc7  16.Kb1  is Anand-Kasimdzhanov, 2005. }
15. axb4 Qc7 16. bxa4
{ Black is down a pawn, and must now justify its absence somehow. } 16... d5
17. e5
{ White still prefers to keep the files and diagonals in the center closed, because his king's position is also open. This move also helps anchor the d4-knight firmly in position. }
17... Nd7 { The pawn is protected:   17...Qxe5 ??  18.Bf4  wins the queen. }
18. f4 { White is now fully prepared for f4-f5. } 18... Nb6
{ Black seems to be developing decent play, but now it transpires that with a few deft moves White can keep matters under control. }
19. Rh3
{ From the other side of the board, the rook helps with defensive duties along the third rank, making White's king position safer. }
19... Nxa4 20. Bf2 { Definitely not allowing Black the idea of ...Nc3. } 20...
Be7
{ After   20...Rc8  White has to use rather exceptional means to keep preventing the dangerous ... Nc3:  21.c4 !  dxc4  The c4-pawn acts as an 'umbrella' shielding White's king from the attack. As a result of its presence, the c-file is no longer usable  (in any meaningful sense)  as an attacking route.  22.Qc2  Nb6  23.Nxe6 !!  A wonderful sacrifice to break through Black's defenses. All of a sudden the white attacking pieces come to life.  fxe6  24.Bxb6  Qxb6  25.Qg6+  Ke7  26.f5  Black is oddly helpless against this mating attack. Lebedev-Sammut, 2009  (email.) }
21. f5
{ White has managed his kingside breakthrough. How White can continue from here is seen in the game Kovchan-Truskavetsky, 2002. }
*

