[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #4: 6 Be3"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Be3 (English Attack) #3: Early Nc4 manuever by Black #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 a6 7. f3
{ Since Black has played a fast ...a6, we've transposed into a Najdorf- specifically that line in which Black chooses ...e6 over the previously discussed ...e5. }
7... b5
{ The stereotypical thrust on the queenside. Black would like to take more space  (and possibly continue with ... b5-b4 to pose the question to White's knight)  and the move also guarantees the c8-bishop an active post in the near future. What is not so obvious is that Black implicitly agrees to keep his king in the centre. The advance g2-g4 will be answered with ... h7-h6, but that will mean that ... O-O is no longer really possible, because his majesty's position would be weakened too much.  The prophylactic   7...h5  historically did not have such a good reputation in the Scheveningen setup, but there are now many strong players defending this approach. In particular, elite American grandmaster Hikaru Nakamura believes in this way of playing. He lost with it to Caruana in 2016,  but beat Topalov twice in 2017. Black players who play this should realize that they can no longer play ...  O-O  after this because ... h7-h5 weakens the king's position too much, and that a White bishop can appear in short order on  g5  since Black has somewhat abandoned that square. In a Khalifman-Van Wely game, 2002,  the white player was able to demonstrate the defects of black's setup. }
8. Qd2
{ 8.g4  would now rule out the defensive construction with ...h5, but it is far from clear that Black wants to do that anyway in the present structure. }
8... Nbd7
{ 8...Bb7  which can be met by:  9.a4  b4  10.Na2  Now Black basically needs to play  10...d5  for consistency, but now White gets to answer with e4-e5.  11.e5  Nfd7  12.f4  Here we see that the white knight has become very strong, mainly due to the very firm control White has of d4. Neither would it be a complete solution if Black at some stage traded knights on d4   ...Nb8-c6xd4  because White would retain blockading capabilities. White has good chances here and proceeded to win in the Holzmueller-Guevara, 2009 e-mail game. }
9. g4 Nb6 { . Then White invariably continued: } 10. a4
{ White is not going to castle long in the near future. He senses weakness in the Black queenside and proceeds to attack it without delay. }
10... Nc4 11. Bxc4 bxc4 12. a5 { So as to make Na4-b6 possible. } 12... Bb7 13.
Na4 d5 14. g5
{ 14.e5  but the consistent followup  14...Nd7  15.f4  would simply lose a pawn to  15...Qh4+  . }
14... Nd7
{ Finally the time has come for White to castle long. Here, it is an attacking move: the d-file is weak. }
15. O-O-O
{ A remarkable decision- incidentally, also a pawn sacrifice- but very well-founded. With almost all the pieces in the game, an underdeveloped black position and the king in the middle, white has every chance on his side. }
15... dxe4 16. Rhf1 c3 { Giving back the goodies. } 17. Nxc3
{ The point of Black's idea is revealed if White takes with the Queen:   17.Qxc3  Rc8  The main idea! Black has counterplay. }
17... Bb4 18. fxe4 Nc5
{ All seems to be in order, though it really isn't.   18...Qxa5 ?  because of  19.Nb3  Qc7  and now the momentous  20.Rxf7 !!  This combination wins decisive material.  20...Kxf7  21.Qxd7+  Qxd7  22.Rxd7+ }
19. Qf2
{ The best move. White threatens both Qxf7# and various discoveries- chiefly Nc6 or Nxe6.  Another possibility is   19.Rxf7 !?  but Black declines the offer:  Qxa5 !  Chessable note Grooten stopped here, but it would appear that after Qe2 or Nb3, White has a large advantage   19...Kxf7 ?!  20.Qf2+  Kg8  21.Nc6  Qc7  22.Nxb4  gives White an advantage. Chessable note: It seems Grooten made a mistake in his evaluations. It is not entirely clear what happens after Black takes on e4. }
19... Qe7 20. Nde2 Nxe4
{ 20...O-O  as played in Van Oosterom-Murray, 2007  (corr.)  but then too White will be left with a significant advantage after the game move,  21.Qh4 ! }
21. Nxe4 Bxe4 22. Qf4 Bg6 23. Qe5 O-O 24. Nf4
{ with a big advantage for white. The threat of Bd4 is just the tip of the iceberg. }
*

