[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #4: 6 Be3"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Be3 (English Attack) #5: Black delays queenside expansion #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 a6 7. f3
{ Since Black has played a fast ...a6, we've transposed into a Najdorf- specifically that line in which Black chooses ...e6 over the previously discussed ...e5. }
7... Be7
{ . While going for this short castling plan, Black adheres to the principle of not making pawn weaknesses on that side of the board. He can bide his time coolly in the face of the coming 'bayonet blast' White might play  (with g2-g4, g5, h2-h4 and then possibly h4-h5 and g5-g6)  . Only in response to the very last of these moves does Black finally need to take action- and even then he might not move a kingside pawn. The game might continue:  The prophylactic   7...h5  historically did not have such a good reputation in the Scheveningen setup, but there are now many strong players defending this approach. In particular, elite American grandmaster Hikaru Nakamura believes in this way of playing. He lost with it to Caruana in 2016,  but beat Topalov twice in 2017. Black players who play this should realize that they can no longer play ...  O-O  after this because ... h7-h5 weakens the king's position too much, and that a White bishop can appear in short order on  g5  since Black has somewhat abandoned that square. In a Khalifman-Van Wely game, 2002,  the white player was able to demonstrate the defects of black's setup. }
8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. g4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. g5 Nd7 13. h4
{ Note that Black is keeping the queen on d8. Thereby the advance h4-h5 is slowed down a bit more, because White has to worry about his g-pawn. Saying that, the queen can also be useful on c7 sometimes  (to help arrange the manoeuvre ... Nd7-e5-c4.)  This is a good time to think properly about Black's square choices for all his pieces in fact, not just the queen. There are a few different options to bear in mind for creating counterplay. For starters, developing the queen's bishop to b7 seems to follow automatically from having played ...b7-b5, but that does not make it the best option. On b7, Black prepares a future ...d6-d5, and then after exd5 Bxd5, the bishop will occupy a very active post. White's central control then leaves something to be desired, which will slow down his attack. On the other hand, Black could also play ... Bc8-e6 instead  (after ... e6-e5 and ...Nd7-c5/ b6.)  Then the bishop will support Black's own pawn storm on the queenside, as well as performing some defensive tasks on the kingside  (in particular, the f7-square comes to mind.) }
13... b4
{ Black cannot do without this move. The c3-knight must be chased away. But there is a difference of learned opinion as regards timing. Both 13 ... Bb7 and 13 ... Qc7 were played here before black decided on ... b5-b4. }
14. Na4
{ Here the knight serves as a barricade against the pawn-storm.   14.Ne2  a5  15.f4  Bb7  16.Ng3  Qc7  17.Kb1  gives Black very clearly defined counterchances  (...Nd7-c5, ...Rf8-b8, ...a5-a4)  . }
14... Qa5 15. b3 Nc5
{ The knight on a4 must be traded off if Black is to obtain real counterplay on the queenside. }
16. Bxc5
{ Since White also recognises this fact, he is prepared to give up his good bishop instead of the knight on a4 ! }
16... dxc5 17. Qf4
{ This interesting position has been tested many times in practice. Although black has the bishop pair, White's strong central position and his blockade on the a4 and especially c4 fields is  (more than)  sufficient for a small advantage. An example can be seen in the game Ye,J - Xu,J, 2003. }
