[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Be3 (English Attack) #7: White delays kingside expansion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Be7
{ A sensible and common pattern of play for Black in the Scheveningen: the idea is to castle quickly and only later make decisions regarding the queenside. }
7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ The outlines of the English attack can now be seen clearly. If Black plays ...a6 at any moment from moves 7-9, we will reach a position discussed within 6... a6, so let's continue looking at what happens if he avoids the move permanently. }
8... Nc6 9. O-O-O { By now the only indepdendent move left is: } 9... d5
{ . The truism is that this break is something Black would always like to accomplish in the Sicilian. While it most often occurs in response to a kingside pawn thrust from White, one can also execute it here- as quite a few strong players have done. It is important that white cannot immediately respond with e4-e5, which is why black first put his horse on c6. }
10. Be2
{ The most promising continuation for White, completing development and connecting the rooks.   10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  Also White seems to have an advantage, it has been proven that in practice Black does not have great problems reaching a draw. }
10... dxe4
{ 10...a6  11.Kb1  Qc7  12.exd5  Nxd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Nb3   14.f4  after which Black won in a game Balogh-Van Wely, 2016.  14...Rd8  And here White can be said to be better, but that proved insufficient to win in the end. }
11. Nxc6
{ This is White's idea. He hopes to reach an advantage in the endgame by virtue of his better piece co-ordination. To which end he begins exchanging pieces; this move scores rather well for him. }
11... bxc6 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Rxd8+ Bxd8 14. Rd1 Be7 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. fxe4
{ In this endgame White has a pawn majority on the queenside. Because his bishops are developed  (in contrast to Black's)  as well as having better targets in general, White has good winning chances here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #5: 6 Be2"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Be2  (Classical): Overview "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2
{ This is called the Classical System of the Scheveningen. White develops his pieces to logical squares: bishops to e3 and e2, short castling and a quick f2-f4. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. f4 Nc6 9. Be3 a6
{ Many players on the black side of this opening choose to play this move now, seeing that it is  (by and large)  indispensable. It may be delayed by one further move, but as we will see, even this represents some kind of concession. After 9... a6, Black will now be able to develop his queen to c7  (without being bothered by moves like Ndb5)  and at the same time he will be ready, after an exchange of knights on d4, to continue with ..b7-b5.  Black can delay the move ...a7-a6 and try and continue in 'pure' Scheveningen fashion with   9...Bd7  which is an instructive move to consider in several respects. This position could, indeed, have also been reached by various other orders in which Black played only with his pieces. Black develops the last minor piece and so postpones for one more move the main decision: does Black want to play on the queenside with ...a6, ...b5  or in the centre with ...e5 ? The answer depends to a large degree on what White does about the prospective knight trade on d4.  10.Qe1 !?  Choosing to go for an attack.   10.Nb3 !  This is the very first example of a standard pattern where Black plays Bc8-d7, and White meets it with Nd4-b3.  For a full explanation of what is going on, see the note to Black's 10th in the main line. At first sight a strange move: White seemingly acknowledges that the exchange of knights would have been to Black's advantage, but then moves the same knight to a square where it doesn't seem that useful. However, he takes the sting out of ...e6-e5,  either with or without a preliminary trade of knights,  by ensuring that it doesn't hit a piece with tempo. So Black should revert to his queenside plans; the move ...a7-a6 can no longer be delayed.  a6  11.a4  Now we obtain, via a different move-order, the same kind of position as in the main line   i.e.  9...a6.  This version is somewhat in White's favour.  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  Bc6  This is the most natural response for Black. The e4-pawn hangs and this constitutes a serious roadblock to White's initiative.  12.Qg3  A useful little insertion for White: he can delay worrying about the e4-pawn for one move.  g6 !?  Now, though, something concrete must be done about the hanging pawn.  13.Bf3  This move avoids the concrete problem which the other bishop move has, but of course there is also a drawback: White now can't use the f3-square for a rook lift. Black has nothing to worry about.  Defending the pawn from d3 has a tactical drawback:   13.Bd3  Nh5  14.Qf2  Nxf4 !  15.Qxf4  e5  16.Qf2  It is less good to win a pawn with   16.Bxe5 ?!  dxe5  17.Qxe5  : Black's game plays itself and after the logical  Bd6  18.Qf6  Qxf6  19.Rxf6  Be5  20.Rff1  Bd4+  21.Kh1  Bxc3  22.bxc3  Rae8  Black had a large advantage in Areschenko-Ftacnik, 2005. He doubles on the e-file and in view of the pin there, the e4-pawn will very soon be regained, leaving him with good prospects in the endgame that follows.  16...exd4  17.Qxd4  Qa5 !  18.Kh1  Qe5  Black was still somewhat for choice in the game Sukandar-Alekseev, 2011.  13...b5  14.a3  a5  (In one move !)  15.Rae1  b4  Now in the games Zarnicki-Kasparov, 1998 and Rudolf-Mekhitarian, 2012 Black gained the upper hand. }
10. a4
{ Let us now clarify what the plans of both sides are. White will be attacking on the kingside, but will also have to decide in very short order exactly how he plans to proceed with this. The main way is to simply throw all the kingside pawns forward, beginning with the g-pawn: g2-g4-g5; and in this case White tends not to allow the opponent's idea of queenside expansion  (with ...Nxd4 and ...b5)  to come to fruition. The second idea is to play Qd1-e1-g3, i.e. posting the queen  (and perhaps also later the rook)  in front of his kingside pawns.  White could play in this second way starting immediately. With   10.Qe1  he initiates the plan of Qe1-g3 and Be2-d3. Then he will set to work opening the position with e4-e5 or f4-f5.  Nxd4  The older setup involves delaying the knight trade:   10...Bd7  11.Qg3  b5  12.a3  Nxd4  It is also interesting to play the queen to the b-file, from where she can initiate some pawn breaks.   12...Qb8 !?  13.Rad1  Nxd4  14.Bxd4  Bc6  Black had little to worry about in Kamsky-Potkin, 2008.  13.Bxd4  Bc6  14.Rae1  Qd7  Black connects his rooks and prepares to send the queen to b7 to put pressure on the white center.  15.Bd3  a5  16.b4  Necessary, because Black wanted to play ...b5-b4 himself.   16.e5  dxe5  17.Bxe5  is not a threat to Black.  16...axb4  17.axb4  e5 !?  After the inevitable complications Black achieved an advantageous endgame that he nevertheless did not win in Svidler-Van Wely, 1996.  11.Bxd4  b5  12.a3  Bb7  13.Qg3  g6  14.Bf3  By analogy to the 9... Bd7 10. Qe1 line, after   14.Bd3  Black can swap off the enemy dark-squared bishop by means of  Nh5  15.Qg4  Nxf4 !  16.Qxf4  e5  and now in the games Sychev-Alekseev, 2016  (blitz)  ( and Recuero Guerra-Fier, 2008, Black triumphed.)  14...a5  Note that in the analogous  9...Bd7  line  (mentioned in notes Black's 9th move)  Black was able to get his a-pawn to  a5  in one move. However, this may not be the most important factor in deciding your 9th move. Here, after both the  15.Nxb5  of Sutovsky-Van Wely, 2008   and the  15.b4  of Kamsky-Mamedyarov, 2008,   Black stood fine. }
10... Qc7
{ Black wants to create play on the queenside, stationing his bishop on b7 and the c6-knight on c4. As already established, White probably wants g2-g4-g5. But there are some nuances which hold both sides up in the execution of these logical plans. If White wants the pawn-storm, he must preface his attack with some prophylaxis against the idea of ...Nxd4 followed by ... e6-e5.   The point is not that this wins a pawn  (although that could be true.)  The point is that the centre will open up to Black's advantage and reveal the flank thrust g2-g4 to have been premature. So White wants to play the prophylactic Nd4-b3 at some stage. That move would threaten the positionally desirable a4-a5, and to avoid losing major space on the queenside Black would have to reply to Nd4-b3 with ... b7-b6. But there are two sides to the coin.   If those moves were inserted now, Black would have a logical plan with which to continue development- i.e. using the a8-h1 diagonal for his queen's bishop. So White postpones the knight's retreat until such time as Black's bishop has committed to the other development- i.e. ... Bc8-d7. Why can't Black start with ...b6 instead, you ask ? Well, White has a little tactic in mind: Nxc6 followed by Bf3, lining up an extremely nasty e4-e5 push that will win material.   In summary, a sort of standoff is occurring between the d4-knight and c8-bishop, where nobody wants to move first- but none of the constructive plans work for each respective side without those pieces moving ! Cue a tense waiting game. }
11. Kh1
{ A useful prophylactic move for several reasons. In this way white wants to prevent black from being able to force the swap of dark-squared bishops on c5 in any variation. In addition, a check on the b6-g1 diagonal is now not possible; and finally, White clears g1 as a retreat square for the e3-bishop in case it gets attacked by a future . ..Ng4.   11.Qe1  White can also still play his 'other' attacking plan in this position, though Black has a few answers.  Nxd4  This is the usual formula.  Black can also prepare a different sort of play with   11...Bd7  12.Qg3  Rac8  13.Kh1  and now  Nb4 !?  arguing that the move a2-a4 has left the b4-square weak.  There's also the idea   13...d5  14.e5  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Ne4  16.Qe3  , played in  Kramnik-Anand, 2003 and leading to rough equality.  12.Bxd4  e5  13.Be3     13.fxe5  dxe5  14.Qg3  Bc5  15.Bxc5  Qxc5+  and Black stood better  (having exchanged off the most effective White attacking piece)  (in)  Kovalev-Van Wely, 2014.   13...exf4  14.Bxf4  Be6  In this intricate position anything can happen. Black seems to have easily survived the opening, but in Jobava-Ivanisevic, 2008,  problems nevertheless appeared. }
11... Re8
{ Black, in turn, bides his time with a waiting move that offers his position various advantages. The f8-square is cleared for a bishop  (or knight !)  and lining up this rook with the e4-pawn and enemy queen is generally useful in the event of tactics in the centre.  As we have mentioned, trying to square the circle of the waiting game doesn't work.   11...b6 ?!  12.Nxc6  Qxc6  13.Bf3  and Black faces major problems.  The moment Black plays   11...Bd7  , the mechanism from the note to Black's 10th springs into action.  12.Nb3  b6  13.Bf3  Rab8  14.g4  Bc8  15.g5  Nd7  16.Bg2  Re8  17.Qd2  Bf8  18.Rad1  b5  19.axb5  axb5  20.Qd3  and Black faced major problems in Wang Hao - Kobalia, 2008. }
12. Bf3
{ Preventing the most desirable deployment of Black's c8-bishop- i.e. to b7. }
12... Rb8
{ Perhaps not strictly a waiting move, because in some cases Black may intend the very concrete ...b7-b5 push. But in any case the fundamental tension in the position remains.  It is still too early for   12...Bd7  -White as usual continues with the g4 plan.  13.Nb3  b6  14.g4  Bc8  15.g5  Nd7  16.Bg2  Bb7  17.Qg4 !?  White had some very interesting attacking possibilities in the blindfold game Anand-Van Wely, 1998. }
13. Qd2
{ Previously, White had lost his patience and simply pushed g4, which carries a rather clever idea made possible by Black's last move.   13.g4  Nxd4  14.Bxd4  e5  15.fxe5  dxe5  16.Ba7 !?  Ra8  17.g5  is the idea: White has avoided the capture of his dark-squared bishop with tempo, and it looks like he will get his knight to d5. However there is a strong and much-needed resource for Black.  Rd8 !  18.Qe2  Ne8  19.Be3  Be6  and by now in Topalov-Kasparov, 1996 it was obvious that White had overplayed his hand. }
13... Bd7
{ Black has exhausted his useful preparatory moves and now needs to get on with development. }
14. Nb3
{ White withdraws his horse from the centre. We already know why: the Black light-squared bishop has been committed to its second choice of square, and cannot so easily reach the h1-a8 diagonal after the automatic response ...b7-b6  (which stops White from clamping down on the queenside with a4-a5.)  Next, White can push his g-pawn without worrying about a reaction in the centre from Black  (as in Topalov-Kasparov above.) }
14... b6 15. g4 { The time is ripe for this push. } 15... Bc8
{ Reaching the long diagonal- which White has just weakened- is so important that Black loses two tempi in order to do it. Of course, the move also creates a retreat square for the f6-knight, which White was threatening to trap. On d7 the knight will stand quite nicely. }
16. g5 Nd7 17. Qf2
{ The queen hastens to the kingside.  Against the alternative   17.Bg2  Black has a very instructive move, specific to this structure and highly deserving of being remembered.  Na5  At first sight a very weird move. Black freely consents to doubled, isolated a-pawns. But the point is that with the two open files on the queenside he will develop compensation of more than sufficient value for the structural problems.  18.Nxa5  bxa5  19.b3  Bb7  20.Ne2  And Black had an advantage in Radjabov-Svidler, 2007. }
17... Bf8
{ Black needs to protect against the idea of Qh4 and Rf3-h3. White has telegraphed fairly clearly that this is what he wants: mate on h7. It is a simple and strong idea, but luckily Black is just in time to defend against it by playing ...g6, ...Bg7 and ...Nf8. }
18. Bg2 { Making way for the aforementioned rook-lift. } 18... Bb7 19. Rad1 g6
{ This position arose on the board in the 24th and final game of the 2nd Karpov-Kasparov world championship match- which happened in Moscow during the autumn of 1985. A world title was at stake. Kasparov held a one-point lead, but in the event of a tied match after 24 games, the reigning champion Karpov would retain his title. Despite this, Kasparov was by no means playing for a draw, even as Black. The game was sharp and thrilling; White gave it his all on the kingside, while Black countered on the queenside. Eventually Kasparov had to offer two pawns to halt the White initiative and weaken the enemy king position. He won the game, in the process beginning fifteen years as the generally acknowledged world champion. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #5: 6 Be2"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Be2  (Classical) #1: Mainline"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2
{ This is called the Classical System of the Scheveningen. White develops his pieces to logical squares: bishops to e3 and e2, short castling and a quick f2-f4. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. f4 Nc6 9. Be3 a6
{ Many players on the black side of this opening choose to play this move now, seeing that it is  (by and large)  indispensable. It may be delayed by one further move, but as we will see, even this represents some kind of concession. After 9... a6, Black will now be able to develop his queen to c7  (without being bothered by moves like Ndb5)  and at the same time he will be ready, after an exchange of knights on d4, to continue with ..b7-b5. }
10. a4
{ Let us now clarify what the plans of both sides are. White will be attacking on the kinsgide, but will also have to decide in very short order exactly how he plans to proceed with this. The main way is to simply throw all the kingside pawns forward, beginning with the g-pawn: g2-g4-g5; and in this case White tends not to allow the opponent's idea of queenside expansion  (with ...Nxd4 and ...b5)  to come to fruition. The second idea is to play Qd1-e1-g3, i.e. posting the queen  (and perhaps also later the rook)  in front of his kingside pawns. }
10... Qc7
{ Black wants to create play on the queenside, stationing his bishop on b7 and the c6-knight on c4. As already established, White probably wants g2-g4-g5. But there are some nuances which hold both sides up in the execution of these logical plans.   If White wants the pawn-storm, he must preface his attack with some prophylaxis against the idea of ...Nxd4 followed by ... e6-e5. The point is not that this wins a pawn  (although that could be true.)  The point is that the centre will open up to Black's advantage and reveal the flank thrust g2-g4 to have been premature. So White wants to play the prophylactic Nd4-b3 at some stage.   That move would threaten the positionally desirable a4-a5, and to avoid losing major space on the queenside Black would have to reply to Nd4-b3 with ... b7-b6. But there are two sides to the coin. If those moves were inserted now, Black would have a logical plan with which to continue development- i.e. using the a8-h1 diagonal for his queen's bishop. So White postpones the knight's retreat until such time as Black's bishop has committed to the other development- i.e. ... Bc8-d7. Why can't Black start with ...b6 instead, you ask ? Well, White has a little tactic in mind: Nxc6 followed by Bf3, lining up an extremely nasty e4-e5 push that will win material.   In summary, a sort of standoff is occurring between the d4-knight and c8-bishop, where nobody wants to move first- but none of the constructive plans work for each respective side without those pieces moving ! Cue a tense waiting game. }
11. Kh1
{ A useful prophylactic move for several reasons. In this way white wants to prevent black from being able to force the swap of dark-squared bishops on c5 in any variation. In addition, a check on the b6-g1 diagonal is now not possible; and finally, White clears g1 as a retreat square for the e3-bishop in case it gets attacked by a future . ..Ng4. }
11... Re8
{ Black, in turn, bides his time with a waiting move that offers his position various advantages. The f8-square is cleared for a bishop  (or knight !)  and lining up this rook with the e4-pawn and enemy queen is generally useful in the event of tactics in the centre.   11...b6 ?!  12.Nxc6  Qxc6  13.Bf3  and Black faces major problems. }
12. Bf3
{ Preventing the most desirable deployment of Black's c8-bishop- i.e. to b7. }
12... Rb8
{ Perhaps not strictly a waiting move, because in some cases Black may intend the very concrete ...b7-b5 push. But in any case the fundamental tension in the position remains. }
13. Qd2
{ Previously, White had lost his patience and simply pushed g4, which carries a rather clever idea made possible by Black's last move. }
13... Bd7
{ Black has exhausted his useful preparatory moves and now needs to get on with development. }
14. Nb3
{ White withdraws his horse from the centre. We already know why: the Black light-squared bishop has been committed to its second choice of square, and cannot so easily reach the h1-a8 diagonal after the automatic response ...b7-b6  (which stops White from clamping down on the queenside with a4-a5.)  Next, White can push his g-pawn without worrying about a reaction in the centre from Black. }
14... b6 15. g4 { The time is ripe for this push. } 15... Bc8
{ Reaching the long diagonal- which White has just weakened- is so important that Black loses two tempi in order to do it. Of course, the move also creates a retreat square for the f6-knight, which White was threatening to trap. On d7 the knight will stand quite nicely. }
16. g5 Nd7 17. Qf2
{ The queen hastens to the kingside.   17.Bg2  Black has a very instructive move, specific to this structure and highly deserving of being remembered.  17...Na5  At first sight a very weird move. Black freely consents to doubled, isolated a-pawns. But the point is that with the two open files on the queenside he will develop compensation-of more than sufficient value- for the structural problems.  18.Nxa5  bxa5  19.b3  Bb7  20.Ne2  And Black had an advantage in Radjabov-Svidler, 2007. }
17... Bf8
{ Black needs to protect against the idea of Qh4 and Rf3-h3. White has telegraphed fairly clearly that this is what he wants: mate on h7. It is a simple and strong idea, but luckily Black is just in time to defend against it by playing ...g6, ...Bg7 and ...Nf8. }
18. Bg2 { Making way for the aforementioned rook-lift. } 18... Bb7 19. Rad1 g6
20. Bc1
{ This position arose on the board in the 24th and final game of the 2nd Karpov-Kasparov world championship match- which happened in Moscow during the autumn of 1985. A world title was at stake. Kasparov held a one-point lead, but in the event of a tied match after 24 games, the reigning champion Karpov would retain his title. Despite this, Kasparov was by no means playing for a draw, even as Black. The game was sharp and thrilling; White gave it his all on the kingside, while Black countered on the queenside. Eventually Kasparov had to offer two pawns to halt the White initiative and weaken the enemy king position. He won the game, in the process beginning fifteen years as the generally acknowledged world champion. }
