11. Qe1
{ White can also still play his 'other' attacking plan in this position, though Black has a few answers. }
11... Nxd4
{ This is the usual formula.   11...Bd7  12.Qg3  Rac8  13.Kh1  and now  13...Nb4 !?  arguing that the move a2-a4 has left the b4-square weak.   13...d5  14.e5  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Ne4  16.Qe3  , played in Kramnik-Anand, 2003 and leading to rough equality.  14.Rac1  Chessable note: With complex play }
12. Bxd4 e5 13. Be3
{ 13.fxe5  dxe5  14.Qg3  Bc5  15.Bxc5  Qxc5+  and Black stood better  (having exchanged off the most effective White attacking piece)  (in Kovalev-Van Wely, 2014.) }
13... exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6
{ In this intricate position anything can happen. Black seems to have easily survived the opening, but in Jobava-Ivanisevic, 2008, problems nevertheless appeared after the queen sortie to g3. }
15. Qg3 *

