{ Many players on the black side of this opening choose to play this move now, seeing that it is  (by and large)  indispensable. It may be delayed by one further move, but as we will see, even this represents some kind of concession. After 9... a6, Black will now be able to develop his queen to c7  (without being bothered by moves like Ndb5)  and at the same time he will be ready, after an exchange of knights on d4, to continue with ..b7-b5. }
10. Qe1
{ he initiates the plan of Qe1-g3 and Be2-d3. Then he will set to work opening the position with e4-e5 or f4-f5. }
10... Bd7 11. Qg3 b5 12. a3 Nxd4
{ 12...Qb8 !?  13.Rad1  Nxd4  14.Bxd4  Bc6  Black had little to worry about in Kamsky-Potkin, 2008. }
13. Bxd4 Bc6 14. Rae1 Qd7
{ Black connects his rooks and prepares to send the queen to b7 to put pressure on the white center. }
15. Bd3 a5 16. b4
{ Necessary, because Black wanted to play ...b5-b4 himself.   16.e5  dxe5  17.Bxe5  is not a threat to Black. }
16... axb4 17. axb4 e5
{ After the inevitable complications Black achieved an advantageous endgame that he nevertheless did not win in Svidler-Van Wely, 1996. }
18. fxe5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Of Scheveningen #5: 6 Be2"]
[Black "Scheveningen with 6.Be2  (Classical) #8: Black plays early Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2
{ This is called the Classical System of the Scheveningen. White develops his pieces to logical squares: bishops to e3 and e2, short castling and a quick f2-f4. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. f4 Nc6 9. Be3 Bd7
{ An instructive move to consider in several respects. This position could, indeed, have also been reached by various other orders in which Black played only with his pieces. Black develops the last minor piece and so postpones for one more move the main decision: does Black want to play on the queenside  (...a6, ...b5)  or in the centre with ...e5 ? The answer depends to a large degree on what White does about the prospective knight trade on d4. }
10. Qe1
{ Choosing to go for an attack.   10.Nb3 !  This is the very first example of a standard pattern where Black plays ...Bc8-d7, and White meets it with Nd4-b3.  For a full explanation of what is going on, see the note to Black's 10th in the main line.  At first sight a strange move: White seemingly acknowledges that the exchange of knights would have been to Black's advantage, but then moves the same knight to a square where it doesn't seem that useful. However, he takes the sting out of ...e6-e5  (either with or without a preliminary trade of knights)  by ensuring that it doesn't hit a piece with tempo. So Black should revert to his queenside plans; the move ...a7-a6 can no longer be delayed.  10...a6  11.a4  Now we obtain, via a different move-order, the same kind of position as in the main line   i.e.  9...a6.  This version is somewhat in White's favour. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6
{ This is the most natural response for Black. The e4-pawn hangs and this constitutes a serious roadblock to White's initiative. }
12. Qg3
{ A useful little insertion for White: he can delay worrying about the e4-pawn for one move. }
12... g6
{ Now, though, something concrete must be done about the hanging pawn. } 13.
Bf3
{ This move avoids the concrete problem which the other bishop move has, but of course there is also a drawback: White now can't use the f3-square for a rook lift. Black has nothing to worry about.   13.Bd3  Nh5  14.Qf2  14...Nxf4 !  15.Qxf4  e5  16.Qf2   16.Bxe5 ?!  dxe5  17.Qxe5  : Black's game plays itself and after the logical  17...Bd6  18.Qf6  Qxf6  19.Rxf6  Be5  20.Rff1  Bd4+  21.Kh1  Bxc3  22.bxc3  Rae8  Black had a large advantage in Areschenko-Ftacnik, 2005. He doubles on the e-file and in view of the pin there, the e4-pawn will very soon be regained, leaving him with good prospects in the endgame that follows.  16...exd4  17.Qxd4  Qa5 !  18.Kh1  Qe5  Black was still somewhat for choice in the game Sukandar-Alekseev, 2011. }
13... b5 14. a3 a5 { In one move ! } 15. Rae1 b4
{ Now in the games Zarnicki-Kasparov, 1998 and Rudolf-Mekhitarian, 2012 Black gained the upper hand. }
16. Nd1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Tal, Mihail vs. Andreopoulos, Mark J, Long Beach 1988"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. f4 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qf3
O-O 9. O-O-O
{ Now that Black's queen on d8 is being 'opposed' along the d-file by a white rook, he has to be careful. }
9... a6
{ This push is somewhat careless.  With   9...Qc7  Black would manage to get the queen off the d-file, but this square is not so attractive. White has a variety of attacking possibilities.  The best reaction seems to be   9...Nxd4  10.Bxd4  Qa5  so that Black can continue with ...e6-e5. }
10. g4
{ This is the tried-and-tested approach, but Tal could have even struck immediately had he been alert:  The most natural move now is   10.e5 !  and indeed it confers a significant advantage upon White already.  Nxd4   10...dxe5 ??  11.Nxc6   10...Ne8  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Qxc6  is extremely favourable for White.  11.Bxd4  dxe5   11...Nd5  12.Nxd5  exd5  is also uninspiring for Black.  12.fxe5  Nd5  13.Ne4  This position carries a lot of immediate danger for Black. }
10... Qc7 11. g5 Nd7
{ This is the kind of moment that Tal was waiting for. And he wasn't the only one ! Velimirovic too, with his famous 'Velimirovic Attack', has often made use of the opportunity presented here. }
12. Nf5
{ This stereotypical horse sacrifice has been a major weapon in Tal's arsenal. He sacrifices a knight to free up the d5-square for his colleague, and with a pawn on f5  (which he will soon get)  he has the firepower needed to harass the enemy royal position in the minimum amount of time. }
12... b5
{ Black rejects the offer, but this isn't a cure either.  Let's take a close look at the acceptance of the sacrifice.   12...exf5  13.exf5  In this position Black has various alternatives.  Probably the calm  Bd8  is one to consider. The bishop does not hang here and the push f5-f6 does not come with gain of time. On the other hand, the bishop stands in the way of the other black pieces and the harmony in Black's camp is sorely lacking. How white should treat this position, though, is not immediately clear.  One obvious option is   13...Qa5 ?!  which White meets with the standard  14.f6 !  gxf6  15.Rg1 !?  fxg5  Trying to keep lines closed with   15...f5  is more or less a case of 'shutting the stable door after the horse has bolted'.  16.Qh5  and White has a wide range of attacking ideas, such as Rg1-g3-h3, Bf1-c4 or Nc3-d5 hinting at Nf6.  16.Bd3 !  Many of White's game-ending ideas are associated with this move.   16.Qh5  Kh8  17.Rd5  Qd8  18.Bd3  f5  19.fxg5  is also possible  16...f5  17.fxg5  Nde5  On the face of it, one might think Black is on the verge of repulsing his opponent's attack since he has taken control of the e5-square. But this would be a completely misleading impression to have.  18.Qh5  Threatening the lethal g5-g6.  Ng6  19.Bc4+  Kh8  20.Nd5  White has ideas of Bb6 as well as Bd2-c3.  Qd8  21.Bb6  Qd7   21...Qe8  22.Nc7  22.Qh6  Black can no longer slip the net which is gradually tightening around him. His pieces trip over each other in a manner which resembles one of those mate-in-two problems to which the answer is 1. Kg1-h1 !  Nce5   22...Bd8  23.Nf4 !  wins immediately.  23.Nf6  Finally making decisive use of Black's terrible co-ordination.  Bxf6  24.gxf6  Rxf6  25.Rxg6 !  Nxg6  26.Re1  White wins because there is nothing to be done about Bd4.  As an indication of how tricky the Black side of this position is, note that the natural   13...b5 ?  can be refuted immediately.  14.Nd5  Qd8  15.f6 !  Always the thematic way to open lines against the black king.  gxf6  16.gxf6  My silicon friend prefers   16.h4  ...  16...Nxf6  17.Bd3 !  White doesn't just threaten Nxf6 followed by Qh5 and mate, but also intends a swift doubling of major pieces on the g-file- which would have severe repercussions of its own.  Kh8  18.Nxf6  Bxf6  19.Qe4  Bxb2+  20.Kxb2  Qf6+  21.Kb1  Qh6  22.Qxc6  and White is even material up.  A subtle possibility for Black is   13...Re8  but then  14.f6  Bf8  15.Nd5  Qa5  16.Bc4  looks to promise good chances. White controls the flow of the struggle.  Probably  14.f6  g6  15.Nd5  is the way to go. }
13. Nd5
{ Tal in his element, a second knight sacrifice ! Perhaps objectively not entirely correct, but of course very difficult to combat in a practical game.  Another decent move is   13.Bg2  as given by the engine. }
13... exd5 14. exd5 Re8
{ Black is not up to the task.  A modern grandmaster would probably find the best way for Black to give back the piece:   14...Nde5  which leads after  15.Nxe7+  Qxe7  16.Qg3  Bf5  17.dxc6  Nxc6  to a position with roughly equal chances. The white attack has been stalled, mainly thanks to the strong f5-bishop. But the isolated pawn on d6 and the possession of the d5-square give White certain long-term advantages which demand a higher level of accuracy from Black to retain the balance going forward. }
15. dxc6 Nc5 16. Nxg7
{ And another knight sacrifice ! Now Black's king position is shattered. The new wave of attack is too much for him to deal with. }
16... Kxg7 17. f5 Bxf5
{ This is not going to help. There are a few other variations that also lose.   17...Bf8  18.Bd4+  Kg8  19.Rg1  The problem for black is that  (due to the strong white pawn on c6)  he cannot make his pieces work together. An example:  Bg7  20.Bxg7  Kxg7  21.Bg2  Kg8  22.Rge1  Re5  23.Rxe5  dxe5  24.b4  Na4  25.Qd3  Nb6  26.Be4  White has conducted the attack slowly, methodically and without rocket science. But now the genuinely deadly threat of Qd8+ has appeared and Black cannot bring any pieces at all to the defence, so his time is up.  After   17...Kg8  18.Rg1  Bf8  19.Bd4  there are no longer any normal methods by which Black can delay the catastrophe which ensues after g5-g6. }
18. Qxf5 Ne6 19. Bd3
{ After   19.Bd3  Rh8  20.Rdf1  Raf8  White can win immediately by forcing g5-g6 through.  21.Rhg1 !  Bd8  22.g6  hxg6  23.Rxg6+  fxg6  24.Qxg6#  with a picturesque epaulette mate. }
*

