[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Rogers, Ian vs. Arencibia Rodriguez, Walter, Salamanca, 1998"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. f4 a6 7. Qf3 Qb6
{ In this way Black would like to drive the active White knight away from its central post. }
8. Nb3
{ The knight stands less well here than on d4. Black suspects that at some point it will have to head back to d4, thus justifying his own use of two tempi rather than one to get his queen to c7. }
8... Nc6 9. Be3 Qc7 10. g4
{ White does not wait to set his flank attack in motion. } 10... b5
{ It is dangerous to try and hold back the floodwaters with   10...h6  in a game Beliavsky - Cabrilo, 1981, White was later able to play h2-h4 and force through g4-g5 anyway, whereupon the h-file fell into his hands. }
11. g5 Nd7 12. O-O-O
{ The most obvious way to play. White castles long,  (usually)  hides the king on b1 and only then looks at further options.There are players who, instead of this, find it necessary to try and castle short instead. That is of course not the safest idea, but it does have the advantage that if Black then places his own king on the queenside, White stands ready to attack the queenside with a2-a4.   12.Bd3  Bb7  Is the alternative route the game might take and now again White has to decide where to castle. }
12... Bb7 13. Kb1
{ Generally a useful move. The king stood poorly on the c-file, and futhermore the c1-square now stands vacant, ready to be used by another White piece. }
13... Rc8
{ Hereby renouncing any ideas of castling long, and instead trying to generate play along the c-file.  One alternative is   13...g6  as seen in the game Kravtsiv - Korobov, 2016. }
14. Bd3 Nc5
{ The alternative   14...Nb4  has been played in various games, giving Black equality, and this looks to be a better idea than the text move. }
15. Qh3
{ A nice idea ! Rogers players his queen away from the diagonal patrolled by Black's b7-bishop, and simultaneously places e6 under fire.The weakness of this pawn  (together with the unprotected rook on h8)  means that in case of g5-g6, Blac kwill have no good way to take the marauding pawn !Clearly, that move is now high on White's agenda. }
15... b4 16. Ne2
{ Definitely worth a look was   16.Nxc5 !  because  dxc5  17.Na4  would lead to great problems for Black. For instance, after  Nd4  18.f5 !  is rather strong. Now Black doesn't have a convincing reply, for example:  exf5   18...c4 ?  is no better, as it fails to  19.Bxd4  cxd3  20.Qxd3  when White has picked up a crucial pawn without his opponent having gained any particular coherence in the placing of his pieces.  It is also bad to advance the e-pawn.   18...e5  19.b3  White has a nearly decisive advantage.  19.Rhe1 !  whereupon the black king finds itself under siege on every front. }
16... Na5
{ This is a blunder in a position which was already dubious.  The correct answer was   16...Nxd3  and that would have led after  17.cxd3 !  Be7  18.Rhg1   18.g6  Is too hasty:  fxg6  19.Qxe6  Qd7  and White is better, but not especially so.  18...g6  19.f5  To a complicated position where White has superior chances. }
17. Bxc5 Nxb3
{ What was this insight ? Well, the point seems to be that after   17...dxc5  18.Nxa5  Qxa5  White is now able to focus his full attention on the single most vulnerable point in Black's position: the pawn on e6 !  19.Bc4 !  Rd8   19...Bxe4  is completely wrong:  20.Bxe6 !  would simply win;   19...Qb6  20.g6 !  and Black can't hold things together anymore.  20.f5  The consequences of this breakthrough are catastrophic for Black. One line could be  e5  21.Qh5  g6  22.fxg6  fxg6  23.Qf3  Qc7  24.Bf7+ !  winning the queen. }
18. Bxb4 Nc5 19. Bxc5 Qxc5 20. g6
{ This is the stereotyped attacking move which we so often come across in the Sicilian. Black's pawn structure will now get torn apart. }
20... Be7
{ After   20...fxg6  the absolute most precise move would be  21.Nd4 ! } 21.
Nd4 { Once again this little tactic helps White out. } 21... Bf6
{ The weaknesses of Black's position are terminal and his resistance effectively ends here. }
22. gxf7+ Kxf7 23. Qxe6+ Kf8 24. Qxf6+
{ White takes the game into an ending ! After   24.Qxf6  gxf6  25.Ne6+  Ke7  26.Nxc5  dxc5  it should be relatively trivial to convert the advantage of two pawns which he has there. }
