[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Almasi, Zoltan vs. Kasparov, Garry, Lyon, 1994"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 e6 7. Qf3
{ A note on the move-order is perhaps called for. White plays his queen to f3 before developing either bishop; the most important idea behind doing so is the prevention of ...b7-b5.  If White wants to include both Be3 and Qf3 in his plan, then beginning with   7.Be3  is somewhat inaccurate. Black can immediately station his queen's bishop on b7, opposing the White queen on the long diagonal. Continuing the line:  b5 !  8.Qf3  Bb7  Black immediately threatens ...b5-b4. Now a2-a3 is unappealing because Black would gain an important 'hook' to latch onto, making a pawn-storm that bit stronger in case White were to castle long. In what follows this will be an important theme.  9.Bd3  Nbd7  10.g4  White has decided not to play a2-a3, and therefore it is likely a matter of time before Black chases the c3-knight. Ultimately, it will want to perch on g3 so as to defend the e4-pawn. Therefore, White uses the time he has now to play g2-g4- preventing that pawn from being blocked by the intended knight rerouting.  b4  Black's best idea now is to drive the knight away.  It is also interesting to strengthen the threat of the ...b5-b4 thrust rather than playing it immediately:   10...Nc5  11.g5  Nfd7  Here, white has an interesting option:  12.b4  I remember that Timman played this move in the eighties against the Englishman Hodgson, who had been trying to follow Timman's earlier game against Chandler.  Nxd3+  13.cxd3  The game doesn't seem to have made databases, but what I remember is that White won. Seemingly, though, Black does not stand badly here. For instance:  d5  14.a3  e5 !  Black can blast the centre open. This is something which he failed to do in the game, where he instead became constricted and lacked prospects for his bishops.  11.Nce2  Nc5  12.Ng3  White has managed to get his knight behind the g-pawn and has a considerable space advantage on the kingside. However, of course, Black's position is more resilient than it might appear at first glance.  Rc8  13.g5  Nfd7  14.h4  Here the Black player in the game Chandler-Timman, 1984 found a very deep strategic plan. You will find this position in the 'problems' section of the book. }
7... Qb6
{ Previously,   7...Qc7  was played, with the idea to proceed regardless with ...b5. Black sets up protection of the b7-square so that he can meet White's tactical idea of e5 with the counterstrike ...Bb7. }
8. a3
{ An interesting find, which to my knowledge is due to the British grandmaster Michael Adams.  Black's idea is that if White's knight leaves the centre, almost by definition it will occupy a less strong post. Furthermore, after   8.Nb3 !?  Qc7  Black obtains a better version of the position-type from the last note.   8.Be3  Qxb2  9.Kd2  d5 !  leads to deep trouble for White. The threat is ...Bb4 and there are additional tactical possibilities associated with ... Nxe4+. }
8... Nc6
{ The most basic point of White's 8th move is that after   8...Qxd4 ?  9.Be3  the queen is trapped and will fall in the very centre of the board. }
9. Nxc6 bxc6
{ The other recapture   9...Qxc6  doesn't really fit with Black's usual central concept, though it is played. }
10. b3
{ This is an interesting way of playing. Now that the c-line for black is closed, white doesn't so much mind the creation of weaknesses along the c-file. White also shields the b2-square and prepares to develop his queen's bishop there.  Sometimes   10.g4  is also played, albeit without much success. }
10... Bb7
{ After the previous main move   10...Be7  White kind of gets what he wants with the queenside fianchetto.  11.Bb2  e5  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.Na4  Qa5+  14.Bc3  Qc7  15.Bc4  O-O  16.O-O  a5  17.Kh1  Ba6  18.Bxa6  Rxa6  White had a slight positional plus in Almasi-Rasik, 1993. }
11. Bb2 d5
{ Kasparov clarifies his intentions: he's occupying the centre immediately and strongly considering a march of the c-pawn. }
12. O-O-O
{ This was criticized by GM Boensch as being too dangerous for White.  After   12.e5  Nd7  13.Na4  Qc7  14.Bd3  c5 =  Black would also have had nothing to complain about. }
12... Qa5 13. e5 Nd7 14. Na4 Qc7 { To stop f5. } 15. Re1
{ But this is a very unnatural move.  Almasi had probably considered continuing his development with   15.Bd3  and rejected it because of  c5  .   15...g6  is a more circumspect response.  But now with  16.f5 !?  White can try and develop some real threats. }
15... g6 16. g4
{ Consistent, but this makes the queenside situation worse still. } 16... c5
{ Threatening ...d5-d4. } 17. Bg2 Rb8
{ An annoying little move: Black protects the b7-bishop and sets up some ideas along the b-file. }
18. Qd1
{ The attempt to break through with   18.f5 ?  succeeds in its immediate objective, but after  c4 !  19.fxe6  fxe6  20.Rhf1  and the cold-blooded  cxb3 !  21.Qf7+  Kd8  it is the White king which faces the more immediate issues ! }
18... c4 { Here Kasparov again proceeds in rather thematic fashion. } 19. Kb1
Qa5
{ A sensible attacking move, but there was something stronger.   19...Bc6 !  was probably stronger, with the immediate threat of ...Bxa4 and ...c3.  20.Nc3  Nc5  21.b4  Qb7  22.Ka1  and now  a5  will provide the jolt needed to break White's sense of security. }
20. Bc3
{ Most likely Kasparov had seen that after   20.Ka2  Bc6  21.Nc3  Bxa3 !  he is breaking through. }
20... Qb5 21. Ka2 Bc6
{ Possibly more to the point was   21...Nc5 !  22.Nxc5  Bxc5 } 22. f5
{ This was what White had been playing for, but due to a lack of piece support the thrust achieves little. }
22... Qb7 23. fxe6 fxe6 24. Nb2 cxb3+ 25. cxb3 Nc5
{ A new piece arrives on the battleground. There isn't a meaningful defence any longer. }
26. Bb4
{ The White king's fortress would also be breached in case of   26.b4  Ne4  27.Bxe4  dxe4  28.Rhf1  - in this case by the humble a-pawn:  a5 !   26.Rhf1  Nxb3  27.Rf6  Bd7  is also unfruitful. }
26... Nxb3 { A useful pseudo-sacrifice to have. } 27. Qxb3 a5 28. Rhf1 axb4 29.
a4
{ Anxious about the fate of his king, White tries to keep the lines in that neighbourhood as closed as possible. }
29... Be7 30. Rc1 Rf8 31. g5
{ A desperate attempt to set up a sort of initiative against the Black king.   31.Rxf8+  Kxf8  32.Rf1+  Kg7  drives the Black king to a safer location, and now Black can think much more seriously about the final offensive. }
31... Bxg5 { But Kasparov is not impressed and gladly accepts the gift. } 32.
Qh3 Rf5 33. Rxf5 exf5 34. Rd1 b3+ 35. Kb1 Rc8
{ There are now several roads that lead to Rome.   35...Qe7  was perhaps the quickest way to get the job done. }
36. Rd3 { This hastens the end, but there was little else to be done anyway. }
36... Bxa4
{ What both players saw was that after   36...Bxa4  37.Nxa4  Rc1+  38.Kb2  Rc2+  39.Kb1  there is the strong continuation  Qb4 !  40.Rxb3  and now Black can finish with a flourish:  Qe1+ !  41.Kxc2  Qc1+  42.Kd3  Qc4#  A pretty mate to have on the board. }
*

