1... Nxb3 { A useful pseudo-sacrifice to have. } 2. Qxb3 a5 3. Rhf1 axb4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Lorenzo de la Riva, Lazaro vs. Fedorchuk, Sergey A, Navalmoral, 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. f4 a6 7. Qf3
{ White is intending to hinder the Black light-squared bishop from getting to b7 by flipping the order of his natural developing moves.   7.Be3  b5  8.Qf3  Bb7  is another variation, but here Black obtains a little perk: the ongoing tension between the bishop and queen along the long diagonal is to his favour. }
7... Qb6
{ This is the modern way: Black wants to continue with ...Qc7 and then ...b5 and ...Bb7 to develop his pieces, but first tries to get the active d4-knight away from its central perch. }
8. Nb3
{ The move   8.Be3 ?  sacrifices material, but not as much as might originally be suspected. After  Qxb2  White's only move is also a rather tricky one which poses Black some problems.  9.Kd2  This surprising possibility solves the problem of the threatened pieces on c3 and a1. The queen on b2 is also somewhat in danger since ... Qb6 ? is met by Nxe6 ! And Black's development is also not great. Therefore, a concrete answer is needed. What a happy coincidence that the move  e5 !  is working for him.  The capture   9...Qxa1 ?  fails to  10.Bb5+  axb5  11.Rxa1  10.Nf5   10.Rb1 ?  Qxb1 !  11.Nxb1  Bg4  traps the White queen in its turn !  10...d5 !  Bringing the idea of ...Bb4 to the fore.  11.Rb1  still doesn't obtain the desired outcome due to  Nxe4+  12.Qxe4  Qxc3+  13.Kxc3  dxe4  , so Black is winning. }
8... Qc7 9. Bd3 b5 10. g4
{ This is what White had in mind, but matters will not proceed strictly according to his simplistic plan. Of course he would like to expand his space advantage on the king's wing and prod Black's knight away from f6. But this pawn push also makes the kingside slightly too 'hot' to be a future home for his king, as we will see later.  Another route, which is not so frequently played, is   10.Be3  Bb7  11.O-O-O  Nbd7  . }
10... Bb7 11. g5 Nfd7 12. O-O
{ Quite an important decision. The white king finds himself in a rather 'drafty' place after this, and while he has a space advantage, he must always worry about the position opening, after which his lack of pawn cover will be ruinous.  In a game Leko-Oll, 1996, White played the interesting idea   12.Bd2 !?  Nc5  13.Ne2  and now the Black player made a mistake.  Nbd7   13...Nc6 !  He was then confronted with  14.Na5  trading off his prized bishop on b7. }
12... g6
{ Black is getting ready to put his dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal. This move is partially directed against an early f4-f5, but it does offer white the possibility of a 'lever' for opening the kingside in another way, i.e. h2-h4-h5. }
13. Be3
{ 13.Qh3  was seen in a 1993 game between the Dutch players Van der Wiel and Martens, which continued  b4  14.Nd1  d5  15.exd5  Bxd5  16.Ne3  whereupon  Bb7  would have been correct.  Instead the game saw the bizarre   16...Qb6 ?!  17.Rf2 !  Bxb3  18.axb3  after which White obtained a large advantage. }
13... Bg7 14. a3 O-O 15. Qf2 Rc8
{ A strange choice.  It seems to me that following   15...Nc6  16.Rae1  Rae8  Black could well be better. He has a plan of ...f7-f5 to make use of the White king's open position. White, meanwhile, has no particularly constructive plan.  17.h4  may only make the situation worse, e.g.  Ne7  18.h5  f5  19.Nd4  Nc5  and Black is simply better. }
16. Rac1
{ Also a somewhat strange move. Is White actually worried about Black taking twice on c3 ?   16.h4  Nc6  17.h5  was consistent }
16... Nc6
{ 16...Bxc3  17.bxc3  Qxc3  would now give White a significant initiative after  18.Bd2  Qc7  19.Ba5  Qc6  20.c4  . }
17. h4 b4 18. Nd1
{ After this, White's queenside structure will remain crippled.   18.Na4  is no use either, because Black is doing well after  Rab8 !  There remains   18.axb4  Nxb4  when Black may be intending to take on c3 so as to win a pawn and gain some squares for queenside operations. After  19.Bd4  e5  20.fxe5  Nxe5  I have a slight preference for the Black position. }
18... bxa3 19. bxa3 a5
{ Probably the thematic   19...Na5 !  was stronger. Black seeks to put his knight on c4. }
20. h5 a4 21. Nd2
{ Because White now seems to be getting somewhere on the kingside, Black now takes action in the centre and it comes none too soon. }
21... d5 22. Qh4
{ After   22.exd5  exd5  23.f5  the defence  Nce5  is adequate for Black's purposes. He threatens ...Nxd3 and ... Ng4, and protects the f7-pawn. }
22... Nd4 23. hxg6 fxg6 24. Bxd4
{ Trading this bishop for a knight is almost invariably wrong.  White wouldn't have been enjoying himself after   24.e5  Nf5  and Black is placed excellently from a positional perspective, but perhaps he should nevertheless have satisfied himself with this.   24.Nf2 ?!  was not a solution because of the strong  Nc5 !  and Black is almost winning. }
24... Bxd4+ 25. Kh2 Nc5
{ The black pieces head to the correct squares as if by autopilot. The threat of ...Nxd3  (and also that of ...dxe4)  becomes current. }
26. Nf2 Rf8
{ The fact that   26...Be3 !  is marginally stronger makes not the slightest bit of difference to anyone. }
*

