1... d5 2. Qh4
{ After   22.exd5  exd5  23.f5  the defence  Nce5  is adequate for Black's purposes. He threatens ... Nxd3 and ... Ng4, and protects the f7-pawn. }
2... Nd4 3. hxg6 fxg6 4. Bxd4
{ Trading this bishop for a knight is almost invariably wrong.  White wouldn't have been enjoying himself after   24.e5  Nf5  and black is placed excellently from a positional perspective, but perhaps he should nevertheless have satisfied himself with this.   24.Nf2 ?!  was not a solution because of the strong  Nc5 !  and Black is almost winning. }
4... Bxd4+ 5. Kh2 Nc5
{ The black pieces head to the correct squares as if by autopilot. The threat of ...Nxd3  (and also that of ...dxe4)  becomes current. }
