[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Korneev, Oleg vs. Shipov, Sergei, Moscow, 1995"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. Bc4 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7 8.
Qe2 O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. Bb3
{ 10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.e5 ?!  Nd5  is just bad for White. } 10... Nd7 11. g4
{ Many strong players begin with   11.Kb1  as a form of prophylaxis against Black's next move in the game. Then, of course, they proceed with the kingside pawn-storm. }
11... Nc5 12. Rhg1
{ After   12.Nxc6  Black will have to trade off his hard-working knight too:  Nxb3+  Note   12...bxc6 ??  loses a piece to  13.Bxc5  +-  13.axb3  bxc6  but this is nothing particularly terrible from his point of view. }
12... Nxb3+
{ Now maybe this trade is a little bit too fast.  The moves   12...Qe8  and   12...Qc7  are also played.   12...Bd7 !? }
13. axb3 Nb4
{ This is Black's idea. He wants to set up the strike ...d6-d5. Another plan, if he can find the time to get a rook to the c-file, is to set up some mating motif based on ...Qa5 and an eventual ...Rxc3. But right now it is all a little bit vague.  In the game Azarov-Dreev, 2004 Black had success with   13...Bd7 !? }
14. Rg3
{ This rook move brings several new attacking ideas into the picture for White, and we shall shortly see how these work.  In a game Ulybin-Shcherbakov, 1989, White continued   14.Kb1  but it seems that this did not represent an improvement of his position at all. }
14... Qa5 { Now, though, Kb1 is forced and White plays it. } 15. Kb1 Bd7
{ It seems like Black is the one with an initiative here, because he is just about to bring a rook to the c-file and set up various mating motifs. But White has a way to 'throw a spanner in the works.' }
16. Nf5
{ A typical knight sacrifice which perhaps was not expected in this precise position, but which nevertheless forces Black onto the back foot. Of course it must be taken. }
16... exf5 17. gxf5
{ We begin to understand a bit why the move Rg3 was included. Now that the g-file is open, the speed with which White can double rooks on that line begins to be somewhat important. Furthermore, with the White pawn on f5, it is also possible that the rook could swing to the h-file, a fact whose significance will shortly be appreciated. }
17... Bf6
{ The only decent move.  If Black instead defends with   17...Rfc8 ?  (to make ...Bf8 possible and also begin queenside operations)  he will not succeed in holding the kingside.  18.Bd4  g6   18...Bf8  fails to  19.Rxg7+ !  Bxg7  20.Qg4  and Black is mated.  Kf8  21.Qxg7+  Ke7  22.Bf6+  Ke8  23.Qg8#   18...f6  19.Rdg1  also doesn't work.  19.Qh5  White mobilises new attacking pieces. I should mention that this move comes with tempo- White threatens Qxh7+ and Rh3 with mate.  Bf8  Here White needs a new idea, which comes in the form of  20.Rg5 !  White breaks the pin along the fifth rank and in fact threatens fxg6 attacking the Black queen all the way over on a5 ! So the following is basically forced.  Rxc3  21.Bxc3  Qa2+  22.Kc1  Be8  23.fxg6  fxg6  and now the nice move  24.Qh3 !  Bf7  Black had to parry Qe6+; White can now opt to take a piece but there is a more brutal finish as well.  25.Rxg6+ !!  Bxg6   25...hxg6  26.Qh8#  26.Qe6+  Bf7  27.Rg1+  and mate comes nevertheless.  To clarify how White proceeds in case of a 'non-move', let's investigate   17...Bc6  . Then there could follow  18.Bd4  f6  19.Rdg1  Rf7  20.Qh5  Qc7  and now the consolidating move  21.f3  . The point is that White's attacking idea Rg6-h6 takes three tempi to get anywhere and he would prefer that Black not be able to take on e4 in the meantime.  a5  22.Rg6 !  Only with the rook in front of the queen can Black be swiftly dispatched.  a4  23.Rh6  axb3  24.Rxh7  Black does not have enough checks to trouble White. }
18. Bd4 { Black's most important defender should be traded off without delay. }
18... Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Rac8
{ Black still plays for the idea of an exchange sacrifice on c3. But isn't that a little too optimistic ?  Another tactical weakness comes to the fore if Black tries to seal the g-file shut with   19...g6  :  20.fxg6  fxg6   20...hxg6  is less good:  21.Qc4  Threatening Rxg6+.  Kg7  22.Qxb4  Qxb4  23.Rxb4  Since here the f-file is closed, Black lacks the counterplay that he would get after the other capture on g6.  21.Qc4+  White retrieves his piece and this leaves the position approximately equal. }
20. Rxb4
{ White gives up yet another exchange. While now ...Rxc3 ceases to be an issue, White is of course behind a whole load of material as well.  It could be that   20.Rxd6  is objectively stronger, but the consequences of this move are harder to calculate.  Bxf5   20...Bc6 ?  fails to  21.Qg4   20...Rxc3  should be calculated.  21.bxc3  Qa2+  22.Kc1  Bb5  23.Qd1  Qa3+  24.Kd2  Nc6  25.Ke1  White has managed to fend off the enemy attack and can now turn his attention to his own attack. The winning chances are excellent.   20...Rfd8  21.Qg4  g6  and now  22.Rxd7  Rxd7  23.fxg6  when too many Black pieces are en prise.  21.exf5  Qxf5  22.Rb6  += }
20... Qxb4 21. Nd5 Qd4
{ Under such continuous pressure, it is not surprising that mistakes are made by the defending side.  After   21...Qb5  White has  22.Qd2 !?  with the threat of Rxg7+ ! and Qg5+ followed by mate. Black seems to be able to keep everything under control with  f6  but now it will be his queen that faces the tactical issues.  23.c4 !  Rxc4  Forced.   23...Qc5 ?  will get forked at the end of a nice long line.  24.Qh6  Rf7  25.Nxf6+  Kf8  26.Rxg7 !  Rxg7  Now White obtains decisive material gains with  27.Nxd7+  Kg8  28.Nxc5  Rxc5  29.Qxd6  24.bxc4  Qxc4  The chances are approximately level now because Black has obtained a fair degree of counterplay.  The normal move   21...Qa5  leads to a situation where one of the players should give perpetual check.  22.Nf6+  Kh8  23.Rh3  gxf6  24.Rxh7+  Or   24.Qh5  Qe1+  25.Ka2  Qa5+  26.Kb1  Qe1+  24...Kxh7  25.Qh5+  Kg7  26.Qg4+  Draw ! }
22. c3 Bb5
{ Quite a good try, but the mistakes had been made.  For instance   22...Qc5  sees Black practically get mated:  23.Nf6+  Kh8  24.Qh5 !  h6   24...gxf6  25.Qh6  25.Qg5 ! }
23. Qc2 Qc5
{ Now that the queen is distracted from the defence of the king's wing, White can permit himself to go 'all in' on a new wave of attack.  After   23...Qe5  24.f4  Qe8  White can win a queen with  25.Nf6+  but instead of actually taking the queen, he can opt to play for mate.  Kh8  26.Rxg7 !  Kxg7  27.Qg2+  Kh8  28.Qh3  Black can resign- even the desperate sacrifice  Qxe4+  need not distract White because he can play  29.Ka2 ! }
24. f6 Rfe8
{ No resistance is really possible now.   24...g6  lets White deliver mate by means of a standard pattern.  25.Qd2  Kh8  26.Qh6  Rg8  27.Qxh7+  Kxh7  28.Rh3# }
25. f3
{ White is trying to be clever, postponing the decision of how to take on g7 to prevent the Black king from running while preparing to line his queen up behind the g3-rook.  Still, it is puzzling that White didn't just play   25.Rxg7+  . The following lines are forced:  Kf8   25...Kh8  26.e5  is mate on h7  26.Rxh7  Kg8  27.Qd2  Kxh7  Neither is the intermediate check   27...Bd3+  exceptionally useful.  28.Kc1  Bxe4  29.Rh8+  Kxh8  30.Qh6+  Bh7  31.Qg7#  28.Qg5  Mate is inevitable. }
25... Re5 { After   25...g6  the point was, unsurprisingly,  26.Qd2  again. }
26. Rxg7+ Kf8 27. Qg2 { Made possible by White's earlier push f2-f3. } 27...
Ke8 28. Rxf7
{ A nice point. White still needs to show something, because he is a rook down. }
28... Kd8 { 28...Kxf7  29.Qg7+  Ke8  30.f7+  is immediately decisive. } 29.
Rf8+ Re8 { White is also winning after   29...Be8  30.f7  . } 30. Qg7
{ Threatening a mate in one   Qe7. } 30... Rc7 31. f7
{ Note the major role played by the f-pawn in all these lines ! } 31... Rxf7
{ Or   31...Rxf8  32.Qxf8+  Kd7  33.Qe8# } 32. Qxf7
{ Mathematically more precise was   32.Rxf7  but this is not so important. }
32... Bd3+ 33. Kc1 { 33.Ka2 ??  Qa5# } 33... Qg1+
{ Black tries to rustle up a perpetual check, but his pieces don't work together well enough.   33...Rxf8  34.Qxf8+  Kd7  35.Qe7+  Kc8  36.Qe8# }
34. Kd2 Qf2+ 35. Kxd3 Qf1+ 36. Kc2 { Heading back to a2, so Black resigned. } *

