1. Rxb4
{ White gives up yet another exchange. While now ...Rxc3 ceases to be an issue, White is of course behind a whole load of material as well.   20.Rxb4 !?  White gives up yet another exchange. While now ...Rxc3 ceases to be an issue, White is of course behind a whole load of material as well.  Qxb4  21.Nd5  Qd4 ?  Under such continuous pressure, it is not surprising that mistakes are made by the defending side.  After   21...Qb5  White has  22.Qd2 !?  with the threat of Rxg7+ ! and Qg5+ followed by mate. Black seems to be able to keep everything under control with  f6  but now it will be his queen that faces the tactical issues.  23.c4 !  Rxc4  Forced.   23...Qc5 ?  will get forked at the end of a nice long line.  24.Qh6  Rf7  25.Nxf6+  Kf8  26.Rxg7 !  Rxg7  Now White obtains decisive material gains with  27.Nxd7+  Kg8  28.Nxc5  Rxc5  29.Qxd6  24.bxc4  Qxc4  The chances are approximately level now because Black has obtained a fair degree of counterplay.  The normal move   21...Qa5  leads to a situation where one of the players should give perpetual check.  22.Nf6+  Kh8  23.Rh3  gxf6  24.Rxh7+  Or   24.Qh5  Qe1+  25.Ka2  Qa5+  26.Kb1  Qe1+  24...Kxh7  25.Qh5+  Kg7  26.Qg4+  Draw !  22.c3  Bb5  Quite a good try, but the mistakes had been made.  For instance   22...Qc5  sees Black practically get mated:  23.Nf6+  Kh8  24.Qh5 !  h6   24...gxf6  25.Qh6  25.Qg5 !  23.Qc2  Qc5  Now that the queen is distracted from the defence of the king's wing, White can permit himself to go 'all in' on a new wave of attack.  After   23...Qe5  24.f4  Qe8  White can win a queen with  25.Nf6+  but instead of actually taking the queen, he can opt to play for mate.  Kh8  26.Rxg7 !  Kxg7  27.Qg2+  Kh8  28.Qh3  Black can resign- even the desperate sacrifice  Qxe4+  need not distract White because he can play  29.Ka2 !  24.f6  Rfe8  No resistance is really possible now.   24...g6  lets White deliver mate by means of a standard pattern.  25.Qd2  Kh8  26.Qh6  Rg8  27.Qxh7+  Kxh7  28.Rh3#  25.f3  White is trying to be clever, postponing the decision of how to take on g7 to prevent the Black king from running while preparing to line his queen up behind the g3-rook.  Still, it is puzzling that White didn't just play   25.Rxg7+  . The following lines are forced:  Kf8   25...Kh8  26.e5  is mate on h7  26.Rxh7  Kg8  27.Qd2  Kxh7  Neither is the intermediate check   27...Bd3+  exceptionally useful.  28.Kc1  Bxe4  29.Rh8+  Kxh8  30.Qh6+  Bh7  31.Qg7#  28.Qg5  Mate is inevitable.  25...Re5  After   25...g6  the point was, unsurprisingly,  26.Qd2  again.  26.Rxg7+  Kf8  27.Qg2  Made possible by White's earlier push f2-f3.  Ke8  28.Rxf7 !  A nice point. White still needs to show something, because he is a rook down.  Kd8   28...Kxf7  29.Qg7+  Ke8  30.f7+  is immediately decisive.  29.Rf8+  Re8  White is also winning after   29...Be8  30.f7  .  30.Qg7  Threatening a mate in one   Qe7.  Rc7  31.f7  Note the major role played by the f-pawn in all these lines !  Rxf7  Or   31...Rxf8  32.Qxf8+  Kd7  33.Qe8#  32.Qxf7  Mathematically more precise was   32.Rxf7  but this is not so important.  32...Bd3+  33.Kc1   33.Ka2 ??  Qa5#  33...Qg1+  Black tries to rustle up a perpetual check, but his pieces don't work together well enough.   33...Rxf8  34.Qxf8+  Kd7  35.Qe7+  Kc8  36.Qe8#  34.Kd2  Qf2+  35.Kxd3  Qf1+  36.Kc2  Heading back to a2, so Black resigned. }
1... Qxb4 2. Nd5 *

