[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Hennings, Artur vs. MÃ¶hring, GÃ¼nther, DDR, 1967"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 d6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4
{ We are familiar with this position, although we saw it arise via a different order. }
7... Be7 8. Qe2
{ The queen is best placed here. White aims to get his king out of the centre quickly with O-O-O, after which the rook is immediately going to enjoy the benefits of the d-file. The other benefit of this square  (rather than d2)  is that it protects the g4-square, stopping a knight incursion there by Black and enabling g2-g4.   8.Qd2  is possible as well but ...Ng4 can sometimes be a worry for White. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O Qc7
{ Black should take his queen off the d-file in case of accidents. } 10. Bb3 a6
11. g4 { Now no more dawdling, but immediate action ! } 11... b5
{ Black begins his own counterplay.  Both players would have been well aware of the considerations surrounding the thematic capture on d4.   11...Nxd4  and now praxis shows that the best reaction is likely  12.Rxd4  .  As usual,   12.Bxd4  invites ...e6-e5 and in particular, here this is a pawn sacrifice.  e5  13.Be3  Bxg4  14.f3  Be6  White obtains some compensation in the form of the open g-file, but this is generally considered not such a great way to play.  Now  12...e5  can be met by  13.Rc4  Qd8  14.g5  Nd7  15.h4  , cuing up an exchange sacrifice.  b5  Now it seems that  16.Rxc8 !?  is quite a handy little exchange sac. In return for his material investment White would obtain absolute control over the d5-square and the elimination of the only possible rival for the a2-g8 diagonal, which is open and therefore extremely useful for him. The bishop on b3 will likely be transformed into a monster.  The rather less adventurous choice of   16.Rb4  also gives White quite good prospects.  16...Rxc8  17.Nd5  ↑ }
12. g5 Nxd4
{ Basically forced, but now White's bishop will be quite active on d4.  The problem with retreating immediately with the king's knight is that White has a trick, by means of which a large advantage can be obtained.   12...Nd7  13.Nd5 !  exd5  14.Nxc6  Qxc6  Even the relatively better   14...Ne5  leads to a very depressing position after  15.Nxe5  dxe5  16.Bxd5  when White has, as we like to say, 'the pawn AND the compensation.'  15.Bxd5  The rook on a8 is skewered. }
13. Bxd4 Nd7 14. Rhg1 Nc5
{ This knight move is played a lot, but maybe black's play after this is too slow.  Lots of games now continue   14...b4  which is definitely an important alternative. }
15. Qh5
{ With this very aggressive queen move, White makes his intentions clear. In addition to a few other tactical ideas, we can see that he almost certainly wants Rg1-g3, which then strongly threatens Rh3. }
15... b4
{ The interesting thing is that this position has been reached on the board many times in practice, with incredible results for White. How should he begin the attack ? }
16. Bf6
{ This move is considered to be the correct continuation of White's attack. The intention is to be able to play the rather picturesque 17. Qh6 straight afterwards.  I came across the natural   16.Nd5 ?  three times in my database, a sacrifice which is unfortunately not correct. Nevertheless, two of the White players managed to win their games.  exd5  17.Bxd5  and now Black has at his disposal the super-accurate  Ne6 !  , which nets two pieces for the rook which White is almost certainly about to take.  18.Bxa8   18.Bf6  doesn't work any more, for instance because after  Nf4  Black is ready to block a discovered check with his knight !  18...Nxd4  19.Rxd4  Qa7  The attack is at an end and the material balance favours Black.  Another try which White can use to start the attack is   16.Qh6  which seems to work, but the downside is that Black has  e5  at his disposal. Nevertheless White's initiative after  17.Nd5  is enough to give an advantage.  gxh6   17...Qd8 ?  18.Nf6+ !  Bxf6  19.gxf6  is mate  18.gxh6+  Kh8  19.Nxc7  Ra7  20.Bxc5  dxc5  21.Nd5  White is better now, but in some way Black can continue the game, at least. }
16... Re8
{ We should also investigate the other rook move:   16...Rd8  17.Rg3 !  bxc3  18.Rh3  and now  h6  is forced. But now there comes a lightning strike deep in the heart of Black's encampment.  19.Qxh6 !!  Nd3+   19...gxh6  20.Rxh6  Bxf6  21.gxf6  and there is no longer any meaningful defence against Rg1+ followed by Rh8#.  20.cxd3  cxb2+  21.Kxb2  Here Black resigned in Bordonada-Sanz Alonso, 1974.  If Black takes with   16...bxc3  he is also put to the sword by the immediate  17.Qh6  . }
17. Rg3
{ White is no longer especially interested in the knight on c3.  Black's defences hold up after   17.Na4  Nxb3+  18.axb3  e5  And also   17.Qh6  Bf8 }
17... bxc3 18. Rh3 cxb2+
{ Once again   18...h6  would lead to the same nice motif with the queen sacrifice.  19.Qxh6 !! }
19. Kb1 Bxf6
{ We already know how to meet   19...h6  : simply  20.Qxh6 !  winning. } 20.
gxf6 Kf8
{ The Black king is forced to flee. White just needs to find the clincher.  Of course we need to know how White can close the mating net after   20...gxf6  . The key move is  21.Qh6  and the rest is just icing on the cake.  Nxe4  22.Rg1+  Ng5  23.Qxf6  Kf8  24.Rxg5  Qd8  25.Rg8+ !  Kxg8  26.Qh6  Next comes Rg3+ with mate. }
21. e5
{ The very strongest continuation.   21.fxg7+  also wins:  Ke7  22.Rf3  Kd8  23.Qg5+  Qe7  24.Rxd6+  Kc7  25.Qxc5+  etc. }
21... Ne4
{ White can choose the finishing touch after   21...gxf6  . The best seems to be  22.Qh6+  Ke7  23.Qxf6+  Kd7  24.Rxd6+  winning the queen. }
22. fxg7+ Ke7 23. Qh4+ f6 24. Qxe4
{ Black could have resigned now with a clear conscience.  Somewhat nicer and also winning is   24.g8=Q  Rxg8  25.Qxh7+  , and White in fact executed this idea one move later: }
24... d5 25. g8=Q Rxg8 26. Qxh7+ *

