[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Jenson, Errol vs. Psakhis, Lev, Las Vegas, 1997"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 Be7 7. Bb3 O-O 8.
Be3
{ White can also delay this move. The other possibility is   8.O-O  Na6  and now  9.f4  , intending to station the queen on f3- behind the f-pawn.  Nc5  10.Qf3  White has managed to post his queen on a nice active square. }
8... Na6
{ A plus side of not playing the Najdorf move-order: this knight can get to c5 without Black needing to worry about the sacrifice on e6 ! }
9. O-O { This combination of ideas looks slightly awkward. } 9... Nc5
{ A multi-purpose move: the knight doesn't just attack e4  (which causes White some short-term problems)  but also defends e6 again, introduces the idea of taking on b3, and clears the way for the advance ...a7-a5-a4, a plan which has been executed in many games. }
10. Qf3
{ This makes White's job harder. The queen impedes the f-pawn and limits the range of future attacking possibilities. In spite of the constraint that White's e4-pawn was under attack, there was a better way to continue.   10.f3  doesn't give Black any particular problems, but White's position is playable too. }
10... a6
{ Psakhis chooses a kind of quasi-Najdorf continuation. The b-pawn will now advance two squares and make way for the queen's bishop to fianchetto and once more hammer the e4-square. }
11. Rad1 Qc7 12. Nde2
{ Another route down which White could have gone is   12.Rfe1  b5  13.a3  Bb7  14.Bc1  but it is clear that Black has the situation under control. }
12... b5 13. e5
{ White shows his cards. However, he seems to have misevaluated the consequences.  The necessary evil was   13.a3  when Black would proceed with  Rb8 !  with the idea ...b5-b4,   axb4  , ...Rb8xb4, again posing White lasting problems. }
13... dxe5
{ Psakhis turns the situation to his advantage. This move causes White's idea to backfire.  In all likelihood White had mostly  (or entirely)  considered the move   13...Bb7  in his calculations. Then the point was  14.exd6  Bxd6  15.Qh3  with sharp, end-to-end play- notwithstanding that Black is still somewhat better in case of  Rad8  . }
14. Qxa8 Bb7 15. Qxf8+
{ White has exchanged a queen and pawn for two rooks. In most cases this is a good exchange, but here it is quite the opposite.  Very similar play results from   15.Qa7  Ra8  16.Qxa8+  Bxa8  . }
15... Kxf8 16. Ng3
{ Let's think about why this position is, indeed, better for Black. He has, as mentioned, only one pawn to balance out the queen-for-two-rooks situation. Furthermore, he has doubled pawns. However, White has even more deep-seated issues, foremost among which is that his pieces simply do not work together. Black has a dominant pawn mass in the centre and the particular way in which it is arranged facilitates his queen working all over the board, making the queen rather preferable to White's two rooks-which lack any means of using the open lines. }
16... Qc6 { Here the queen is perfectly placed. } 17. f3 Ng4
{ This move hits the hammer on the nail. The bishop on e3 is White's best piece, and Black seeks to drive it away from its duties. }
18. Bf2
{ Now, as on all other moves, Black wins material.  In case the bishop vacates the g1-a7 diagonal, there will follow some consequences along the same line, e.g.   18.Bc1  Nxb3  19.cxb3  Qc5+  20.Kh1  Nf2+  21.Rxf2  Qxf2  and Black is winning. }
18... Nxb3 19. axb3
{ 19.cxb3  was marginally better, though it makes no difference in any real sense. }
19... Nxf2 20. Rxf2
{ Black can now take an exchange, but he doesn't even want it !  Another depressing variation is   20.Kxf2  b4  21.Nce2  Qc5+ !  22.Ke1  Qxc2  23.Rc1  Qxb3 }
20... b4
{ There was also nothing particularly wrong with capturing the exchange by means of   20...Bc5 }
21. Nce4 f5
{ After   21...f5  22.Nd2  Black can choose to take his 'courses' in a couple of different orders-  Qxc2  or in fact ...Bc5. }
*

