[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Moe, Mogens vs. Grooten, Herman, Copenhagen, 1984"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4
{ We can see this as a kind of 'Fischer/Sozin Attack' against the Scheveningen- an idea previously considered to not be as dangerous as the sister system against the Najdorf. }
6... Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Bb3 Na6
{ This is an important difference with the Najdorf: now the a6-square is still available for a knight, and Black can then go quickly to c5 with it in order to neutralise the b3-bishop. Were it only possible to go there via d7, Black would be slowed down by the problems associated with sacrifices on e6. }
9. f4 Nc5 10. Qf3 a5
{ This is an idea I once conceived over the board. Now it is rather well known ! The goal is to pose a question to the b3-bishop. }
11. f5
{ Mr. Moe does not let the grass grow beneath his feet but rather goes straight for his main idea. This move is in line with what Fischer originally wanted: increasing pressure on the e6-pawn and trying to force it to give way  (...e5 or ...exf5)  -which would then give White the d5-square for his pieces.  I also got this position in an old game against IM Willy Hendriks. Black had few problems in reaching a comfortable game following:   11.a4  e5  12.fxe5  dxe5  13.Nf5  Bxf5  14.exf5  e4  A good zwischenzug: Black has a passed pawn and now sets it in motion with tempo.  By the way, if you ever write a chess book in English, you should decide between the words 'zwischenzug' and 'intermezzo' for the concept of an in-between move. For me, German and Italian both sound similarly classy, so I use the words about equally...  15.Qe2  Nxb3  16.cxb3  Here Black can almost be considered a pawn up for our purposes: White cannot liquidate his doubled b-pawns anytime soon.  The most frequently played move is   11.O-O-O  , which leads after  a4  12.Bc4  a3  13.b3  to an interesting position which is generally considered marginally better for Black. }
11... a4 12. Bc4 a3 13. fxe6
{ A super-sharp answer from the white player. He leaves Black to his own devices on the queenside and tries to crush him  (i.e. me)  in the centre.  More normal would be   13.b4  but then I had seen the nice  Ncxe4 !  ahead of time.  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Qxe4  d5  and Black is doing very well. }
13... fxe6
{ I remember coming to the conclusion that I would make my life easiest by simply taking back. The f-file has opened and so Black has the extra threat of ...Nfxe4, as well as medium-term chances against the White king- which is biding its time in the centre to an extent which is becoming somewhat suspicious. I had no idea what White was planning. His next move was a surprise and it occasioned me some practical difficulties, but objectively after it White is lost. Ready ? }
14. Nf5
{ A crazy idea. White thought for a long time before executing it, and when he did I nearly fell off my chair. }
14... axb2 { Played at pace, because why would I not want this tempo ? } 15.
Rb1
{ Time for me to follow my opponent into the 'think tank'. On a practical level the problem is significant: thanks to the 'Fischer bishop' on c4  (and the knight it supports on f5)  White has some pressure on the black position. All his pieces are active, while a few of Black's still have to be developed. After calculating a few lines and not finding a clear win for Black, a certain sense of panic ensued: was I going to lose against this ridiculous construction ?   Then I closed my eyes to calm down and just tried to understand the position without calculating. I had a couple of epiphanies, one after the other: the first was that White's pieces were active 'beyond their means', that is to say, overextended. His position is tactically vulnerable in a few ways: the f-file, the a5-e1 diagonal  (on which reposes a king which, in a deep sense, is weaker than mine)  , the undefended pieces on c3 and c4. Which brings us to the second epiphany.   That bishop on c4. Isn't it just the cornerstone on which every single aspect of White's position rests ? Near-impossible to exchange, but wouldn't it be enough to...simply hound it ? }
15... b5
{ I admit: maybe two exclamation marks are excessive. The first is fully merited, the second may simply be my unique style of self-congratulating after managing to find my way through the 'morass'.  Many years later I saw that the computer suggested:   15...Nfd7 !?  A fully logical move, but one I didn't consider at the time.  16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.Qg3  Ne5  with a dominating position for Black.   15...Nfxe4  was the first move I considered, but after  16.Nxe4  I did not find the correct follow-up.  Nxe4 ?  This is what I saw at the time.  Instead, the right move is given instantly by the engines:   16...Kh8 !  and Black wins due to having a multitude of threats, foremost among them being ...Rxf5.  17.Nxe7+  Not   17.Qxe4 ?  Qa5+  followed by...Qxf5- a detail I was able to see.  17...Qxe7  18.Qxe4  d5 ?  Even here there is   18...Ra4 !  with an advantage after  19.Bxe6+  Qxe6  20.Qxe6+  Bxe6  21.Rxb2  but White may be able to scavenge a draw due to the opposite-coloured bishops.  19.Bxd5  and now it is White that wins !  Another logical move,   15...Kh8 ?!  did not give what I wanted either:  16.Nxe7  Qxe7  17.O-O !  After the inaccurate   17.Bxc5 ?  Black can get an advantage if he is able to find the cute  Nd5 !  .   17...dxc5  18.O-O  Bd7  19.Rxb2  leaves a long game to be played.  For instance:  18.Qg3  dxc5  and the d5-knight is immune due to  19.exd5  exd5+  and Black wins.  The super-principled   15...d5 !!  is actually the most accurate move in this position. But you have to see one or two details to play it.  16.exd5  and now another brilliant move.  Na4 !!  A faintly absurd move, adding to the chaos in the position by putting another piece en prise.  Not   16...exd5 ?  17.Nxd5  Nxd5  18.Qxd5+  Be6  19.Nxe7+  Qxe7  20.Bxc5  and Black must find  Qf7  to stay equal.  17.Nxa4  What else ?  Rxa4  18.Bb3  Bb4+  An important intermediate move, with which Black not only disturbs the white king, but also disarms any future d6+ that White may play.  19.Ke2  exf5  20.d6+  Kh8  21.Bxa4  f4 !  The double threat of ...fxe3 and ... Bg4 costs White his life. These are typical computer variations, impossible for a flesh-and-blood player to hack through while at the board. }
16. Bxc5
{ There are again countless lines that needed to be calculated.  After   16.Bxb5 ?  exf5  is simply over.  After   16.Nxb5  I had seen that I could take on e4.  Ncxe4  This is the simpler way.  At the time I didn't consider   16...Nfxe4  much, because it voluntarily signs up for a second pin along the h1-a8 diagonal. But this wins too:  17.O-O  Kh8 !  18.Bxc5  Bb7 !  and having defused both pins, Black can proceed to take back his piece.  19.Bd4  Rxf5  20.Qd3  Rxf1+  21.Kxf1  d5  is winning for Black.   16...Ra4  leads to a large advantage too:  17.Nxe7+  Qxe7  18.Bxc5  dxc5  19.Qe2  Ba6  20.e5  Nd5  17.Nxe7+  Qxe7  18.O-O  d5  Black has consolidated his material plus.   16.e5  Bb7  17.Nxe7+   17.exf6  loses for White as well:  Bxf3  18.fxe7  Qa5  19.exf8=Q+  Rxf8  and way too many White pieces are still attacked.  17...Qxe7  18.exf6  Rxf6  With ...bxc4 to follow.  We would transpose to the game after   16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.Bxc5   17.e5 ?  Nfe4 !  17...bxc4 !  18.e5  . }
16... bxc4
{ So I have removed the piece which was giving me such headaches 2 moves ago. }
17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. e5
{ White had clearly set his sights on this, but it doesn't save his position from being overrun.  After   18.Bf2  (to enable castling)  I was planning  Ra3  though better is the predictable engine move   18...d5  . }
18... Nd5 19. Nxd5
{ 19.exd6  now loses:  Qh4+  20.Qg3  After   20.Bf2  there is a hyper-accurate solution, and a human one.  I would of course have played  Rxf3   20...Qg5 !  21.Qg3  Qc1+  21.Bxh4  Rxc3  winning a piece.  20...Qxg3+  21.hxg3  Nxc3  Again, Black has more than enough material to decide the game. }
19... exd5 20. Qxd5+
{ 20.Bxd6  Qh4+  21.g3   21.Qg3  Qe4+ !  21...Rxf3  22.gxh4  c3 !  White has no way to stop ...Rxa2, since Ke2 runs into ...Bg4. }
20... Be6 21. exd6
{ 21.Qxd6  Qh4+  This check decides the game.   21.Bxd6  Qh4+  is much the same as the game. }
21... Qh4+ { Here too, this wins. } 22. g3 Bxd5 23. gxh4 c3
{ Finishing the game in style.  I suspect my technique would also have been adequate to seal the deal after   23...Bxh1  when I am a full rook up. }
24. Ke2 Bxh1 25. Kd3
{ Trying to take on c3, but White can't even manage to do this.  After   25.Rxh1  I would play  Rxa2  26.Bd4  Ra1 }
25... Rf3+ 26. Kc4 Bg2 27. Bb4 Rf1
{ The b-pawn promotes and so my opponent decided to call it a day. } *

