ns, impossible for a flesh-and-blood player to hack through while at the board.  After   16.Bxb5 ?  exf5  is simply over.  After   16.Nxb5  I had seen that I could take on e4.  Ncxe4  This is the simpler way.  At the time I didn't consider   16...Nfxe4  much, because it voluntarily signs up for a second pin along the h1-a8 diagonal. But this wins too:  17.O-O  Kh8 !  18.Bxc5  Bb7 !  and having defused both pins, Black can proceed to take back his piece.  19.Bd4  Rxf5  20.Qd3  Rxf1+  21.Kxf1  d5  is winning for Black.   16...Ra4  leads to a large advantage too:  17.Nxe7+  Qxe7  18.Bxc5  dxc5  19.Qe2  Ba6  20.e5  Nd5  17.Nxe7+  Qxe7  18.O-O  d5  Black has consolidated his material plus.   16.e5  Bb7  17.Nxe7+   17.exf6  loses for White as well:  Bxf3  18.fxe7  Qa5  19.exf8=Q+  Rxf8  and way too many White pieces are still attacked.  17...Qxe7  18.exf6  Rxf6  With ...bxc4 to follow.  We would transpose to the game after   16.Nxe7+  Qxe7  17.Bxc5   17.e5 ?  Nfe4 !  17...bxc4 !  18.e5  .  I admit: maybe two exclamation marks are excessive. The first is fully merited, the second may simply be my unique style of self-congratulating after managing to find my way through the 'morass'.    There are again countless lines that needed to be calculated. }
