[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Nakamura, Hikaru vs. Hou, Yifan, Hoogeveen, 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g4 h6 7. Rg1
{ A somewhat rare order in the Keres attack. Nakamura may want to confuse his opponent.  More than 2000 games have been played beginning with   7.h4 }
7... e5
{ Hou tries to profit from White's alternative order, but this attempt backfires somewhat. She weakens the light squares for somewhat questionable compensation.   The normal move is   7...Nc6  Now White should probably continue within the normal channels of the Keres:  8.h4  Even if Nakamura wanted   8.Be3  first, he still cannot very well avoid playing  a6  9.h4  with the well-known position type again.  8...h5  with a transposition to the main line. }
8. Bb5+ { An interesting insertion. } 8... Nbd7
{ The trade of light-squared bishops should apparently favour White, but Hou played   8...Bd7  in another game, which took place after the present one. Clearly she had enough faith in her position to try it again- a year later, against Kateryna Lagno. Following  9.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  10.Nf5  Nc5  11.Qf3  Ne6  Black had a playable position. She even won the game later. }
9. Nf5 a6 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. g5
{ The most active move and one which places Black's plans under serious doubt. He needed to calculate accurately. }
11... Nxe4
{ The possibility of this pseudo-sacrifice came as part and parcel of White's last move.   11...hxg5  12.Bxg5  Nxe4  loses immediately because after  13.Nxg7+  Bxg7  14.Nxe4  d5  15.Nf6+  Black can already resign. }
12. Nxg7+ { The knight naturally sells itself as dearly as possible. } 12...
Bxg7 13. Nxe4 Qc6
{ This is the only way to stay in the game.   13...d5 ?  would now lead to a different kind of calamity:  14.gxh6 ! }
14. Qd3
{ White opted to develop quietly and avoid gobbling the d6-pawn. It seems he now stands better.  After   14.Nxd6+  Ke7  15.Nxc8+  Raxc8  White has completely lost his activity and the time he spent with the knight that's just been traded off served only to help Black develop his pieces. Nimzovich used to call pieces like that 'tempo suckers'. }
14... Ke7 15. gxh6 Bxh6 16. Bxh6 Rxh6
{ Now it is White whose development is proceeding at pace, and he has some ideas about how to profit from the unsafe position of the black king. }
17. Qe3 { Little moves can sometimes be both beautiful and strong. } 17... Rh5
{ The only move which stops the White queen's deadly incursion to g5. } 18. Rd1
{ At first sight a strange decision.  You were probably expecting   18.O-O-O  . White brings his rook into the game and simultaneously brings his king into safety. But this still doesn't make it a good move. After  Bf5  the White knight can only move to one square on pain of mate on c2, and there follows  19.Nc3  Rah8  20.Nd5+  Kd7  21.Rd2  Rxh2  with a completely playable game for Black.  So maybe White can begin with   18.Ng3 !?  Rxh2  and only now  19.O-O-O !  This line could have been played. The king has been brought to safety and the White pieces are all active, while Black still has to develop the queenside. After  Be6  White can pose immediate problems by returning his knight to e4 with  20.Ne4  which carries the double threat of Rxd6 and Qg5+. }
18... Bf5 19. Ng3
{ This was naturally the idea. With no white king on c1   unlike in the variation with  18.O-O-O  , the knight can calmly move back to g3. }
19... Bxc2
{ Hou loses her self-control.  With   19...Rah8 !  the Chinese player would have brought about an interesting exchange sacrifice.  20.Nxh5 ?!  The engine gives   20.h3 !  which is the kind of bizarre move that would never occur to a human being.  20...Rxh5  and White will still have many problems making something significant of his material advantage. }
20. Nxh5 Bxd1 21. Kxd1
{ An even more convincing move was possible:   21.Qg5+ !  Kd7  22.Qf5+  Kc7  23.Qxf7+  Kb6  24.Kxd1  and Black has no way of generating compensation, not even after  Rc8  25.Qb3+ }
21... Qd5+ 22. Ke2 Qxa2
{ Black has won back her material, but now the fierce attack upon her king develops anew. }
23. Qg5+ Kd7 24. Qf5+
{ Enough for the win, but there was something stronger.  A player of the caliber of Nakamura could have been expected to notice the critical nuance that is   24.Rc1 !  An absolutely rock-solid move which cuts off the Black king and after  Qxb2+  25.Kf1  Black is powerless against the combined effect of the three white attacking pieces. }
24... Ke7
{ After   24...Kc7  25.Rc1+  Kb6  26.Rc2  Qb3  some work would have remained to be done. }
25. Qc2 Qa5 26. Ng3 { His knight will be coming back to the light squares. }
26... Qb5+ 27. Kf3 Qc6+ 28. Qe4 Rh8 29. Nf5+ Kd7 30. h4
{ Now that he has gained control of all the noteworthy central squares, Nakamura can set his passed pawn in motion. The position has become technically won and Nakamura finishes matters crisply. }
30... Qb5 31. Rd1 Qxb2 32. Nxd6 Kc7 33. Nc4 Qb5 34. Nxe5 f6 35. Rc1+ Kb8 36.
Rb1 f5 37. Qxf5 Qd5+ 38. Qe4 Rf8+ 39. Ke3 Qc5+ 40. Qd4 Qxd4+ 41. Kxd4 Rf4+ 42.
Ke3 Rxh4 43. f4 Kc7 44. f5 Kd6 45. Ng6 Rh7 46. Rd1+ Kc7 47. Kf4 b5 48. f6 Rf7
49. Ke5 *

