Qb3+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Polgar, Judit vs. Topalov, Veselin, Hoogeveen, 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6
{ We have obtained a Scheveningen setup from the Najdorf order. Judit would like to replicate the ideas of the Keres attack here too. }
7. g4 h6
{ The most frequent answer to the idea of g4-g5.  Those who love tactical play and do not shy away from major complications should continue with:   7...e5  8.Nf5  g6  White must let the knight on f5 be taken, there is no sense in going back.  9.g5  gxf5  10.exf5  The most promising continuation. From here on, tactical factors assume pride of place in any discussion about the evaluation or best move...  Simply recapturing with   10.gxf6  gives Black all the prospects after  f4  .  10...d5   10...Ng8  11.Qf3  is clearly better for White.  11.Qf3  The old continuation   11.gxf6  also leads to head-spinning complications:  d4  12.Bc4  Qc7  13.Qd3  dxe3  14.O-O-O  exf2  15.Bxf7+  We can find two interesting games in the database here: Shirov-Van Wely, 2000  (1-0)  and Topalov-Van Wely, 2000  (0-1)  . The tactical skirmishes that take place are so complicated that all three players must have prepared the exact line with computers. In the first game Van Wely makes a mistake, but in the second he shows the correct path.  11...d4  12.O-O-O  Nbd7  Practice shows that white scores very well from the present position, although there is little objective reason for this. Shirov and Polgar are big supporters of the white position; while Svidler, Anand and Van Wely dare to play black. The most recent match between two grandmasters from here is J. van Foreest-Van Wely, 2018  (0-1)  . }
8. Bg2
{ You could be forgiven for thinking that the analogy with the Keres attack allows White to continue   8.h4  , but there are reasons why this is not so common.  e5  9.Nf5  g6  10.Nxh6  Bxh6  11.Bxh6  Bxg4  with an unclear position in Georgiadis-Svidler, 2018. }
8... g5
{ The text move is a standard and ambitious way for Black to try and take control over the e5-square in a variety of Sicilian positions. He sees the fact that this move creates some other kingside weaknesses as being of lesser importance.  Here the 'main line' is   8...Nc6  9.h3  -which is often contested at the world-elite level as well, for instance see Anand-Vachier-Lagrave, 2015. }
9. Qe2 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Ne5 11. h3 Nfd7
{ Topalov prefers to cement his control over e5 even more firmly right now, rather than develop. The assumption is that White cannot do very much with her lead in development.   11...Qc7  would be a typical developing move, but perhaps the then-world-champion was worried about direct actions White might take against the knight on e5, such as  12.f4  or   12.Nf3. }
12. f4
{ Polgar now tries to get active. The fact that there will almost certainly not be an opportunity to disturb the e5-knight with a pawn ever again doesn't really bother her. }
12... gxf4 13. Bxf4 b5
{ The most active move. Black prepares to develop his queen's bishop and at the same time questions the c3-knight. With this move, of course, Black signals his understanding that his king will remain in the centre. Short castling was removed from the realm of practical politics by the push ...g5, and now the same is done for long castling by the present move. Black need not worry about the long diagonal, though: White's bishop on g2 is being effectively muzzled by the knight on e5. }
14. Rhf1
{ Perhaps this is a slightly inaccurate way of continuing the plan begun two moves ago.   14.Qf2  was probably better; the reasons why are about to become clear. }
14... Bb7
{ I used this position regularly in my training sessions for talented players. I would say this a typical example of finding a 'defining move'; the opening is over and a plan must be found, because the opponent is surely making their own plan as well. So what is available to White here ? If we look at the pawn structure, we see that White's central pawn on e4 is firmly blockaded by the Black knight on e5 and that Black - as mentioned earlier - has this strong outpost permanently in his hands.   We must accept this feature of the position and just try to play 'around' it. By having exchanged the f-pawn for Black's g-pawn, though, we have left Black with some static weaknesses of his own. Sometime in the future, the h5-square could also be a nice outpost for a knight, especially combined with play along the half-open f-file. The opponent's plans should also be taken into account.   In this case, the advance ... b5-b4 is a problem. The c3-knight has no natural escape square  (assuming for a moment that we would prefer not to sacrifice it on d5.)  Going to a4 is not pleasant after ... Qa5, but going to b1 is completely out of the question: the knight is just bad there. With all these reflections in mind, Judit came to the following formidable move:   In view of what follows in the game,   14...b4 !?  was probably necessary for Topalov. It does not take much imagination to conclude that he was afraid of the standard sacrifice  15.Nd5 !?  exd5  16.exd5  , after which White does in fact generate sufficient compensation. }
15. Qf2
{ This is one of the nicest 'little moves' I have seen. It is deep and deceptively strong. The queen itself lines up on the f-file opposite the weakest square in Black's king position-f7-and protects the h4-square for a possible future manoeuvre Bf4-g3-h4  (striking at the heart of Black's kingside dark squares.)  But as we already know, the double-edged 8th move by Black didn't only open a new diagonal for White's bishop, but it also created an outpost for a knight on h5.   White's queen's knight can now head there, via the e2-square which has just been vacated. Black will regret not having played ...b5-b4 on the previous move, and that in turn explains why White could have done even better by inverting the order of her last 2 moves. }
15... Rc8 16. Nce2
{ The knight heads to the square it had been eyeing, even without being explicitly forced to do so  (though of course Black might have been intending the typical ...Rxc3 sacrifice.) }
16... Bg7
{ The d6-pawn is not White's priority and so Topalov does not make it his either. The bishop is diverted to the long diagonal, where it threatens to take part in various ideas on the side of the board, such as ... Nc4 with a sacrifice on b2 to come.  Black could have tried to cross his opponent's plans with   16...h5 !?  but this move has other problems. White gains new options after  17.g5  and Black can choose either to make a martyr of his pawn with h5-h4, or allow White to fix it in place, which will then open up the ideas of attacking it  (Ne2-g3, Qf2-e2 and Nxh5)  as well as Bg2-h3 softening up the e6- and f7- points in readiness for a future push g5-g6. }
17. Ng3 Rh7
{ Forced: the f7-pawn required protecting anew and the g7-bishop needed a retreat square on h8 in order to not have to leave its great diagonal immediately. }
18. Nh5 Bh8 19. Kb1
{ An important prophylactic move. The king leaves the c-file and the c1-h6 diagonal. White is about to play an idea which would not be possible without having first prepared it in this way. }
19... Nc5
{ A perfectly logical move, which however has a tactical defect; one so well-concealed that even one of the greatest tactical talents in the world, Judit Polgar, was unable to find it during the game.  Black needed to play   19...Qb6 !?  and White would have continued her stated plan with Bf4-g3-h4. }
20. Bg3
{ Both players missed a strong tactical shot for the attacking side.  The hidden move was   20.Nf5 !  a move that they may both have seen for a moment, but quickly rejected. The idea behind it is not that simple:  exf5  Essentially, the knight needs to be taken because of how well it stands on f5.  Black can opt to just protect d6, but this doesn't end well.   20...Rc6  21.Nfg7+ !  A nice interference motif !  Bxg7   21...Rxg7  22.Bxe5  22.Nxg7+  Rxg7  23.Bxe5  Rh7  24.Qg3  and White is unquestionably winning.   20...Nc4  is useless:  21.Bxd6  exf5  22.Bxc5  Qc7  23.Bd4  and Black's position is just a wreck.  21.Bxe5  A surprising exchange. Because white almost never gives this bishop for a knight, the move may have been a blind spot in the minds of both players. But the move is strong because of  Bxe5  22.Qxf5  and the rook has nowhere to go ! The problem is that it cannot leave the protection of the f7-pawn on pain of mate. This tactic was something that Kb1 helped set up- note that without it, Black would have ...Qg5+ here. }
20... Nxe4
{ Topalov is forced to take this pawn, but in so doing he opens the position while his king remains dangerously stuck in the centre. }
21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Bh4 Qc7 23. Bf6
{ The White player's plan is now about to be completed. She will trade off Black's good dark-squared bishop and thereby free up the f6-square for her knight. Observe how she has brought the weaknesses of Black's king position into sharp focus. }
23... Bg6
{ A nice variation occurs if Black plays   23...Bb7  . The answer then is  24.Bxh8  Rxh8  25.Ng7+  Kd7  Now there comes a beautiful mate, as follows:  or   25...Kd8  26.Qf6+  Qe7  27.Ndxe6+  fxe6  28.Rxd6+  Nd7  29.Nxe6+  Ke8  30.Qg6+  with mate next.  26.Qxf7+ !  Nxf7  27.Rxf7+  Kd8  28.Ndxe6# }
24. Bxh8 Rxh8
{ Black is also lost after   24...Bxh5  25.Bxe5  dxe5  After   25...Bg6  White can simply play  26.Bg3  -since the c2-pawn is adequately protected, there will be no technical problems in converting the piece advantage.  26.Nxe6  White breaks through. }
25. Nf6+ { Beginning the king hunt ! } 25... Kd8
{ The king has to go to the line of fire of the d1-rook. } 26. h4
{ Even the g6-bishop is not immune from the tactics.   26.Qh4  Qe7  is, surprisingly enough, not that significant for White. }
26... Qc5
{ Veselin clears the c7-square for his king so as to try and run it to safety on the queenside.  After   26...h5  White has the interesting option of  27.Qf4 !  threatening Qxe5 ! and Nc6# ... }
27. h5 Bh7 28. Qh4
{ Judit is not bothered by the counterplay on c2 that Black now has. She puts her pieces in promising positions to continue attacking the enemy king. }
28... Bxc2+
{ White's idea in chasing down the Black light-squared bishop is illustrated by the following line:   28...Kc7  29.Nxh7  Rxh7  30.Rxf7+ !  Rxf7  31.Nxe6+  winning the queen ! }
29. Nxc2
{ Maybe not the best, but it doesn't spoil anything.  White could also have ignored Black's check:   29.Ka1 !  Kc7   29...Bxd1 ?  gives us a nice mating picture:  30.Nd5+  +-  Kd7  31.Qe7#  30.Nxc2  Qxc2  31.Rc1  White wins the queen. }
29... Qxc2+ 30. Ka1 Rc4 { Trying for a counterstrike. } 31. Ne4+ Kc7 32. Nxd6
Rf4
{ This is an original concept, but won't be sufficient to save Black.  After   32...Rc5  we would see the same kind of king hunt as occurred in the game.  33.Qe7+  Kb6  34.Qb7+ }
33. Qe7+ Kb6 34. Qb7+ Ka5
{ The Black king has been driven all the way to a5  (a familiar picture if we have also seen the game Kasparov - Topalov, which is called the Pearl of Wijk aan Zee)  - but White still has to find a good move to continue the attack. Judit is up to the task.   After   34...Kc5  35.Qc6  Nc6  White wins with  36.Nb7 }
35. Qa7
{ There is no way to prevent White from playing Nb7+ next, and the mating net is beginning to definitively tighten. }
35... b4
{ Carving out an escape route for the king offers only temporary respite.  After   35...Rxf1  , White can win the queen with checks:  36.Nb7+  Kb4  37.Qd4+  Nc4   37...Qc4  38.Qd6+  38.Qc5+  Ka4  39.b3+ }
36. Rfe1 Nf3 37. Rc1
{ Judit could have played something crisper, but this is a sure route to the full point. }
37... Nxe1 38. Rxc2 Nxc2+ 39. Kb1
{ A possible follow-up was   39.Kb1  Nd4  , after which White delivers a cute mate with  40.Nb7+  Kb5  41.Qc5+  Ka4  42.Qa5# }
*

