{ Diagram I used this position regularly in my training sessions for talented players. I would say this a typical example of finding a 'defining move'; the opening is over and a plan must be found, because the opponent is surely making their own plan as well. So what is available to White here ? If we look at the pawn structure, we see that White's central pawn on e4 is firmly blockaded by the Black knight on e5 and that Black - as mentioned earlier - has this strong outpost permanently in his hands. We must accept this feature of the position and just try to play 'around' it. By having exchanged the f-pawn for Black's g-pawn, though, we have left Black with some static weaknesses of his own. Sometime in the future, the h5-square could also be a nice outpost for a knight, especially combined with play along the half-open f-file. The opponent's plans should also be taken into account. In this case, the advance ... b5-b4 is a problem. The c3-knight has no natural escape square  (assuming for a moment that we would prefer not to sacrifice it on d5.)  Going to a4 is not pleasant after ... Qa5, but going to b1 is completely out of the question: the knight is just bad there. With all these reflections in mind, Judit came to the following formidable move:  In view of what follows in the game,   14...b4 !?  was probably necessary for Topalov. It does not take much imagination to conclude that he was afraid of the standard sacrifice  15.Nd5 !?  exd5  16.exd5  , after which White does in fact generate sufficient compensation. }
2. Qf2
{ This is one of the nicest 'little moves' I have seen. It is deep and deceptively strong. The queen itself lines up on the f-file opposite the weakest square in Black's king position-f7-and protects the h4-square for a possible future manoeuvre Bf4-g3-h4  (striking at the heart of Black's kingside dark squares.)  But as we already know, the double-edged 8th move by Black didn't only open a new diagonal for White's bishop, but it also created an outpost for a knight on h5. White's queen's knight can now head there, via the e2-square which has just been vacated. Black will regret not having played ...b5-b4 on the previous move, and that in turn explains why White could have done even better by inverting the order of her last 2 moves. }
