[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Zhu, Chen vs. Ehlvest, Jaan, Gibraltar, 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4 h6 7. h4 Nc6 8. Rg1
h5 { The standard reaction for Black. } 9. gxh5 Nxh5 10. Bg5 Nf6 11. Qd2 Qb6
12. Nb3
{ White doesn't want to enter an endgame because of Black's better structure. }
12... a6 13. O-O-O Bd7 14. Rg3
{ The usual way to try and make progress for White. The rook can sometimes be transferred across the third rank and cause problems in the Black camp. }
14... Qc7 15. Bg2 Nh5
{ This move is not so common. By playing it, Ehlvest indicates that he doesn't need the option of long castling. Rather, his idea is to play the queen's rook to c8  (as he proceeds to do next.)   15...Be7  was featured in, among other high-level encounters, a game of the 1984 world championship match between Karpov and Kasparov. }
16. Rh3 Rc8 17. Kb1 b5
{ A difficult moment for White. Where do her chances lie ? The black king will definitely be staying in the centre, but attacking it there is not so simple. You could think about using the standard sacrifice Nc3-d5 to crack open the centre- but this is unlikely to be effective unless the recapture   exd5  comes with discovered check. It turns out she lacks exactly one tempo to set this idea up properly. }
18. a3
{ Maybe the lesser evil. However, White is too late to prevent the thrust ...b5-b4, and the game move rather gives Black a way to open lines on the queenside.  The crude attempt to set up Nc3-d5 with   18.Qe2 ?!  doesn't work because after  b4  19.Nd5  exd5  20.exd5+  Ne5  21.f4  there is  Bg4  , winning for Black.  The other method,   18.Qe1  b4  19.Nd5  exd5  20.exd5+  also sees White run out of steam somewhat because of the calm defence  Ne7  21.Re3  f6 ! }
18... b4 { Anyway ! Ehlvest does not wait for a printed invitation. } 19. axb4
Nxb4 20. Bf1 e5
{ A very double-edged move. Black voluntarily gives up the d5-square, but he hopes to be able to place his bishop on e6 and in this way achieve something on the queenside. However, there are some snags in his plan.  A logical and less committal approach was   20...Rb8  . After all, Black has to set up some ideas against the enemy king. This move may help with ...Nxc2-based tactics in some cases. }
21. Rh2 Rb8
{ With the same idea as 20... Rb8.  Perhaps he realised now that   21...Be6 ?!  would be well met by  22.Bh3 !  with problems for Black. }
22. Bh3 { Of course White wants to trade the light-squared bishops. } 22... Bc6
{ But the black player does not cooperate. Rightly so, although the concessions he has already made  (chiefly, the move ...e5)  constitute a major concession. }
23. Nd5
{ We see this theme very often in the Najdorf  (and other Sicilian lines)  and the pattern which follows is a standard one. More often than not, this jump is a strategic mistake for White if he is  (as here)  obliged to take back with a pawn. Another good rule of thumb is that if the pawn recapture will be forced, Black should give up his bishop for the knight, rather than a knight.  The principled way to play was   23.f4 !?  when, at the cost of the often-critical dark-squared bishop, White manages to open some lines in the centre. The evaluation after  Nxf4  24.Bxf4  exf4  25.Qxf4  is up for debate, but this position certainly makes greater demands of Black than the one after the text move, because his king  (committed as it is to stay in the centre)  is now a little open. }
23... Bxd5 24. exd5 Be7
{ Black was fairly happy to trade off his light-squared bishop, and now uses the time to threaten to take full control over the central dark squares. }
25. Qc3 { A nice move made possible by tactics. } 25... Qb6
{ 25...Qxc3 ?!  doesn't quite lose a piece, but the endgame is not great for Black if White sees a little nuance.  26.bxc3  Bxg5  27.hxg5  Nxd5  28.Rxd5  Nf4  29.Rd1 !  Else Black simply takes on h3 and the position is fine for him.  Rxh3  30.Rxh3  Nxh3  31.Rh1  Rxb3+  32.cxb3  Nxg5  +=  Here, Black only has winning chances if his opponent overpresses.   25...Qb7  allows  26.Na5  which is decidedly not to Black's advantage. }
26. Be3 Qb5 27. Bf1
{ Chasing the Black queen forward, something to which Ehlvest probably did not have any objection. }
27... Qa4 28. Ba7
{ 28.Nc1  would have defended against the ideas of ...Qa2, but also left White in a rather passive position. After  O-O !  Black would be ready for ...Rfc8, and this would bring about major difficulties for White. }
28... Ra8 29. Qc7
{ It is understandable that White wants to create some confusion in the Black ranks, but this move leaves her further from safety.  Going back with   29.Be3  was relatively better, but Black has two moves that leave him with an advantage and reasonable winning chances: 29... Nf6 and 29... O-O. }
29... O-O
{ 29...a5 !?  was also playable.  Black can insert   29...Qa2+  30.Kc1  first and then play  O-O !  The threats against the White king are already quite significant, and in this order it is not clear that White has anything better than  31.Qxe7  transposing to the game, i.e.  Rfc8  with a huge attack. }
30. Qxe7
{ White retained grovelling chances after   30.Qa5  Qxa5  31.Nxa5  Rxa7  , because she can win the piece back on b4.  32.c3  Nxd5  33.Rxd5  Nf4  34.Rd1  Rc8  and Black is in extremely good shape, but not yet winning. }
30... Rfc8
{ Despite the piece advantage, there is no longer any salvation to be had for White. }
31. f3
{ Trying to give it back while closing the c-file doesn't work:   31.Bc5  doesn't work:  Rxc5 !  32.Nxc5  Qxc2+  33.Ka1  Qxd1# }
31... Qa2+ 32. Kc1 Qxb3 33. Rdd2
{ Black should ignore the attempt to trade queens with   33.Qe8+  and instead play  Kh7 ! }
33... Qa2 34. Kd1 Qb1+ 35. Ke2 Ng3+
{ The knight, for so long sidelined on h5, now makes its voice heard with decisive effect. }
36. Kf2 Nxf1 37. Rh1 Rxc2 38. Rxc2 Nd3+ { Playing for mate ! } 39. Kg2 Nf4+
{ 39...Nf4+  40.Kf2  Qxc2+  41.Kxf1  Qe2+  42.Kg1  Qg2# } *

