1. Nd5
{ We see this theme very often in the Najdorf  (and other Sicilian lines)  and the pattern which follows is a standard one. More often than not, this jump is a strategic mistake for White if he is  (as here)  obliged to take back with a pawn. Another good rule of thumb is that if the pawn recapture will be forced, Black should give up his bishop for the knight, rather than a knight.  The principled way to play was   23.f4 !?  when, at the cost of the often-critical dark-squared bishop, White manages to open some lines in the centre. The evaluation after  Nxf4  24.Bxf4  exf4  25.Qxf4  is up for debate, but this position certainly makes greater demands of Black than the one after the text move, because his king  (committed as it is to stay in the centre)  is now a little open. }
1... Bxd5 2. exd5 Be7
{ Black was fairly happy to trade off his light-squared bishop, and now uses the time to threaten to take full control over the central dark squares. }
3. Qc3 { A nice move made possible by tactics. } 3... Qb6
{ 25...Qxc3 ?!  doesn't quite lose a piece, but the endgame is not great for Black if White sees a little nuance.  26.bxc3  Bxg5  27.hxg5  Nxd5  28.Rxd5  Nf4  29.Rd1 !  Else Black simply takes on h3 and the position is fine for him.  Rxh3  30.Rxh3  Nxh3  31.Rh1  Rxb3+  32.cxb3  Nxg5  +=  Here, Black only has winning chances if his opponent overpresses.   25...Qb7  allows  26.Na5  which is decidedly not to Black's advantage. }
