[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Kanarek, Marcel vs. Movsesian, Sergei, Warsaw, 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4 h6 7. Bg2
{ White avoids the heavy theory.  As we already know,   7.h4  is the main variation here. }
7... a6
{ Inadvisable is   7...e5 ?!  because after  8.Nf5  g6  9.Ne3  White has the strong d5-outpost securely in his grasp. }
8. h3 Qc7 9. Be3 b5
{ A sharp move that is tactically justified.   9...Nc6  is more often played. Intense struggles followed in the games Malakhov-Smirin, 2009 and Ponomariov-Kasimdzhanov, 2002. }
10. a3
{ Since ...b5-b4 is beginning to become a significant feature of the position, White must lose time preventing it.   10.e5  should be properly answered with  Bb7  11.exd6   11.Bxb7  comes down to the same thing:  Qxb7  12.Qf3  Qxf3  13.Nxf3  dxe5  14.Nxe5  Nbd7  11...Bxd6  12.Bxb7  Qxb7  and Black has no issues. }
10... Bb7 11. f4 Nbd7 12. Nb3
{ A rather passive move.  In multiple games-such as Kudrin-Stopa, 2009 and Kobalia-Wallace, 1998- White continued with   12.Qe2  Nc5  13.Bd2  ,and scored well; winning both of those games. But right here, Black doesn't appear to be in trouble yet. }
12... Be7 13. Qe2 Rc8 14. O-O-O Qb8
{ Movsesian  (!)  is now ready for an exchange sacrifice on c3, and White has to do something about it. At this point the game becomes unique.  In the precedent game Spoelman-Kazhgaleyev, 2005, Black played   14...Nb6  and came under some light pressure following  15.g5  Nfd7  16.g6  Nc4  17.gxf7+  Kxf7  . He later won because of a mistake by his young opponent. }
15. Bd4
{ Egging Black forward.  The most natural seems to be   15.Rd3  but here too Black can do the same thing:  Rxc3 !?  16.Rxc3  Nxe4  and since he has the central pawns, Black can claim fair compensation for the exchange.  The only way to completely rule out the sacrifice is   15.Bd2  , and after  Nc5  16.Kb1  White stands a little bit better. }
15... e5 16. Be3
{ After   16.fxe5  dxe5  17.Bf2  Black also plays the sacrifice:  Rxc3 !  18.bxc3  Bxa3+  19.Kb1  Qc7  with good play for Black. }
16... Rxc3
{ By now this is not a surprise. Once again there comes the well-known exchange sacrifice. }
17. bxc3 Nxe4
{ The position is now very problematic for White. Black threatens ... Nxc3 and ...Ng3. What does White have to play in response ? }
18. Ba7
{ This simply can't be it. White goes fishing in troubled waters.  After   18.Qd3  Nxc3 !  19.Qxc3   19.Bxb7  Nxd1  wins for Black.  19...Bxg2  20.Rh2  Be4  the position is no bed of roses for White, but he is still in the game.  The zero-thought solution   18.Bxe4 ?!  Bxe4  19.Rhe1  gives a nearly lost position after  d5 ! }
18... Nxc3 { Movsesian does not miss a trick. } 19. Qf2
{ 19.Qd3  Qxa7  20.Qxc3  Bxg2  is totally over. } 19... Nxd1
{ Because Black attacks the White queen with this intermediate move, he gets back his exchange.  A winning position would also result from   19...Qc7  20.Rd3  Bxg2  21.Qxg2  O-O  . }
20. Rxd1 Qa8 21. Bxb7 Qxb7 22. fxe5 Nxe5
{ Preparing ... Bxa3+ with   22...dxe5  also gets the job done. } 23. Na5 Qc7
24. Bb6 Qc3
{ After   24...Qc3  Black is already two pawns to the good and threatens to take a third one on a3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
