[Result "*"]
[FEN "1qr1k2r/1b1nbpp1/p2ppn1p/1p6/4PPP1/PNN1B2P/1PP1Q1B1/2KR3R w k - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bd4
{ Egging Black forward.  The most natural seems to be   15.Rd3  but here too Black can do the same thing:  Rxc3 !?  16.Rxc3  Nxe4  and since he has the central pawns, Black can claim fair compensation for the exchange.  The only way to completely rule out the sacrifice is   15.Bd2  , and after  Nc5  16.Kb1  White stands a little bit better. }
1... e5 2. Be3
{ After   16.fxe5  dxe5  17.Bf2  Black also plays the sacrifice:  Rxc3 !  18.bxc3  Bxa3+  19.Kb1  Qc7  with good play for Black. }
2... Rxc3
{ By now this is not a surprise. Once again there comes the well-known exchange sacrifice. }
3. bxc3 Nxe4
{ The position is now very problematic for White. Black threatens ... Nxc3 and ...Ng3. What does White have to play in response ? }
