[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Smeets, Jan vs. Werle, Jan, Groningen, 2002"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In the annotations that follow I have drawn from Ftacnik's earlier remarks. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. f3 e6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qd2
a6
{ So, via a less usual move-order, we have an English attack on the board in which Black has opted for the Scheveningen structure with ...e7-e6. }
9. g4 Qc7 10. O-O-O Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O
{ A courageous decision to castle right in front of the pawn-storm which is definitely just about to be launched for real.   11...e5  is also played fairly often. After  12.Qd2  Black continues with  Be6  13.g5  Nd7  but the results here, and especially after  14.Nd5  Bxd5  15.Qxd5  are rather good for White.  Another possibility is the direct   11...b5  , but after  12.g5  Black's knight will have to go to h5, where it does not stand well at all.  Nh5  13.f4  Various problems  (such as Be2 or f4-f5)  now face Black. }
12. g5 Nd7 13. h4 Ne5
{ Of course   13...b5  is also a reasonable thing to play. But White's attack is already quite strong:  14.h5  Now White proceeded to crash through conclusively in Cheparinov-Pogorelov, 2003, with the instructive motif of the 6th rank pawn duo:  Bb7  15.g6  e5  16.Qd2  b4  17.h6 !  And it's pretty much over already. }
14. f4 Nc6 15. Qd2 b5 16. h5 Rd8
{ But this is decidedly too slow, besides which the rook will actually later be needed on the f-file-as we are about to see.  White was also for choice after   16...b4  17.Na4 !  stopped the black pawn-storm in its tracks in the game Bernardskiy-Pugachov, 2009.  A game which Black managed to win, albeit of course not in a clean fashion, was Muzychuk, A-Polajzer, 2006. He played   16...Rb8  and after  17.g6  b4  18.Na4  met  Na5  there was already some counterplay to be had. }
17. g6
{ There is no point delaying the opening of lines towards the Black king. }
17... Bf6
{ The idea of moving the bishop now is to let Black take back on f7 with the queen. However, after White's energetic continuation at this point, Black's formation is revealed to not hold water.  Neither does the other bishop move let Black lessen his suffering:   17...Bf8  18.Qg2 !  with immense pressure. }
18. Bd3
{ Maintaning the pawn on g6 for now.  After   18.gxf7+  Qxf7  Black has survived the worst of it.  And after   18.gxh7+  Kh8  19.Qf2  Rb8  it isn't completely clear to me how White keeps his initiative ticking over. }
18... Rb8
{ Catastrophe also awaits after Ftacnik's suggested   18...fxg6  :  19.hxg6  h6  and now White needs just one preparatory move before beginning the sacrifices.  20.Kb1 !  For instance now  Rb8  and the drama begins on the kingside.  21.e5  Be7  22.f5 !  Nxe5  23.Bxh6  White breaks through. }
19. e5
{ Ftacnik: 'With this typical square-clearing move, Smeets tries to show that the black bishop on f6 may not be exactly stable. ' }
19... dxe5 20. Ne4
{ It is still not time for   20.gxh7+  Kh8  because White is better served by keeping Black guessing what the g6-pawn will do next. }
20... Be7
{ After for instance   20...exf4  21.Nxf6+  gxf6  22.gxh7+  the g-file would be cleared and it would be open season on the Black king. The foremost threat White has is actually just to bring multiple major pieces to the g-file and deliver mate on g7 or g8. Because of the weakness of his back ranks Black cannot really defend himself. An example of how things could play out:  Kh8  23.Rhg1  Qe7   23...fxe3  24.Qg2  24.Qg2  Qf8  25.h6 !  Threatening a nice pawn-mate-in-two, Qg7+ Qxg7 hxg7#.  f5   25...Qxh6  26.Qg8+  26.Bxf5  Swapping off a crucial defender of the back rank. We see that the undeveloped c8-bishop stops Black from preventing the mate in a line like  exf5  27.Rxd8  Nxd8  28.Qg8+  Qxg8  29.hxg8=Q#  . }
21. gxf7+
{ And now it becomes clear both why the rook should have stayed on f8, and why White didn't take his numerous earlier chances to capture on h7. }
21... Kh8
{ After   21...Kxf7  22.Ng5+  White has very good attacking chances.  Bxg5  23.fxg5 }
22. Qg2
{ This move conceals an idea of the greatest ingenuity and originality. } 22...
Bb7
{ Black has finally connected his rooks. But the white attack is already irresistible.  The beauty is that White is not that interested in material, nor should he be. Of this last, the line   22...exf4 !?  provides a particularly spectacular illustration. White goes for the same idea as in the game-  23.Qg6 !  Ne5  and now:  24.Bd4 !!  A great attacking concept. The e5-knight and d8-rook are important defenders.  Rxd4   24...Bb7  doesn't help:  25.Ng5  and mate on h7 can't be stopped.  One major point of White's last move was that after   24...Nxg6  25.hxg6  Black can't simply keep the h-file shut:  h6  nevertheless gets mated in one after  26.Rxh6#  .  25.Nf6  Nxg6   25...Nxd3+  26.Rxd3  and here White delivers forced mate. The black rook has been diverted from d8 and no longer controls the back rank, so Black can't take on f6 with the bishop. Also, ... gxf6 runs into Qg8# and ...hxg6 leads to the usual discovered mate. There is no other way of protecting against Qxh7#.  26.hxg6  h6  27.Rxh6+ !  gxh6  28.Rg1  White has almost no pieces left, but with what he does have, he forces mate ! The bishop once again is tied to f8 and so can't take on f6, leaving the main line as  Bf8  29.g7+  Bxg7  30.f8=Q+  Bxf8  31.Rg8# !  A beautiful finish ! }
23. Qg6
{ With this formidable move the attack gains unstoppable momentum. The minor pieces  (Bd3 and Ne4)  play essential roles in the mate motifs that this move generates. Ftacnik: 'A beautiful move that shows the flair of the attacker. White doesn't look back when there is a clear path to the opponent's king.' }
23... Nb4
{ There are some alternatives that should be calculated:   23...hxg6 ?  24.hxg6+  Bh4  25.Rxh4#  The move   23...Rxd3  looks logical, to eliminate the dangerous d3-bishop. White doesn't need to take any notice of it, however.  24.Rdg1  Rd1+   24...Bf8  25.Nf6  25.Kxd1  Qd8+  26.Kc1  Qf8  27.Bc5 !  whereupon the threat Ng5 forces decisive material gain.  Bxc5  Or   27...Rd8  28.Ng5  winning the queen  (and, apparently, leading to mate in seven.)  28.Nf6  gxf6  29.Qxf6+  Qg7  30.Qxg7# }
24. Rdg1
{ It is not important to Smeets whether he has a piece more or less. He plays for mate. }
24... Bf8
{ In the line   24...Nxd3+  25.Kb1  Rg8  White should first take a small time-out for  26.cxd3  before proceeding.  Bd5  27.fxg8=Q+  Rxg8  28.fxe5  Qxe5  29.Qg4  and White is a full rook up. }
25. Nf6
{ Not difficult but no less pretty for that.   25.Ng5  was the same deal. }
25... Nxd3+ 26. Kb1
{ Werle now makes a sporting gesture: he shows respect for his opponent's pretty attack by giving him the chance to deliver mate on the board. }
26... hxg6 27. hxg6+ Bxh1 28. Rxh1# *

