[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Giri, Anish vs. Brandenburg, Daan, Dieren, 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ Black opts for the immediate Scheveningen setup. } 6. Be3 Be7 7. f3
{ Immediately going for the setup known as the English attack. White wants to organise g2-g4 very quickly- in some books this thrust is called a 'bayonet attack'. }
7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. g4 Nd7
{ One of the main ideas.  An important alternative for Black is   10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  b5 }
11. h4 Nxd4
{ Here Black can change things up with   11...Nde5  threatening to win a pawn  (...Nxd4 followed by ... Nxf3)  . White normally replies  12.Qg2  . A nice example illustrating Black's chances was Quesada Perez-Morozevich, 2005. }
12. Bxd4 b5 13. g5 Bb7 14. a3
{ 14.Kb1  is the most popular move. The game continuation trades off the temporary stability of the c3-knight for the potential problems associated with allowing Black a 'hook' for future queenside counterplay. }
14... Qc7
{ This automatic developing move is perhaps not the best. It was also played in a blitz game Ivanchuk-Grischuk,2009, which Black won; but in that game White obtained a winning position before blundering it away.  The strongest players have continued here with   14...Rc8  and Black swiftly develops an attack. }
15. Bh3
{ Now this is a new move. White hopes to set up a lethal attack  (based on the pawn push g5-g6)  in such a way that the bishop's line of sight to the traditional weakness on e6 can become a factor. }
15... Ne5 16. Qg2 Nc6 17. Be3
{ The tempting   17.Bf6  leads after  Ne5  (with the intention of ...Nc4)  to a situation where Black has good counterchances. }
17... b4
{ Black is trying to lever open the White queenside- which had been weakened by the move a2-a3. Having that move is indeed a drawback of White's position, but Giri has correctly reckoned that his kingside attack is the more important than the nascent queenside play.  Offering a repetition makes sense here.   17...Ne5  18.Bd4  but now if Black played on with  Nc4  then once again White's attack would probably land first.  19.g6 !? }
18. axb4 Nxb4
{ Diagram Black has opened the b-file for his attack thanks to the tempo gained against the c3-knight. But in this case his attack doesn't get to develop much ! }
19. g6
{ White doesn't have a choice but to press on. This pawn sacrifice was consistent with  (and probably envisaged before)  White's 15th move. }
19... hxg6
{ In such a situation consideration must always be given to the 'active counter'   19...f5 !  In this case it's actually the only defence. Now White should open lines quickly.  20.gxh7+  Too slow is   20.Kb1  h6  21.Qd2  Rab8  when the g- and h- files can no longer be cleared:  22.Bxh6 ?!  gxh6  23.Qxh6  Bf6  24.g7   24.Rxd6  Bc8  ∓  24...Bxg7  25.Rhg1   25.Qxe6+  Kh8  26.Qxd6  Qxd6  27.Rxd6  fxe4  with a decisive advantage for Black.  25...Bc8  Black is placed reasonably well to make use of his material plus, and can move over to the attack on the queenside himself.  20...Kh8  21.h5  White holds some trump cards, but Black is very much in the game after  Bf6 }
20. h5 Bf6
{ This move allows the White attack to proceed apace.  Neither would Black be successful with the brazen   20...gxh5 ?  trying to call White's bluff. White can break the remaining defensive fortifications apart, starting with the amazing 21. Bf5.  21.Bf5 !!  Winning straight away.  There is also a mating attack after   21.Bd4  e5  22.Bf5 !?  ,for instance:  exd4 ?  23.Rxh5  Rfc8  24.Rdh1  with mate.  21...exf5  22.Rxh5  Bf6   22...Rfc8  23.Rdh1  23.Rdh1  g6  Now White's clincher makes use of.. . the undefended queen on c7.  24.Rh8+ !  Bxh8  25.Qh3  Na2+  26.Nxa2  Bxb2+  27.Kxb2  f6  28.Qh8+  Kf7  29.Qh7+  Ke8  30.Qxc7  and White wins.  Relatively best was   20...g5  but White should, after  21.Bxg5  Kh8  22.f4  Rab8  23.Bxe7  Qxe7  24.Rhg1  Rg8  25.f5  retain the lion's share of winning chances. }
21. hxg6 { This pawn is decidedly a thorn in Black's side. } 21... Bxc3
{ There was no longer any real defence to be had against the nice combination with which White now proceeds to win.  That being said,   21...Rfe8  (giving the e6-pawn extra protection and freeing up the f8 flight square for his king)  was a more stubborn move for Black, though it doesn't save the game. White needs to expand the range of his ideas a little bit, in order to defend against the counterplay Black threatens by means of ...Bxc3 and ...Na2+.  22.Bd4 !  White wants to exchange the most important defender of Black's kingside.  The 'standard useful move'   22.Kb1  also works in this position. The point is that the very second Black takes on c3, the f6-bishop's absence will be felt on the other side of the board.  Bxc3  23.gxf7+  Kxf7  24.bxc3  Qxc3  now loses for Black due to  25.Bd4  .  22...e5  Shielding the bishop from exchange.  After the trade   22...Bxd4  23.Rxd4  Qc5  24.gxf7+  Kxf7  25.Rhd1  Rad8  White can obtain a winning position by means of  26.e5 !  23.gxf7+  Qxf7  24.Bb6  Na2+  25.Nxa2  Qxa2  26.Bf5  Black has avoided getting mated by the first wave of attack, but unfortunately for him the defensive task has only just begun, and when it ends it will end badly. For instance:  Bc8  27.Bh7+  Kf8  28.Rxd6  Be6  29.Bc5  and White will win soon. }
22. Bxe6
{ Nicely done. White doesn't take back on c3, but offers up one more piece on the altar. The most important point is that the g6-pawn helps with the attack along the h-file. }
22... Rfb8
{ Likewise   22...Bxb2+  23.Kxb2  Qxc2+  24.Qxc2  Nxc2  doesn't offer any respite because after  25.Rh7 !!  there is no way to stop White doubling along the h-file. }
23. Rh8+
{ Giri finishes the game in style.  Also not wrong was   23.gxf7+  Kf8  24.bxc3  Ke7  25.Qg5+  Kxe6  26.Qf5+  Ke7  27.Bg5+  Kf8  28.Rh8# }
23... Kxh8 24. Bxf7 Bxb2+ 25. Kb1
{ Black resigned. A deadly check along the h-file will follow in extremely short order. }
*

