[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Movsesian, Sergei vs. Kasparov, Garry, Sarajevo, 2000"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. f3 b5 8. Qd2
Nbd7 9. O-O-O Bb7 10. g4
{ This is a moment at which Black makes an important choice of approach. Something has to be done about Nf6, because g4-g5 is threatened. }
10... Nb6
{ This is seen as the most important alternative. Black moves his queen's knight away to vacate the square for the other knight. In addition, he rules out the a4-square as a potential new home for the c3-knight, which makes ... b5-b4 an important positional threat. Note that there are no other good squares the knight can go to: on b1 it is dominated, and on e2 it blocks the f1-bishop in and allows Black the idea of ...Nc4, which is yet another possibility set up by the text move.  White, as usual in the Sicilian, would usually much rather trade his light-squared bishop for the b6-knight instead of the dark-squared bishop.  If Black were to play   10...h6  , that would imply  (for the most part)  a commitment to keeping his king in the centre. Long castling is not completely impossible  (in the distant future)  but short castling would leave Black extremely vulnerable to a quick g4-g5, opening lines with disastrous effect. }
11. Qf2
{ This possibility has also been known for a while. In addition to the fact that White's queen can no longer be hit by ...Nb6-c4, the first player also introduces the possibility of a nasty discovered-attack trick such as Nxe6 ! }
11... Nfd7
{ Giving White the time needed to clear a retreat square on c1 for his dark-squared bishop.  There is no time for   11...b4 ?  because of  12.Nxe6  fxe6  13.Bxb6  as seen in Garrido Dominguez-Komljenovic, 2002. }
12. Kb1 Rc8
{ Now long castling is definitively ruled out.  We could wonder about the logical   12...b4  . However it seems that after  13.Nce2  Nc4  White can simply tuck his bishop back into place on c1 and show Black's demonstrations to have been a little premature.  14.Bc1 ! }
13. Bd3
{ Given the subsequent course of events, most people who took the White side of this position after the present game chose a different move.   13.Nce2  removes the continuation Black chose in the game from consideration, and yields an interesting game. In a rapid game J.Polgar-Svidler, 2001 White managed to sacrifice and crash through the Black defensive lines in a manner which objectively may have been less than fully correct. }
13... Rxc3
{ Every player who plays the Sicilian must have this thematic exchange offering in his arsenal. GM Loek van Wely once said that he hardly even considered it to be a sacrifice. The white pawn structure is, indeed, mutilated badly enough that we barely need look for other compensation. }
14. bxc3 Qc7
{ The strong Polish grandmaster Wojtkiewicz had already played the exchange sacrifice in 1992, and continued here with the move   14...d5  - a choice which was later copied by the Slovak grandmaster Ftacnik. }
15. Ne2 Be7 16. g5
{ For what it's worth, the most popular move chosen by those with the misfortune to face this exchange sacrifice was   16.h4  . }
16... O-O
{ Herein lies the difference with 10... h6, the other common choice of Black players in this line. If there is no pawn weakness on his kingside, Black may permit himself short castling. Of course, there is still no guarantee that an attack will not take place  (h2-h4-h5 and g5-g6)  but this takes rather a long time to set in motion and Black can hope to ask probing questions on the other side of the board in the meantime. As we know from extensive analysis of similar Sicilian positions, even the arrival of a pawn on g6 is not necessarily cause for panic either. }
17. h4 Na4
{ Thus Kasparov improved on an older game. Due to White's pawn weaknesses, a swift attack is more or less guaranteed.  The older game Zagrebelny-Lingnau, 1993 continued   17...d5  18.h5  dxe4  19.Bxe4  Bxe4  20.fxe4  Nc4  21.Bc1  b4  22.cxb4  Bxb4  but after  23.Rh3 !  Black did not have enough to show for the material he had sacrificed. }
18. Bc1
{ After this passive move Black is definitely going to be for choice.  The search for counterchances with   18.h5  may not be crowned with success after  Ne5  but  19.Bd4  keeps the damage within manageable bounds. }
18... Ne5
{ Also rather strong was   18...d5 !  or the natural   18...Rc8  , for instance.  White now seeks his redemption on the other side of the board, but it will be too slow. }
19. h5 d5
{ A good moment for Black to crack open the centre and use it to transfer even more pieces to the attack on the queenside.  Also interesting was   19...f5 !? }
20. Qh2
{ May as well try.  After   20.h6  Black plays the customary  g6  and it is not clear how White can rustle up anything at all.  White's core problem in this position is that   20.g6  never actually delivers the goods in this position. Black can simply react  Bf6  - while there are several alternatives, this one seems best. }
20... Bd6 21. Qh3
{ Here the lady is very isolated from the struggle. In theory this move aids the kingside attack by targeting the e6-pawn in preparation for g5-g6, but White may not survive long enough for it to make a difference.  The alternative is   21.Bf4  leading to a good game for Black after  Nxc3+  22.Nxc3  Qxc3  23.Qd2  Qc7  , but perhaps White can resist better here than in the game. }
21... Nxd3
{ A surprising exchange, but Kasparov has made an excellent judgment call that it is justified here. }
22. cxd3
{ 22.Rxd3 ?  dxe4  sees the b7-bishop come to life, and now there is no way for White to avoid losing material. }
22... b4
{ Opening the position in a slightly unexpected way.  The obvious-looking   22...Nxc3+ ?  is in fact rather bad for Black. There follows  23.Nxc3  Qxc3  24.Bb2  Qb4  25.g6 !  and White takes over the initiative. In fact Black is lost in view of the detail that  Be5  is not working:  meanwhile   25...dxe4  26.h6 !  Be5  27.d4  is too late-White wins here too.  26.d4  Bf4  27.h6 !  Bxh6  28.gxf7+  Rxf7  29.Qxe6  White crashes through. }
23. cxb4
{ Also after   23.c4  dxc4  24.g6   24.dxc4  Be5 !  24...cxd3  25.Rxd3  Rc8  26.gxf7+  Kxf7  Black's initiative has far beyond manageable size.  Let's think about what happens if White tries to set his own attack in motion:   23.g6 ?  Nxc3+  24.Nxc3  bxc3  and thanks to the threat of ...c2+ it has become clear that White has misprioritised.  25.Ka1  c2  26.Rde1  Be5+  27.Bb2  Qc3 !  could be the elegant finish. }
23... Rc8 24. Ka1
{ Defending the knight with   24.Qf1  loses immediately:  Qc2+  25.Ka1  Bxb4  and now for instance  26.g6  Bc3+  27.Nxc3  Qxc3+  28.Kb1  Qb4+  29.Ka1  Rxc1+  30.Rxc1  Qb2#  is mate. }
24... dxe4
{ Black also wants his other bishop to contribute.  Prettier was   24...Bxb4 !?  but let's not allow that to interrupt our narrative too much. }
25. fxe4
{ Taking the other way on e4 leads to forced mate:   25.dxe4 ?  Be5+  26.Nd4  Bxd4+  27.Rxd4  Qxc1+  28.Rxc1  Rxc1# }
25... Bxe4
{ In view of the previous comment, we can see how vital it is that White be able to block ...Be5+ with the d-pawn. So this move, while eye-catching, should not be regarded as a mere 'trick'. }
26. g6
{ White is convinced.  Needless to say,   26.dxe4  Be5+  is mate as before.  Also after   26.Rhg1  Black will deliver mate, beginning with  Qc2 ! }
26... Bxh1 27. Qxh1 Bxb4 28. gxf7+ { 28.gxh7+  Kh8 } 28... Kf8
{ The king uses White's far-advanced pawn as a shield from checks. } 29. Qg2
Rb8
{ Black's rook is best placed on the b-file. With such a preponderance of force on the queenside it is certain that the days of the White king there are numbered. }
30. Bb2 { 30.Bd2  Ba3  31.Bc1  Bxc1  32.Rxc1  Qb6  leads to inevitable mate. }
30... Nxb2 31. Nd4
{ If White takes back it's mate in 4:   31.Kxb2  Bd2+  32.Ka1  Bc3+ } 31...
Nxd1
{ Kasparov goes for a classy finish. He allows the knight fork on e6, but the material gain comes too late for White. }
32. Nxe6+ Kxf7
{ After   32...Kxf7  33.Qxg7+   33.Nxc7  Bc3+  33...Kxe6  34.Qxc7   34.Qh6+  Kf5  sees Black escape the checks  34...Bc3+  Black will first win the queen and then give mate on b1. }
*

