[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Hillarp Persson, Tiger vs. Grooten, Herman, Hoogeveen, 2007 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. f3
Nc6 9. g4 O-O 10. O-O-O Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. g5 Nd7 13. h4 Rb8
{ After this somewhat unusual move, my opponent sank into deep thought. He later told me that he himself had also played this line of the Scheveningen with black, so I apparently did not really surprise him with my opening choice. He did not know the text move but he immediately recognized the merits of the move. Later it turned out that there were several grandmasters who had previously chosen this move- among them, the then world champion in Khalifman-Kasparov, 1988. I myself had a recollection of being shown the idea by GM Loek van Wely. He briefly summarised the idea for Black in the coming play: pawn to b4, knight to c4 via e5 or to a4  (and then c3)  via c5.  The most usual approach here is   13...b4  14.Na4  Qa5  15.b3  Nc5  .  In a game Leko-Kasparov, 2003, the Black player opted for   13...Qc7  and since then others have followed his example. }
14. Be3 Qa5
{ An aggressive move that as far as I know had never been played in this position. By the way, via a change of move order, I wanted to force the king to b1. If the b-line then opens, it will be to my benefit if the White king is along it ! But the queen is probably less good here than on c7.   14...b4  has been played by Black a couple of times, with not especially excellent results.   14...Qc7  is more normal, arranging to continue with ...Nd7-e5-c4. }
15. Kb1 b4 16. Ne2 Nc5
{ Most likely Black needs to wait for the right moment to commit this knight, and only move it to c5 or e5 when circumstances reveal more clearly which one would be better.  So, for instance,   16...Bb7  17.Nd4  Ne5 }
17. Nd4 Bb7
{ Maybe the bishop had to go to d7:   17...Bd7  Here it continues the protection of e6 and makes way for a rook to come to c8. This move was played in De la Villa Garcia-Guliev, 2002, which ended after a very volatile game in triumph for the second player. }
18. h5 { The situation is getting quite precarious for Black. } 18... Rfd8
{ The idea here is to prepare the central break ...d6-d5, but this is altogether too slow. The rook has to  (in any case)  not leave the protection of the weak f7-pawn.  Yet, saying that, it is already too late for   18...d5 ?!  to be much use because of  19.g6 !  dxe4   19...Bf6  doesn't hold water either after  20.h6 !  fxg6  21.hxg7  Bxg7  22.Qh2  when the queen manoeuvre is also decisive.  h5  23.Rg1  There is no way to defend the weak pawn on g6.  Another try seems to be   19...Qc7  but White can also meet this with the thematic queen switch to the kingside, which he sets up as follows:  20.e5 !  20.h6 !  White's attack is breaking through. For example:  fxg6  21.hxg7  Rf7  22.Qh2  with a double attack on h7 and b8.  Maybe   18...Na4  was a good idea to try and scare White- but White nevertheless comes out on top with good play. }
19. g6
{ The standard break. White's initiative is much faster, as can now be seen. }
19... Bf6 { One of the most principled standard reactions to g5-g6. } 20. gxf7+
{ Luring the king out its fortress, but maybe there was a better choice.  Once again the dangerous queen lift along the second rank came into consideration:   20.Qh2  , setting up a future h5-h6 or perhaps simply aiming to continue with Bc4  (attacking the Black king position from a second angle.) }
20... Kxf7
{ It is remarkable that the king is not completely busted yet, even on f7. }
21. Rg1 Na4
{ Black has no choice and goes for an all-or-nothing attack on the other side of the board. The position is discussed by GM Jacob Aagaard in the context of game-defining choices that players sometimes have to make. }
22. Bh3
{ My opponent thought for a long time over this move, thereby indicating that he agreed with me that the position was absolutely critical.  Rather better is the move which Aagaard suggested:   22.Bc4 !  The bishop plays a dual role here. On the one hand it attacks the weak point e6, and on the other it fulfils defensive functions- protecting the a2-pawn, and possibly also blocking the b-file. It will become clear later why these are important. }
22... Nc3+
{ The time has come for the black player to show his cards, because things would go downhill very quickly if he had to meekly cover the e6-pawn. }
23. bxc3 bxc3 24. Nb3 Bxe4
{ Of course there is no way back: Black presses on.  I saw that I could play   24...cxd2  , but the endgame after  25.Nxa5  Bxe4+  26.Nb3  Bxf3  27.Rxd2  Bxh5  didn't inspire confidence. White can for instance play to trade off the bishop on f6 with  28.Bg5  and thereby leave the Black pawns weak. }
25. Qc1
{ Of course the bishop could not be taken, because the pin on the b-file means White's queen will hang. The climax now approaches fast. My opponent had very little time to play his next 15 moves- perhaps only as many seconds- and partly prompted by this, I decided to play the interesting combination which followed. }
25... Rxb3+
{ Played after 20 minutes thought, and I didn't see any refutation. So why not ? In hindsight, though, the move is just a bit too optimistic.  Here   25...Bxf3 ?  was completely losing:  26.Rdf1  Be4  27.h6  g6  28.Rxf6+  Kxf6  29.Bg5+  Kf7  30.Bxd8  Qxd8  31.Qf4+  Bf5  32.Bxf5  exf5  33.Qc4+  and the end is nigh.  The only playable move here is   25...Bd5  although Black still has somewhat the worse of things after  26.Rd4 !  Rdc8   26...Bxd4 ?  27.Bxd4  e5  28.Qg5  27.h6  with a tricky position. }
26. axb3 Rb8
{ 'When one says A, one must also say B.' The German-derived chess truism is apposite in this position. }
27. fxe4
{ In mortal time trouble my opponent goes terribly wrong. There was a remarkable defense of which I had seen the first move, but not the follow-up. And here the story becomes interesting. After the game, I was congratulated by a large mass of people I didn't know. Among them was chess journalist Peter Doggers  (who started at ChessVibes and now works permanently at chess.com.)  He directed me to a table with a chessboard and asked me to play through the combination and make some remarks. Of course I wanted to fulfil his request, so my comments ended up being recorded on video  (in Dutch, @@LinkStart@@http://www.youtube@@LinkEnd@@. com/watch ?v=9VT71eyScj8 .)  What a shame, then, that the combination was not correct ! Discussion about it was happening on all kinds of sites, and inevitably some of the audience had turned on their silicon helpers and subjected the game to scrutiny. I did the same when I woke up the next morning in my B&B- and saw the refutation that everyone was talking about.  This computer defense starts with the obvious only move, which is:   27.Bxe6+ !  The bishop simply must be taken because otherwise it protects b3 and White will accomplish nothing.  Kxe6  Now there comes the second sacrifice:  28.Rxd6+ !  which is also with check. The important feature of this move is that it clears the d1-square for the eventual escape of White's king. Again, it must be taken. If not, White simply takes on e4 anyway.  Kxd6  29.Bf4+  Now the point is revealed. Black must give up the bishop on f6 in order to not simply lose the rook on b8. In either case, a vital piece for his attack will have been traded off. Nevertheless, the better way to go is  Be5  30.fxe4  Kc6  31.Bxe5  Qxe5  when Black has managed to maintain material equality. Despite this fact, White is definitely better  (if not winning)  because of Black's dreadfully unsafe king position.  Black now brings this crazy game to a pretty conclusion. }
27... Rxb3+ { My point had always been this exquisite second rook sacrifice. }
28. cxb3 c2+
{ White resigned at this point: Black administers the final touch with his last two pieces after having sacrificed no fewer than 4 of their colleagues. My opponent told me afterwards that he had not appreciated what this pawn sacrifice accomplished before it appeared on the board. Indeed, mate follows in three moves. }
29. Kxc2
{ 29.Kxc2  Qc3+  30.Kb1  It is amusing to remember that a few clubmates were following this game live and thought that I had just forced a draw with ... Qa1 +, Kc2, Qc3 + and so on. However, I was planning something else:  Qxb3+  and mate follows. My opponent resigned as soon as he'd noticed this elegant finish.   29.Qxc2  Qa1# }
29... Qc3+ *

