[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Ljubojevic, Ljubomir vs. Andersson, Ulf, Wijk aan Zee, 1976"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 a6 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Be3 Be7 9. f4 d6
{ This is the moment when White chooses whether he will attack the enemy king by means of a pawn storm, or just with pieces. In this game he chooses the latter. }
10. Qe1 O-O 11. Qg3 Bd7
{ Today   11...Nxd4  is considered to be the way for Black to obtain a level game:  12.Bxd4  b5  13.a3  Bb7  and here White has tried a selection of different attacking moves, none of which gives an objective edge.  14.Kh1   14.Rae1   14.Bd3 }
12. e5
{ An exceptionally dangerous pawn sacrifice for Black to have to deal with over the board. }
12... dxe5
{ Andersson shows the necessary courage and accepts the gift.  In the game Bok-Iturrizaga, 2014, Black declined the sacrifice with   12...Ne8  but after  13.Nxc6  Bxc6  14.Bd3  g6  15.Rae1  White had achieved a small plus. }
13. fxe5 Nxe5
{ Timman wrote regarding 12. e5  (in his 'Bible of Chess Analysis'- to my knowledge published only in Dutch)  that in the present game, Andersson knew that White's push was premature; and also that his own reaction to seeing the game had been: 'if this is any good, Black must stop playing the Sicilian !' As yet, though, things have not gotten that far. }
14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Rad1
{ With this, white threatens some kind of move with the d4-knight, unveiling the threat of Rxd6. It is important for Black to prepare a reaction, without making too many other concessions. }
15... Qb8
{ This is a typical Andersson move. In fact, it is the only one that successfully prepares the retreat of the d6-bishop in readiness for the above-mentioned idea by White.  In a game Neurohr-Darga, 1994, Black played   15...Rad8  16.Nb3  Nd5  and perhaps now White could have gained the upper hand by means of  17.Rxd5 !? }
16. Rd3
{ Another original attacking move. The rook is naturally immune   16...Nxd3 ?  17.Bxd6  . White threatens the annoying Re3. }
16... Ne8 { Another Black piece has retreated to the back rank ! } 17. Ne4 Bc7
{ It is worth pointing out what happens if Black takes the rook:   17...Nxd3  18.Bxd6  Nxd6   18...Qa7  19.c3 !  Nxd6  20.Nf6+  Kh8  21.Bxd3  and Black must give up one of the two attacked pieces, because  gxf6 ?  22.Qh4  f5  23.Qf6+  Kg8  24.Rf3  Rfd8  25.Qh6 !  is mate.  19.Nf6+  Kh8  20.Nxd7  Qc7  21.Nxf8  Nxb2 ?  It might appear that since Black has two pawns for the piece, and neither of White's knights is exceptionally safe, he has weathered the storm. But now there comes a crushing double knight sacrifice.   21...Nc5  is relatively better, but among other things White can choose to enter a 2-pawn-up endgame with  22.b4  Nce4  23.Qxg7+ !!  Kxg7  24.Nfxe6+  .  22.Ndxe6  fxe6  23.Nxh7  Kxh7  24.Qh3+  Kg8  25.Qxe6+  Nf7   25...Kh7  26.Rf3  is very close to mate  26.Kh1 !!  +-  With the unstoppable threat of Bh5, winning back the piece with interest and a mating attack. }
18. Rc3
{ And again white appears to be playing on the queenside, although in reality his laser-sharp vision is directed at the other side of the board. White threatens Rxc7. }
18... Nc6
{ Timman writes about this: 'Andersson knows better than anyone what pieces to withdraw in such positions, and where to.' It is indeed a pleasure to see how the Swedish grandmaster defends himself against one of the most dangerous tacticians in the world in a sophisticated way. }
19. Bxc7 Nxd4
{ Black counted on this excellent intermediate move and indeed he rescues himself by means of it.  Now   19...Qxc7 ?  would lose immediately to  20.Nf6+  Kh8  21.Qxc7  Nxc7  22.Nxd7  Nxd4  23.Bd3  and since the c7-knight and f8-rook are both hanging, Black loses material.  Ndb5  is the only try.   23...Rfc8  24.Nb6  Going for the same idea with the other knight also doesn't work-   23...Ncb5  24.Nxf8  Nxc3  25.bxc3  hits the remaining knight, which is an unfortunate detail.  24.Rc5  Rfd8  25.Nb6  Rab8  26.a4  Whoops ! Something has clearly gone wrong for Black. A knight falls. }
20. Bd3 Qa7
{ Now Black threatens a terrible discovered  (and double)  check with ...Ne2. }
21. Nc5 { Ljubojevic adds more fuel to the fire. } 21... Bb5
{ After   21...Nxc7  White is probably best off seeking the safe haven of a perpetual check, which is set up in spectacular fashion:  22.Bxh7+  It is better not to enter lines like   22.Qxc7 ?  Nb5 !  23.Bxb5   23.Qxd7 ?  Nxc3  23...Bxb5  24.Rf2  Bc6  and Black is for choice.  Another option is   22.Rf2  Rfd8  23.Qxc7  Be8  24.Qxb7  winning back the pawn. But Black can take it again and definitely not stand worse:  Qxb7  25.Nxb7  Rdb8  26.Nd6  Rxb2  22...Kxh7  23.Qxg7+  Kxg7  24.Rg3+  Now the rook executes a pendulum swing between g3 and h3. }
22. Be5
{ Again, an unprotected black piece is attacked with tempo. And another White piece reaches a menacing new post- but still there is nothing particularly wrong with Black's game. }
22... Nc6
{ Andersson finds the right defence again. It seems that he has survived the worst of the storm and that White should bail out somehow. What a shame, then, that Ljubojevic was not yet aware of that fact...   22...Rd8 ?!  23.Bxh7+  Kxh7  24.Qh4+  Kg8  25.Bxd4  would have been better for White. }
23. Bxh7+
{ A sacrifice to begin the attack on Black's king for real. The question is whether it is enough for a victory. Timman: 'Wonderful ! The manoeuvres on the queenside were just a feint, this is where the action is really at !  White could again force a draw in the manner already mentioned:   23.Bxg7  Nxg7  24.Bxh7+  Kxh7  25.Qxg7+  Kxg7  26.Rg3+  with perpetual check. }
23... Kxh7 24. Rf4
{ This was White's attacking idea: swing the rook in and hope for mate ! But analysis shows that Black has great defensive resources. Such great ones, indeed, that he is winning by force. However, the details of exactly how are very difficult, if not impossible, to find over the board for a human. }
24... f6
{ Andersson misses a good defensive option here, which was indicated by Timman- but he wrote that it was winning for White ! At the end of a long variation, however, Timman misses a great move for Black. So let's get stuck in.   The move is   24...f5 !  and we have to follow the line some way to figure out why this move might be any better than the seemingly less weakening ...f6.  25.Rh4+  Kg8  26.Qg6  Nxe5  27.Qxe6+  Rf7  28.Qxe5  One of the sacrificed pieces has been recovered and now that the queen protects the c5-knight, White is ready for Rc3-h3.  Rd8  29.Rch3  It looks like White has created an unstoppable mate threat-what is Black meant to do about the threat of Rh8 ? But the following moves serves as a handy illustration of the many hidden possibilities on offer in Sicilian games.  Re7 !!  This formidable move decides the game in Black's favour. Not only does it create a flight square for the Black king, but it also dislodges the enemy queen from its central post, the importance of which will be seen in the main line below:  There was also   29...Rd1+  and Black would also score the full point here.  30.Kf2  Rf1+  31.Kg3  Now in this instructive position Black must find another only move and then continue walking a tightrope.  Rf6 !  32.Qd5+  Kf8  33.Rh8+  Ke7  34.Rxe8+  Bxe8  35.Qe5+  Kf7  36.Rh8  and now finally  Bd7 !  is a suitably crazy-looking move with which Black can take over the initiative at last.  37.Nxd7  Qf2+  38.Kh3  Re1  39.Rf8+  Kg6  40.Rxf6+  Kg5 !  and Black is winning !  30.Qxe7  Neither is   30.Rh8+  Kf7  31.Qxf5+  Nf6  useful for White, even though the rook on d8 is hanging:  32.Rxd8  Moving the queen out of the way of ...Rf1+ tricks places it in the way of a knight fork:   32.Qg5  Rd1+  33.Kf2  Ne4+  32...Re1+  33.Kf2  Rf1+  This skewer decides the game in Black's favour.  30...Rd1+  31.Kf2  Rf1+  32.Kg3  Now the Black queen, for so long sidelined on the miserable a7-square, has a chance to give her 'opinion'.. .  After   32.Ke3  Re1+  White once more has his queen skewered.  32...Qb8+ !  This is the point- execution at long distance. White is unceremoniously mated !  Black would find himself beautifully mated if he were to try and defend by means of   24...Kg8 ??  - the queen is sacrificed again with  25.Bxg7  Nxg7  26.Qxg7+  Kxg7  27.Rg3+  Kh6  but now White has a second rook available and so can deliver more than just perpetual check.  28.Rh4#  Strangely enough, Black had another defensive possibility by which he could have kept a slight advantage, namely   24...Nxe5 !?  25.Rh4+  Kg8  26.Qxe5  and now once more the Black queen gets included in the defensive effort with   26.Qh3 ??  Ng6  26...Qb6 !!  .  27.Rch3  f6  Black has defended e6 and so gets to keep his material advantage. }
25. Rh4+ Kg8 26. Qh3
{ This doesn't just threaten Rh8 but also sets up Qxe6 ideas. } 26... Nd8 27.
Bd4 b6
{ 27...e5 ?  is no good because after  28.Rh8+  Kf7  29.Rxf8+  Kxf8  30.Ne6+ !  White wins the queen.  Nxe6  31.Bxa7 }
28. Nxe6 Nxe6 29. Qxe6+ Qf7 { 29...Rf7  30.Rch3  is forced mate. } 30. Qe4
{ This is typical of the 'calculator' Ljubojevic. Because there is a threat of mate on the kingside and a rook attacked on the queenside, he seems to have won. Andersson was short of time and that's why he misses the right defence here. }
30... g5
{ Timman later demonstrated that Black was fine after   30...Qxa2 !  31.Qh7+   31.Qxa8 ?!  actually loses to  Qb1+  32.Kf2  Qf1+  33.Kg3  Qe1+  34.Kh3   34.Bf2  Qe5+  35.Kh3  Qe6+  36.Kg3  Nd6 !  with a killer initiative  34...Bd7+  35.g4  g5  36.Rh5  Qf1+  Black wins decisive material.  31...Kf7  32.Qh5+  Kg8  White must restrict himself to giving perpetual check. }
31. Rh6 Ra7 32. Rch3 Qg7 33. Rg6 Rff7 34. c4
{ and here black resigned. Timman: 'And with this  (and I also speak on behalf of grandmasters Raymond Keene, Ken Rogoff and Gudmundur Sigurjonsson, before whose excited eyes I demonstrated the present game)  I sign off on my analysis. I want to convey to you the feeling that came to us during that session in the Spanish town of Orense: that this was the best game of the past twenty years.' }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Ljubojevic, Ljubomir vs. Andersson, Ulf"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1pqbbppp/p1nppn2/8/3NPP2/2N1B1Q1/PPP1B1PP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. e5
{ An exceptionally dangerous pawn sacrifice for Black to have to deal with over the board. }
1... dxe5
{ Andersson shows the necessary courage and accepts the gift.  In the game Bok-Iturrizaga, 2014, Black declined the sacrifice with   12...Ne8  but after  13.Nxc6  Bxc6  14.Bd3  g6  15.Rae1  White had achieved a small plus. }
2. fxe5 Nxe5
{ Timman wrote regarding 12. e5  (in his 'Bible of Chess Analysis'- to my knowledge published only in Dutch)  that in the present game, Andersson knew that White's push was premature; and also that his own reaction to seeing the game had been: 'if this is any good, Black must stop playing the Sicilian !' As yet, though, things have not gotten that far. }
3. Bf4 Bd6 4. Rad1
{ With this, white threatens some kind of move with the d4-knight, unveiling the threat of Rxd6. It is important for Black to prepare a reaction, without making too many other concessions. }
*

