[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Kamsky, Gata vs. Van Wely, Loek, Wijk aan Zee, 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 a6 7. O-O Be7 8. a4
Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. f4 Qc7 11. Kh1 Re8 12. Qe1
{ We already know this plan from other games. With the pawn already on a4 White usually chooses something else, but the present move is not completely without venom either. }
12... Nxd4
{ The usual way to answer. Black wants to clear up the situation in the center quickly. }
13. Bxd4 e5 14. Be3
{ The trade with   14.fxe5  dxe5  15.Qg3  is somewhat more popular. Here it is important that White already has his king on h1, so that Black has no possibility of equalising instantly with the bishop-trade ... Bc5. Now, though, Black has to go through some contortions to avoid being steamrollered immediately.  Bd8  16.Be3   16.Rxf6 ?!  doesn't promise anything, but Black does need to be accurate.  Bxf6   16...exd4 !?  gives a smaller advantage, but perhaps less stress.  17.Nd5  Qd6  18.Bc3   18.Bc5  Qc6  19.Rf1  Bd8  is similar  18...Bd8  White's initiative runs out of steam.  16...Kh8  Visually we can see that White has an initiative, but it proves difficult to use in any meaningful sense.  17.Bg5  Be6  18.Rad1  and now two moves have been played successfully for Black in practice:  Ng8  and 18... Be7. }
14... exf4 15. Bxf4 Be6 16. a5
{ At the time, a new idea. Kamsky wants to place Black's queenside pawns in a bind, and later develop pressure on that side of the board.  Previously   16.Qd2  was tried,  as well as   16.Qg3  . }
16... Nd7
{ This is Black's normal plan. The knight aims for e5. If Black had the time, he could even consider trying to put the bishop there  (... Be7-f6-e5)  but in this case he doesn't. }
17. Qg3 Ne5 18. Be3 Bf8 { Another normal reaction is   18...Rac8  19.Bb6  Qc6 }
19. Bb6 Qc6 20. Bd3
{ Initiating an interesting concept. White protects two of his pawns- on c2 and e4. The square which this bishop just left is made available for a 'pit stop' of the c3-knight on its way to d4, where it will stand a great deal better than in its current location. }
20... g6 21. Ne2 Bg7
{ Kamsky thought  (rightly)  that the swap of the beautiful e5-knight for his light-squared bishop would not be something his opponent wanted. He was right, partly because this swap would also lead to the dark-squared bishops being traded.   21...Nxd3 ?!  22.cxd3  Qb5  We should also consider the move   22...Qc2  . Now a possible continuation is  23.Qf3  Bg7  24.Bd4 !  Bxd4  25.Nxd4  Qc7  when White has a comfortable edge.  23.Bd4  Bg7  24.Bxg7  Kxg7  25.Nf4  White is better again. }
22. Nd4
{ The knight has arrived on d4 and this opens up the option of playing Nxe6. Here Black does not have a whole lot of options. }
22... Qd7 23. Rad1 Rac8
{ Maybe   23...Nc4  was better ? Well, after  24.Bxc4  Bxc4  25.Rfe1  Be5  26.Qf3  White is on top because he is poised to clamp the d6-pawn in place with a grip of incredible strength: b2-b3, c2-c4 and there will be no way out. }
24. b3
{ Here too White tries to make the same mechanism work. So Van Wely takes action to stop it immediately. }
24... Bg4 25. Rd2 Nxd3 26. Qxd3 d5
{ This was the idea. If White had managed to achieve c2-c4, the position would have been very much under his control. }
27. h3
{ 27.exd5  Qxd5  would pose Black no problem at all. The two weaknesses  (on e4 and d6)  have been exchanged for each other, and the opening of the centre favours Black with his bishops. Black is fine even if, as seems likely, the bishop-pair gets traded off somewhere in the near future. }
27... dxe4
{ Van Wely is well known as a 'pawn grabber' but here he had another route down which to go.  After the Ftacnik-endorsed   27...Bh6 !?  Black could have injected some much-needed dynamism into his position.  28.hxg4  dxe4  29.Qe2  Bxd2  30.Qxd2  Qxg4  Black has two pawns and a rook against two pieces. This material balance could go either way, depending on how well Black is able to generate tactics against the enemy king. }
28. Qe3 Be6 29. c4
{ White has managed to build up a nice central position. His pawn structure on the queenside is beautiful and his pieces hold their central outposts firmly. The queenside pawn majority may become useful in a future endgame, and the question is really what Black can summon up by way of compensation. }
29... h5
{ Heading fearlessly for a situation where White has a queen against rook, bishop and pawn.  Much safer was   29...Qe7  but after  30.Qxe4  White would also have had the better of this game. }
30. Nb5
{ Even stronger was   30.Nf5 !?  Here too the queen must be given. After  Qxd2  31.Qxd2  Bxf5  32.Qg5 !  White has the advantage. }
30... axb5 31. Rxd7 Bxd7 32. Qf4
{ Perhaps letting the advantage slip somewhat.  More logical was   32.Bd4 !?  Bxd4   32...bxc4 ??  33.Bxg7  Kxg7  34.Qd4+  wins a piece.  33.Qxd4  Here, despite Black's strong e-pawn, White has a small and stable advantage.  Re7  Less good is   33...Bc6  when after  34.Qf2  Rf8  35.cxb5  Bxb5  36.Re1  White has managed to get the e-pawn completely under control.  34.cxb5  Bxb5  35.Re1  Rce8  36.Re3  Whether this is actually enough to win, however, is still up for debate. }
32... Be6 33. cxb5 Bxb3 34. Be3
{ It is understandable that White wants to put black's passed pawn 'under lock and key'. When that is done, he can begin to push with a5-a6.  A nice positional trap is   34.Rc1 !?  which Black has to meet by  Bc4  , leaving the position not entirely clear.  Instead, by trading on c1 with   34...Rxc1+ ??  Black would lose immediately. After  35.Qxc1  there is very simply no way to prevent the a-pawn from running. }
34... Bc4 35. Rc1
{ Trading off the b5-pawn is not a healthy thing for White's winning chances.  But   35.Rb1  Bd3  36.Rb3  Bc2  doesn't keep them either at this point. }
35... Bxb5 36. Rxc8 Rxc8 37. Qxe4 Bc6
{ White has an advantage, but most likely in name only, after the trade   37...Ba6  38.Bd4  because Black is extremely solid and has good fortress chances. }
38. Qc2 Re8 39. Bf2 Re6 40. Kg1 Be5 41. Qb3 Bf4 42. h4
{ The game would have ended in a draw after   42.Qc4  Bc7  43.Qc3  Re2 } 42...
Re4 43. Qb6 Be5
{ This move is rather lax, but there still isn't any punishment available.  After   43...Re6  to leave the c6-bishop protected, White would have no means of breaking through. Nothing suggests itself after  44.Qd8+  Re8  . }
44. Qc5
{ Perhaps Kamsky had seen the consequences of the alternative and therefore tried to play the same idea in a different way.  Here there was an opportunity to create a passed pawn:   44.a6  with the following variations.  Ra4  45.a7  Here   45.axb7  gives nothing because of  Ra1+  46.Be1  Bxb7  47.Qe3  White even has to be careful to avoid   47.Qxb7 ?  which actually loses to  Bg3 !  47...Bg7  Here neither side is playing for anything in particular.  45...Ra1+  46.Be1  Rxe1+  47.Kf2  Ra1  Black is temporarily material up, but he loses the rook.  48.Qd8+  Kg7  49.a8=Q  Rxa8  50.Qxa8  Finally we get the material balance with which the game will most likely also end: queen against two bishops and two pawns. The pawn structure, with no breaks or entry points for White, dictates that he will not win this game. }
44... Bc7
{ The game was still basically a draw after   44...Bd7  45.g3  Bg7  , on balance of probability }
45. a6 Ra4 46. Bd4
{ This strong move is probably what Black missed. White prevents all the tactics based on ...Ra1+, and with the same bishop sets up some mating motifs against the Black king. The fact that this costs him the a-pawn is not so relevant, because Black's pieces are not in a position to defend adequately. }
46... Rxa6
{ There was one more opportunity to create a fortress- this time with only a rook and pawn for the queen.   46...bxa6  47.Qxc6  Rxd4  48.Qxc7  Re4  49.Qc8+  Kg7  50.Qxa6  Now Black takes another pawn:  Rxh4  51.Qa1+  Kg8  52.Qe5  Rg4  Now the first question is whether the white king can cross the fourth rank. After the first question, there are two more to come: even if White somehow succeeds in pushing the black rook back from first g4 and then f5, maybe there is no way through after it parks itself on e6. I doubt all three of these problems can be resolved in White's favour. Most likely, this position is still within the drawing zone. }
47. Qe7
{ Not only threatening the c7-bishop but also intending a queen move to the long diagonal- either f6 or e5  (in case Black stops defending the latter square.) }
47... Ba5 { 47...Ra4  48.Bc5  Bf4  49.Qf8+  Kh7  50.Qxf7+  Kh8  51.Qxg6  +- }
48. Qe5 Kf8 49. Qd6+ Ke8 { 49...Kg8  50.Qb8+  is just mate-  Kh7  51.Qh8# } 50.
Bf6
{ Now the Black pieces are so badly out of position that he cannot muster any defence of the e7-square. }
50... Bb6+ 51. Kh2 { Here Black resigned because mate is inevitable. } *

