{ Not only threatening the c7-bishop but also intending a queen move to the long diagonal- either f6 or e5  (in case Black stops defending the latter square.) }
4... Ba5 { 47...Ra4  48.Bc5  Bf4  49.Qf8+  Kh7  50.Qxf7+  Kh8  51.Qxg6  +- } 5.
Qe5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Vogt, Lothar vs. Andersson, Ulf, Cienfuegos, 1975"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Be2 a6 7. f4 Qc7 8. O-O
Be7 9. Kh1 Nc6 10. Be3 Nxd4
{ Andersson sometimes took the opportunity to see if he could free his game with early action in the center.   10...O-O  is of course the most played option. }
11. Qxd4
{ Seems logical but has disappointed in practice.  It is more usual to take back with the bishop.   11.Bxd4  The Black position can also be liberated with  e5  12.fxe5  dxe5  but he then has to calculate the exact consequences of the exchange sacrifice  13.Rxf6 !?  The best reaction is in fact to avoid accepting the exchange and just take back the bishop.  exd4  After   13...Bxf6  14.Nd5  Qd6  15.Bc3  and now the logical  Bd8 ?!  White can get an initiative with  16.Bb4  Qc6  17.Qe1  .  14.Nd5  Qe5  15.Rf2  Bd6  16.g3  O-O  and Black has chances of an advantage. }
11... O-O
{ One should now play   11...e5  which has also appeared on the board.  12.Qd3  O-O  13.a4  See Almasi-De la Riva Aguado, 2002, among others. }
12. Rad1
{ Currently   12.a4  with the idea of holding back ... b7-b5 is seen as more promising for White. }
12... b5
{ Seeing that black has pushed on the wing without having played ...e5, White tries to profit from the slightly unstable position in the centre. Hence: }
13. e5 dxe5 14. Qxe5
{ This may not be something White should aim for, but on a superficial level things seem to have worked out.   14.fxe5  is met by the simple  Nd7  and White is saddled with a weak e5-pawn. The key question is whether he can strike while the iron is hot with  15.Bd3 !?  seeing that it is rather dangerous for Black to take on e5.  Nc5   15...Nxe5 ?  16.Bf4  wins for White in view of  Bf6  17.Ne4   15...Qxe5  loses material to  16.Be4  Rb8  17.Qa7 !   17.Qxe5  Nxe5  18.Ba7  Bd7  would still be playable for Black. }
14... Qb8
{ This is the characteristic backwards-queen-move upon which Ulf Andersson appears to have held a patent !   14...Qxe5 ?!  is no good:  15.fxe5  Nd5   15...Nd7 ?  16.Bf3  Rb8  17.Ba7  simply wins an exchange without losing anything in return.  16.Nxd5  exd5  17.Bf3  and now after  Bf5  18.c3  Black will have a terminally weak isolated pawn. }
15. Qxb8
{ White finds that his bag of tricks is suddenly empty and therefore decides to exchange the queens, but the endgame is very beneficial for black.  Now   15.Bf3  could have been met by  Bb7 }
15... Rxb8 16. Ba7 Ra8 17. Bb6 Bb7
{ A great moment for a strategic discussion. The queens have been exchanged, a state of affairs which Black players tend not to object to because it means White will not be able to develop a kingside attack. Black is in principle better here because he has an important outpost on d5 and can start a minority attack on the queenside, the final target of which will be White's c-pawn. pawn c2. In addition, he can use the half-open c-line for various operations that may be beneficial. A somewhat less obvious weakness is the one on f4. Only much later will this last factor play a role in the development of the game. }
18. a3 Rfc8
{ Black chooses the f-rook. Why ? Because he has decided that during the development of his queenside attack, he wants to keep two pairs of rooks on the board. For one thing, White's rooks can only operate along the d-file, and there is no particular prospect of him gaining an entry square there, so there is no need to fight for the d-file. For another, the a8-rook can actually be quite useful on the queenside. }
19. Ba5
{ This not only covers the knight on c3  (in particular, against the threat of ... Bxa3)  but also prevents ... b5-b4 in the long run. However, the bishop is not in the best position here. }
19... g6
{ We get another instructive moment here. With this little pawn move Black fixes the enemy pawn on f4. This can become an important target later on, especially if Black has a rook on c4. In addition to that, the pawn move provides a way for the Black king to enter battle on the kingside. }
20. h3
{ The psychological effect of Black's solid but useful moves begins to pay dividends. White, in his impatience, allows his f4-pawn to be isolated.  Better was   20.Bf3 }
20... h5
{ Black wants to separate  (by means of ... h5-h4)  the f4-pawn from its natural protector on the g-file. It helps that at this moment White cannot plug the hole by playing g2-g3, because that's illegal. }
21. Bf3
{ Playing into Black's hands a little bit, but in my opinion the b7-bishop was sufficiently strong that soon enough White would find himself compelled to trade it off.   21.h4  prevents Black's aforementioned idea, but at the cost of creating more dreadful weaknesses in his own camp. }
21... Bxf3 22. Rxf3 h4
{ This is the position Black was going for. The f4-pawn is completely fixed in position and has no natural protector. At the same time, thanks to the exchange of light-squared bishops, Black's rooks can count on the use of the c4-square. }
23. Rd2 Rc4
{ Here another aspect of the minority attack appears: the occupation of the outpost on c4  (as mentioned by Nimzovich in his famous book 'My System'.)  The rook is very well positioned here, providing lateral pressure against the f4-pawn. It must therefore be expelled, but that leads to new weaknesses in white's camp. }
24. b3
{ This pawn set weakens squares on the c-file and this is another thing Black is often thrilled to see in the Sicilian. }
24... Rc6 25. a4
{ White naturally needs to do something about his a3-pawn and chooses to pose the question to Black's strong b5-pawn. }
25... b4 26. Ne2
{ White now has a backwards pawn on c2, but black cannot get his pieces to control c3 sufficiently fast to prevent that pawn from being exchanged with c2-c4. Yet there is a move available with which Black would obtain a winning position.  Placing the knight on the edge of the board would lead to swift tragedy for White:   26.Na2 ?  Ne4 !  and Black wins material. The rook on d2 cannot go to e2 because of ... Ng3+, and for that reason, on the very next move c2 will become undefended. }
26... Rac8
{ The strongest move was   26...Rb8 !  keeping the bishop on a5 perfectly corralled. White would then have to play  27.c3  bxc3  28.Rxc3  Rxc3  29.Bxc3  Rxb3  when Black has accomplished everything he wanted. }
27. c4
{ Resolving White's issues on the c-file, but in their place comes a new one on the neighbouring b-file: the backward pawn on b3.  It would be logical for White to try and trade off all the rooks with   27.Nd4  Rc3  28.Rxc3  Rxc3  29.Rd3  Rxd3  30.cxd3  . However, this doesn't really solve his problems- the pawn structure is still fractured. Black could, for instance, continue in the following way.  Nd5  31.Ne2  Bd6  and with ...Kg7-f6-f5 in the pipeline, things are continuing to go slowly but surely wrong for White. }
27... bxc3 28. Rxc3 Nd5
{ In some sense, this move is the culmination of the strategic changes that began when White exchanged his e-pawn for Black's d-pawn. Black now has a pawn on e6 to defend the beautiful outpost on d5, and White has no pawn to attack it- hence the knight will be almost impossible to dislodge. }
29. Rxc6 Rxc6
{ Now begins a new phase of the game. White has two weaknesses: the one on b3- for the moment still a backward pawn- and the one on f4, which is for all intents and purposes isolated. Black's strategy will be to attack first the one and then the other, hoping to disrupt White's co-ordination more each time until his position collapses under the weight of its own internal contradictions. But of course he will have to pay attention to White's one active idea: b3-b4-b5, which if realised would make the backward pawn into a rather strong passed pawn. }
30. Rb2
{ White immediately telegraphs his intention to do just that, but it isn't quite so simple. }
30... Bf6 31. Ra2
{ Here   31.Rb1 ?  looks like a try, but the b-pawn is not worth the collapse of everything else in White's position.  Rc2  32.Ng1  Nxf4  and it transpires that White must give up at least two pawns before the b-pawn even gets to b5. When it gets there, the play will still be insufficient. It is important to note that  33.b4  can be answered by the nice prophylactic move  Ra2 !  when even the prospect of a passed b-pawn will be erased. }
31... Rc8
{ A very strong move, which is almost pure prophylaxis. Black prepares to bring his rook to b8 and halts the b-pawn in its tracks.  It seems like Black could have a trick, but it fails.   31...Nxf4  32.Nxf4  Rc1+  33.Kh2  Be5  34.Bd2  Rd1  Now Black threatens both ...Rxd2 and ...g5. But White can defend against both by playing  35.g3 !  hxg3+  36.Kg2 }
32. Bd2
{ Naturally   32.b4  would be met by the same move  Rb8  with the win of a pawn. }
32... Rb8 33. Nc1 { The positions of the White pieces make a sad impression. }
33... Nb4
{ I suspect that Andersson was reluctant to trade off his great knight for the 'bad' bishop on d2. But as Petrosian put it: 'it doesn't matter what is taken off the board, only what stays on.' And here that is absolutely the correct attitude. }
34. Bxb4
{ White needs to give up the bishop.   34.Ra3 ?  Bb2  is just wretched. } 34...
Rxb4
{ Now Black has a vantage point from which to put pressure on both White's weaknesses mentioned above- b3 and and f4. It is beyond doubt that both Black pieces function better than their opposite numbers. }
35. Rf2 Be7 { Preparing to add nails to the coffin of the White f-pawn. } 36.
Rf3 Bd6 37. Ne2
{ It is a miracle that White can still defend all his pawns at all, but now he is left completely passive and the final blow must come soon. }
37... Re4 38. Rd3 { An active defence. } 38... Bc5
{ Why would Black trade off his bishop for the crippled White knight ?  He would rather not play   38...Bxf4  39.Nxf4  Rxf4  because White gets active with  40.Rd6  -though, saying that, the ending after  Rb4  41.Rxa6  Rxb3  must also be winning. }
39. Rc3 Bf2 { Holding the enemy king in place. } 40. Rc2 Kg7
{ The time is ripe to activate the Black king- White's is not going anywhere for the foreseeable future, so this is another advantage to add to Black's list. }
41. Ng1
{ Giving up a pawn, but there was nothing else to do anyway.  Of course, White could have tried   41.Rb2  which is still a reasonable move. But he would surely have been aware that Black would continue with  a5  and then complete his intended king manoeuvre to f5. }
41... Rxf4 42. Nf3 Bg3 43. Kg1 Re4 { Keeping the king cornered. } 44. Kf1 Re3
{ Black is no longer bothered about the idea of b3-b4. The threats against the White king are now the most salient feature of the position; Black stands ready to tighten his mating net with ...e5-e4. }
45. Rb2 { 45.b4  e5  46.Rc1  Rb3  is rather similar. } 45... e5 46. Rb1 e4
{ The continuation could have been   46...e4  47.Nd2  f5  48.b4  Ra3  49.b5  Also after   49.a5  Ra2  the pawns are going nowhere.  49...Rxa4  50.b6  Ra2  51.Nc4  Rf2+  52.Kg1  Rc2  White's counterplay is halted with plenty of time to spare. }
*

