[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games: Scheveningen"]
[Black "Karpov, Anatoly vs. Kasparov, Garry, Moscow, 1985"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is perhaps one of the most memorable games in the whole of chess history. Let me bring you back to that time and set the scene by telling the story of the 1984 match. A year before the present game, the first 'K-K' match had occurred. It was a match using the format of a race to 6 wins, with unlimited rounds.   This had actually been the kind of match Fischer wanted to play against Karpov a further nine years earlier, but at the time FIDE didn't agree- and when Fischer refused to play under other circumstances, they simply awarded Karpov the title. So Karpov had to prove to his public that he was the strongest player in the world, and he did so by fending off two challenges from Korchnoi. The 1984 match was then Karpov's third challenge, which was not from Korchnoi or even the aging ex-champion Smyslov  (who reached the Candidates final that year !)  but from Smyslov's vanquisher Kasparov, who was then just a young genius from Azerbaijan.   The match reached 5-0 in Karpov's favour and everyone thought it would soon be over. But at exactly that juncture, Kasparov began playing in the 'attrition' style. He made Karpov play against his own systems; whatever Karpov played with White, Kasparov would try it in a game soon after, and of course many draws ensued. In amongst them, though, Kasparov scored three wins. Yet at exactly this moment, with the action reaching a crescendo and the score at 5-3, the match was called off by FIDE president Florencio Campomanes.   Both players were furious. Kasparov because he claimed his opponent was about to collapse, Karpov because he only had to win one game. Picking up the action in 1985, the new arrangement was for a 24-game match  (as in Reykjavik 1972, and before that)  with two extra rights granted to the champion: he would have the right to a rematch if he lost, and in case of a 12-12 tie, he would retain his title. With 22 of 24 games played and the score tied, Kasparov managed to win the penultimate round and take the lead.   This meant he just needed to draw the present game. Meanwhile, Karpov, with white, absolutely had to win that game to keep his world title. I remember very well that at the time of the game I was playing for the Eindhoven Chess Club in a top-division match in Hilversum against HSG. At this time there was no internet yet, but we did have the ability to get a 'nearly' live transmission of the match using Teletext- a board was set up next to the device so that we could follow the Moscow game while playing our own. Of course, this board attracted a great deal more attention than any of our own boards, notwithstanding that we were some of the highest-ranked players in the Netherlands.   Several thousand miles away from the world championship match, we were feeling its tension. At a certain moment, when Kasparov opened the position with a double pawn sacrifice, some of us actually abandoned our own games to watch ! Nobody was making predictions or kibitzing: we were all just enthralled by the high drama, perfectly well aware that we were watching the unfolding of one of chess history's most defining moments. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e6 7. O-O Be7 8. f4
O-O 9. Kh1 Qc7 10. a4 Nc6 11. Be3 Re8
{ This order of moves has become commonplace in our modern tournament practice. The significance of this subtle rook move is discussed elsewhere in this book. }
12. Bf3 Rb8 13. Qd2
{ As we explained in the chapter introduction, both sides are perfectly content to make waiting moves. However, Black now has no more useful ones and should now commit his bishop. }
13... Bd7
{ Now that Black has shown his cards regarding the light-squared bishop, white can stage a pawn storm. To do this, he first needs to stabilise his centre, i.e. prevent Black from opening things up with .. e6-e5. }
14. Nb3
{ Still following the chapter introduction.  The immediate   14.g4 ?!  doesn't work so well. The variation that follows is an instructive illustration of my points about this line.  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  e5 !  and the white center is broken apart, which completely disrupts the flow of his kingside attack. Incidentally, the structure after  16.Be3  exf4  17.Bxf4  Be6  18.g5  Nd7  is also interesting. White controls the d5-square, and Black the e5-square. The two sides will probably play their respective knights to those squares soon. }
14... b6
{ Otherwise White was threatening to establish a grip on the queenside with a4-a5. }
15. g4 { Finally beginning to advance. } 15... Bc8
{ Black makes d7 available for his knight and begins the delayed routing of his light-squared bishop to its optimal post on the long diagonal where it projects a shadow all the way down to the white king in the opposite corner. }
16. g5 Nd7 17. Qf2
{ White's most direct plan is to place two major pieces on the h-file with which to attack the h7-pawn. Of course, the question is how he means to accomplish this. In any case, Bf3-g2 is a good idea. But to then continue with Rf3-h3 is a bit crude, unless of course it delivers mate immediately. More reasonable would be the attempt to make use of the rook in its present  (and not bad)  position on the f-file. Under some circumstances, White can play f4-f5 and possibly g5-g6. At the same time, the rook on a1, which currently is not doing useful work, can be transferred over to the h-file via d1. When it gets to d1, the e3-bishop can be tucked back into position on c1. While solving the problem of the two pieces Black will be attacking when he plays ... Na5-c4, an additional perk is that the move gets out of the way of the rook and allows it to swing to the kingside via d3. }
17... Bf8
{ Black has a rather refined defensive timeline in mind. The bishop goes back to f8, from where it will head to g7 after that square has been cleared by ...g7-g6. That would then leave the f8-square free for a knight, and then Black would be defending the weak h7-pawn against any mating attempts. At the same time, Black is preparing to answer a possible f4-f5 with ...exf5 followed by central play. It is essential that he counter White's piece control of d5 to do this- by ...Bb7  (as played next)  or possibly ...Nb4. }
18. Bg2 Bb7 19. Rad1
{ White follows the above plan. It is also fully in Karpov's style that he first wants to mobilize all forces before taking concrete action. }
19... g6 20. Bc1
{ In this way White prepares the rook-lift over the third rank. } 20... Rbc8
{ Continuing the trench warfare. Both players are busy preparing their pieces- on both flanks- to realize their full potential later. }
21. Rd3
{ As mentioned before, White leaves the f1-rook in place. By doing so, he leaves the option of f4-f5 open.  White still doesn't really have active options. The thrust   21.f5  would commit to an attack which ultimately lands too slowly after the natural reply  Nce5  , with which Black gains perfect control over the e5-square. }
21... Nb4 22. Rh3 Bg7
{ Black has timed everything precisely: the f8-square is ready to receive his knight just at the moment when it might be needed. }
23. Be3
{ The writing is on the wall: White no longer has a concept of how to continue his attack.  After   23.Qh4  Black defends himself with  Nf8  The question is whether the situation now called for a decisive thrust:   23.f5 !?  exf5  24.exf5  Bxg2+  25.Kxg2  Qb7+  26.Kg1  Now the White king's position is more open than Black's. Nevertheless, his attacking possibilities are also more evident. There is sometimes a possibility of f5-f6 in addition to the present threat of fxg6.  Rc4  Black has to create something, but he does allow his opponent's main threat of fxg6.   26...Nf8 ?!  27.f6  Bh8  is no fun for Black.  27.fxg6  Rg4+   27...Ne5  28.gxh7+  Kh8  29.Rg3  Rh4  doesn't equalise either.  28.Rg3  Rxg3+  29.hxg3  Ne5  30.gxh7+  Kh8  This position could be rather advantageous for White, though of course it remains double-edged in practice. What is clear is that Karpov missed a major opportunity to generate winning chances. }
23... Re7
{ This move received much praise from several commentators afterwards. The rook has a prophylactic function  (defending the seventh rank)  , and doubling along the e-file is also made possible. We will soon see why Kasparov is so eager to double his rooks on this closed file. }
24. Kg1
{ Karpov continues making prophylactic moves  (he would rather ...Bxg2 did not come with check)  but this is of course not an attacking move in any sense.  He had,nevertheless, to play   24.f5  .  exf5  and now it was possible to complicate matters with  25.Bd4 !?  For instance:   25.exf5  Bxg2+  26.Qxg2  Rce8  when Black has great counterplay  25...Bxd4  26.Nxd4  fxe4  27.Qh4  Nf8  28.Nxe4  Bxe4  29.Bxe4  and White has no particular advantage, but the position is unbalanced enough for his needs. }
24... Rce8
{ Bringing everything under control. Now White can't afford to open the e-file. }
25. Rd1 f5
{ And now Kasparov can even opt for an active choice like this one. This push was one of the secondary intentions of black's brilliant 23 ... Re7 ! move. }
26. gxf6 Nxf6
{ A pawn sacrifice to start us off. Did Kasparov calculate the consequences accurately ?  Nothing is too badly wrong with   26...Bxf6  but after  27.Qd2  Bxc3  28.bxc3  Na2  29.Qxd6  White could nevertheless count on a small advantage. }
27. Rg3
{ Karpov does not take up the challenge. If he had done so, he would probably have retained the world title. What would the chess world look like nowadays ?  After   27.Bxb6  Ng4   27...Qb8  28.a5  28.Bxc7  Nxf2  29.Bxd6  Nxd1  30.Bxe7  Nxc2  31.Nxd1  Rxe7  32.e5  White would have had an extra pawn, and furthermore Kasparov's bishop pair is getting traded. While Black could obviously have continued  (for instance with ...g5)  there is no doubt that the pawn advantage is quite healthy. }
27... Rf7 { But Kasparov offers the pawn a second time, and now it is taken. }
28. Bxb6 Qb8 29. Be3 Nh5 30. Rg4 Nf6
{ Black is perfectly fine to draw the game. } 31. Rh4
{ Karpov had to try this, but on its new post the rook looks singularly unhealthy.   31.Rg3  Nh5  32.Rf3  Nf6  temporarily avoids the repetition, but White has nothing better than 31. Rg3 anyway. }
31... g5
{ Now the cat is truly among the pigeons. It is unbelievable that the young Kasparov played in such determined fashion in a game where the world title was at stake. }
32. fxg5 Ng4
{ He is not to be distracted.  After   32...Nxe4  there was the disturbing prospect that White might sacrifice a queen for promising compensation:  33.Bxe4 !?  Rxf2  The cold-blooded   33...Bxe4 !  , however, keeps some advantage.  34.Bxh7+  Kf7  35.Bxf2  White's chances should be preferred. }
33. Qd2 Nxe3 34. Qxe3 Nxc2
{ The second player wins back one of his pawns, but he is still down the second one. Compensation is offered by the bishop pair, and especially by the unsafe position of the white king. }
35. Qb6
{ Maybe not the most normal place for the queen, but White's problems had already begun.  After   35.Qe2  the Black queen peeps out from her hidey-hole on b8:  Qa7+  36.Kh1  Ne3  37.Rxd6 ?   37.Rg1  is relatively better but Black still keeps the upper hand by playing  Nxg2  38.Qxg2  Rf2  37...Ref8 !  Black takes over the initiative. There is no way of parrying the double threat of ...Rf2 and ...Rf1+. }
35... Ba8 { In mutual time trouble, Kasparov sets up a nasty trick. } 36. Rxd6
{ An ugly error made under clock pressure.  Forced was   36.Qxb8  but after  Rxb8  White must be satisfied with  37.Bh3  Not   37.Nd2 ?  Ne3  38.Re1  Bd4  37...Rxb3  Or the safe   37...Re7  .  38.Bxe6  Bd4+  39.Kh1  Rxb2  when Black is surely not worse. }
36... Rb7
{ Undoubtedly Karpov missed this until it was too late. Black suddenly stands poised to grab the full point. }
37. Qxa6 Rxb3
{ Kasparov doesn't take advantage of White's slip in the most optimal fashion.  With the nasty   37...Nb4 !  38.Qe2  Qxd6  Kasparov would have ended the game immediately. }
38. Rxe6 Rxb2
{ Understandable, but there was better.  Objectively,   38...Ne3 !  39.Rxe8+  Qxe8  brings about a completely winning position. }
39. Qc4 { Karpov manages to find the only move to stay in the game. } 39... Kh8
40. e5
{ But exactly on the last move before the time control, white plays a dud and Black wins without further trouble.  Here   40.Rxe8+  Qxe8  41.Nd1  Na3  42.Qd3  Ra2  43.g6  would have generated enough play to split the point- not that that would have been any use. }
40... Qa7+ 41. Kh1 Bxg2+ 42. Kxg2 Nd4+
{ White resigned, which made Kasparov the new world champion. He was  (and is)  a truly remarkable player; the strongest in the world for at least 15 years and only dethroned in 2000... by his own protege, Kramnik. }
*

