[Black "Rueda, Libardo vs. Browne, Walter S"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/1p2bppp/p2pbn2/4p1B1/Pn2PP2/1NN5/1PP1B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White indicated with his last move that he would quite like to get active. But he has overlooked something. What might that be ? }
1... Qb6+ 2. Kh1 Nxc2 { White had probably missed this. } 3. Qxc2 Bxb3
{ Black had a healthy extra pawn, which he was able to swiftly convert into a full point. }
4. Qd3 O-O 5. Ra3 Rfe8 6. a5 Qb4 7. f5 Rac8 8. Qf3 d5 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. exd5 Ne4
11. Qg4 Bxg5 12. d6 Nf2+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises & Solutions"]
[Black "Ponomariov, Ruslan vs. Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1r1k1/1pqbbppp/p2p1n2/4pP2/PP2P3/1RNBB3/2PQ2PP/R6K b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What is Black's best move ? Work out some variations. } 1... d5 2. exd5 e4
{ This is naturally the point. White can't take the pawn, because then he would lose a piece. }
3. Bf1
{ Starting to go wrong.   21.Nxe4 ?  Nxe4  22.Bxe4  Qe5  is simply a double attack  (on the a1-rook and e4-bishop)  that White can't resolve.   21.Be2  was necessary but after this Black could nevertheless claim an advantage with:  Bxf5  or   21...Bxb4  22.Rxb4  Qxc3  also deserves consideration and gives Black something. }
3... Bxf5
{ More concrete was   21...Ng4  22.Bf4   22.Bg1  e3  23.Qe2  Bxf5  22...Bd6  and White can't patch the leak anymore. For instance  23.Bxd6  Qxd6  24.g3  Qf6 }
4. b5 Ng4 5. Bg1 Bc5
{ Black gets a major advantage in this way, but he could have won immediately.   23...e3  24.Qe2  Qe5  is curtains. }
6. d6 Bxd6 7. Nd5 Qxc2
{ Black has won enough material that we can stop commentary. } 8. Qxc2 Rxc2 9.
h3 Nf2+ 10. Bxf2 Rxf2 11. bxa6 bxa6 12. Bxa6 Be6 13. Rd1 Ra2 14. Bb5 Bxd5 15.
Rbb1 Re5 16. Bf1 e3 17. Rb6 e2 18. Bxe2 Bxg2+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
