[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises & Solutions"]
[Black "Kovchan, Alexander vs. Karjakin, Sergey"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2q2rk1/1p2bppp/p2pbn2/P3p3/2r1P3/2N1BP2/1PPQ2PP/R1NR2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ With which strong move can Black take over the initiative ? } 1... d5
{ The rule of thumb is that if black can manage to execute the breakthrough ... d6-d5, he has good play. Is this possibility tactically justified here ? Yes, because after }
2. exd5 { Black can actually just take back twice on d5. } 2... Nxd5 3. Nxd5
Bxd5 4. c3
{ Forced, otherwise Black takes on c2. But Black's game is pleasant anyway.  The point is that   19.Qxd5 ?  would lose to  Rd8 }
4... Bc6 { 19...e4  is a strong alternative. } 5. Nd3 Qf5 6. Nf2
{ 21.b3  might have defended better, but after  Rh4  Black also has a great game. }
6... Rh4 7. Qe2 Qh5 8. h3 e4
{ The last good move to make sure White doesn't get back into the game. } 9.
Bd4 Bd8 10. Ng4 exf3 11. Qe5 Qg6 12. Qg3 Rh5 13. Bb6 Bxb6+ 14. axb6 f5 15. Rd6
Qg5 16. Rxc6 fxg4 17. Rc4 gxh3 18. Qxg5 Rxg5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises & Solutions"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Timman, Jan H"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2q2rk1/2nb1ppp/p2ppbP1/7P/1p1NPN2/1Pr1BP2/P1PQ4/1K4RR w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. h6
{ With this well-known type of pawn sacrifice White manages to open, by force, some lines against the enemy king. After the practically forced }
1... fxg6 2. hxg7 Rf7
{ we reach a critical position. How does White administer the knockout ?  After   24...Bxg7  White plays  25.Qh2  winning in short order. }
3. Rxh7 { This rook sacrifice brings the game to an immediate conclusion. }
3... Kxh7
{ Or   25...Rxg7  26.Rxg7+  Bxg7  and White breaks through with  27.Nxg6  :  Kf7  28.Bh6  Bf6  29.Qf4 !  e5  30.Nxe5+  dxe5  31.Rg7+  Ke8  32.Qxf6  could be one conclusive sample line. }
4. Qh2+ Kxg7 5. Nxg6
{ Here, too, the knight capture on g6 is the move which takes down the last of Black's defences.   27.Rxg6+  is less clear but also winning. }
5... Rxe3 6. Ne7+ Kf8 7. Nxc8
{ Black can't avoid further material losses and so resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises & Solutions"]
[Black "Shirov, Alexei vs. Anand, Viswanathan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1rb1r1k1/5Rbp/p1p1p1p1/2Bp2q1/8/2N2Q2/PPP4P/5R1K b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the game, Black played 24 .. . Qd8. He writes in his commentary to the game that he had intended 24 ... e5 but that he only at this moment realised that white had a forced win following that move. So: a  What was the win after 24... e5 ? And, b  How did White win after 24 ...Qd8 ? }
1... Qd8
{ He had planned   24...e5  but then became aware that White had a hidden winning opportunity here.  25.Rxg7+ !  Kxg7  26.Bf8+ !  The move that Anand hadn't seen beforehand.  No good is   26.Qf7+ ?  because of  Kh6 !  27.Bf8+   27.Qxe8  Bh3 !  wins  27...Rxf8  28.Qxf8+  Kh5  and Black is in fact winning, in spite of his exposed king.  26...Kh8  27.Qf7  Mate cannot be prevented except by huge material sacrifices. }
2. Rxg7+ Kxg7 3. Qf7+ Kh8 4. Bd6
{ The problem with 24... Qd8 was this little move. The queen on d8 is overloaded and cannot take on d6, but at the same time the bishop threatens the deadly Be5 as well as the capture of the b8-rook. }
4... e5
{ After   27...Qxd6  28.Qxe8+  Kg7  29.Rf7+  Kh6  30.Qh8 !  White develops a large mating attack, which cannot be defended against. The main variation is as follows:  e5  31.Qxh7+  Kg5  32.h4+  Kg4  33.Qh6  Bf5   33...e4  34.Qg5+  Kh3  35.Qg2+  Kxh4  36.Rh7#  34.Qg5+  Kf3  35.Qg2+  Ke3  36.Qe2+  Kd4  37.Rxf5  gxf5  38.Qd3+  Kc5  39.Na4+  Kb4  40.Qa3+  White wins the Black queen and mate will follow shortly afterwards. }
5. Bxb8 Bf5 6. Bc7 Qe7 7. Qxe7 Rxe7 8. Bd8 Re6 9. Re1 Kg8 10. Bc7 d4 11. Ne4 c5
12. Kg2
{ Not the most efficient way of dispatching the opponent.  Anand expected   35.Bxe5  after which he would have resigned:  Rxe5  36.Nf6+  Kf7  37.Rxe5  Kxf6  38.Rxc5 }
12... c4 13. Kf3 Re7 14. Bd6 Re6 15. Bc7 h6 16. c3 g5 17. Ng3 e4+ 18. Kg2 dxc3
19. bxc3 Bg6 20. Rd1 Re7 21. Rd6 Kf7 22. Bd8 Re8 23. Bb6 e3 24. Rd7+
{ After   47.Rd7+  Kg8  48.Rd8  no questions remain about the result. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises & Solutions"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Topalov, Veselin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4rb1k/2r3p1/pp2p1Pp/2nq4/P5N1/4B2Q/1PP3RP/5R1K w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ After lengthy preparations White is finally ready to land the decisive blow. How does he do so in the maximally effective manner ? }
1. Bxh6
{ The text is simpler than   34.Nxh6  , although that move wins too, as follows:  gxh6  35.Bxh6 !  Bxh6  36.Qxh6+  Kg8  37.g7  Qxg2+  38.Kxg2  Rxg7+  39.Kh1  with a winning endgame for White- although significant technical work remains to be done. }
1... gxh6 2. g7+
{ Another cute move.  Certainly not   35.Rxf8+ ?  Rxf8  36.g7+  Kxg7  which wins the queen after  37.Ne3+  but at too high a cost.   37.Qxh6+ ??  Kf7 !  and Black even wins. }
2... Bxg7
{ After   35...Rxg7  36.Qxh6+  Kg8  White has the strong   36...Rh7  37.Rxf8+  37.Nf6+  available. }
3. Nxh6 { Threatening Nf7+ followed by Qh8#. } 3... Qxg2+ 4. Qxg2 Bxh6
{ 37...Kh7  38.Qh3  Bxh6  39.Rf6  wins for White. } 5. Qg6
{ After   38.Qg6  Rg8  39.Qxh6+  Rh7  40.Qf6+  Rhg7  41.Qh4+  Rh7  42.Qd4+  Rhg7  43.Rf7  White isn't merely trading rooks, but also threatening mate starting with Qh4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises & Solutions"]
[Black "Madl, I. vs. Summermatter, D."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/3nbppp/p2pp3/1p4PQ/3BP2P/2NB4/PPP2P2/2KR3R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black clears the f8-square for a defensive piece  (bishop or knight.)  How can white create attacking chances against the enemy king ? }
1. Bxg7
{ This bishop sacrifice breaks up the Black kingside.   14.e5  is also almost winning.  g6  15.Qf3  Rb8  16.exd6  Bxd6  17.h5 !  and the lines and diagonals towards the black king bring White the victory. For instance:  Or, alternatively, White can delay the  (unstoppable)  push and first play something like   17.Ne4  Bb7  18.Qh3  which is also difficult for Black to handle.  17...Qxg5+  18.Kb1  Be5  19.hxg6  hxg6  20.Ne4  Qf5  21.Bxe5  Nxe5  22.Qg3  Rb6  23.Qh4  winning. }
1... Kxg7 { The sacrifice cannot very well be refused. } 2. Qh6+ Kh8
{ 15...Kg8  makes no difference } 3. e5 Nf8 4. Ne4
{ White wants to play Nf6 and hammer away at the h7-pawn until it drops. } 4...
Ng6 { 17...dxe5  Mokry,K  18.Nf6  +- } 5. Nf6 Bxf6 6. gxf6
{ Of course White wants the g-file open. } 6... Rg8 7. h5 Qf8
{ Now White finishes in style.  If the knight retreats with   20...Nf8  then White will trade the rooks:  21.Rdg1  and after that is done, mate will follow on g7. }
8. Qxh7+ { 21.Qxh7+  Kxh7  22.hxg6#  is mate ! } *

